SECTION 3. FINDINGS.
================================================================================

Congress finds the following:

--- Constitutional Basis ---

(1) The Constitution of the United States vests in Congress, under Article I,
Section 8, the power to promote the general welfare, regulate commerce among
the several states, and secure for limited times to authors and inventors the
exclusive right to their respective writings and discoveries, for the purpose
of promoting the progress of science and the useful arts.

(2) The Tenth Amendment to the Constitution reserves to the states and to the
people powers not delegated to the federal government, establishing the
foundational principle that governance is most legitimate and most effective
when exercised at the scale closest to the people it serves.

(3) The Fourteenth Amendment guarantees to all persons equal protection under
the law and prohibits the deprivation of life, liberty, or property without
due process, establishing an affirmative constitutional obligation to ensure
that the material conditions necessary for a dignified human life are not
systematically withheld from any class of persons.

(4) The current intellectual property regime, having extended copyright terms
to the life of the author plus seventy years and having permitted the systematic
shelving of patents without productive deployment, no longer fulfills the
constitutional mandate to promote the progress of science and the useful arts,
but instead operates primarily to concentrate the benefits of creative and
innovative work in corporate entities at the expense of individual creators and
the general public.

--- National Security and Systemic Fragility ---

(5) The material security of the United States is currently dependent upon a
global monetary architecture in which the United States dollar functions as the
world's primary reserve currency, a status historically maintained through the
denomination of global energy markets in dollars and enforced through the
projection of military power. This architecture is subject to accelerating
structural fragility as energy markets diversify, as rival monetary systems
develop, and as the domestic social and fiscal costs of maintaining dollar
hegemony through military projection mount.

(6) The concentration of critical infrastructure -- including energy generation
and distribution, food production and supply chains, communications networks,
and data systems -- in centralized corporate entities creates systemic single
points of failure vulnerable to cyberattack, supply chain disruption, financial
instability, and deliberate sabotage by foreign and domestic adversaries.

(7) The concentration of data infrastructure in a small number of privately
held corporations constitutes a national security vulnerability, as the
capture, disruption, or coercion of these entities by foreign adversaries or
domestic actors could deprive the American people of access to communications,
financial systems, and essential services simultaneously and without recourse.

(8) A nation whose communities possess distributed, locally governed capacity
to generate energy, produce food, manufacture essential goods, and coordinate
resources through resilient peer-to-peer networks is materially more secure
against both foreign adversarial action and domestic systemic failure than a
nation dependent upon centralized corporate infrastructure subject to
single-point disruption.

(9) The current trajectory of global energy markets, monetary systems, and
military alliance structures -- including the ongoing Europeanization of NATO
and the conditional and transactional character of current American alliance
commitments -- makes the diversification of American national security
foundations away from petrodollar dependence an urgent strategic priority.

--- Resource Abundance and Systemic Misallocation ---

(10) The United States and the world currently produce sufficient food to
adequately nourish all people on earth, yet hundreds of millions of people
suffer from food insecurity due not to absolute scarcity of productive capacity
but to the systemic misallocation of food as a speculative commodity rather
than a provisioned necessity.

(11) The United States currently contains approximately fifteen million vacant
residential properties while hundreds of thousands of people lack stable
housing, a disparity that reflects not a scarcity of shelter but the treatment
of housing as a speculative financial asset rather than a provisioned necessity.

(12) Vast quantities of federal land currently lie unused or are leased at
below-market rates to extractive industries, representing a public asset whose
productive potential for community resilience, food security, renewable energy
generation, and affordable housing remains unrealized.

(13) The treatment of land, housing, and essential resources primarily as
speculative financial assets rather than as provisioned necessities constitutes
a systemic misallocation that produces preventable poverty, housing insecurity,
food insecurity, and community instability, imposing substantial costs on
public welfare and national resilience.

--- The Existing Commons and the Prefigurative Argument ---

(14) Federated commons institutions -- including community land trusts, worker
cooperatives, tenant cooperatives, food cooperatives, credit unions,
time-banking networks, open-source software communities, and solidarity economy
networks -- already exist and function throughout the United States and
internationally, demonstrating through sustained practical operation that
community-governed shared resources can provide stable housing, meaningful
employment, food security, and cultural vitality without dependence on
extractive financial mechanisms.

(14A) The worker cooperative sector in the United States comprises
approximately 1,300 enterprises employing not fewer than 15,000 worker-owners,
coordinated nationally through the United States Federation of Worker
Cooperatives (USFWC) and its development partner the Democracy at Work
Institute, and supported internationally through the National Cooperative
Business Association (NCBA CLUSA), which has coordinated cooperative
development programs in more than 20 countries since its founding in 1916.
These organizations constitute existing national technical assistance
infrastructure capable of supporting rapid cooperative formation under this Act.

(14B) The community land trust sector in the United States is documented
through a national census maintained by Grounded Solutions Network, which
serves as the primary practitioner network for CLTs and shared equity housing
programs. The Champlain Housing Trust in Burlington, Vermont -- the largest
community land trust in the United States, stewarding over 2,400 rental
apartments and approximately 670 shared-equity homes across three counties,
with 8 percent of Burlington households residing in its properties -- is the
most studied domestic model of CLT-scale democratic land stewardship and
provides the primary operational precedent for the Community Land Trust
framework established under Title III of this Act.

(14C) The first modern American community land trust, New Communities in
Albany, Georgia, was founded in 1969 by Civil Rights Movement organizers to
provide Black farming families with permanent, secure access to land. The
community land trust model has, from its origins, been inseparable from the
project of racial justice and economic self-determination. The Federation of
Southern Cooperatives has advanced Black cooperative economic development for
decades, demonstrating that cooperative governance can address the material
legacies of racial economic exclusion. These organizations represent the
historical and moral foundation of the commons development this Act extends.

(14D) The solidarity economy sector in the United States is coordinated
through the New Economy Coalition, which connects more than 200 organizations
building commons-oriented institutions. Time-banking infrastructure is provided
nationally through hOurworld and TimeBanks USA. Cooperative financial
infrastructure is provided through the National Cooperative Bank and through
1,432 Treasury-certified Community Development Financial Institutions operating
throughout the United States as of 2025, all of which constitute the existing
financial network through which Bootstrap Grant distribution and Stewardship
Credit issuance under this Act will flow during the transition period.

(15) The Nobel Prize-winning research of economist Elinor Ostrom demonstrated
empirically that communities are capable of sustainably governing shared
resources without either privatization or central government administration,
provided that governance structures meet defined design principles including
clear boundaries, collective decision-making, effective monitoring, proportional
sanctions, accessible conflict resolution, recognized autonomy, and nested
governance at appropriate scales.

(16) Federally funded research programs have demonstrated the capacity to
produce intellectual outputs of significant civilian value that are naturally
compatible with commons governance -- including the DARPA Systematizing
Confidence in Open Research and Evidence program, whose research credibility
assessment tools, replicability datasets, and open-source methodological
innovations were developed through federal investment, are maintained by a
commons-oriented institution committed to open science, and constitute a model
for the mandatory commons contribution of publicly funded research established
under Title V of this Act.

(17) The open-source software commons -- including the Linux operating system,
the Wikipedia knowledge commons, and the broader ecosystem of openly licensed
software and knowledge -- has demonstrated that commons-based peer production
can generate productive value exceeding that of proprietary alternatives,
without requiring intellectual property monopoly as an incentive for
contribution.

(17A) Creative Commons licensing and the Open Definition maintained by the
Open Knowledge Foundation together constitute the existing legal and technical
infrastructure upon which the Intellectual Property Commons established under
Title V of this Act is built. Works already released under Creative Commons
licenses are eligible for IP Commons contribution without relicensing conflicts.
The Open Definition's criteria shall inform the IP Commons Governance Council's
determinations of what constitutes a genuinely open contribution under Title V
of this Act.

(17B) The open access policy framework governing publicly funded research --
including the National Institutes of Health public access policy, the National
Science Foundation's open access requirements, and the 2022 Office of Science
and Technology Policy memorandum requiring immediate open access for all
federally funded research -- constitutes an existing federal commitment to
commons availability of publicly funded knowledge. The mandatory commons
contribution provisions of Section 503 of Title V of this Act codify and extend
that policy framework. The Confederation of Open Access Repositories (COAR),
which coordinates open access repository networks representing more than 130
institutions in 35 countries, provides the primary existing international
infrastructure for commons-compatible research dissemination; the Technical
Standards Body established under Section 701(d) of Title VII of this Act shall
ensure that the IP Commons attribution and access architecture is interoperable
with COAR repository standards.

(18) Existing federated cooperative institutions demonstrate that federated
commons can operate at significant scale while maintaining democratic
governance, community accountability, and material provision for members.
The Mondragon cooperative federation in the Basque Country of Spain, comprising
more than 100 cooperatives with approximately 80,000 worker-owners spanning
manufacturing, retail, finance, and education, is the primary international
proof of concept for federated cooperative enterprise at scale. The Champlain
Housing Trust, Dudley Neighbors Incorporated in Boston's Roxbury and North
Dorchester neighborhoods, the California Community Land Trust Network
coordinating more than 50 CLTs statewide, the New Economy Coalition, and the
Federation of Southern Cooperatives, among others, demonstrate the same
capacity domestically.

(18A) LabGov (the Laboratory for the Governance of the Commons) developed the
Co-City Protocol for urban commons governance, and its collaboration with the
City of Bologna produced the Bologna Regulation on Public Collaboration for
Urban Commons in 2014, which has since been adopted in adapted form by more
than 200 cities. This instrument provides the primary international precedent
for the municipal commons governance architecture that this Act extends to the
national level.

(18B) The 2014 Farm Bill established an Interagency Working Group on
Cooperative Development coordinating the Departments of Agriculture, Treasury,
Justice, Labor, and Housing and Urban Development, the Internal Revenue Service,
and the Small Business Administration. That working group constitutes an
existing federal coordination mechanism on which this Act builds, and which
the Office of Federated Stewardship is authorized to convene, expand, and
formalize as the primary federal-commons coordination body during the OFS Phase.

(19) This Act does not create a new institutional system from theoretical
foundations. The cooperative institutions, community land trusts, open-source
commons, and solidarity economy networks that this Act recognizes, connects, and
capitalizes already exist and already function throughout the United States and
internationally. This Act removes the legal barriers, provides the technical
infrastructure, and supplies the financial capitalization necessary for these
existing institutions to scale from the margins of the current economy to its
foundation.

--- The Commons as Democratic Deepening ---

(20) Federated Commons Membership, as established by this Act, is not a
government benefit or welfare transfer. It is a form of democratic economic
citizenship -- a bundle of membership rights in cooperative institutions that
collectively provide for the material conditions of a dignified life, each of
which the member participates in governing. The governance rights and the
provision rights are inseparable and mutually constitutive.

(21) The concentration of economic and political power in centralized corporate
and governmental institutions has progressively eroded the capacity of ordinary
citizens to exercise meaningful self-governance over the conditions of their
material lives. The federated commons architecture established by this Act
restores that capacity by distributing governance of land, knowledge, data, and
productive enterprise to the communities that depend upon them.

(22) This Act does not diminish democratic governance. It extends democratic
governance into the domains of economic and material life where it has
historically been absent, fulfilling the constitutional promise of
self-governance at every scale from the neighborhood to the nation.

--- The Open Information Environment ---

(23) The establishment of a federated commons for land, data, and intellectual
property, governed by transparent and auditable protocols under the principles
established by this Act, naturally produces an information environment of
substantially greater transparency regarding the governance of institutions that
affect the public interest than currently exists under the proprietary model.
This transparency serves the public interest in accountability, including the
interest of a free press in reporting on the exercise of institutional power,
without requiring specific affirmation of press rights beyond those already
guaranteed by the First Amendment to the Constitution.

(24) The abandoned works mechanism established under Section 506(a)(2) of
Title V of this Act is grounded in the common law abandonment doctrine, which
has long recognized that property rights may be forfeited through sustained
non-use combined with the manifest intent to abandon, and in the constitutional
text of Article I, Section 8, which limits Congress's authority to grant
exclusive intellectual property rights to "limited times." Congress finds that
a copyright exercised through fourteen consecutive years of complete commercial
inactivity constitutes an abandonment of the commercial character of that right,
and that the contribution of such abandoned works to the commons, with full
attribution retained in the original creator, is consistent with the
constitutional mandate to promote the progress of science and the useful arts.
Congress further finds that the voluntary dedication pathway established in
Section 506(a)(1) of Title V of this Act is the primary mechanism by which
works enter the IP Commons; the abandoned works mechanism operates as a
secondary and narrowly tailored doctrine applicable only to works whose
rights-holders have for an extended period made no active use of, and taken no
active decision about, the commercial character of their rights.


