SECTION 4. DEFINITIONS.
================================================================================

In this Act:

(1) ASYNCHRONOUS RESOURCE COORDINATION or ARC.-- The term "Asynchronous
Resource Coordination" means the protocol-driven, peer-to-peer discovery and
exchange of metabolic resources -- including energy, water, food, material
goods, labor availability, and Commons Credits -- between Federated
Mesh-connected devices and Qualified Federated Networks, operating through the
metabolic signaling functions of the Federated Mesh Open Standard without
dependence upon centralized administrative authorization, real-time human
direction, or proprietary intermediary platforms, such that resource surpluses
and deficits within and between Qualified Federated Networks are continuously
identified and matched through automated signaling, subject at all times to the
governance parameters established by the relevant Qualified Federated Network
through its collective-choice arrangements under Standard 3 of the Ostrom
Standards of Stewardship, and subject to human review and override through the
Human-in-the-Loop Layer pursuant to Section 803 of this Act.

(2) COMMONS CREDIT.-- The term "Commons Credit" means a unit of account issued
through the National Resilience Ledger, denominated in and redeemable for
verifiable units of community productive output, recognized as legal tender for
transactions within a Qualified Federated Network, and not redeemable for
United States dollars except through mechanisms expressly authorized under
Title VI of this Act.

(3) COMMONS FINANCIAL NODE.-- The term "Commons Financial Node" means a credit
union, community development financial institution, the National Cooperative
Bank, or other cooperatively structured or mission-aligned financial entity
that has registered with the Office of Federated Stewardship pursuant to
Section 107 of this Act and that provides Commons Credit issuance, Bootstrap
Grant distribution, and inter-network financial services within the Federated
Network, without being required to meet the full certification requirements
applicable to a Qualified Federated Network.

(4) COMMONS MEMBER.-- The term "Commons Member" means an individual who holds
Federated Commons Membership pursuant to Title II of this Act, and who is
thereby entitled to the Guaranteed Provision Standard and to governance
participation rights in the cooperative institutions comprising that
individual's Federated Commons Membership portfolio.

(5) COMMONS PERMANENCE ASSET.-- The term "Commons Permanence Asset" means a
resource designated pursuant to Section 307 of this Act as essential to the
long-term productive and ecological resilience of a Qualified Federated Network,
including soil health and agricultural land, freshwater systems, seed stocks,
foundational intellectual property, and critical commons infrastructure, which
may not be transferred, traded, or otherwise alienated from the commons
regardless of surplus conditions or collective authorization.

(6) COMMUNITY LAND TRUST or CLT.-- The term "Community Land Trust" means a
nonprofit organization that acquires and holds land in perpetual stewardship for
the benefit of a defined community, provides long-term affordable access to land
and housing through ground leases to individual residents and cooperative
enterprises, retains permanent restrictions preventing the resale of land at
speculative market value, and operates under democratic governance by its
resident members pursuant to the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship defined in
Section 102 of Title I.

(7) FEDERATED COMMONS MEMBERSHIP.-- The term "Federated Commons Membership"
means the comprehensive membership status held by a Commons Member within a
Qualified Federated Network, comprising a portfolio of cooperative memberships
that collectively provide the Guaranteed Provision Standard, including mandatory
baseline memberships in a Community Land Trust, a food cooperative, a healthcare
cooperative, a Data Commons, and the Intellectual Property Commons established
under this Act, together with such elective cooperative memberships as the
Commons Member may hold in labor cooperatives, energy cooperatives, childcare
cooperatives, elder care cooperatives, transportation cooperatives,
communications cooperatives, and other cooperative enterprises operating within
the Qualified Federated Network, each carrying corresponding democratic
governance rights in the institution providing that membership's provisions.

(8) FEDERATED MESH.-- The term "Federated Mesh" means the decentralized digital
and legal interoperability architecture that enables Qualified Federated Networks
to discover one another, exchange resource availability signals, coordinate
commons resource flows, verify compliance with the Ostrom Standards of
Stewardship, and conduct Commons Credit transactions, without dependence upon
centralized servers, proprietary intermediaries, or single points of
administrative control, and that operates in accordance with the Federated Mesh
Open Standard established under Title VII of this Act.

(9) FEDERATED MESH OPEN STANDARD or FMOS.-- The term "Federated Mesh Open
Standard" means the open, non-proprietary, publicly documented technical
protocol established under Section 701 of this Act governing peer-to-peer device
discovery, cryptographic identity verification through Physical Unclonable
Functions, resource availability signaling, Commons Credit transaction
processing, and Asynchronous Resource Coordination within and between Qualified
Federated Networks, compliance with which is required of all integrated circuits
manufactured or imported into the United States after the effective date
established in Section 701(b) of this Act.

(10) GUARANTEED PROVISION STANDARD.-- The term "Guaranteed Provision Standard"
means the minimum bundle of material provisions to which every Commons Member is
entitled through Federated Commons Membership, regardless of the member's
location within the Federated Network, labor contributions, Commons Credit
balance, or any other condition, comprising: adequate housing meeting the
standards established under Section 202 of this Act; adequate nutrition meeting
the standards established under Section 203 of this Act; access to healthcare
meeting the standards established under Section 204 of this Act; connectivity
and access to tools and materials for productive and creative work meeting the
standards established under Section 205 of this Act; and access to educational
resources and the Intellectual Property Commons meeting the standards established
under Sections 206 and 207 of this Act.

(11) HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP LAYER or HITL.-- The term "Human-in-the-Loop Layer"
means the governance mechanism established under Section 803 of this Act by
which human deliberation, exercised through the Accountability Coordination DAO
or Manual Merit Review processes, constitutes the final and non-delegable
authority over any determination made within a Qualified Federated Network that
materially affects the rights, provisions, standing, or obligations of an
individual Commons Member, and by which any automated determination affecting an
individual may be suspended, reviewed, and overridden by human deliberation
within the timeframes established under Section 803 of this Act.

(12) INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY COMMONS.-- The term "Intellectual Property Commons"
means the federated repository of creative works, technical innovations,
traditional knowledge, and other intellectual contributions established under
Title V of this Act, held in common for the benefit of all Commons Members and
the general public, governed by the IP Commons Governance Council established
under Section 509 of this Act, in which all contributions are protected by
immutable attribution registration, freely accessible to any Commons Member for
use, deployment, performance, remix, or further development under the copyleft
license established under Section 507 of this Act, and from which no
contribution may be removed, re-enclosed, or subjected to proprietary licensing
by any individual, enterprise, or governmental authority.

(13) ACCOUNTABILITY COORDINATION DAO.-- The term "Accountability Coordination
DAO" means a locally constituted, peer-elected body operating within a Qualified
Federated Network pursuant to Section 804 of this Act, whose members are trained
in restorative conflict resolution, whose function is to coordinate, record, and
track restorative agreements and accountability processes through the Federated
Mesh, whose proceedings are conducted through human deliberation without recourse
to automated behavioral prediction or algorithmic risk assessment, and which
serves as the technical coordination and registry infrastructure for the
resolution of disputes, reparative justice processes, and non-violent community
safety responses within the Qualified Federated Network. Authority to adjudicate
disputes or determine accountability outcomes rests with the human deliberative
body and its participants; the Accountability Coordination DAO does not itself
constitute a decision-making authority over the rights or standing of any
individual Commons Member.

(14) NATIONAL RESILIENCE LEDGER or NRL.-- The term "National Resilience Ledger"
means the distributed digital ledger established under Section 601 of this Act,
maintained on the Federated Mesh rather than on any centralized server or
governmental database, recording the issuance and transfer of Commons Credits,
the registration of Community Land Trust land holdings and associated Stewardship
Credit issuances, the attribution registrations of contributions to the
Intellectual Property Commons, the certification status of Qualified Federated
Networks and Qualified Federated Cooperatives, and the Commons Membership Records
of individual Commons Members, and whose contents are publicly auditable by any
Commons Member but are accessible in their individually identified form only by
the Commons Member to whom they pertain, pursuant to the privacy protections
established under Title IV of this Act.

(15) OFFICE OF FEDERATED STEWARDSHIP or OFS.-- The term "Office of Federated
Stewardship" means the transitional administrative body established within the
Department of Commerce under Section 107 of this Act, whose functions are
limited to receiving and processing applications for Qualified Federated Network
certification, maintaining a public registry of certified Qualified Federated
Networks and Qualified Federated Cooperatives, distributing Bootstrap Grants
pursuant to Section 106 of this Act, providing technical assistance to
organizations seeking certification, and publishing annual reports on the state
of the Federated Network, and which shall have no authority to revoke, suspend,
or condition the certification of any Qualified Federated Network except upon a
finding of Consensus Failure by the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism established
under Section 104 of this Act.

(16) OSTROM STANDARDS OF STEWARDSHIP.-- The term "Ostrom Standards of
Stewardship" means the eight governance design principles, derived from the
empirical research of Nobel laureate Elinor Ostrom on the sustainable
self-governance of common-pool resources, that are required to be incorporated
into the bylaws and operational protocols of every Qualified Federated
Cooperative and Qualified Federated Network pursuant to Section 102 of this Act,
comprising: Standard 1, Defined Boundaries; Standard 2, Local Congruence;
Standard 3, Collective-Choice Arrangements; Standard 4, Peer Monitoring;
Standard 5, Graduated Sanctions; Standard 6, Accessible Conflict Resolution;
Standard 7, Jurisdictional Autonomy; and Standard 8, Nested Governance, each as
defined and operationalized in Section 102 of this Act.

(17) PEER-TO-PEER AUDIT or P2P-A.-- The term "Peer-to-Peer Audit" means the
decentralized, automated, and human-reviewable compliance verification mechanism
established under Section 103 of this Act, by which the certification status and
Ostrom Standards compliance of each Qualified Federated Network is continuously
monitored through a combination of: self-reporting by the audited network of its
resource metabolism data to the National Resilience Ledger; independent
verification of that reported data by three or more geographically diverse
Qualified Federated Networks algorithmically assigned as auditing peers; and
algorithmic cross-validation of reported data against physical outputs measurable
through the Federated Mesh Open Standard, with any discrepancy between reported
and verified data constituting a Compliance Flag triggering the graduated
response procedures established under Section 103(c) of this Act, and with any
automated Compliance Flag subject to human review through the Human-in-the-Loop
Layer upon request by the audited network.

(18) PHYSICAL UNCLONABLE FUNCTION or PUF.-- The term "Physical Unclonable
Function" means a hardware-level cryptographic identity mechanism that derives a
unique, non-reproducible identifier from the microscopic physical variations
inherent in the manufacturing process of an integrated circuit, such that the
identifier cannot be cloned, transferred, or simulated without physical
replication of the specific circuit at the atomic level, and which serves as the
foundational identity verification mechanism for all devices operating within the
Federated Mesh pursuant to Section 702 of this Act, ensuring that no device may
falsely represent its identity, location, or resource outputs to the Federated
Mesh without physical detection.

(19) QUALIFIED FEDERATED COOPERATIVE or QFC.-- The term "Qualified Federated
Cooperative" means a legally incorporated cooperative enterprise or community
land trust that: is owned and democratically controlled by its members on a
one-member, one-vote basis or such other collective-choice arrangement as
satisfies Standard 3 of the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship; operates for the
mutual benefit of its members and the broader community within its defined
boundaries; has incorporated the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship into its
governing bylaws in the manner required by Section 102 of this Act; has
connected to the Federated Mesh through a compliant device meeting the
requirements of Section 701 of this Act; and has been registered with the Office
of Federated Stewardship pursuant to Section 107 of this Act or, following the
network maturity threshold established under Section 107(f) of this Act, has
been certified through the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism.

(20) QUALIFIED FEDERATED NETWORK or QFN.-- The term "Qualified Federated
Network" means a self-sovereign legal association comprising two or more
Qualified Federated Cooperatives that: operate in geographic or functional
proximity sufficient to coordinate resource flows through the Federated Mesh;
have adopted a shared federated governance charter incorporating the Ostrom
Standards of Stewardship at the network level pursuant to Section 101 of this
Act; have achieved certification through the Office of Federated Stewardship or,
following the network maturity threshold established under Section 107(f) of
this Act, through the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism; hold legal personhood for
the purposes of entering contracts, holding land titles, holding attribution
registrations in the Intellectual Property Commons, and maintaining accounts on
the National Resilience Ledger; and are capable of providing the full Guaranteed
Provision Standard to all Commons Members within their geographic or functional
scope, whether through internal capacity or through federated resource-sharing
arrangements with neighboring Qualified Federated Networks.

(21) WITNESSED PHYSICAL REGISTRATION.-- The term "Witnessed Physical
Registration" means the attribution registration pathway established under
Section 504(b)(3) of this Act by which a creator who lacks direct access to a
Federated Mesh-connected device may register a creative work, technical
innovation, or traditional knowledge contribution to the Intellectual Property
Commons through the assistance of a certified QFN Witness, who documents the
work through photography, video, written description, or other appropriate means,
co-signs the registration on the National Resilience Ledger using the Witness's
own cryptographic keypair, and provides the originating creator with a durable
physical credential confirming the registration reference number, with the
creator's attribution thereby established on the National Resilience Ledger as
of the documented creation date regardless of the creator's personal technical
capability or connectivity, and with the QFN Witness subject to the graduated
sanctions of Section 102(f) of this Act for any false or fraudulent registration.

(22) ZERO-KNOWLEDGE PROOF or ZKP.-- The term "Zero-Knowledge Proof" means a
cryptographic protocol by which one party may demonstrate to another party that
a specific statement is true -- including without limitation that a device holds
a valid certification, that a Commons Member holds an active Federated Commons
Membership, or that a Qualified Federated Network has met a defined compliance
threshold -- without revealing to the verifying party any underlying personal
information, identifying data, location data, or other information beyond the
binary verification of the statement itself, and which serves within the
Federated Mesh as the primary mechanism for confirming membership status,
certification status, and compliance status in contexts where privacy protection
requires that verification occur without disclosure of the information that
underlies it, pursuant to the privacy architecture established under Title IV of
this Act.


================================================================================
TITLE I -- THE FEDERATED NETWORK ARCHITECTURE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the legal existence, governance
requirements, certification architecture, and administrative infrastructure of
the Federated Network before any transfer of assets, issuance of credits, or
delivery of provisions occurs under this Act. No provision of Titles II through
XI of this Act shall be operative with respect to any Qualified Federated
Network or Qualified Federated Cooperative until that network or cooperative has
achieved certification pursuant to this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 101. LEGAL PERSONHOOD AND RECOGNITION OF QUALIFIED FEDERATED NETWORKS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) RECOGNITION AS LEGAL PERSONS.-- A Qualified Federated Network certified
pursuant to Section 103 of this Act is hereby recognized as a legal person under
federal law, with capacity to:

    (1) acquire, hold, and transfer title to real property, including land
    transferred pursuant to Title III of this Act;

    (2) enter into contracts with natural persons, corporations, governmental
    entities, and other Qualified Federated Networks;

    (3) hold attribution registrations in the Intellectual Property Commons
    pursuant to Title V of this Act;

    (4) maintain accounts on the National Resilience Ledger and issue Commons
    Credits pursuant to Title VI of this Act;

    (5) bring and defend civil actions in federal and state courts in its own
    name; and

    (6) exercise such other capacities as are necessary to carry out the
    purposes of this Act.

(b) RELATIONSHIP TO STATE LAW.-- The legal personhood conferred upon a Qualified
Federated Network by subsection (a) of this Section is a federal recognition
that operates independently of and in addition to any legal status the network
or its constituent Qualified Federated Cooperatives may hold under the laws of
any state. Nothing in this Act shall be construed to preempt state cooperative
corporation law, state nonprofit law, or state community land trust law except
insofar as such laws directly conflict with the rights and capacities conferred
by this Act, in which case federal law shall govern.

(c) INTERNAL GOVERNANCE SUPREMACY.-- The internal governance documents of a
Qualified Federated Network, including its federated charter and the bylaws of
its constituent Qualified Federated Cooperatives, shall govern all internal
matters of resource allocation, membership rights, cooperative management, and
dispute resolution, provided that such documents comply with the Ostrom
Standards of Stewardship as defined in Section 4(16) of this Act and as
operationalized in Section 102 of this Title. No federal agency, state
government, or external private party shall direct, override, or substitute its
judgment for the internal governance determinations of a Qualified Federated
Network except:

    (1) upon a judicial finding of violation of the Constitution of the United
    States or of a federal statute of general applicability; or

    (2) upon a finding of Consensus Failure by the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism
    established in Section 103 of this Title, triggering the graduated response
    procedures of Section 103(c).

(d) PROTECTION FROM HOSTILE ACQUISITION.-- No Qualified Federated Network or
Qualified Federated Cooperative, nor any land, intellectual property, or other
asset held by such network or cooperative in commons stewardship, shall be
subject to acquisition through hostile takeover, leveraged buyout, eminent
domain for private benefit, or any other mechanism by which a private party
seeks to convert commons assets to private ownership. Any attempted acquisition
in violation of this subsection shall be void ab initio and shall constitute
grounds for injunctive relief without bond in any federal court of competent
jurisdiction.

(e) NETWORK AUTONOMY AND SELF-DETERMINATION.-- The right of a Qualified
Federated Network to determine its own membership criteria, internal rules,
resource allocation priorities, and governance structures, consistent with the
Ostrom Standards of Stewardship and the provisions of this Act, is hereby
recognized as a fundamental attribute of the legal personhood conferred by this
Section. This right of self-determination shall be construed broadly in favor of
network autonomy in any proceeding in which it is at issue.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 102. OSTROM STANDARDS OF STEWARDSHIP.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL REQUIREMENT.-- No entity shall be certified as a Qualified Federated
Cooperative or recognized as a constituent member of a Qualified Federated
Network under this Act unless its governing bylaws, operational protocols, and
technical configurations collectively and demonstrably satisfy each of the eight
Ostrom Standards of Stewardship set forth in subsections (b) through (i) of this
Section. Satisfaction of each Standard shall be assessed at initial
certification pursuant to Section 103 of this Title and at each subsequent
biennial compliance review conducted through the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism.
Failure to maintain satisfaction of any Standard shall trigger the graduated
response procedures of Section 103(c) of this Title. The operationalization of
each Standard in this Section draws upon the continuing empirical research of
the Ostrom Workshop in Political Theory and Policy Analysis at Indiana
University -- founded by Nobel laureate Elinor Ostrom and Vincent Ostrom and
the primary institutional home for ongoing commons governance research -- whose
accumulated case study literature on the conditions under which communities
successfully self-govern shared resources provides the evidentiary foundation
for each Standard as defined herein. The IP Commons Governance Council
established under Section 509 of Title V of this Act shall maintain a standing
advisory relationship with the Ostrom Workshop, and shall consult the Workshop's
research findings in conducting the mandatory adequacy reviews of the Ostrom
Standards required under Section 212 of Title II of this Act.

(b) STANDARD 1 -- DEFINED BOUNDARIES.--

    (1) REQUIREMENT.-- The bylaws of a Qualified Federated Cooperative shall
    contain a clear and publicly accessible description of:

        (A) the natural persons, households, and enterprises who hold membership
        in the cooperative and are thereby entitled to participate in its
        governance and receive its provisions;

        (B) the geographic boundaries, legal descriptions, or functional scope
        of the common-pool resources -- including land parcels, data systems,
        intellectual property holdings, productive infrastructure, and shared
        services -- under the cooperative's stewardship; and

        (C) the criteria and procedures by which new members may be admitted to
        the cooperative and existing members may withdraw or be sanctioned,
        consistent with Standard 5 of this Section.

    (2) TRANSPARENCY REQUIREMENT.-- The membership registry and resource
    boundary descriptions required by paragraph (1) of this subsection shall be
    recorded on the National Resilience Ledger in a form accessible to any
    Commons Member of any Qualified Federated Network, provided that individually
    identifying personal information of members shall be protected in accordance
    with the privacy provisions of Title IV of this Act.

    (3) PROHIBITION ON EXCLUSIONARY CRITERIA.-- No Qualified Federated
    Cooperative shall establish membership criteria that discriminate on the
    basis of race, color, national origin, sex, gender identity, sexual
    orientation, religion, disability, age, or any other characteristic protected
    under federal law. Membership criteria shall relate solely to the
    cooperative's defined geographic boundaries, functional scope, or capacity
    to provide provisions.

(c) STANDARD 2 -- LOCAL CONGRUENCE.--

    (1) REQUIREMENT.-- The rules governing the use, allocation, and distribution
    of resources within a Qualified Federated Cooperative shall be:

        (A) proportional to the local ecological, economic, and social conditions
        within the cooperative's defined boundaries, including local resource
        availability, climate conditions, population density, and existing
        infrastructure capacity;

        (B) calibrated to the actual labor, capital, and material contributions
        required from members to sustain the cooperative's productive capacity;
        and

        (C) subject to periodic review and revision by the cooperative's
        membership through the collective-choice arrangements required by
        Standard 3 of this Section, to ensure continued congruence with changing
        local conditions.

    (2) PROHIBITION ON EXTERNALLY IMPOSED UNIFORMITY.-- No federal agency, state
    government, or network-level governance body shall require a Qualified
    Federated Cooperative to adopt resource allocation rules that are not
    congruent with the cooperative's local conditions, except that minimum
    provision standards established under Title II of this Act shall apply
    universally as a floor below which no cooperative's rules may operate.

(d) STANDARD 3 -- COLLECTIVE-CHOICE ARRANGEMENTS.--

    (1) REQUIREMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Cooperative shall operate under
    a governance structure that:

        (A) provides every member with a direct, meaningful, and regularly
        exercised right to participate in the making and revision of the
        operational rules governing the cooperative's resource allocation,
        membership criteria, provision standards, and dispute resolution
        procedures;

        (B) ensures that no operational rule governing the cooperative may be
        adopted, amended, or repealed except through a collective decision-making
        process in which all affected members have had a genuine opportunity to
        participate;

        (C) prohibits the concentration of governance authority in any individual,
        officer, board, or subset of members in a manner that forecloses
        meaningful participation by the broader membership; and

        (D) provides for governance participation through accessible means,
        including in-person assembly, digital participation through the Federated
        Mesh, and proxy arrangements for members who are temporarily unable to
        participate directly, such that no member is excluded from governance by
        reason of physical distance, disability, or temporary incapacity.

    (2) VOTING STANDARD.-- The default voting standard for operational decisions
    shall be one member, one vote. A Qualified Federated Cooperative may adopt
    alternative collective-choice arrangements -- including consensus
    decision-making, delegative voting, or quadratic voting mechanisms --
    provided that the alternative arrangement demonstrably provides equivalent
    or greater meaningful participation to all members than the one-member-one-
    vote standard, and provided that the alternative arrangement is itself adopted
    through a one-member-one-vote process.

    (3) GOVERNANCE RECORD.-- All collective decisions made pursuant to this
    Standard shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger in a form
    accessible to the cooperative's members, with sufficient detail to allow any
    member to verify that the decision was made through a compliant
    collective-choice process.

(e) STANDARD 4 -- PEER MONITORING.--

    (1) REQUIREMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Cooperative shall maintain a
    monitoring system that:

        (A) continuously tracks the health, availability, and utilization of the
        common-pool resources under the cooperative's stewardship, including
        energy production and consumption, food production and distribution, land
        use and ecological health, and Commons Credit flows;

        (B) makes the resulting resource health data available in real time on
        the National Resilience Ledger in aggregated form accessible to all
        Commons Members of the Federated Network, subject to the individual
        privacy protections of Title IV of this Act;

        (C) is operated by or directly accountable to the cooperative's
        membership, such that no external party controls the monitoring function
        or has exclusive access to its outputs; and

        (D) is integrated with the Federated Mesh Open Standard to enable
        automated cross-validation of reported data by the Peer-to-Peer Audit
        mechanism established in Section 103 of this Title.

    (2) PROHIBITION ON INDIVIDUAL BEHAVIORAL SURVEILLANCE.-- Nothing in this
    Standard shall be construed to authorize the monitoring of individual member
    behavior, communications, location, consumption patterns, or personal
    activities. Monitoring under this Standard is limited to the health and
    utilization of shared resources at the aggregate level. Individual-level data
    contributing to aggregate resource metrics shall be anonymized at the point
    of collection and shall not be stored in individually identifiable form
    except with the express, specific, and revocable consent of the individual
    member concerned.

(f) STANDARD 5 -- GRADUATED SANCTIONS.--

    (1) REQUIREMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Cooperative shall maintain a
    published schedule of corrective responses to violations of the cooperative's
    operational rules, which shall:

        (A) be proportional to the severity, context, and frequency of the
        violation, ranging from informal notice and community dialogue for minor
        or first violations to suspension of resource access privileges for
        serious or repeated violations;

        (B) prioritize restoration of harm to the cooperative and its members
        over punishment of the violating member;

        (C) provide the violating member with notice of the alleged violation, a
        meaningful opportunity to respond before any sanction is imposed, and
        access to the conflict resolution mechanisms required by Standard 6 of
        this Section;

        (D) prohibit permanent expulsion from the cooperative as a sanction for
        any violation that has been fully addressed through the reparative
        process, except upon a finding by the Accountability Coordination DAO that permanent
        expulsion is necessary to protect the physical safety of other members;
        and

        (E) be applied consistently and without discrimination across the
        cooperative's membership.

    (2) NETWORK-LEVEL SANCTIONS.-- Where a violation by a Qualified Federated
    Cooperative of the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship is detected through the
    Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism, network-level sanctions shall be applied
    through the graduated response procedures of Section 103(c) of this Title
    rather than through the individual-level sanctions procedures of this
    Standard.

(g) STANDARD 6 -- ACCESSIBLE CONFLICT RESOLUTION.--

    (1) REQUIREMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Cooperative shall provide its
    members with access to a conflict resolution mechanism that:

        (A) is local, rapid, and low-cost, accessible to all members regardless
        of their financial resources, technical capability, or physical location
        within the cooperative's boundaries;

        (B) operates through human deliberation by peer-elected members trained
        in restorative conflict resolution, without recourse to automated
        determination or algorithmic assessment of fault or remedy;

        (C) prioritizes the restoration of relationships, the repair of harm, and
        the reintegration of all parties into the cooperative community over the
        assignment of blame or the imposition of punishment;

        (D) records its proceedings and determinations on the National Resilience
        Ledger in a form accessible to the parties and to the cooperative's
        membership, subject to the privacy protections of Title IV of this Act;
        and

        (E) provides a pathway for appeal of any determination to the Human-in-
        the-Loop Layer established under Section 803 of this Act, accessible to
        any party who believes the determination was reached through a non-
        compliant process.

    (2) RELATIONSHIP TO ACCOUNTABILITY COORDINATION DAO.-- The conflict
    resolution mechanism required by this Standard shall, where the Qualified
    Federated Cooperative operates within a Qualified Federated Network that has
    constituted an Accountability Coordination DAO pursuant to Section 804 of this
    Act, be provided through or in coordination with that Accountability
    Coordination DAO. Where no Accountability Coordination DAO has yet been
    constituted, the cooperative shall establish an interim conflict resolution
    body meeting the requirements of paragraph (1) of this subsection.

(h) STANDARD 7 -- JURISDICTIONAL AUTONOMY.--

    (1) REQUIREMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Cooperative shall maintain in
    its bylaws an explicit assertion of its right to devise, adopt, enforce, and
    revise its internal governance rules, resource allocation protocols,
    membership criteria, and conflict resolution procedures without interference
    from external governmental authorities, subject only to:

        (A) the Constitution of the United States and federal statutes of general
        applicability;

        (B) the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship and other requirements of this
        Act; and

        (C) the federated governance charter of the Qualified Federated Network
        of which the cooperative is a constituent member, to the extent that
        charter governs matters appropriately resolved at the network level
        pursuant to Standard 8 of this Section.

    (2) FEDERAL RESTRAINT.-- No federal agency shall promulgate regulations,
    issue guidance, impose conditions on federal assistance, or take any other
    administrative action that has the effect of directing or constraining the
    internal governance decisions of a Qualified Federated Cooperative or
    Qualified Federated Network on matters within the cooperative's or network's
    legitimate domain under this Standard, except as expressly authorized by this
    Act or by another federal statute enacted with specific reference to this Act.

    (3) STATE RESTRAINT.-- To the extent permitted by the Supremacy Clause of
    the Constitution, no state law or regulation shall be applied to override the
    internal governance decisions of a Qualified Federated Cooperative or
    Qualified Federated Network on matters within the cooperative's or network's
    legitimate domain under this Standard.

(i) STANDARD 8 -- NESTED GOVERNANCE.--

    (1) REQUIREMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Cooperative shall be capable of
    federating -- that is, of organizing its governance, monitoring, resource
    coordination, conflict resolution, and enforcement activities into multiple
    nested layers of governance, with each layer exercising authority over
    matters appropriately resolved at its scale and no layer exercising authority
    over matters more appropriately resolved at a smaller or larger scale.

    (2) GOVERNANCE LAYERS.-- The nested governance architecture of the Federated
    Network shall comprise at minimum the following layers:

        (A) the individual Qualified Federated Cooperative, governing the
        internal affairs of its membership and the common-pool resources within
        its defined boundaries;

        (B) the Qualified Federated Network, governing the coordination of
        resources, resolution of inter-cooperative disputes, and shared
        infrastructure among its constituent cooperatives;

        (C) regional federations, where constituted, governing resource flows,
        shared infrastructure, and inter-network coordination across multiple
        Qualified Federated Networks within a defined geographic or functional
        region; and

        (D) the national commons governance structures established under this
        Act, including the IP Commons Governance Council established under
        Section 509 of this Act and the technical standards governance
        established under Title VII of this Act, governing network-wide
        standards, the Intellectual Property Commons, and the National
        Resilience Ledger.

    (3) SUBSIDIARITY PRINCIPLE.-- Decisions shall be made at the lowest
    governance layer capable of effectively addressing the matter at issue. No
    higher governance layer shall exercise authority over a matter that can be
    effectively addressed by a lower layer. Where a matter genuinely requires
    resolution at a higher layer -- including inter-cooperative resource disputes,
    network-wide compliance failures, or matters affecting the integrity of the
    National Resilience Ledger -- the higher layer shall exercise only the
    authority necessary to address the specific matter and shall return
    governance to the lower layer upon resolution.

    (4) INTER-LAYER CONFLICT RESOLUTION.-- Where a conflict arises between the
    governance decisions of different layers of the nested governance
    architecture, the conflict shall be resolved:

        (A) first, through good-faith negotiation between the affected layers;

        (B) second, through the Accountability Coordination DAO process established under Section
        804 of this Act, if negotiation fails; and

        (C) third, through the Human-in-the-Loop Layer established under Section
        803 of this Act, if mediation fails to produce a resolution within the
        timeframe established under Section 803(b) of this Act.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 103. CERTIFICATION PROTOCOL AND PEER-TO-PEER AUDIT.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) CERTIFICATION REQUIREMENT.-- No entity shall exercise the rights, receive
the benefits, or bear the obligations of a Qualified Federated Cooperative or
Qualified Federated Network under this Act unless it has achieved and maintains
current certification pursuant to this Section. Certification shall be a
continuing requirement, not a one-time determination, and shall be subject to
ongoing verification through the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism established in
subsection (c) of this Section.

(b) INITIAL CERTIFICATION -- OFFICE OF FEDERATED STEWARDSHIP PHASE.--

    (1) APPLICATION.-- During the period preceding the network maturity threshold
    established under Section 107(f) of this Act, an entity seeking certification
    as a Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network shall
    submit to the Office of Federated Stewardship an application comprising:

        (A) the entity's governing bylaws, federated charter, and operational
        protocols, demonstrating compliance with each of the eight Ostrom
        Standards of Stewardship as required by Section 102 of this Title;

        (B) a technical compliance certification, executed by a qualified
        technical reviewer approved by the Office of Federated Stewardship,
        confirming that the entity's digital infrastructure meets the Federated
        Mesh Open Standard requirements of Section 701 of this Act and the
        cryptographic integrity requirements of Section 702 of this Act;

        (C) a description of the entity's defined boundaries, membership
        composition, and common-pool resources pursuant to Standard 1 of Section
        102(b) of this Act;

        (D) a description of the mandatory baseline cooperative memberships the
        entity provides or has arranged to provide through federated
        resource-sharing agreements with neighboring Qualified Federated
        Networks, demonstrating capacity to deliver the Guaranteed Provision
        Standard to all Commons Members within its scope; and

        (E) for entities seeking certification as a Qualified Federated Network,
        a list of constituent Qualified Federated Cooperatives, each of which
        must hold or simultaneously achieve individual certification as a
        Qualified Federated Cooperative.

    (2) REVIEW PERIOD.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall complete its
    review of a certification application within ninety days of receipt of a
    complete application. An application shall be deemed complete upon the
    Office's written acknowledgment of receipt. If the Office fails to complete
    its review within ninety days, the application shall be deemed provisionally
    approved and the entity shall be entitled to exercise the rights of a
    certified Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network
    pending final determination, subject to the condition that any deficiencies
    identified in a subsequent determination shall be remediated within the cure
    period established under subsection (c)(2)(A) of this Section.

    (3) CERTIFICATION DETERMINATION.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall
    certify an applicant upon a finding that the application demonstrates
    compliance with all requirements of this Act. The Office shall deny
    certification only upon a specific written finding identifying each
    requirement with which the applicant has failed to demonstrate compliance,
    and shall provide the applicant with a sixty-day cure period during which the
    applicant may remedy identified deficiencies and resubmit without payment of
    any additional fee. Denial after the cure period shall be subject to appeal
    pursuant to subsection (f) of this Section.

    (4) REGISTRATION ON NATIONAL RESILIENCE LEDGER.-- Upon certification, the
    Office of Federated Stewardship shall record the entity's certified status on
    the National Resilience Ledger within five business days, triggering the
    automated rights and obligations associated with certified status under this
    Act.

    (5) FEES.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall not charge fees for
    initial certification applications submitted by entities with fewer than five
    hundred members or by entities located in geographic areas designated as
    underserved pursuant to Section 105(b) of this Act. For all other entities,
    fees shall be set at a level sufficient to recover the Office's
    administrative costs and shall not exceed the amount necessary for that
    purpose.

(c) ONGOING CERTIFICATION -- PEER-TO-PEER AUDIT MECHANISM.--

    (1) CONTINUOUS MONITORING.-- Following initial certification, the ongoing
    certification status of every Qualified Federated Cooperative and Qualified
    Federated Network shall be maintained and verified through the Peer-to-Peer
    Audit mechanism, which shall operate as follows:

        (A) SELF-REPORTING.-- Each certified entity shall continuously publish
        its resource metabolism data -- including energy production and
        consumption, food production and distribution, land use metrics, Commons
        Credit flows, governance participation rates, and Ostrom Standards
        compliance indicators -- to the National Resilience Ledger in the
        standardized format established by the technical standards governance
        body under Title VII of this Act.

        (B) PEER ASSIGNMENT.-- The Federated Mesh shall algorithmically assign
        to each certified entity a rotating panel of three or more auditing
        peers, selected from geographically and functionally diverse certified
        entities within the Federated Network, with the assignment rotation
        occurring on a schedule established under Title VII to prevent the
        formation of persistent auditing relationships that could give rise to
        collusion or capture.

        (C) PEER VERIFICATION.-- Each assigned auditing peer shall independently
        verify the audited entity's self-reported data against:

            (i) physical outputs measurable through the Federated Mesh Open
            Standard, including energy meter readings, agricultural yield sensors,
            water system telemetry, and Commons Credit transaction records;

            (ii) the audited entity's historical data patterns on the National
            Resilience Ledger; and

            (iii) data reported by neighboring entities whose resource flows
            intersect with those of the audited entity.

        (D) ALGORITHMIC CROSS-VALIDATION.-- The Federated Mesh shall
        independently cross-validate self-reported data against physical outputs,
        flagging for human review any discrepancy exceeding the tolerance
        thresholds established under Title VII of this Act.

        (E) CONSENSUS DETERMINATION.-- A Compliance Flag shall be issued against
        a certified entity when two or more of its assigned auditing peers
        independently report a discrepancy between the entity's self-reported
        data and verifiable physical outputs, or when the algorithmic
        cross-validation identifies a discrepancy and at least one auditing peer
        confirms it. A single peer report, unconfirmed by either a second peer
        or algorithmic cross-validation, shall not constitute a Compliance Flag
        but shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger as a notation
        pending subsequent review.

    (2) GRADUATED RESPONSE PROCEDURES.-- Upon issuance of a Compliance Flag
    against a certified entity, the following graduated response procedures shall
    apply:

        (A) LEVEL 1 -- NOTICE AND CURE.-- For a first Compliance Flag, or for a
        Compliance Flag involving a discrepancy below the materiality threshold
        established under Title VII of this Act, the certified entity shall
        receive written notice of the Flag, a specific description of the
        identified discrepancy, and a ninety-day cure period during which the
        entity may remediate the discrepancy and demonstrate compliance to its
        auditing peers. A Level 1 Flag that is fully remediated within the cure
        period shall be recorded as resolved on the National Resilience Ledger
        and shall not affect the entity's certification status.

        (B) LEVEL 2 -- ENHANCED MONITORING.-- For a second Compliance Flag
        within a twenty-four-month period, or for a first Compliance Flag
        involving a discrepancy at or above the materiality threshold, the
        certified entity shall be placed under Enhanced Monitoring, comprising:
        an expanded auditing peer panel of not fewer than five peers; monthly
        rather than continuous self-reporting verification; and a mandatory
        governance review conducted through the Human-in-the-Loop Layer pursuant
        to Section 803 of this Act within sixty days of the Flag's issuance.
        Enhanced Monitoring status shall remain in effect for not less than
        twelve months following full remediation of the underlying discrepancy.

        (C) LEVEL 3 -- PROVISIONAL DECERTIFICATION.-- For a third Compliance
        Flag within a thirty-six-month period, or for a Compliance Flag
        indicating a pattern of deliberate misreporting, the certified entity
        shall be subject to Provisional Decertification, comprising: suspension
        of the entity's ability to issue Commons Credits or receive Stewardship
        Credits under Title VI of this Act; suspension of the entity's access to
        the Intellectual Property Commons under Title V of this Act; transfer of
        the entity's auditing peer assignment to a special panel constituted by
        the IP Commons Governance Council and the technical standards governance
        body; and mandatory Human-in-the-Loop review within thirty days.
        Provisional Decertification shall not affect the entity's Commons
        Members' individual Federated Commons Membership or Guaranteed Provision
        Standard entitlements, which shall be maintained through federated
        resource-sharing arrangements with neighboring Qualified Federated
        Networks during the period of Provisional Decertification.

        (D) LEVEL 4 -- DECERTIFICATION AND PROTOCOL DECOUPLING.-- Where a
        Provisional Decertification is not resolved within one hundred eighty
        days, or where a Compliance Flag indicates that a certified entity has
        been captured by a hostile actor, is engaged in deliberate enclosure of
        commons assets, or is systematically violating the rights of its Commons
        Members, the entity shall be subject to full Decertification and Protocol
        Decoupling, comprising: removal of the entity's certified status from the
        National Resilience Ledger; disconnection of the entity's devices from
        the Federated Mesh through the Entropy Lock mechanism established under
        Section 804 of Title VIII of this Act; transfer of any land held by the
        entity in Community Land Trust to a neighboring Qualified Federated
        Network designated by the Human-in-the-Loop Layer to ensure continued
        provision of the Guaranteed Provision Standard to affected Commons
        Members; and referral of any evidence of criminal conduct to the
        appropriate law enforcement authority. Full Decertification shall be
        subject to appeal pursuant to subsection (f) of this Section on an
        expedited basis.

    (3) PROTECTION OF COMMONS MEMBERS DURING SANCTIONS.-- In all graduated
    response procedures under this subsection, the continuity of the Guaranteed
    Provision Standard for individual Commons Members shall be the paramount
    consideration. No sanction imposed on a Qualified Federated Cooperative or
    Qualified Federated Network shall result in the loss, suspension, or
    diminution of any individual Commons Member's Guaranteed Provision Standard
    entitlements. The Office of Federated Stewardship, during the OFS Phase, and
    the regional federation governance layer, following the network maturity
    threshold, shall maintain a Commons Member Protection Fund sufficient to
    ensure provision continuity for Commons Members of any entity subject to
    Level 3 or Level 4 sanctions.

(d) HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP REVIEW OF AUTOMATED DETERMINATIONS.--

    (1) AVAILABILITY.-- Any certified entity that receives a Compliance Flag
    generated through the automated Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism may request
    Human-in-the-Loop review of the Flag within thirty days of its issuance. The
    request shall suspend the automatic progression of graduated response
    procedures at the current level pending completion of the review.

    (2) CIRCUIT BREAKER.-- Upon request for Human-in-the-Loop review, a
    seventy-two-hour Circuit Breaker period shall immediately take effect, during
    which no automated sanction may be imposed or escalated. The Circuit Breaker
    period shall be followed by the full Human-in-the-Loop review process
    established under Section 803 of this Act.

    (3) GROUNDS FOR REVIEW.-- Human-in-the-Loop review of a Compliance Flag may
    be granted on any of the following grounds:

        (A) the discrepancy identified by the automated mechanism was caused by
        sensor failure, connectivity disruption, natural disaster, or other
        circumstance beyond the entity's control;

        (B) the entity's self-reported data was accurate and the automated
        mechanism erred in its cross-validation;

        (C) the discrepancy was identified and remediation was underway prior to
        issuance of the Compliance Flag; or

        (D) the Compliance Flag reflects a genuine discrepancy but the automatic
        graduated response is disproportionate to the severity of the discrepancy
        in context.

    (4) OUTCOME.-- Following Human-in-the-Loop review, the reviewing body may:
    confirm the Compliance Flag and the applicable graduated response; modify the
    graduated response to a lower level upon finding that the circumstances
    warrant; dismiss the Compliance Flag upon finding that the automated mechanism
    erred; or suspend the graduated response for a defined period upon finding
    that remediation is genuinely underway. All Human-in-the-Loop review outcomes
    shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger.

(e) EXISTING COOPERATIVE AND CLT CERTIFICATION PATHWAYS.--

    (1) EXPEDITED PATHWAY FOR EXISTING ORGANIZATIONS.-- A cooperative enterprise,
    community land trust, credit union, or solidarity economy network that was
    legally organized and actively operating prior to the date of enactment of
    this Act shall be eligible for certification through an expedited pathway
    that:

        (A) recognizes the entity's existing governance structures, membership
        records, and operational history as evidence of compliance with the
        Ostrom Standards of Stewardship to the extent that such structures,
        records, and history demonstrate the functional equivalent of each
        Standard, without requiring the entity to restructure its governance
        solely for the purpose of formal compliance;

        (B) requires the entity to adopt such amendments to its governing
        documents as are necessary to address any material gap between its
        existing governance and the requirements of Section 102 of this Act, with
        technical assistance provided by the Office of Federated Stewardship
        pursuant to Section 107(c)(4) of this Act;

        (C) provides a one-hundred-eighty-day transition period during which the
        entity may operate as a provisionally certified Qualified Federated
        Cooperative while completing any required governance amendments; and

        (D) waives the technical compliance certification requirement of
        subsection (b)(1)(B) of this Section for a period of three hundred
        sixty-five days from the date of provisional certification, during which
        the entity shall connect to the Federated Mesh and achieve full technical
        compliance, with Bootstrap Grant funding available for the costs of
        technical integration pursuant to Section 106 of this Act.

    The following existing federal recognitions shall be treated as satisfying
    the corresponding Ostrom Standards of Stewardship requirements, reducing the
    certification burden for entities holding them: USDA Rural Utilities Service
    electric or telecommunications cooperative borrower status shall be treated
    as satisfying Standard 1 (Defined Boundaries) and Standard 3 (Collective-
    Choice Arrangements) in their entirety, given the RUS lending program's
    existing requirements for member-owned, democratically governed utility
    structure; NCUA-chartered credit union status shall be treated as satisfying
    Standard 1 and Standard 3 in their entirety; USDA Capper-Volstead Act
    agricultural marketing cooperative status shall be treated as satisfying
    Standard 1, Standard 2 (Local Congruence), and Standard 3 in substantial
    part; and Treasury CDFI Fund certification shall be treated as satisfying
    Standard 4 (Peer Monitoring) financial reporting requirements in substantial
    part. No entity holding any of these existing federal recognitions shall be
    required to separately demonstrate compliance with the corresponding
    Standards; the OFS shall certify compliance with those Standards upon the
    entity's submission of evidence of its current federal recognition status.

    (2) FEDERATION QUALIFICATION PATHWAY.-- An existing federation of cooperative
    enterprises, community land trusts, or solidarity economy networks seeking
    recognition as a Qualified Federated Network shall be eligible for a
    Federation Qualification assessment that:

        (A) evaluates the existing federation's governance structures against the
        Ostrom Standards of Stewardship at the network level, with particular
        attention to Standard 8 -- Nested Governance -- and the federation's
        existing mechanisms for inter-cooperative resource coordination, dispute
        resolution, and collective decision-making;

        (B) identifies any gaps between existing federation governance and the
        requirements of this Act and provides a defined remediation pathway with
        technical assistance;

        (C) recognizes the federation's existing inter-cooperative agreements as
        the foundation for the federated governance charter required under Section
        101(a) of this Act, requiring amendment only to the extent necessary to
        achieve compliance; and

        (D) provides that constituent cooperatives of a qualifying federation may
        achieve individual QFC certification simultaneously with the federation's
        network certification, through a consolidated application process.

    (3) COMMONS FINANCIAL NODE REGISTRATION.-- A credit union or community
    development financial institution seeking registration as a Commons Financial
    Node pursuant to Section 4(3) of this Act shall submit a simplified
    registration to the Office of Federated Stewardship demonstrating: its
    cooperative or mission-aligned governance structure; its commitment to
    providing Commons Credit issuance, Bootstrap Grant distribution, and
    inter-network financial services within the Federated Network; and its
    technical capacity to connect to the National Resilience Ledger. Commons
    Financial Node registration shall not require full QFC certification but
    shall require compliance with the financial integrity standards established
    under Title VI of this Act.

(f) APPEALS.--

    (1) RIGHT OF APPEAL.-- Any entity whose certification application has been
    denied, whose certification has been suspended through Provisional
    Decertification, or whose certification has been revoked through full
    Decertification and Protocol Decoupling shall have the right to appeal the
    determination.

    (2) APPEAL BODY -- OFS PHASE.-- During the OFS Phase, appeals shall be heard
    by the Federated Accountability Board established under Section 1103 of this
    Act, composed of randomly selected certified Qualified Federated Network
    representatives, which shall not include any entity that served as an
    auditing peer in the proceeding being appealed.

    (3) APPEAL BODY -- POST-OFS PHASE.-- Following the network maturity threshold
    established under Section 107(f) of this Act, appeals shall be heard by a
    standing Appeals Panel constituted through the nested governance architecture
    of the Federated Network, with composition and procedures established by the
    network-level governance body under Title VIII of this Act.

    (4) STANDARD OF REVIEW.-- The appeal body shall review certification denials
    and decertification decisions de novo, without deference to the initial
    determination. The burden of demonstrating non-compliance shall rest with the
    party asserting non-compliance, not with the entity seeking certification.

    (5) EXPEDITED REVIEW FOR FULL DECERTIFICATION.-- Appeals of full
    Decertification and Protocol Decoupling decisions shall be processed on an
    expedited basis, with a preliminary hearing within fourteen days of the
    appeal's filing and a final determination within sixty days.

    (6) INTERIM RELIEF.-- The appeal body may grant interim relief suspending the
    effects of a Provisional Decertification or full Decertification pending
    final determination of the appeal, upon a showing that: the appeal raises
    substantial questions of fact or law; the harm to Commons Members from
    continued sanctions outweighs the harm to the Federated Network from their
    suspension; and the appealing entity is not engaged in conduct that poses an
    immediate threat to the physical safety of Commons Members or the integrity
    of the National Resilience Ledger.


