SEC. 104. DECOUPLING OF CERTIFICATION AUTHORITY FROM EXECUTIVE BRANCH.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PURPOSE.-- The purpose of this Section is to ensure that the certification,
decertification, and ongoing governance of Qualified Federated Networks and
Qualified Federated Cooperatives under this Act cannot be used as instruments of
political control by any administration of the Executive Branch, and that the
long-term integrity and autonomy of the Federated Network rests upon the
distributed governance of the network itself rather than upon the continued good
faith of any governmental authority.

(b) LIMITATIONS ON EXECUTIVE AUTHORITY DURING OFS PHASE.--

    (1) SCOPE OF EXECUTIVE AUTHORITY.-- During the period preceding the network
    maturity threshold established under Section 107(f) of this Act, the
    authority of the Executive Branch over the certification and governance of
    Qualified Federated Networks and Qualified Federated Cooperatives is strictly
    limited to the administrative functions expressly assigned to the Office of
    Federated Stewardship under Section 107 of this Act. No executive officer,
    department, agency, or instrumentality of the United States shall exercise
    any authority over the internal governance, resource allocation, membership
    decisions, or operational protocols of any certified Qualified Federated
    Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network beyond what is expressly
    authorized by this Act.

    (2) PROHIBITION ON DISCRETIONARY CERTIFICATION DENIAL.-- The Office of
    Federated Stewardship shall have no discretion to deny certification to any
    applicant that demonstrates compliance with the requirements of this Act.
    Certification is a ministerial determination -- a finding of compliance with
    objective statutory criteria -- and not a discretionary grant of governmental
    favor. No executive officer shall direct, pressure, or otherwise influence
    the Office of Federated Stewardship to deny, delay, or condition
    certification on the basis of the political positions, advocacy activities,
    membership composition, or resource allocation decisions of the applicant.

    (3) PROHIBITION ON SELECTIVE ENFORCEMENT.-- The graduated response procedures
    of Section 103(c) of this Act shall be applied uniformly to all certified
    entities on the basis of objective compliance data generated through the
    Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism. No executive officer shall direct the
    initiation, acceleration, or suspension of graduated response procedures
    against any certified entity on the basis of factors other than the entity's
    demonstrated compliance with the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship and the
    technical requirements of this Act.

    (4) PROHIBITION ON DEFUNDING AS CONTROL MECHANISM.-- The authorization of
    appropriations under Section 1106 of this Act shall not be construed to
    grant the Executive Branch authority to withhold, redirect, or condition
    Bootstrap Grants, Stewardship Credits, or other financial benefits
    established under this Act as a mechanism for influencing the governance or
    operational decisions of any Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified
    Federated Network. Financial benefits established under this Act are
    entitlements that flow automatically upon certification and compliance, not
    discretionary grants subject to executive conditions.

    (5) NON-DELEGATION OF GOVERNANCE AUTHORITY.-- The Executive Branch shall not
    delegate, contract, or otherwise transfer to any private party the authority
    to make certification determinations, impose graduated response sanctions, or
    exercise any other governance function over the Federated Network assigned to
    the Office of Federated Stewardship under this Act.

(c) AUTOMATED DISBURSEMENT PROTECTION.--

    (1) GENERAL RULE.-- The issuance of Stewardship Credits upon CLT land
    acquisition pursuant to Section 306 of this Act, the distribution of
    Bootstrap Grants pursuant to Section 106 of this Act, and the automated
    Commons Credit transactions conducted through the National Resilience Ledger
    pursuant to Title VI of this Act are non-discretionary functions triggered
    automatically by the occurrence of defined conditions verifiable through the
    Federated Mesh. No executive officer, department, or agency shall have
    authority to:

        (A) delay, suspend, redirect, or cancel automated disbursements that
        have been triggered by verified conditions under this Act;

        (B) impose conditions on automated disbursements beyond those expressly
        established in this Act; or

        (C) require manual review or approval of automated disbursements as a
        precondition to their execution, except in cases of documented fraud or
        system integrity failure reported through the Peer-to-Peer Audit
        mechanism.

    (2) TECHNICAL ARCHITECTURE REQUIREMENT.-- The National Resilience Ledger
    shall be designed and maintained such that the automated disbursement
    functions described in paragraph (1) of this subsection are technically
    insulated from executive override. Specifically:

        (A) automated disbursement functions shall be executed through smart
        contract protocols on the Federated Mesh that are triggered by verified
        on-ledger conditions without requiring any off-ledger authorization;

        (B) the smart contract code governing automated disbursements shall be
        open-source, publicly auditable, and modifiable only through the
        governance process established under Title VII of this Act, which shall
        require supermajority approval by the IP Commons Governance Council and
        ratification by the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism before any modification
        takes effect; and

        (C) no administrative account, master key, or override mechanism shall
        exist that would permit any single actor -- governmental or private --
        to suspend or redirect automated disbursements unilaterally.

(d) TRANSITION TO SELF-SOVEREIGN CERTIFICATION.--

    (1) NETWORK MATURITY THRESHOLD.-- Upon the occurrence of the network maturity
    threshold established under Section 107(f) of this Act, the authority to
    certify new Qualified Federated Cooperatives and Qualified Federated Networks
    shall transfer automatically and irrevocably from the Office of Federated
    Stewardship to the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism of the Federated Network
    itself. Following this transfer:

        (A) the certification of new entities shall be conducted entirely through
        the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism, without involvement of the Office of
        Federated Stewardship or any other governmental body;

        (B) the ongoing compliance monitoring of existing certified entities
        shall continue through the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism as established
        under Section 103(c) of this Act, without governmental involvement except
        as provided in subsection (d)(3) of this Section;

        (C) the Office of Federated Stewardship shall retain only the ministerial
        functions described in Section 107(e) of this Act, and shall exercise no
        substantive authority over the Federated Network; and

        (D) the Federated Network shall assume full responsibility for the
        integrity of its own certification architecture, subject to the judicial
        review provisions of subsection (e) of this Section.

    (2) IRREVOCABILITY OF TRANSFER.-- The transfer of certification authority to
    the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism upon the network maturity threshold is
    irrevocable by executive action. No executive order, agency rule, or
    administrative determination shall have the effect of returning certification
    authority to the Office of Federated Stewardship or any other governmental
    body following the transfer. Any attempt to reassert governmental
    certification authority following the transfer shall be subject to immediate
    injunctive relief in any federal court of competent jurisdiction, without
    requirement of bond, upon the application of any certified Qualified
    Federated Network or Commons Member.

    (3) RESIDUAL GOVERNMENTAL ROLE.-- Following the transfer of certification
    authority, the role of the federal government with respect to the Federated
    Network shall be limited to:

         (A) maintaining the legal framework established by this Act and enacting
        such amendments as may be necessary to address unforeseen circumstances,
        through the normal legislative process;

        (B) providing the financial capitalization mechanisms established under
        Titles III and VI of this Act, including Stewardship Credit issuance and
        Bootstrap Grant distribution, which shall continue to operate on an
        automated basis as provided in subsection (c) of this Section;

        (C) maintaining the military-civilian strategic sync provisions of Title
        IX of this Act; and

        (D) representing the interests of the Federated Network in international
        forums and negotiations, in consultation with the Federated Network
        governance bodies.

(e) JUDICIAL REVIEW AND CONSTITUTIONAL PROTECTION.--

    (1) CONSTITUTIONAL SAFE HARBOR.-- Any action taken in good faith by a
    federal officer or employee to implement the transfer of certification
    authority under this Section, including actions that result in the reduction
    of executive authority over the Federated Network, shall not give rise to
    civil or criminal liability under any federal or state law.

    (2) JUDICIAL REVIEW OF EXECUTIVE OVERREACH.-- Any attempt by the Executive
    Branch to exercise authority over the Federated Network in excess of the
    limitations established by this Section shall be subject to judicial review
    in any federal district court of competent jurisdiction upon the application
    of:

        (A) any certified Qualified Federated Network or Qualified Federated
        Cooperative;

        (B) any Commons Member whose Guaranteed Provision Standard entitlements
        are affected by the executive action; or

        (C) any member of Congress acting pursuant to their oversight authority.

    (3) STANDARD OF REVIEW.-- In any proceeding challenging executive action
    under this Section, the court shall apply de novo review without deference to
    the executive's interpretation of its own authority under this Act. The
    burden of demonstrating that the challenged action falls within the scope of
    authority expressly conferred by this Act shall rest with the Executive
    Branch.

    (4) PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION STANDARD.-- In any proceeding seeking preliminary
    injunctive relief against executive overreach under this Section, the court
    shall apply a modified preliminary injunction standard under which:

        (A) a showing that the challenged executive action exceeds the authority
        expressly conferred by this Act shall constitute a sufficient showing of
        likelihood of success on the merits;

        (B) any disruption to the Guaranteed Provision Standard of Commons
        Members caused by the challenged executive action shall constitute
        irreparable harm per se; and

         (C) the balance of equities shall account for the irreparable harm to
    Commons Members established under subparagraph (B) of this paragraph.

   (5) PUBLIC INTEREST.-- For the purposes of any proceeding under this
    Section, the continuity of Commons Members' Guaranteed Provision Standard
    entitlements shall be considered a substantial component of the public
    interest analysis.


