SEC. 105. GEOGRAPHIC COVERAGE OBLIGATIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PURPOSE.-- The purpose of this Section is to ensure that the Federated
Network established by this Act extends its geographic reach to all communities
within the United States, with particular attention to rural, remote,
economically distressed, and historically underserved communities, and that the
benefits of Federated Commons Membership and the Guaranteed Provision Standard
are not concentrated in urban and technically sophisticated areas while leaving
other communities without access. The Federated Network shall be understood as a
national infrastructure obligation, not a voluntary amenity available only to
communities with existing organizational capacity.

(b) DESIGNATION OF UNDERSERVED AREAS.--

    (1) INITIAL DESIGNATION.-- Within one hundred eighty days of the date of
    enactment of this Act, the Office of Federated Stewardship shall publish an
    initial map of Underserved Areas, defined as geographic areas in which:

        (A) no Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network is
        currently operating or seeking certification;

        (B) the nearest existing community land trust, worker cooperative, food
        cooperative, or solidarity economy network is located more than fifty
        miles away or is separated from the area by geographic barriers that
        substantially impede access;

        (C) the area contains a population with median household income below
        eighty percent of the applicable area median income as determined by the
        Department of Housing and Urban Development; or

        (D) the area has been designated as a persistent poverty county, a food
        desert, a medically underserved area, or a digital divide community by
        any federal agency.

    (2) CRITERIA OVERLAP.-- An area meeting any one of the criteria in paragraph
    (1) of this subsection shall qualify for Underserved Area designation. An
    area meeting two or more criteria shall be designated a Priority Underserved
    Area and shall receive preferential treatment in Bootstrap Grant allocation
    pursuant to Section 106(g) of this Act.

    (3) UPDATING.-- The Underserved Area map shall be updated annually to reflect
    changes in network coverage, demographic conditions, and federal designations.
    An area shall be removed from Underserved Area designation only upon
    demonstration that a certified Qualified Federated Network operating within
    the area is providing the full Guaranteed Provision Standard to all Commons
    Members within its scope.

    (4) PUBLIC ACCESSIBILITY.-- The Underserved Area map shall be published on
    the National Resilience Ledger and on a publicly accessible governmental
    website, in formats accessible to persons with disabilities and in the most
    commonly spoken languages of the designated areas.

(c) COVERAGE EXPANSION OBLIGATIONS.--

    (1) NATIONAL COVERAGE TARGET.-- It is the policy of the United States that
    Federated Commons Membership and the Guaranteed Provision Standard shall be
    accessible to every resident of the United States within ten years of the
    date of enactment of this Act. The Office of Federated Stewardship shall
    establish interim coverage targets at two-year intervals and shall report
    annually to Congress on progress toward those targets.

    (2) AFFIRMATIVE OUTREACH OBLIGATION.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship
    shall conduct affirmative outreach in all designated Underserved Areas,
    including:

        (A) direct engagement with existing community organizations, tribal
        governments, local governments, religious institutions, and civic
        associations to identify potential cooperative formation candidates and
        provide information about the certification process and available
        Bootstrap Grants;

        (B) provision of multilingual outreach materials in accessible formats
        appropriate to the literacy levels and communication norms of the
        communities being served;

        (C) establishment of mobile technical assistance teams capable of
        providing in-person formation assistance in communities that lack
        reliable internet connectivity or local organizational infrastructure;
        and

        (D) coordination with the Departments of Agriculture, Housing and Urban
        Development, Health and Human Services, and Energy to align existing
        federal rural development, affordable housing, food security, and energy
        access programs with the cooperative formation pathways established by
        this Act.

    (3) NETWORK EXPANSION OBLIGATION.-- Every certified Qualified Federated
    Network that is geographically adjacent to a designated Underserved Area
    shall:

        (A) include in its annual self-reporting to the National Resilience
        Ledger a description of its efforts to extend network coverage into
        adjacent Underserved Areas;

        (B) make its technical assistance capacity, governance expertise, and
        Federated Mesh infrastructure available to nascent cooperative formation
        efforts in adjacent Underserved Areas at no cost; and

        (C) enter into federated resource-sharing agreements to provide the
        Guaranteed Provision Standard to residents of adjacent Underserved Areas
        who seek Federated Commons Membership prior to the establishment of a
        locally certified Qualified Federated Network in their area.

    (4) TRIBAL COMMUNITIES.-- The coverage expansion obligations of this Section
    shall be implemented with particular care and cultural sensitivity in Native
    American, Alaska Native, and Native Hawaiian communities, consistent with the
    federal trust responsibility and the principles of tribal self-determination.
    The Office of Federated Stewardship shall:

        (A) conduct government-to-government consultation with tribal governments
        prior to conducting outreach in tribal communities;

        (B) recognize tribal governance structures as presumptively satisfying
        the collective-choice and jurisdictional autonomy requirements of the
        Ostrom Standards of Stewardship, subject only to such modifications as
        are necessary to achieve technical compatibility with the Federated Mesh;

        (C) provide enhanced Bootstrap Grant allocations for tribal cooperative
        formation efforts pursuant to Section 106(d) of this Act; and

        (D) ensure that the Witnessed Physical Registration pathway established
        under Section 504(b)(3) of this Act is fully operational and accessible
        in all tribal communities prior to extending IP Commons registration
        requirements to those communities.

(d) CONNECTIVITY INFRASTRUCTURE OBLIGATIONS.--

    (1) FINDING.-- Congress finds that meaningful participation in the Federated
    Network requires a baseline level of digital connectivity, and that the
    absence of such connectivity in many Underserved Areas constitutes a barrier
    to Federated Commons Membership that must be affirmatively addressed as a
    condition of the network's fulfillment of its national coverage obligations.

    (2) COORDINATION WITH EXISTING PROGRAMS.-- The Office of Federated
    Stewardship shall coordinate with the Federal Communications Commission, the
    Department of Agriculture's ReConnect Program, the National
    Telecommunications and Information Administration, and all other federal
    agencies administering broadband deployment or digital equity programs to
    ensure that:

        (A) Underserved Areas designated pursuant to subsection (b) of this
        Section are prioritized in all federal broadband deployment and digital
        equity funding decisions;

        (B) broadband infrastructure deployed with federal funding in Underserved
        Areas is designed to support Federated Mesh Open Standard compatibility
        pursuant to Section 701 of this Act; and

        (C) digital literacy programs funded through federal digital equity
        initiatives include training in Federated Mesh participation, cooperative
        governance, and Federated Commons Membership registration.

    (3) MESH-NATIVE CONNECTIVITY.-- Where conventional broadband infrastructure
    is not available or is not projected to become available within three years
    in a designated Underserved Area, the Office of Federated Stewardship shall
    fund the deployment of Federated Mesh-native connectivity infrastructure --
    including low-power mesh radio networks, community-owned wireless
    infrastructure, and satellite-based Federated Mesh access points --
    sufficient to enable:

        (A) Witnessed Physical Registration of creative works and traditional
        knowledge pursuant to Section 504(b)(3) of this Act;

        (B) participation in the collective-choice governance processes of a
        Qualified Federated Cooperative through digital means;

        (C) access to the National Resilience Ledger for Commons Membership
        Record verification and Commons Credit transactions; and

        (D) basic Asynchronous Resource Coordination signaling between the
        community and neighboring Qualified Federated Networks.

    (4) ANALOG REDUNDANCY.-- In recognition that digital connectivity cannot be
    guaranteed in all circumstances and that the Guaranteed Provision Standard
    must be maintained even during connectivity disruptions, every Qualified
    Federated Network operating in or adjacent to a designated Underserved Area
    shall maintain analog redundancy systems pursuant to Section 706 of this Act,
    including physical ledger records of land boundaries and core resource
    rights, paper-based Commons Membership credential systems, and non-digital
    resource coordination protocols capable of maintaining basic provision
    continuity for a period of not less than ninety days without Federated Mesh
    connectivity.

(e) RURAL AND AGRICULTURAL COMMUNITY PROVISIONS.--

    (1) AGRICULTURAL COOPERATIVE INTEGRATION.-- The Office of Federated
    Stewardship shall establish a specific certification pathway for existing
    agricultural cooperatives, including farmer-owned marketing cooperatives,
    rural electric cooperatives, and agricultural credit associations, that
    recognizes the long history and established governance practices of the
    agricultural cooperative sector and provides for the integration of these
    cooperatives into the Federated Network with minimal administrative burden.

    (2) COORDINATION WITH USDA.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall
    enter into a memorandum of understanding with the Department of Agriculture
    within one hundred eighty days of the date of enactment of this Act to:

        (A) align the certification requirements of this Act with existing USDA
        cooperative development programs, including the Rural Cooperative
        Development Grant (RCDG) program, the Socially-Disadvantaged Groups
        Grant (SDGG) program, the Value-Added Producer Grant (VAPG) program, the
        Rural Economic Development Loan and Grant (REDLG) program administered
        through rural electric cooperative intermediaries, and the Rural Energy
        for America Program (REAP), ensuring that existing USDA Cooperative
        Development Center grantees under the RCDG and SDGG programs are
        recognized as technical assistance providers within the OFS's Bootstrap
        Grant framework and are eligible for Formation Grant and Transition Grant
        disbursements to expand their services to the QFC certification context;

        (B) ensure that USDA cooperative development assistance is directed
        toward helping existing agricultural cooperatives achieve QFC
        certification under this Act, with the RCDG program's $200,000 per-
        Center ceiling treated as a floor below the Bootstrap Grant amounts
        available for comparable work under Section 106 of this Act, so that
        transition to QFC certification does not reduce the financial support
        available to existing USDA Cooperative Development Centers; and

        (C) coordinate the federal surplus agricultural land transfer provisions
        of Section 302 of this Act with USDA's existing farmland protection and
        agricultural conservation programs, including the Agricultural
        Conservation Easement Program and the Farm and Ranch Lands Protection
        Program, ensuring that surplus federal agricultural land transfers to CLT
        stewardship are structured to maximize ecological health and long-term
        food production capacity.

    (3) FOOD COMMONS PRIORITY.-- In rural and agricultural communities, the food
    cooperative membership component of the Guaranteed Provision Standard shall
    be recognized as the foundational commons institution around which other
    cooperative memberships are organized, reflecting the centrality of food
    production and land stewardship to rural community identity and resilience.

(f) REPORTING AND ACCOUNTABILITY.--

    (1) ANNUAL COVERAGE REPORT.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall
    submit to Congress an annual report on geographic coverage that includes:

        (A) the current Underserved Area map with a description of changes from
        the prior year;

        (B) the number of new Qualified Federated Cooperatives and Qualified
        Federated Networks certified in each state and territory during the
        reporting year, disaggregated by urban, suburban, rural, and tribal
        designation;

        (C) the estimated number of residents in each state and territory who
        have achieved Federated Commons Membership during the reporting year and
        the estimated number who remain without access to a certified Qualified
        Federated Network;

        (D) a description of outreach activities conducted in designated
        Underserved Areas during the reporting year and an assessment of their
        effectiveness;

        (E) an assessment of progress toward the national coverage targets
        established under subsection (c)(1) of this Section; and

        (F) recommendations for legislative or administrative action to
        accelerate coverage expansion in areas where progress is lagging.

    (2) COVERAGE GAP REMEDIATION.-- Where the annual coverage report identifies
    a designated Underserved Area in which no certified Qualified Federated
    Network has been established and no certification application is pending
    after five years from the date of enactment of this Act, the Office of
    Federated Stewardship shall:

        (A) convene a community assembly in the affected area, in coordination
        with local governments, tribal governments, and community organizations,
        to assess barriers to cooperative formation and identify potential
        formation candidates;

        (B) provide enhanced technical assistance and Bootstrap Grant funding
        pursuant to Section 106(d) of this Act specifically targeted at the
        identified barriers; and

        (C) report to Congress within one year of the community assembly on the
        specific actions taken and the projected timeline for establishment of a
        certified Qualified Federated Network in the area.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 106. BOOTSTRAP GRANT PROGRAM.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PURPOSE.-- The purpose of this Section is to provide the initial financial
capitalization necessary for the formation of new Qualified Federated
Cooperatives and Qualified Federated Networks, the transition of existing
cooperative enterprises and community land trusts into certified network
participation, the technical integration of existing organizations into the
Federated Mesh, and the extension of network coverage into designated Underserved
Areas. Bootstrap Grants are not discretionary subsidies but investments in the
commons infrastructure whose long-term productive capacity will generate returns
to the national economy that far exceed their initial cost. No Bootstrap Grant
recipient shall be required to repay a Bootstrap Grant, but all recipients shall
be subject to the use restrictions and reporting requirements of this Section.
The Bootstrap Grant Program builds upon and expands existing federal cooperative
support programs, including the USDA Rural Cooperative Development Grant (RCDG)
program and the USDA Socially-Disadvantaged Groups Grant (SDGG) program, which
together provide grants to Cooperative Development Centers for rural cooperative
formation and technical assistance. The Bootstrap Grant amounts established in
this Section are calibrated to exceed the RCDG program's existing ceiling of
$200,000 per Cooperative Development Center, reflecting the national scope and
additional technical infrastructure requirements of QFN certification. The
Department of Labor's Employee Ownership Initiative and the WORK Act programs
serve a complementary function specifically for worker cooperative formation and
conversion; the Office of Federated Stewardship shall coordinate with the
Department of Labor to ensure Bootstrap Grants supplement rather than duplicate
those programs, filling the gap for non-rural cooperative formation,
non-worker-ownership cooperative domains, and the technical integration
requirements that existing federal programs do not address. The 2014 Farm Bill
Interagency Working Group on Cooperative Development provides the existing
federal coordination structure on which the OFS shall build in administering
this Section; the OFS Director shall chair or co-chair that working group during
the OFS Phase, and shall seek to expand its membership to include the Federal
Communications Commission and the Department of Energy.

(b) GRANT STREAMS.-- The Bootstrap Grant Program shall comprise the following
distinct grant streams, each administered by the Office of Federated Stewardship
pursuant to the eligibility criteria, award amounts, and use restrictions
established in this Section:

    (1) FORMATION GRANTS -- for the legal and administrative costs of forming a
    new Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network where none
    previously existed;

    (2) TRANSITION GRANTS -- for the costs incurred by existing cooperative
    enterprises, community land trusts, credit unions, and solidarity economy
    networks in achieving QFC or QFN certification under this Act;

    (3) TECHNICAL INTEGRATION GRANTS -- for the costs of connecting existing or
    newly formed organizations to the Federated Mesh, including hardware
    procurement, software integration, and technical training;

    (4) COVERAGE EXTENSION GRANTS -- for the costs of extending Federated
    Network coverage into designated Underserved Areas, available to both nascent
    cooperative formation efforts in those areas and to existing Qualified
    Federated Networks undertaking expansion into adjacent Underserved Areas;

    (5) CREATOR TRANSITION GRANTS -- for individuals currently dependent on
    intellectual property income who are transitioning to the commons economy,
    providing bridge support during the transition period established under Title
    V of this Act; and

    (6) RESILIENCE DEMONSTRATION GRANTS -- for the ten to twenty communities
    designated as Federated Resilience Demonstration Zones pursuant to Section
    1003 of this Act, providing enhanced capitalization to support the
    comprehensive implementation of all commons infrastructure components in a
    defined geographic area within an accelerated timeframe.

(c) ELIGIBILITY.--

    (1) FORMATION GRANTS.-- An applicant shall be eligible for a Formation Grant
    if it:

        (A) is a group of five or more natural persons or two or more existing
        organizations seeking to form a new Qualified Federated Cooperative or
        Qualified Federated Network;

        (B) has adopted or committed in writing to adopt governing documents
        consistent with the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship as required by
        Section 102 of this Act;

        (C) has identified a defined geographic area or functional scope within
        which it intends to operate; and

        (D) has not previously received a Formation Grant for the same
        cooperative formation effort.

    (2) TRANSITION GRANTS.-- An applicant shall be eligible for a Transition
    Grant if it:

        (A) is a legally organized cooperative enterprise, community land trust,
        credit union, time bank, solidarity economy network, or similar
        organization that was actively operating prior to the date of enactment
        of this Act;

        (B) has submitted or committed in writing to submit a certification
        application to the Office of Federated Stewardship within one year of
        receiving the grant; and

        (C) has identified specific governance amendments, technical integrations,
        or operational changes required to achieve certification and provided a
        reasonable cost estimate for those changes.

    (3) TECHNICAL INTEGRATION GRANTS.-- An applicant shall be eligible for a
    Technical Integration Grant if it:

        (A) holds current certification as a Qualified Federated Cooperative or
        Qualified Federated Network, or has received a Formation Grant or
        Transition Grant under this Section; and

        (B) has identified specific technical integration costs associated with
        connecting to the Federated Mesh, achieving Federated Mesh Open Standard
        compliance, or implementing the cryptographic integrity requirements of
        Section 702 of this Act.

    (4) COVERAGE EXTENSION GRANTS.-- An applicant shall be eligible for a
    Coverage Extension Grant if it:

        (A) is a nascent cooperative formation effort located in a designated
        Underserved Area, meeting the eligibility criteria of paragraph (1) of
        this subsection; or

        (B) is a certified Qualified Federated Network that is geographically
        adjacent to a designated Underserved Area and has committed in writing to
        extend network coverage and provide the Guaranteed Provision Standard to
        residents of that area within three years of receiving the grant.

    (5) CREATOR TRANSITION GRANTS.-- An applicant shall be eligible for a
    Creator Transition Grant if they:

        (A) are a natural person who has derived more than fifty percent of their
        annual income from intellectual property royalties, licensing fees, or
        related sources in at least two of the three years preceding the date of
        application;

        (B) have contributed or committed in writing to contribute their
        intellectual property to the Intellectual Property Commons pursuant to
        Title V of this Act within one year of receiving the grant; and

        (C) have achieved or are actively seeking Federated Commons Membership
        within a certified Qualified Federated Network.

    (6) RESILIENCE DEMONSTRATION GRANTS.-- Eligibility for Resilience
    Demonstration Grants shall be determined through the community designation
    process established under Section 1003 of this Act, and shall not be subject
    to the individual application process applicable to other grant streams under
    this Section.

(d) AWARD AMOUNTS.--

    (1) FORMATION GRANTS.-- Formation Grants shall be awarded in amounts
    sufficient to cover the reasonable legal, administrative, and organizational
    costs of cooperative formation, not to exceed:

        (A) fifty thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated Cooperative with
        fewer than one hundred anticipated members;

        (B) one hundred thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated Cooperative
        with one hundred or more anticipated members; and

        (C) two hundred fifty thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated Network
        comprising two or more Qualified Federated Cooperatives.

    (2) TRANSITION GRANTS.-- Transition Grants shall be awarded in amounts
    sufficient to cover the reasonable costs of governance amendment, legal
    restructuring, and operational adaptation required to achieve certification,
    not to exceed:

        (A) seventy-five thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated Cooperative
        with fewer than five hundred members;

        (B) one hundred fifty thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated
        Cooperative with five hundred or more members; and

        (C) five hundred thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated Network.

    (3) TECHNICAL INTEGRATION GRANTS.-- Technical Integration Grants shall be
    awarded in amounts sufficient to cover the reasonable costs of Federated Mesh
    connection, hardware procurement, software integration, and technical
    training, not to exceed:

        (A) twenty-five thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated Cooperative
        with fewer than one hundred members;

        (B) seventy-five thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated Cooperative
        with one hundred or more members; and

        (C) two hundred thousand dollars for a Qualified Federated Network.

    (4) COVERAGE EXTENSION GRANTS -- UNDERSERVED AREAS.-- Coverage Extension
    Grants awarded to cooperative formation efforts in designated Underserved
    Areas shall be awarded at one hundred fifty percent of the applicable
    Formation Grant amount. Coverage Extension Grants awarded to existing
    Qualified Federated Networks for expansion into adjacent Underserved Areas
    shall be awarded at one hundred fifty percent of the applicable Technical
    Integration Grant amount, plus an additional amount not to exceed two hundred
    fifty thousand dollars for community outreach, multilingual materials, and
    mobile technical assistance in the target area.

    (5) PRIORITY UNDERSERVED AREAS.-- All grant amounts applicable to activities
    in designated Priority Underserved Areas, as defined in Section 105(b)(2) of
    this Act, shall be awarded at two hundred percent of the applicable base
    amount.

    (6) TRIBAL COMMUNITIES.-- All grant amounts applicable to activities in
    Native American, Alaska Native, or Native Hawaiian communities shall be
    awarded at two hundred percent of the applicable base amount, in recognition
    of the particular barriers to cooperative formation created by the historical
    disruption of indigenous governance and economic systems.

    (7) CREATOR TRANSITION GRANTS.-- Creator Transition Grants shall be awarded
    as monthly stipends in amounts sufficient to replace the applicant's
    intellectual property income during the transition period, not to exceed:

        (A) three thousand dollars per month for a period not exceeding twenty-
        four months; or

        (B) the applicant's average monthly intellectual property income in the
        two years preceding the application, whichever is less.

    (8) COST OF LIVING ADJUSTMENT.-- All grant amounts established in this
    subsection shall be adjusted annually for inflation using the Consumer Price
    Index for All Urban Consumers published by the Bureau of Labor Statistics.

(e) USE RESTRICTIONS.--

    (1) AUTHORIZED USES.-- Bootstrap Grant funds shall be used solely for the
    purposes for which the grant was awarded, as specified in the grant
    application and the grant agreement executed between the recipient and the
    Office of Federated Stewardship.

    (2) PROHIBITED USES.-- Bootstrap Grant funds shall not be used for:

        (A) compensation to officers, directors, or managers of the recipient
        organization at rates exceeding the median compensation for comparable
        positions within certified Qualified Federated Networks as published
        annually by the Office of Federated Stewardship;

        (B) lobbying activities, as defined in the Lobbying Disclosure Act of
        1995;

        (C) the acquisition of land or physical assets that will not be held in
        commons stewardship consistent with the requirements of this Act;

        (D) the payment of existing debts or obligations of the recipient
        organization incurred prior to the date of the grant application, except
        where such debts are directly related to the cooperative formation or
        transition activities for which the grant is awarded; or

        (E) any purpose that would result in the private enrichment of any
        individual member, officer, or affiliate of the recipient organization
        beyond the Guaranteed Provision Standard.

    (3) COMMONS REINVESTMENT OBLIGATION.-- Any Bootstrap Grant funds not
    expended for authorized purposes within three years of the grant award shall
    be returned to the Bootstrap Grant Program fund and reallocated to Priority
    Underserved Areas pursuant to subsection (c)(4) of this Section.

(f) REPORTING REQUIREMENTS.--

    (1) ANNUAL REPORT.-- Each Bootstrap Grant recipient shall submit an annual
    report to the Office of Federated Stewardship describing:

        (A) the specific uses of grant funds during the reporting year, with
        documentation sufficient to verify compliance with the use restrictions
        of subsection (e) of this Section;

        (B) the progress made toward the cooperative formation, certification,
        technical integration, or coverage extension goals for which the grant
        was awarded;

        (C) the number of individuals who have achieved Federated Commons
        Membership as a direct result of the grant-funded activities; and

        (D) any obstacles encountered in achieving the grant's objectives and
        the steps taken or proposed to address them.

    (2) FINAL REPORT.-- Upon completion of the activities for which a Bootstrap
    Grant was awarded, the recipient shall submit a final report to the Office of
    Federated Stewardship demonstrating the outcomes achieved and the disposition
    of all grant funds.

    (3) PUBLIC AVAILABILITY.-- All annual and final reports submitted pursuant
    to this subsection shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger and
    made publicly available, subject to the redaction of any individually
    identifying personal information of natural persons.

(g) ALLOCATION PRIORITIES.--

    (1) GENERAL PRIORITY ORDER.-- In allocating Bootstrap Grant funds among
    eligible applicants, the Office of Federated Stewardship shall prioritize
    applications in the following order:

        (A) first, applications from designated Priority Underserved Areas;

        (B) second, applications from designated Underserved Areas that are not
        Priority Underserved Areas;

        (C) third, applications from Native American, Alaska Native, or Native
        Hawaiian communities;

        (D) fourth, applications from communities with existing cooperative
        infrastructure seeking Transition Grants or Technical Integration Grants;

        (E) fifth, applications from Federated Resilience Demonstration Zones
        pursuant to Section 1003 of this Act; and

        (F) sixth, all remaining eligible applications, allocated on a first-
        come, first-served basis subject to the availability of funds.

    (2) PROHIBITION ON POLITICAL CRITERIA.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship
    shall not consider the political positions, advocacy activities, voting
    patterns, or electoral history of any applicant community, organization, or
    individual in making Bootstrap Grant allocation decisions. Allocation
    decisions shall be based solely on the eligibility criteria, award amounts,
    and priority order established by this Section.

    (3) ANNUAL ALLOCATION REPORT.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall
    publish an annual report on Bootstrap Grant allocations, including the total
    amount awarded in each grant stream, the geographic distribution of awards,
    the number of applications received and approved in each priority category,
    and the reasons for any denial of a complete and eligible application.

(h) FUNDING.-- There are authorized to be appropriated to the Bootstrap Grant
Program such sums as may be necessary to carry out the purposes of this Section,
to be derived from the National Resilience Ledger capitalization mechanism
established under Section 601 of this Act and from such general appropriations
as Congress may provide. The Secretary of the Treasury shall ensure that
Bootstrap Grant funding is maintained at a level sufficient to process all
eligible applications within ninety days of receipt, and shall report to
Congress within thirty days whenever the available Bootstrap Grant fund balance
falls below an amount sufficient to process applications projected to be received
in the following six months.


