SEC. 107. OFFICE OF FEDERATED STEWARDSHIP.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established within the Department of Commerce an
office to be known as the Office of Federated Stewardship. The Office of
Federated Stewardship is a transitional administrative body whose existence and
authority are coextensive with the OFS Phase defined in subsection (f) of this
Section. The Office shall exercise no authority beyond what is expressly
conferred by this Act, shall at all times interpret its mandate narrowly in
favor of Federated Network autonomy consistent with Section 104 of this Title,
and shall conduct its affairs with the explicit institutional understanding that
its purpose is to make itself unnecessary.

(b) DIRECTOR.--

    (1) APPOINTMENT.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall be headed by a
    Director, appointed by the President with the advice and consent of the
    Senate, for a term of five years. The Director may be reappointed once for a
    second five-year term and shall not serve more than two terms in total.

    (2) QUALIFICATIONS.-- The Director shall have demonstrated expertise in
    cooperative governance, community land trust administration, commons resource
    management, or a related field, and shall not, at the time of appointment or
    during their term, hold any financial interest in any corporation, private
    equity fund, or other entity whose interests are adverse to the commons values
    established by this Act.

    (3) REMOVAL.-- The Director may be removed by the President only for cause,
    defined as demonstrated neglect of duty, malfeasance in office, or conduct
    inconsistent with the requirements of this Act. The Director shall not be
    removed for exercising the Office's authority in a manner that reduces
    executive influence over the Federated Network consistent with Section 104 of
    this Act. Any removal of the Director shall be subject to judicial review
    pursuant to Section 104(e) of this Act upon the application of any certified
    Qualified Federated Network.

    (4) ACTING DIRECTOR.-- In the event of a vacancy in the position of Director,
    the most senior career employee of the Office of Federated Stewardship shall
    serve as Acting Director until a new Director is appointed, provided that the
    Acting Director shall have full authority to carry out all functions of the
    Office during the period of vacancy and shall not be subject to direction by
    any political appointee of the Executive Branch with respect to certification
    determinations or Bootstrap Grant allocations.

(c) FUNCTIONS.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall perform the following
functions during the OFS Phase:

    (1) CERTIFICATION ADMINISTRATION.-- Receive, process, and determine
    certification applications from entities seeking Qualified Federated
    Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network status pursuant to Section 103 of
    this Title, in strict accordance with the ministerial certification standard
    established under Section 104(b)(2) of this Act.

    (2) REGISTRY MAINTENANCE.-- Maintain and publish a current registry of all
    certified Qualified Federated Cooperatives, Qualified Federated Networks, and
    Commons Financial Nodes, recorded on the National Resilience Ledger and
    updated within five business days of any certification, decertification, or
    change in certification status.

    (3) BOOTSTRAP GRANT ADMINISTRATION.-- Administer the Bootstrap Grant Program
    established under Section 106 of this Act, including receiving and processing
    grant applications, executing grant agreements, disbursing grant funds,
    reviewing annual and final grant reports, and recovering improperly expended
    grant funds.

    (4) TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE.-- Provide technical assistance to organizations
    seeking certification, including:

        (A) guidance on governance document drafting consistent with the Ostrom
        Standards of Stewardship;

        (B) referrals to qualified technical reviewers for Federated Mesh
        compliance certification;

        (C) assistance with the existing cooperative and CLT certification
        pathways established under Section 103(e) of this Act;

        (D) multilingual assistance and accessible format materials for
        communities with limited English proficiency or literacy barriers; and

        (E) mobile technical assistance teams for communities in designated
        Underserved Areas.

    (5) UNDERSERVED AREA MAPPING.-- Establish, maintain, and annually update the
    Underserved Area map pursuant to Section 105(b) of this Act, and conduct the
    affirmative outreach obligations established under Section 105(c)(2) of this
    Act.

    (6) REPORTING.-- Submit to Congress the annual coverage report required by
    Section 105(f)(1) of this Act, the annual Bootstrap Grant allocation report
    required by Section 106(g)(3) of this Act, and such other reports as this Act
    requires or Congress requests.

    (7) INTERAGENCY COORDINATION.-- Coordinate with the Departments of
    Agriculture, Housing and Urban Development, Health and Human Services,
    Energy, Commerce, and Labor, the Federal Communications Commission, the
    National Telecommunications and Information Administration, the Small
    Business Administration, the Department of the Treasury's Community
    Development Financial Institutions Fund, and all other relevant federal
    agencies to align existing federal programs with the cooperative formation,
    coverage expansion, and commons infrastructure objectives of this Act,
    pursuant to the memoranda of understanding authorized under Section 105(e)(2)
    of this Act and such other interagency agreements as the Director determines
    appropriate. The Director shall chair or co-chair the Interagency Working
    Group on Cooperative Development established pursuant to the Agricultural Act
    of 2014 (the 2014 Farm Bill) during the OFS Phase, and shall seek to expand
    that working group's membership to include the Federal Communications
    Commission, the Department of Energy, and the Department of Justice's
    Antitrust Division where not already represented, so that the working group
    serves as the primary federal interagency coordination mechanism for this
    Act's implementation rather than a parallel structure being erected alongside
    it.

    (8) FEDERATED ACCOUNTABILITY BOARD SUPPORT.-- Provide administrative support
    to the Federated Accountability Board established under Section 1103 of this
    Act, including scheduling of hearings, maintenance of appeal records, and
    publication of appeal decisions on the National Resilience Ledger.

(d) LIMITATIONS ON OFFICE AUTHORITY.-- Notwithstanding any other provision of
this Act, the Office of Federated Stewardship shall not:

    (1) direct, condition, or otherwise influence the internal governance
    decisions, resource allocation priorities, membership criteria, or
    operational protocols of any certified Qualified Federated Cooperative or
    Qualified Federated Network, except through the certification and graduated
    response procedures expressly established in Section 103 of this Title;

    (2) collect, store, or share individually identifying personal information
    about Commons Members beyond what is strictly necessary for the
    administration of certification and Bootstrap Grant functions, and in all
    cases subject to the privacy protections of Title IV of this Act;

    (3) establish relationships with any private contractor, consultant, or
    technology provider that would give that party access to National Resilience
    Ledger data, Federated Mesh infrastructure, or Commons Member information
    beyond what is strictly necessary for the performance of a specific,
    time-limited administrative function;

    (4) accept direction from any political appointee of the Executive Branch
    with respect to individual certification determinations or Bootstrap Grant
    allocation decisions; or

    (5) take any action that would have the effect of concentrating governance
    authority over the Federated Network in the Office of Federated Stewardship
    or any other governmental body, or that would delay or obstruct the transfer
    of certification authority to the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism upon the
    network maturity threshold established in subsection (f) of this Section.

(e) RESIDUAL FUNCTIONS FOLLOWING NETWORK MATURITY THRESHOLD.-- Following the
transfer of certification authority pursuant to subsection (f) of this Section,
the Office of Federated Stewardship shall retain only the following ministerial
functions:

    (1) maintaining the public registry of certified entities on behalf of the
    federal government for purposes of legal recognition and federal program
    coordination, updated on the basis of certification determinations made by
    the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism;

    (2) administering the Bootstrap Grant Program pursuant to Section 106 of this
    Act for such period as Bootstrap Grant funding continues to be appropriated
    by Congress, with allocation decisions made pursuant to the objective criteria
    of Section 106(g) and without substantive discretion;

    (3) submitting the annual coverage and Bootstrap Grant reports to Congress
    pursuant to subsections (c)(5) and (c)(6) of this Section, based on data
    published on the National Resilience Ledger by the Federated Network;

    (4) providing administrative support to the Federated Accountability Board
    pursuant to subsection (c)(8) of this Section for appeals of decisions made
    during the OFS Phase that remain pending at the time of the transition; and

(f) NETWORK MATURITY THRESHOLD AND SUNSET PROVISIONS.--

    (1) NETWORK MATURITY THRESHOLD DEFINED.-- For the purposes of this Act, the
    network maturity threshold shall be deemed to have occurred when all of the
    following conditions have been simultaneously satisfied:

        (A) not fewer than one thousand Qualified Federated Networks have
        achieved and maintained certification for a period of not less than two
        consecutive years;

        (B) certified Qualified Federated Networks collectively provide the
        Guaranteed Provision Standard to not fewer than ten million Commons
        Members in not fewer than forty states and territories of the United
        States;

        (C) the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism has operated continuously for not
        less than two years, has processed not fewer than five hundred compliance
        reviews, and has demonstrated a false positive rate -- defined as
        Compliance Flags subsequently overturned on Human-in-the-Loop review --
        of not greater than five percent;

        (D) the National Resilience Ledger has operated continuously for not
        less than two years without a systemic integrity failure, defined as an
        event causing loss, corruption, or unauthorized alteration of records
        affecting more than one percent of registered Commons Members; and

        (E) the IP Commons Governance Council established under Section 509 of
        this Act has been constituted, has conducted not fewer than two annual
        governance cycles, and has certified to the Office of Federated
        Stewardship that the Intellectual Property Commons is operating in
        accordance with the requirements of Title V of this Act.

    (2) DETERMINATION OF THRESHOLD OCCURRENCE.-- The Director of the Office of
    Federated Stewardship shall monitor progress toward the network maturity
    threshold on a continuous basis and shall publish quarterly progress reports
    on the National Resilience Ledger. Upon the Director's determination that all
    conditions of paragraph (1) of this subsection have been satisfied, the
    Director shall:

        (A) publish a notice of threshold occurrence on the National Resilience
        Ledger and in the Federal Register, specifying the date on which the
        threshold was satisfied and the date, ninety days thereafter, on which
        the transfer of certification authority will take effect;

        (B) submit a report to Congress confirming the threshold occurrence and
        describing the state of the Federated Network at the time of transfer;
        and

        (C) initiate the transfer protocols established in the technical
        standards governance framework under Title VII of this Act to formally
        transition certification functions to the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism.

    (3) CONGRESSIONAL REVIEW OF THRESHOLD DETERMINATION.-- Congress shall have
    ninety days from the publication of the notice of threshold occurrence to
    review the Director's determination. During this period:

        (A) either chamber of Congress may, by resolution, request an independent
        audit of the threshold conditions by the Government Accountability Office,
        which shall complete its audit within sixty days of the request;

        (B) if the Government Accountability Office determines that one or more
        threshold conditions have not been satisfied, the transfer of
        certification authority shall be suspended pending satisfaction of the
        disputed conditions; and

        (C) if no resolution requesting an independent audit is adopted within
        ninety days, or if the Government Accountability Office confirms the
        threshold determination, the transfer shall take effect on the date
        specified in the Director's notice.

    (4) TRANSFER OF CERTIFICATION AUTHORITY.-- Upon the effective date of
    transfer established pursuant to paragraph (2)(A) of this subsection:

        (A) all pending certification applications shall be transferred to the
        Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism for determination, with the Office of
        Federated Stewardship providing all application materials and staff
        expertise necessary to ensure continuity of processing;

        (B) all ongoing graduated response proceedings shall be transferred to
        the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism, with the Office providing complete
        records of all prior proceedings;

        (C) the Federated Accountability Board shall be reconstituted as a
        standing body of the Federated Network pursuant to Section 1103 of this
        Act, independent of the Office of Federated Stewardship; and

        (D) the Office of Federated Stewardship shall be reduced to its residual
        functions as established in subsection (e) of this Section, with
        corresponding reductions in staffing and budget.

    (5) FULL SUNSET.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall be fully
    dissolved upon the occurrence of both of the following conditions:

        (A) the network maturity threshold transfer has been in effect for not
        less than five years, during which the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism has
        continued to operate in accordance with the requirements of Section 103
        of this Act without systemic failure; and

        (B) Bootstrap Grant funding has been fully expended or its administration
        has been assumed by the Federated Network's own financial infrastructure
        pursuant to Title VI of this Act.

    (6) DISPOSITION OF OFFICE ASSETS AND RECORDS UPON DISSOLUTION.-- Upon full
    dissolution of the Office of Federated Stewardship:

        (A) all records of certification determinations, Bootstrap Grant awards,
        and Underserved Area mapping shall be transferred to the National
        Resilience Ledger and maintained in perpetuity as part of the commons
        governance record;

        (B) all physical assets of the Office shall be transferred to the nearest
        certified Qualified Federated Network for use in commons infrastructure
        purposes;

        (C) all career employees of the Office shall be offered positions within
        the Federated Network governance structure or within other federal
        agencies, with priority placement assistance provided by the Office of
        Personnel Management; and

        (D) the legal authority of the Office of Federated Stewardship shall
        terminate, and no governmental body shall thereafter exercise the
        certification, grant administration, or registry functions of the Office
        except through new legislation enacted by Congress.

(g) STAFFING AND INDEPENDENCE.--

    (1) CAREER STAFF.-- The substantive functions of the Office of Federated
    Stewardship shall be performed by career civil servants appointed through
    competitive examination, with demonstrated expertise in cooperative
    governance, community development, commons resource management, digital
    infrastructure, or related fields. Political appointees of the Executive
    Branch shall have no role in individual certification determinations,
    Bootstrap Grant allocation decisions, or Underserved Area mapping.

    (2) CONFLICTS OF INTEREST.-- No employee of the Office of Federated
    Stewardship shall, during their employment or for a period of two years
    following separation from employment, hold a financial interest in or accept
    employment with any entity whose certification application was reviewed,
    approved, or denied during that employee's tenure, or any entity that
    received a Bootstrap Grant administered by that employee.

    (3) WHISTLEBLOWER PROTECTION.-- Any employee of the Office of Federated
    Stewardship who in good faith reports to Congress, the Government
    Accountability Office, or any appropriate oversight authority that the Office
    is being directed to act in violation of the limitations established by
    Section 104 of this Act shall be entitled to the full protections of the
    Whistleblower Protection Act of 1989, and shall additionally be entitled to
    immediate transfer to a position outside the Office of Federated Stewardship
    upon request, without loss of grade, pay, or benefits.

(h) AUTHORIZATION OF APPROPRIATIONS.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
to the Office of Federated Stewardship such sums as may be necessary to carry
out the functions of this Section during the OFS Phase. Appropriations for the
Office shall be reduced proportionally following the network maturity threshold
to reflect the transfer of certification functions to the Peer-to-Peer Audit
mechanism, and shall be reduced to the minimum amount necessary to carry out the
residual functions of subsection (e) of this Section following that transfer. No
appropriation shall be made to the Office following its full dissolution pursuant
to subsection (f)(5) of this Section.


================================================================================
TITLE II -- FEDERATED COMMONS MEMBERSHIP
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the architecture, content,
portability, and governance of Federated Commons Membership -- the bundle of
democratic cooperative memberships that collectively constitute a complete
material life within the commons economy. Federated Commons Membership is not a
government benefit, welfare transfer, or public assistance program. It is a form
of democratic economic citizenship in which the rights to material provision and
the obligations of cooperative governance are inseparable and mutually
constitutive. No provision of this Title shall be construed to create a
relationship of dependency between Commons Members and any governmental
authority. The primary enforceable obligations created by this Title run to the
Qualified Federated Networks within which Commons Members hold membership, with
federal obligations arising as specified in Sections 202(d) and 210(c) of this
Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 201. FEDERATED COMMONS MEMBERSHIP -- ARCHITECTURE AND SCOPE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL ARCHITECTURE.-- Federated Commons Membership, as defined in Section
4(7) of this Act, comprises a portfolio of cooperative memberships held by a
Commons Member within a Qualified Federated Network. The portfolio is organized
into two tiers:

    (1) THE MANDATORY BASELINE PORTFOLIO -- comprising those cooperative
    memberships whose provisions are so fundamental to a dignified material life
    that every Commons Member must have access to them as a condition of
    Federated Commons Membership, regardless of circumstances, location,
    contribution history, Commons Credit balance, or any other condition; and

    (2) THE ELECTIVE PORTFOLIO -- comprising those cooperative memberships that
    Commons Members may hold in addition to the mandatory baseline, reflecting
    individual circumstances, skills, preferences, and community availability,
    and whose provisions supplement but do not substitute for the Guaranteed
    Provision Standard delivered through the mandatory baseline portfolio.

(b) MANDATORY BASELINE PORTFOLIO.-- The mandatory baseline portfolio shall
comprise membership in each of the following five cooperative domains:

    (1) a Community Land Trust providing housing tenure pursuant to Section 203
    of this Title;

    (2) a food cooperative providing nutritional provisions pursuant to Section
    204 of this Title;

    (3) a healthcare cooperative providing access to healthcare services pursuant
    to Section 205 of this Title;

    (4) the Data Commons established under Title IV of this Act, providing data
    sovereignty protections and data trust governance rights pursuant to Section
    206 of this Title; and

    (5) the Intellectual Property Commons established under Title V of this Act,
    providing access to the commons knowledge base and attribution registration
    services pursuant to Section 207 of this Title.

(c) ELECTIVE PORTFOLIO.-- The elective portfolio may include membership in any
of the following cooperative domains, as available within the Commons Member's
Qualified Federated Network or accessible through federated resource-sharing
arrangements with neighboring networks:

    (1) labor cooperatives, providing meaningful work and democratic
    participation in productive enterprise;

    (2) energy cooperatives, providing access to cooperative renewable energy
    infrastructure;

    (3) childcare cooperatives, providing cooperative childcare services;

    (4) elder care cooperatives, providing cooperative elder care and assisted
    living services;

    (5) transportation cooperatives, providing cooperative mobility
    infrastructure;

    (6) communications cooperatives, providing cooperative telecommunications
    infrastructure;

    (7) time banks and mutual aid networks, providing peer-to-peer exchange of
    skills, labor, and community support; and

    (8) such other cooperative enterprises as are certified as Qualified
    Federated Cooperatives under Title I of this Act and are willing to extend
    membership to Commons Members within the network.

(d) GOVERNANCE RIGHTS.-- Every cooperative membership comprising the Federated
Commons Membership portfolio carries corresponding democratic governance rights
in the cooperative institution providing that membership's provisions. These
governance rights are not separable from the provision rights -- a Commons
Member cannot hold the provisions of a cooperative membership without holding
the corresponding governance rights, and cannot be denied governance rights
while receiving provisions. Specifically:

    (1) membership in a Community Land Trust carries governance rights in the
    CLT's land use, housing development, and community planning decisions
    pursuant to Standard 3 of Section 102(d) of this Act;

    (2) membership in a food cooperative carries governance rights in the
    cooperative's production, procurement, and distribution decisions;

    (3) membership in a healthcare cooperative carries governance rights in the
    cooperative's service delivery, provider relationships, and resource
    allocation decisions;

    (4) membership in the Data Commons carries governance rights in the data
    trust's data use policies, privacy standards, and governance protocols
    pursuant to Title IV of this Act;

    (5) membership in the Intellectual Property Commons carries governance rights
    in the IP Commons Governance Council elections and policy deliberations
    pursuant to Title V of this Act; and

    (6) membership in any elective cooperative carries governance rights in that
    cooperative's internal decisions pursuant to Standard 3 of Section 102(d) of
    this Act.

(e) INSEPARABILITY OF PROVISION AND GOVERNANCE.-- The inseparability of
provision rights and governance rights established in subsection (d) of this
Section is a fundamental structural feature of Federated Commons Membership and
shall be enforced as follows:

    (1) no Qualified Federated Cooperative shall deliver provisions to a Commons
    Member while denying or substantially impairing that member's governance
    rights;

    (2) no Qualified Federated Cooperative shall condition the delivery of
    provisions on the waiver of governance rights;

    (3) no Qualified Federated Cooperative shall structure its governance in a
    manner that formally preserves governance rights while substantively rendering
    them meaningless through information asymmetry, procedural barriers, or the
    effective concentration of decision-making authority; and

    (4) any Commons Member who believes their governance rights are being denied
    or substantially impaired while their provision rights are being delivered
    shall have recourse to the conflict resolution mechanisms of Standard 6 of
    Section 102(g) of this Act and the Human-in-the-Loop Layer of Section 803 of
    this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 202. THE GUARANTEED PROVISION STANDARD.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DEFINITION AND UNCONDITIONAL CHARACTER.-- The Guaranteed Provision Standard,
as defined in Section 4(10) of this Act, is the minimum bundle of material
provisions to which every Commons Member is entitled through Federated Commons
Membership. The Guaranteed Provision Standard is unconditional -- it does not
depend upon the Commons Member's labor contributions, Commons Credit balance,
length of membership, compliance history, or any other condition -- subject only
to the requirement that the Commons Member maintain active Federated Commons
Membership in a certified Qualified Federated Network. The Guaranteed Provision
Standard shall not be reduced, suspended, or terminated as a sanction against
any individual Commons Member for any reason. Sanctions for violations of
cooperative governance rules shall be administered exclusively through the
graduated sanctions mechanism of Standard 5 of Section 102(f) of this Act and
shall not include reduction or termination of provision standard entitlements.

(b) COMPONENTS.-- The Guaranteed Provision Standard comprises the five provision
components delivered through the mandatory baseline portfolio established in
Section 201(b) of this Act:

    (1) HOUSING -- as specified in Section 203 of this Title;

    (2) NUTRITION -- as specified in Section 204 of this Title;

    (3) HEALTHCARE -- as specified in Section 205 of this Title;

    (4) CONNECTIVITY AND TOOLS -- as specified in Section 206 of this Title; and

    (5) KNOWLEDGE ACCESS -- as specified in Section 207 of this Title.

(c) FLOOR CHARACTER.-- The Guaranteed Provision Standard establishes a floor,
not a ceiling. Nothing in this Title shall be construed to limit the ability of
Qualified Federated Networks to provide provisions exceeding the minimum
standards established in Sections 203 through 207 of this Title, or to limit the
ability of individual Commons Members to supplement their provisions through
elective cooperative memberships, Commons Credit transactions, time-banking
participation, or any other lawful means.

(d) PROVISION DELIVERY OBLIGATION.-- Every Qualified Federated Network bears an
affirmative and legally enforceable obligation to deliver the Guaranteed
Provision Standard to every Commons Member within its scope. This obligation:

    (1) is a condition of QFN certification under Section 103 of this Title and
    shall be continuously monitored through the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism;

    (2) cannot be discharged by reference to resource constraints unless the
    network has exhausted all available federated resource-sharing arrangements
    with neighboring Qualified Federated Networks and has reported the resource
    constraint to the Office of Federated Stewardship or, following the network
    maturity threshold, to the regional federation governance layer;

    (3) survives the imposition of Level 1 or Level 2 sanctions on the network
    under Section 103(c)(2) of this Act, and shall be maintained through
    federated resource-sharing arrangements during Level 3 or Level 4 sanctions
    as provided in Section 103(c)(3) of this Act; and

    (4) is enforceable by individual Commons Members through the conflict
    resolution mechanisms of Standard 6 of Section 102(g) of this Act, the
    Human-in-the-Loop Layer of Section 803 of this Act, and, where those
    mechanisms fail to produce a remedy within the timeframes established
    therein, through civil action in any federal court of competent jurisdiction.

(e) ADEQUACY REVIEW.-- The Guaranteed Provision Standard shall be subject to
mandatory periodic review to ensure that the minimum provisions established in
Sections 203 through 207 of this Title remain genuinely adequate to support a
dignified material life in light of changing economic conditions, technological
capabilities, and community needs. Specifically:

    (1) the IP Commons Governance Council shall conduct a comprehensive adequacy
    review of the Guaranteed Provision Standard not less than once every four
    years, in consultation with Commons Members across all regions of the
    Federated Network through the participatory governance tools established
    under Title VII of this Act;

    (2) the results of each adequacy review shall be published on the National
    Resilience Ledger and submitted to Congress with recommendations for any
    legislative amendments necessary to maintain the genuine adequacy of the
    Standard; and

    (3) in the interim between comprehensive reviews, any Qualified Federated
    Network may petition the IP Commons Governance Council for an emergency
    adequacy determination with respect to a specific provision component upon a
    showing that changed circumstances have rendered that component materially
    inadequate within the network's geographic area.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 203. HOUSING PROVISION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STANDARD.-- The housing component of the Guaranteed Provision Standard shall
consist of access to a private, secure, and permanently affordable dwelling unit
that meets all of the following minimum requirements:

    (1) PHYSICAL ADEQUACY.-- The dwelling unit shall:

        (A) provide not less than one hundred fifty square feet of enclosed
        living space per adult occupant and not less than one hundred square feet
        per minor occupant, with a minimum total unit size of three hundred square
        feet regardless of occupancy;

        (B) maintain structural integrity sufficient to provide protection from
        weather, temperature extremes, and physical hazards, meeting or exceeding
        the applicable building codes of the jurisdiction in which the unit is
        located;

        (C) provide access to potable water, functional sanitation facilities,
        adequate heating and cooling for the local climate, and natural lighting
        in all primary living spaces;

        (D) provide functional kitchen facilities sufficient for the preparation
        and storage of food adequate to meet the nutrition standard of Section
        204 of this Title; and

        (E) meet all applicable accessibility standards under the Americans with
        Disabilities Act of 1990 for units occupied by members with disabilities,
        and provide for reasonable accommodation of disability-related needs in
        all units.

    (2) TENURE SECURITY.-- The housing tenure provided through CLT membership
    shall be:

        (A) permanent and non-evictable except upon a finding by the Mediation
        DAO, subject to Human-in-the-Loop review, that the member has engaged in
        conduct posing an immediate and documented threat to the physical safety
        of other residents, and only after all less restrictive interventions have
        been exhausted;

        (B) free from rent increases beyond the actual cost of maintenance,
        repair, and infrastructure improvement, with no component of the housing
        payment constituting profit to any individual or entity;

        (C) transferable to the member's household upon the member's death or
        incapacity, subject to the CLT's membership criteria; and

        (D) portable within the Federated Network pursuant to Section 210 of this
        Title, such that a member who relocates to another Qualified Federated
        Network retains their housing entitlement and shall be provided with
        equivalent housing by the receiving network within a reasonable time not
        to exceed ninety days.

    (3) COMMUNITY SPACE.-- Every CLT community shall provide, in addition to
    individual dwelling units, shared community space comprising:

        (A) not less than twenty square feet of indoor common space per resident,
        suitable for community gatherings, cooperative governance meetings, and
        shared activities;

        (B) access to outdoor green space within a reasonable walking distance of
        all dwelling units; and

        (C) shared workshop, fabrication, and creative workspace sufficient to
        support the productive and creative activities of resident members,
        meeting the connectivity and tools standard of Section 206 of this Title.

(b) ANTI-SPECULATION ENFORCEMENT.-- The housing component of the Guaranteed
Provision Standard shall be delivered exclusively through Community Land Trusts
operating pursuant to Title III of this Act. No component of the housing payment
made by a Commons Member shall constitute rent in the conventional sense -- that
is, payment for the use of land whose value is determined by speculative market
forces. The CLT ground lease structure shall ensure that:

    (1) the land underlying all commons housing is permanently held in trust and
    is not subject to sale, mortgage, or speculative valuation;

    (2) any equity accumulated by a Commons Member in their dwelling unit through
    improvement or long-term occupancy is shared between the member and the CLT
    according to the limited-equity formula established in the CLT's ground
    lease, ensuring that the member benefits from their investment without the
    unit becoming unaffordable to future members; and

    (3) upon a member's departure from the CLT, whether by relocation within the
    network, death, or other circumstance, the dwelling unit is returned to the
    commons and made available to the next eligible member at an equivalent
    affordable rate.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 204. NUTRITION PROVISION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STANDARD.-- The nutrition component of the Guaranteed Provision Standard
shall consist of access to food sufficient in quantity, quality, and cultural
appropriateness to maintain the good health of all Commons Members. Specifically,
each Qualified Federated Network shall ensure that every Commons Member has
access to:

    (1) CALORIC AND NUTRITIONAL ADEQUACY.-- A daily supply of food meeting not
    less than the Dietary Reference Intakes established by the National Academies
    of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine for the member's age, sex, and health
    status, comprising a diversity of food groups sufficient to prevent
    nutritional deficiency;

    (2) CULTURAL APPROPRIATENESS.-- Food that is appropriate to the cultural,
    religious, and personal dietary practices of the Commons Member, to the
    extent that the network's food production and procurement capacity permits,
    with the network making good-faith efforts to expand capacity to meet
    documented cultural and dietary needs within its membership;

    (3) PRODUCTION PROXIMITY.-- To the greatest extent feasible, food produced
    within or adjacent to the network's geographic area through cooperative
    farming, community gardening, urban agriculture, and related practices,
    reducing dependence on long-distance supply chains and strengthening local
    food sovereignty; and

    (4) COMMONS REINVESTMENT.-- Food provisions shall be delivered through
    cooperative food enterprises whose surplus, if any, is reinvested in the food
    commons -- in expanding production capacity, improving food quality, reducing
    the labor burden of food production through appropriate technology, or
    extending food provisions to neighboring Underserved Areas -- and not
    distributed as private profit.

(b) FOOD SOVEREIGNTY PRINCIPLE.-- The nutrition provision established by this
Section shall be understood as an expression of food sovereignty -- the right of
communities to define their own food systems according to their own values,
needs, and ecological conditions -- and not merely as a caloric adequacy
standard. Qualified Federated Networks shall have broad discretion in determining
how the nutrition standard is met, including through community kitchens, food
cooperative distribution systems, community-supported agriculture arrangements,
traditional food practices, and such other means as the network's
collective-choice processes determine appropriate.

(c) FOOD COMMONS ASSETS.-- All agricultural land, food production
infrastructure, seed stocks, and traditional agricultural knowledge used to
deliver the nutrition provision shall be designated as Commons Permanence Assets
pursuant to Section 4(5) of this Act and shall not be subject to external trade,
sale, or transfer except as permitted by the provision priority rule established
under Section 307(d) of this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 205. HEALTHCARE PROVISION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STANDARD.-- The healthcare component of the Guaranteed Provision Standard
shall consist of access to comprehensive healthcare services delivered through
cooperative healthcare enterprises certified as Qualified Federated Cooperatives
under Title I of this Act. Comprehensive healthcare services shall include:

    (1) PRIMARY CARE -- including preventive care, routine health maintenance,
    management of chronic conditions, and acute care for non-emergency
    conditions, provided by qualified healthcare practitioners within a
    reasonable geographic distance of or accessible through cooperative
    transportation arrangements from the Commons Member's dwelling;

    (2) EMERGENCY CARE -- including access to emergency medical services and
    emergency department care without financial barrier, with the cooperative
    healthcare network bearing the cost of emergency care delivered outside the
    network's facilities where network facilities are not accessible in time to
    address a life-threatening condition;

    (3) MENTAL HEALTH AND SUBSTANCE USE SERVICES -- including community-based
    mental health care, counseling, peer support, and substance use treatment
    services, provided through a trauma-informed, recovery-oriented model that
    recognizes the relationship between mental health and the material conditions
    of life;

    (4) DENTAL AND VISION CARE -- including routine dental and vision services
    sufficient to maintain oral and ocular health; and

    (5) TRADITIONAL AND COMMUNITY MEDICINE -- including recognition of and access
    to traditional healing practices, community health workers, and culturally
    grounded healing traditions, particularly in indigenous and immigrant
    communities where such practices are central to community health identity.

(b) HEALTHCARE COOPERATIVE GOVERNANCE.-- Healthcare cooperatives delivering the
healthcare provision shall be governed by their members -- including both
healthcare workers and healthcare recipients -- pursuant to Standard 3 of Section
102(d) of this Act. The governance structure of healthcare cooperatives shall
ensure that:

    (1) healthcare workers have meaningful governance rights over clinical
    practice standards, working conditions, and the cooperative's relationship
    with its patient members;

    (2) patient members have meaningful governance rights over the cooperative's
    service priorities, accessibility standards, and resource allocation; and

    (3) no governance arrangement shall permit the interests of either healthcare
    workers or patient members to systematically override those of the other,
    with conflicts between worker and patient interests resolved through the
    conflict resolution mechanisms of Standard 6 of Section 102(g) of this Act.

(c) MENTAL HEALTH AND THE MATERIAL CONDITIONS OF LIFE.-- Congress finds that the
mental health burdens experienced by communities living under conditions of
housing insecurity, food insecurity, economic precarity, and exposure to systemic
injustice are substantially caused by those material conditions rather than by
individual pathology. The delivery of the Guaranteed Provision Standard through
Federated Commons Membership -- providing permanent housing, adequate nutrition,
meaningful democratic participation in cooperative governance, and freedom from
the chronic stress of material insecurity -- is itself a mental health
intervention of the first order. The mental health services required by
subsection (a)(3) of this Section shall be understood as complementary to, not
substitutes for, the material security provided by the Guaranteed Provision
Standard as a whole.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 206. CONNECTIVITY AND TOOLS PROVISION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STANDARD.-- The connectivity and tools component of the Guaranteed Provision
Standard shall consist of access to the physical and digital infrastructure
necessary for meaningful participation in cooperative governance, productive
work, creative expression, and commons knowledge access. Specifically, each
Qualified Federated Network shall ensure that every Commons Member has access to:

    (1) DIGITAL CONNECTIVITY.-- A Federated Mesh-connected device meeting the
    Federated Mesh Open Standard requirements of Section 701 of this Act,
    sufficient for participation in cooperative governance through digital means,
    access to the National Resilience Ledger, Commons Credit transactions, and
    access to the Intellectual Property Commons; provided that where a personal
    device is not available, shared community devices located in accessible
    community spaces shall satisfy this requirement;

    (2) PRODUCTIVE TOOLS AND MATERIALS.-- Access to shared workshop, fabrication,
    and making infrastructure sufficient to support the productive work activities
    of Commons Members, including hand tools, power tools, basic fabrication
    equipment, agricultural implements, and such specialized equipment as the
    network's collective-choice processes determine appropriate to the productive
    activities of its membership;

    (3) CREATIVE TOOLS AND MATERIALS.-- Access to shared creative infrastructure
    sufficient to support the creative expression of Commons Members, including
    musical instruments, art materials, performance space, recording equipment,
    and such other creative resources as the network determines appropriate; and

    (4) REPAIR AND MAINTENANCE.-- Ongoing maintenance, repair, and replacement of
    the tools, equipment, and devices provided through this provision component,
    ensuring that the physical infrastructure of the commons remains functional
    and accessible to all members.

(b) OPEN-SOURCE REQUIREMENT.-- All software, operating systems, and digital
platforms used to deliver the connectivity provision of this Section shall be
open-source and shall operate on the Federated Mesh Open Standard. No proprietary
software platform shall be required as a condition of meaningful participation in
Federated Commons Membership governance or provision access.

(c) ACCESSIBILITY.-- The connectivity and tools provision shall be delivered in a
manner accessible to Commons Members with disabilities, older adults, and members
with limited technical literacy, including through in-person technical assistance,
accessible interface design, and multilingual support.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 207. KNOWLEDGE ACCESS PROVISION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STANDARD.-- The knowledge access component of the Guaranteed Provision
Standard shall consist of access to the full body of knowledge, creative works,
technical innovations, and educational resources held in the Intellectual
Property Commons established under Title V of this Act, together with access to
such educational programming, apprenticeship pathways, and cooperative learning
infrastructure as the Qualified Federated Network provides.

(b) IP COMMONS ACCESS.-- Every Commons Member shall have unrestricted access to
the Intellectual Property Commons for purposes of:

    (1) using, deploying, performing, remixing, building upon, and otherwise
    engaging with any work or innovation held in the commons;

    (2) registering their own creative works, technical innovations, and
    traditional knowledge contributions through the attribution registration
    pathways established under Title V of this Act; and

    (3) participating in the governance of the IP Commons through the IP Commons
    Governance Council electoral and deliberative processes established under
    Section 509 of this Act.

(c) EDUCATIONAL ACCESS.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall provide or
arrange access to educational programming that:

    (1) is available to Commons Members of all ages and at all levels of prior
    educational attainment;

    (2) includes both formal educational pathways and informal learning through
    cooperative apprenticeship, mentorship, and peer-to-peer knowledge sharing;

    (3) is delivered through cooperative educational institutions where available,
    and through open-source and commons-licensed educational resources in all
    cases; and

    (4) includes education in cooperative governance, commons stewardship,
    Federated Mesh technical literacy, and the historical and theoretical
    foundations of the commons economy, ensuring that Commons Members have the
    knowledge necessary to meaningfully exercise their governance rights.


--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 208. ELECTIVE PORTFOLIO MEMBERSHIPS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PURPOSE.-- The elective portfolio established under Section 201(c) of this
Act supplements the mandatory baseline portfolio by providing Commons Members
with access to cooperative institutions serving additional domains of material
and social life. The establishment of elective cooperative enterprises within the
Federated Network is a matter of community self-determination -- it emerges from
the collective-choice processes of Qualified Federated Networks in response to
demonstrated community need -- and not a federal mandate.

(b) INCENTIVE STRUCTURE.-- The Act provides the following incentives for the
formation of elective portfolio cooperatives within the Federated Network:

    (1) Formation Grants, Transition Grants, and Technical Integration Grants are
    available for elective cooperative formation and integration pursuant to
    Section 106 of this Act;

    (2) elective cooperatives that achieve QFC certification are eligible for the
    full range of commons infrastructure benefits, including National Resilience
    Ledger access, Commons Credit issuance, and IP Commons membership; and

    (3) the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism shall track and report on elective
    cooperative availability across the network, with the annual coverage report
    required by Section 105(f)(1) of this Act including data on elective
    cooperative coverage as well as mandatory baseline coverage.

(c) LABOR COOPERATIVE PROVISIONS.-- Labor cooperatives occupying the elective
portfolio carry particular significance for the commons economy and shall receive
specific recognition as follows:

    (1) labor cooperatives are the primary institutions through which Commons
    Members exercise democratic control over productive enterprise, and their
    proliferation within the Federated Network is a central objective of this
    Act;

    (2) the cooperative business conversion mechanism established under Section
    304 of this Act shall provide a specific pathway for existing businesses to
    convert to labor cooperative status and join the Federated Network; and

    (3) no Commons Member shall be required to hold membership in any specific
    labor cooperative as a condition of Federated Commons Membership, reflecting
    the principle that meaningful work is a dimension of human flourishing that
    the commons enables but does not compel.

(d) TIME BANKS AND MUTUAL AID.-- Time banks and mutual aid networks occupying
the elective portfolio serve functions that are qualitatively different from
other cooperative enterprises -- they are the primary mechanisms through which
Commons Members exchange care, skill, and community support in ways that the
formal cooperative economy does not capture. The Act recognizes time banks and
mutual aid networks as essential commons infrastructure and provides:

    (1) Formation Grants specifically designated for time bank and mutual aid
    network formation pursuant to Section 106(b)(1) of this Act;

    (2) Commons Credit recognition for time bank credits earned within the
    Federated Network, at exchange rates established through the Commons Credit
    governance process of Title VI of this Act; and

    (3) technical integration support for connecting time bank ledgers to the
    National Resilience Ledger, enabling inter-network portability of time bank
    credits pursuant to Section 210 of this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 209. THE COMMONS MEMBERSHIP RECORD.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- Every Commons Member shall hold a Commons Membership Record
-- a portable, individually controlled digital and physical record documenting
the member's Federated Commons Membership portfolio, provision entitlements,
contribution history, and attribution registrations. The Commons Membership
Record is the property of the individual Commons Member and not of any Qualified
Federated Network, governmental authority, or other entity.

(b) CONTENTS.-- The Commons Membership Record shall contain:

    (1) the member's cryptographic identity -- their public key, or their
    pseudonymous keypair where the member has elected pseudonymous participation
    pursuant to the privacy provisions of Title IV of this Act -- establishing
    their identity within the Federated Network without requiring disclosure of
    their legal name or other personally identifying information to any party
    beyond those with whom the member chooses to share it;

    (2) a record of the member's current mandatory baseline cooperative
    memberships and elective portfolio memberships, including the name and
    certification status of each cooperative and the date of membership
    commencement;

    (3) a record of the member's Commons Credit balance and transaction history,
    maintained on the National Resilience Ledger and accessible to the member
    through their cryptographic identity;

    (4) a record of the member's attribution registrations in the Intellectual
    Property Commons, including the title, creation date, and registration
    reference number of each registered work;

    (5) a record of the member's governance participation history, including
    attendance at cooperative governance meetings and participation in
    collective-choice processes, maintained in aggregated form sufficient to
    support the cooperative's Peer-to-Peer Audit reporting obligations without
    disclosing individually identifying behavioral data; and

    (6) such other information as the member elects to include, including health
    information shared voluntarily with healthcare cooperative providers, dietary
    preferences shared with food cooperative providers, and other personal
    information relevant to the delivery of specific provision components.

(c) INDIVIDUAL CUSTODY.-- The Commons Membership Record shall be held in the
individual custody of the Commons Member through one or more of the following
means:

    (1) a Federated Mesh-connected personal device carrying the member's private
    cryptographic key and a local copy of their record;

    (2) a durable physical credential -- a tamper-evident document containing the
    member's public key reference number and a QR code linking to their ledger
    record -- issued by the certifying Qualified Federated Network and renewable
    upon loss or damage; or

    (3) a secure key custody arrangement with a Commons Financial Node designated
    by the member, under which the Financial Node holds the member's private key
    in trust and produces it upon the member's request, subject to the fiduciary
    obligations established under Title VI of this Act.

(d) PRIVACY ARCHITECTURE.-- The privacy of the Commons Membership Record shall
be protected as follows:

    (1) NO CENTRAL AGGREGATION.-- No governmental authority, Qualified Federated
    Network, or other entity shall maintain a centralized database aggregating
    the Commons Membership Records of multiple Commons Members. Each member's
    record exists on the National Resilience Ledger in encrypted form, accessible
    only through the member's private cryptographic key;

    (2) CONSENT-BASED DISCLOSURE.-- No component of a Commons Member's record
    shall be disclosed to any Qualified Federated Network, cooperative enterprise,
    governmental authority, or other party without the member's active, specific,
    and revocable consent, except as provided in paragraph (3) of this
    subsection;

    (3) LIMITED EXCEPTIONS.-- A Commons Member's certification status -- the
    binary fact of whether they hold active Federated Commons Membership -- may
    be verified by any Qualified Federated Network through a Zero-Knowledge Proof
    pursuant to Section 4(22) of this Act, without disclosure of any other
    component of the member's record, for the sole purpose of confirming the
    member's entitlement to the Guaranteed Provision Standard upon arrival at the
    network; and

    (4) PROHIBITION ON NEIGHBOR SURVEILLANCE.-- No Commons Member, Qualified
    Federated Cooperative, Qualified Federated Network, or governmental authority
    shall use the Federated Mesh, the National Resilience Ledger, the Commons
    Membership Record system, or any other commons data infrastructure to monitor,
    track, profile, or surveil the activities, location, associations,
    communications, or consumption patterns of any other Commons Member without
    that member's express, specific, and revocable consent. Violations of this
    prohibition shall constitute a serious violation of the Ostrom Standards of
    Stewardship subject to Level 3 graduated response under Section 103(c)(2)(C)
    of this Act, and shall additionally constitute a cause of action for the
    affected Commons Member in any federal court of competent jurisdiction.

(e) LAW ENFORCEMENT ACCESS.-- Access to Commons Membership Records and Federated
Mesh data by law enforcement agencies shall be governed as follows:

    (1) NO AUTOMATIC ACCESS.-- No federal, state, or local law enforcement agency
    shall have automatic or routine access to any component of the Federated
    Mesh, the National Resilience Ledger, or any Commons Member's record;

    (2) WARRANT REQUIREMENT.-- Any law enforcement access to Federated Mesh data
    or Commons Membership Records shall require a judicial warrant issued upon a
    showing of probable cause by a court of competent jurisdiction, specifying
    with particularity the records sought and the specific investigation for which
    they are sought;

    (3) HEIGHTENED STANDARD.-- In recognition of the role of the Federated
    Network as protected community infrastructure and the particular harm that
    law enforcement surveillance causes to commons governance and community
    trust, warrants for Federated Mesh data shall be issued only upon a showing
    that:

        (A) the records sought are directly relevant to the investigation of a
        specific serious harm that has occurred or is actively in progress;

        (B) less intrusive investigative means have been exhausted or are
        demonstrably unavailable; and

        (C) the scope of the warrant is narrowly tailored to the specific records
        necessary for the investigation;

    (4) NOTIFICATION.-- The Commons Member whose records are sought shall be
    notified of any warrant within thirty days of its execution, except where a
    court of competent jurisdiction finds that notification would endanger an
    ongoing investigation, in which case notification shall be deferred for not
    more than one hundred eighty days; and

    (5) PROHIBITION ON BULK COLLECTION.-- No law enforcement warrant shall
    authorize bulk collection of Federated Mesh data or Commons Membership
    Records. Each warrant shall specify individual members or cooperative entities
    whose records are sought, and shall not authorize the collection of records
    of non-targeted members through network-wide surveillance.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 210. PORTABILITY OF FEDERATED COMMONS MEMBERSHIP.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PORTABILITY PRINCIPLE.-- Federated Commons Membership travels with the
Commons Member. A member who relocates from one Qualified Federated Network to
another retains their Federated Commons Membership and their entitlement to the
full Guaranteed Provision Standard at the receiving network. No network may deny
a Commons Member the Guaranteed Provision Standard on the basis of their origin
network, length of prior membership, contribution history at prior networks, or
any other condition related to their history within the Federated Network.

(b) TRANSFER PROCESS.-- When a Commons Member relocates to a new Qualified
Federated Network, the following transfer process shall apply:

    (1) the member presents their Commons Membership Record -- through their
    personal device, physical credential, or key custody arrangement -- to the
    receiving network, which verifies the member's active membership status
    through a Zero-Knowledge Proof pursuant to Section 4(22) of this Act;

    (2) the receiving network shall acknowledge the member's Federated Commons
    Membership and begin delivering the Guaranteed Provision Standard within
    seven days of presentation of a valid Commons Membership Record;

    (3) the receiving network shall provide the member with housing meeting the
    standard of Section 203 of this Title within ninety days of transfer, and
    shall provide interim housing meeting minimum safety standards within seven
    days if permanent housing is not immediately available;

    (4) the member's Commons Credit balance shall transfer automatically through
    the National Resilience Ledger upon the member's cryptographic authorization;
    and

    (5) the member's attribution registrations in the Intellectual Property
    Commons shall remain unaffected by relocation, as they are held on the
    National Resilience Ledger and are not associated with any specific network.

(c) INTER-NETWORK COST ALLOCATION.-- The cost of providing the Guaranteed
Provision Standard to a transferring Commons Member shall be borne by the
receiving network from the date of transfer. The receiving network may submit a
cost-sharing request to the regional federation governance layer where the volume
of incoming transfers in a given period creates a material burden on the
network's provision capacity, and the regional federation shall maintain a
Portability Solidarity Fund for this purpose, funded through a defined
contribution from all networks within the regional federation.

(d) INTERNATIONAL PORTABILITY.-- Where bilateral or multilateral commons
federation agreements have been established with foreign commons networks
pursuant to Section 1005 of this Act, the portability provisions of this Section
shall extend to transfers between the United States Federated Network and
participating foreign commons networks, subject to the terms of the applicable
federation agreement.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 211. EXISTING COOPERATIVE INTEGRATION INTO FEDERATED COMMONS MEMBERSHIP.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) RECOGNITION OF EXISTING MEMBERS.-- Individuals who hold membership in an
existing cooperative enterprise, community land trust, credit union, or
solidarity economy network that achieves QFC or QFN certification pursuant to
Section 103(e) of this Act shall be recognized as Commons Members from the date
of the organization's certification, without requirement of individual
re-enrollment, provided that:

    (1) the certifying organization notifies each existing member of their
    Commons Membership status and the rights and obligations it carries within
    thirty days of certification; and

    (2) each existing member has the opportunity to review and accept or decline
    Federated Commons Membership within ninety days of notification, with
    non-response treated as acceptance.

(b) GAP FILLING.-- Where an existing cooperative enterprise achieves QFC
certification but does not itself provide all five components of the mandatory
baseline portfolio, the certifying cooperative shall enter into federated
resource-sharing agreements with neighboring Qualified Federated Networks to fill
the gaps within one hundred eighty days of certification, with Bootstrap Grant
funding available for the costs of establishing those arrangements pursuant to
Section 106(b)(4) of this Act.

(c) LEGACY GOVERNANCE STRUCTURES.-- Existing cooperatives that achieve
certification through the expedited pathway of Section 103(e)(1) of this Act may
retain governance structures that differ from the specific mechanisms described
in Section 102 of this Act, provided that those structures demonstrably fulfill
the functional requirements of each Ostrom Standard. The Office of Federated
Stewardship shall not require structural uniformity but shall require functional
compliance.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 212. MEMBERSHIP ADEQUACY REVIEW.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PERIODIC REVIEW.-- The adequacy of the Federated Commons Membership
framework -- including the mandatory baseline portfolio, the Guaranteed Provision
Standard, the portability provisions, and the governance rights architecture --
shall be subject to a comprehensive review not less than once every four years,
conducted by the IP Commons Governance Council in consultation with Commons
Members across all regions of the Federated Network.

(b) REVIEW PROCESS.-- The adequacy review shall be conducted through the
participatory governance tools established under Title VII of this Act,
specifically including Decidim-compatible deliberative platforms enabling Commons
Members to submit testimony, proposals, and assessments of the membership
framework's functioning in their communities. The review process shall be
conducted in all languages spoken by more than one percent of the Commons Member
population.

(c) OUTCOMES.-- Following each adequacy review, the IP Commons Governance
Council shall publish a comprehensive report on the National Resilience Ledger
and submit it to Congress, containing:

    (1) an assessment of whether the Guaranteed Provision Standard remains
    genuinely adequate to support a dignified material life across the geographic
    and demographic diversity of the Commons Member population;

    (2) an assessment of whether the governance rights architecture is
    functioning as intended, with particular attention to whether any categories
    of members are experiencing systematic exclusion from meaningful governance
    participation;

    (3) recommendations for legislative amendments, network governance reforms,
    or technical infrastructure improvements necessary to address identified
    inadequacies; and

    (4) a summary of the testimony and proposals submitted by Commons Members
    during the review process, disaggregated by region, demographic category, and
    thematic concern.


================================================================================
TITLE III -- THE FEDERATED LAND COMMONS
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the legal architecture by which land
-- the foundational material substrate of all human community -- is progressively
removed from the speculative market and placed under permanent community
stewardship through Community Land Trusts federated within the Qualified
Federated Network. Land held in the Federated Land Commons is not nationalized,
collectivized, or otherwise subject to governmental ownership or control. It is
held in perpetual stewardship by the communities that inhabit and depend upon it,
governed by democratic cooperative institutions under the Ostrom Standards of
Stewardship, and permanently protected from re-entry into speculative markets.
The Federated Land Commons does not abolish private property in the conventional
sense. It creates a superior form of community stewardship that provides
communities with a permanent alternative to speculative private ownership of
essential land, which better serves their material needs and long-term
resilience.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 301. COMMUNITY LAND TRUST LEGAL FRAMEWORK.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) LEGAL STATUS.-- Community Land Trusts operating within the Federated Network
shall be organized as nonprofit corporations or cooperative enterprises under
applicable state law, shall achieve certification as Qualified Federated
Cooperatives pursuant to Section 103 of Title I of this Act, and shall hold land
titles in perpetual stewardship pursuant to the requirements of this Section.
CLT legal status under this Act is in addition to and does not preempt any state
law governing nonprofit corporations, cooperative enterprises, or community land
trusts. The Office of Federated Stewardship shall consult the census of
community land trusts and shared equity programs maintained by Grounded Solutions
Network in establishing the initial Underserved Area map required under Section
105(b) of this Act, treating that census as the baseline documentation of
existing CLT coverage against which coverage gaps are measured; and shall enter
into a memorandum of understanding with Grounded Solutions Network within one
hundred eighty days of the Office's establishment to coordinate CLT practitioner
technical assistance resources with the OFS's certification support functions.

(b) PERPETUAL STEWARDSHIP REQUIREMENT.-- Land held by a Community Land Trust
pursuant to this Act shall be held in perpetual stewardship, meaning:

    (1) the CLT shall hold the land in trust for the benefit of its current and
    future members and the broader community within its defined boundaries, not as
    a financial asset to be leveraged, mortgaged, or speculated upon;

    (2) the CLT may not sell, transfer, or otherwise alienate land held in commons
    stewardship except:

        (A) to another Community Land Trust or Qualified Federated Cooperative
        operating within the Federated Network, for continued commons stewardship
        purposes;

        (B) to a governmental entity for a legitimate public purpose, subject to
        the anti-speculation protections of subsection (c) of this Section; or

        (C) pursuant to a court order issued upon a finding of extraordinary
        circumstances by a court of competent jurisdiction, subject to the
        requirement that any proceeds from such transfer be reinvested in the
        acquisition of equivalent land within the Federated Network;

    (3) the CLT shall maintain the land in productive use consistent with its
    stewardship obligations, which include at minimum the maintenance of housing,
    food production, ecological health, and community infrastructure functions
    appropriate to the land's characteristics and the community's needs; and

    (4) upon dissolution of a Community Land Trust, all land held in commons
    stewardship shall transfer automatically to the nearest certified Qualified
    Federated Network, and shall not revert to private ownership or governmental
    ownership under any circumstances.

(c) ANTI-SPECULATION PROVISIONS.--

    (1) GROUND LEASE STRUCTURE.-- All housing and productive enterprise occupying
    land held by a Community Land Trust shall be governed by a ground lease
    between the CLT and the occupying household or enterprise. The ground lease
    shall:

        (A) provide for permanent, secure tenure at a ground lease fee that
        reflects only the actual cost of land maintenance, ecological stewardship,
        and CLT administration, with no component constituting speculative land
        value rent;

        (B) include a limited-equity resale formula governing any equity
        accumulated by the occupying household or enterprise, ensuring that the
        occupant receives a fair return on improvements and long-term occupancy
        while the unit remains affordable to subsequent occupants at equivalent
        income levels;

        (C) prohibit the subletting or assignment of the ground lease at market
        rates, ensuring that the anti-speculation protection is not circumvented
        through informal rental arrangements; and

        (D) provide for reversion of the ground lease to the CLT upon the
        occupant's departure, with the CLT obligated to offer the vacated unit to
        the next eligible household at an equivalent affordable rate within ninety
        days.

    (2) PROHIBITION ON SPECULATIVE VALUATION.-- No land held in commons
    stewardship pursuant to this Act shall be assessed, appraised, or valued for
    any purpose -- including property taxation, eminent domain compensation, or
    financial reporting -- on the basis of speculative market value. The value of
    commons land for all such purposes shall be assessed on the basis of its use
    value -- the value of the specific productive, residential, and ecological
    functions it performs for the community -- and not on the basis of
    hypothetical market transactions.

(3) PROPERTY TAX TREATMENT.-- Land held in commons stewardship pursuant to
this Act is eligible for the Stewardship Payment in Lieu of Taxes program
established under subsection (d) of this Section. A state or local
jurisdiction that elects to exempt such land from property taxation shall
receive an annual federal payment equal to the property tax revenue the
jurisdiction would otherwise have collected on that land, calculated
pursuant to subsection (d) of this Section. No state or local jurisdiction
is required to exempt commons land from property taxation as a condition
of any provision of this Act, and nothing in this Section shall be
construed to preempt, displace, or limit the property tax authority of any
state or local government.

        (A) the purpose of property taxation is to capture a portion of the value
        created by public investment in community infrastructure for public
        benefit, and land held in commons stewardship already serves the public
        benefit directly and permanently;

        (B) property taxation of commons land creates a financial burden that, if
        unrelieved, would require the CLT to raise ground lease fees, undermining
        the affordability protection that is the commons land's primary public
        benefit; and

        (C) the Stewardship Credit issuance mechanism of Section 306 of this Act
        provides the federal government with a means of recognizing the public
        value of commons land without imposing a tax burden that would undermine
        that value.

(d) STEWARDSHIP PAYMENT IN LIEU OF TAXES PROGRAM.--

    (1) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established within the Department of the
    Treasury a Stewardship Payment in Lieu of Taxes program, administered
    in coordination with the Office of Federated Stewardship, to compensate
    state and local jurisdictions that elect to exempt commons land from
    property taxation pursuant to subsection (c)(3) of this Section.

    (2) ELECTION.-- A state or local jurisdiction electing to participate
    in the program established by this subsection shall notify the Office
    of Federated Stewardship of that election with respect to each parcel
    of commons land within its taxing jurisdiction. A jurisdiction's
    election under this paragraph is revocable at any time upon notice to
    the Office of Federated Stewardship, with the jurisdiction resuming
    ordinary property tax authority over the affected parcel from the date
    of revocation.

    (3) PAYMENT CALCULATION.-- The annual payment to an electing
    jurisdiction with respect to a parcel of commons land shall equal the
    five-year average annual property tax yield of that parcel, calculated
    using the same methodology established under Section 306(a)(1)(A) of
    this Act, adjusted annually for inflation using the Consumer Price
    Index published by the Bureau of Labor Statistics.

    (4) FUNDING.-- Payments under this subsection are authorized to be
    appropriated as provided in Section 1106 of Title XI of this Act, and
    shall not be subject to the five percent of estimated productive value
    cap established for Bootstrap Grant Program appropriations under
    Section 1106(c)(3) of that Title.

    (5) NO EFFECT ON STEWARDSHIP CREDIT ISSUANCE.-- Payments under this
    subsection are in addition to, and have no effect on, the Stewardship
    Credit issuance to the receiving Community Land Trust under Section
    306(a)(1) of this Act. The payments under this subsection compensate
    the taxing jurisdiction for foregone revenue, while the Stewardship
    Credit issuance under Section 306(a)(1) capitalizes the Community Land
    Trust itself, and the two mechanisms serve distinct purposes that do
    not offset one another.


