SEC. 302. FEDERAL SURPLUS LAND TRANSFER.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) IDENTIFICATION OF SURPLUS FEDERAL LAND.-- Within two hundred seventy days of
the date of enactment of this Act, the Secretary of the Interior, in
consultation with the Secretary of Agriculture, the Secretary of Defense, the
Secretary of Housing and Urban Development, and the heads of all other federal
agencies holding land, shall complete a comprehensive inventory of all federally
owned or controlled land and shall identify as Surplus Federal Land all parcels
that:

    (1) are not currently in active use for a critical federal mission, defined as
    national defense operations, active law enforcement functions, critical
    infrastructure operation, or ongoing scientific research requiring the
    specific parcel;

    (2) are not designated as National Parks, National Monuments, Wilderness
    Areas, or other protected natural areas whose protection serves a recognized
    public interest;

    (3) have not been identified for transfer to state or local governments under
    existing federal land disposal programs that are actively progressing toward
    completion; and

    (4) have productive potential for residential, agricultural, renewable energy,
    or ecological restoration uses consistent with the purposes of this Act.

(b) PRIORITY CATEGORIES.-- Within the inventory of Surplus Federal Land, the
following categories shall be designated as Priority Transfer Parcels for
expedited transfer to Community Land Trusts pursuant to subsection (c) of this
Section:

    (1) federally owned land within or adjacent to designated Underserved Areas
    as defined in Section 105(b) of this Act;

    (2) former federal correctional facility sites being decommissioned
    through any applicable Federal decommissioning process, including any
    such process later established by Federal law for that purpose;

    (3) former military base sites identified for closure under the Base
    Realignment and Closure process and not required for the military-civilian
    strategic sync purposes of Title IX of this Act;

    (4) federally owned urban and suburban land currently held by the General
    Services Administration as excess property;

    (5) federally owned agricultural land currently leased to commercial
    agricultural enterprises at below-market rates; and

    (6) federally owned land within tribal territories or adjacent to tribal
    communities, subject to the tribal consultation requirements of Section
    105(c)(4) of this Act.

    (7) federal land located within, adjacent to, or formerly comprising
    part of the documented historical land base of a community for which a
    Reparative Justice Commission established under the Human Reclamation
    and Community Restorative Act, or any comparable body later
    established by Federal law for that purpose, has issued a finding
    documenting the loss of land as a component of harm experienced by
    that community, with priority within this category given to parcels
    most proximate to the community's documented historical land base.

(c) TRANSFER PROCESS.--

    (1) TRANSFER AUTHORITY.-- The Secretary of the Interior is hereby authorized
    and directed to transfer Surplus Federal Land identified pursuant to
    subsection (a) of this Section to certified Community Land Trusts operating
    within Qualified Federated Networks, without requirement of monetary
    consideration from the receiving CLT, subject to the perpetual stewardship
    conditions of Section 301(b) of this Act and the reversion provisions of
    paragraph (4) of this subsection.

    (2) TRANSFER PRIORITIZATION.-- Transfers of Priority Transfer Parcels shall
    be completed within three hundred sixty-five days of the completion of the
    inventory required by subsection (a) of this Section. Transfers of remaining
    Surplus Federal Land shall be completed within five years of that date,
    subject to the availability of certified CLTs capable of stewarding the
    transferred parcels.

    (3) MATCHING PROCESS.-- Where no certified CLT exists within or adjacent to a
    Surplus Federal Land parcel at the time the parcel is identified for transfer,
    the Office of Federated Stewardship shall conduct targeted outreach and
    provide enhanced Bootstrap Grants pursuant to Sections 105(c)(2) and
    106(b)(4) of this Act to support the formation of a CLT capable of receiving
    and stewarding the parcel within three years.

    (4) REVERSION CONDITIONS.-- Land transferred to a CLT pursuant to this
    Section shall be subject to a deed restriction providing that if the receiving
    CLT is decertified pursuant to Section 103(c)(2)(D) of this Act and no
    neighboring Qualified Federated Network assumes stewardship within one hundred
    eighty days, the land shall revert to federal ownership for subsequent
    transfer to another CLT, and shall not under any circumstances revert to
    private ownership.

    (5) ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION.-- Where a Surplus Federal Land parcel requires
    environmental remediation prior to productive use -- including former
    industrial sites, contaminated military installations, or degraded
    agricultural land -- the transfer of the parcel shall be accompanied by a
    federal remediation commitment sufficient to bring the parcel to a condition
    suitable for the intended commons stewardship use, with remediation costs
    borne by the federal government and not passed to the receiving CLT.

