SEC. 303. RIGHT OF FIRST REFUSAL.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is hereby established a federal Right of First
Refusal for certified Qualified Federated Cooperatives and Qualified Federated
Networks with respect to the sale of residential and commercial property by
corporate entities, providing these commons institutions the first opportunity to
purchase such property before it is offered to other buyers in the speculative
market.

(b) SCOPE.-- The Right of First Refusal established by this Section shall apply
to any sale, transfer, or other disposition of:

    (1) multi-family residential property comprising five or more dwelling units,
    owned in whole or in part by a corporate entity -- defined as any entity other
    than a natural person or a certified Qualified Federated Cooperative --
    regardless of whether the corporate entity is a for-profit or nonprofit
    organization;

    (2) commercial or industrial property of one acre or more in size, owned in
    whole or in part by a corporate entity; and

    (3) agricultural land of five acres or more, owned in whole or in part by a
    corporate entity, with particular priority given to parcels currently leased
    to tenant farmers or used for community-supported agriculture.

(c) NOTICE REQUIREMENT.-- Any corporate entity intending to sell, transfer, or
otherwise dispose of property subject to this Section shall provide written
notice to:

    (1) the Office of Federated Stewardship, which shall publish the notice on
    the National Resilience Ledger within five business days of receipt;

    (2) any certified Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated
    Network whose defined geographic boundaries include or are adjacent to the
    subject property; and

    (3) any tenant households or cooperative enterprises currently occupying the
    subject property, who shall have independent rights under this Section as
    provided in subsection (e) of this Section.

(d) EXERCISE PERIOD.-- Upon receipt of notice pursuant to subsection (c) of this
Section, any eligible Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated
Network shall have ninety days to exercise the Right of First Refusal by
delivering to the selling entity:

    (1) a written notice of intent to purchase, specifying the exercising entity's
    certification status and its intention to hold the property in commons
    stewardship pursuant to Section 301 of this Act; and

    (2) evidence of financing commitment sufficient to complete the purchase at
    the price and on the terms offered to other prospective buyers, which may
    include a commitment of acquisition support through the Commons Infrastructure
    Capitalization Fund pursuant to Section 306(b)(3) of this Act or through
    Bootstrap Grant supplementation pursuant to Section 106 of this Act.

(e) TENANT RIGHT OF FIRST REFUSAL.-- In addition to the institutional Right of
First Refusal established in subsection (a) of this Section, tenant households
currently occupying residential property subject to this Section shall have an
independent Right of First Refusal, exercisable either individually or
collectively through a tenant cooperative formed for the purpose of acquiring the
property. The tenant Right of First Refusal shall:

    (1) be exercisable during the same ninety-day period as the institutional
    Right of First Refusal, with the tenant cooperative's exercise taking
    precedence over an institutional exercise where both are timely made;

    (2) be supported by technical assistance from the Office of Federated
    Stewardship in forming a tenant cooperative, achieving QFC certification, and
    securing acquisition support through the Commons Infrastructure Capitalization
    Fund pursuant to Section 306(b)(3) of this Act within the exercise period; and

    (3) not be conditioned on the tenant cooperative's prior QFC certification,
    provided that the cooperative commits to seeking certification within one
    hundred eighty days of completing the purchase, with Bootstrap Grant funding
    available for the certification costs pursuant to Section 106(b)(2) of this
    Act.

(f) PURCHASE PRICE.-- The purchase price payable by an exercising Qualified
Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network upon exercise of the Right
of First Refusal shall be the price offered to other prospective buyers, as
stated in the notice provided pursuant to subsection (c) of this Section.
Provided, however:

    (1) an exercising entity may, within thirty days of delivering its notice
    of intent to purchase pursuant to subsection (d)(1) of this Section, petition
    the Federated Accountability Board for a use-value determination on the grounds
    that the offered price includes a speculative premium substantially in excess
    of the property's assessed use value as determined pursuant to Section
    301(c)(2) of this Act. The petition shall toll the exercise period for not
    more than forty-five additional days;

    (2) where the Federated Accountability Board grants a use-value determination,
    the exercising entity may elect to purchase at the assessed use value; the
    selling entity shall thereupon have the right to decline the sale at use value
    and withdraw the property from the market for a period of not less than two
    years, during which the Right of First Refusal obligations of this Section
    shall continue to apply to any subsequent offer to sell; and

    (3) no exercising entity shall be compelled to pay any amount in excess of
    the price offered to other prospective buyers, and no selling entity shall be
    compelled to sell at assessed use value in lieu of withdrawing the property
    from sale pursuant to paragraph (2) of this subsection.

(g) ENFORCEMENT.-- Any sale, transfer, or other disposition of property subject
to this Section made in violation of the notice requirements of subsection (c) or
the exercise rights of subsections (d) and (e) shall be:

    (1) voidable at the election of any Qualified Federated Cooperative or
    Qualified Federated Network whose Right of First Refusal was violated,
    exercisable within two years of the date on which the violation came to the
    entity's attention;

    (2) subject to civil penalties of not less than twenty percent of the
    property's sale price, payable to the Bootstrap Grant Program fund established
    under Section 106 of this Act; and

    (3) subject to injunctive relief in any federal court of competent
    jurisdiction upon application of any affected Qualified Federated Cooperative,
    Qualified Federated Network, or tenant household.

