SEC. 304. COOPERATIVE BUSINESS CONVERSION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PURPOSE.-- This Section establishes mechanisms for the conversion of existing
privately owned businesses to worker cooperative ownership and Qualified Federated
Cooperative status, addressing both the demonstrated preference of many business
owners for a dignified succession that preserves their enterprise's contribution
to the community, and the broader goal of progressively transitioning productive
enterprise from extractive private ownership to democratic commons stewardship.

(b) THE SUCCESSION CRISIS OPPORTUNITY.-- Congress finds that a significant
proportion of small and medium-sized business owners in the United States are
approaching retirement age without an identified succession plan, and that the
absence of accessible cooperative conversion pathways has resulted in the
unnecessary closure, acquisition by private equity, or asset stripping of
enterprises whose employees, customers, and communities would be better served by
conversion to worker cooperative ownership. The mechanisms established by this
Section are designed to make cooperative conversion the most accessible,
financially attractive, and logistically supported succession option available to
retiring business owners.

(c) RIGHT OF FIRST OFFER -- EMPLOYEE BUYOUT.--

    (1) ESTABLISHMENT.-- Any business owner who intends to sell, transfer, or
    close a business employing five or more persons shall, before making the
    business available to other buyers or taking steps toward closure, provide the
    business's employees with a Right of First Offer -- the first opportunity to
    make an offer to purchase the business as a worker cooperative.

    (2) NOTICE.-- The business owner shall provide written notice of their intent
    to sell, transfer, or close the business to all employees not less than one
    hundred eighty days before the intended sale, transfer, or closure date. The
    notice shall include a description of the business's assets, liabilities, and
    recent financial performance sufficient for the employees to make an informed
    assessment of the cooperative conversion opportunity.

    (3) EMPLOYEE RESPONSE PERIOD.-- Employees shall have one hundred twenty days
    from receipt of notice to organize a worker cooperative, seek QFC
    certification, and make a bona fide offer to purchase the business. The
    Office of Federated Stewardship shall provide technical assistance for
    cooperative formation and Commons Infrastructure Capitalization Fund
    acquisition support applications during this period pursuant to Section
    107(c)(4) of this Act.

    (4) GOOD FAITH NEGOTIATION.-- The business owner shall negotiate in good faith
    with the employee cooperative during the response period. The business owner
    is not required to accept the employees' offer, but shall not sell the
    business to another buyer at a price equal to or lower than the employees'
    offer without first offering the employees the opportunity to match that
    price.

(d) COMMONS ACQUISITION SUPPORT FOR COOPERATIVE CONVERSION.-- Worker cooperatives
seeking to purchase a business pursuant to this Section shall be eligible for
acquisition support through the Commons Infrastructure Capitalization Fund
established under Section 306(b)(3) of this Act, on the following terms:

    (1) interest rate of zero percent;

    (2) repayment denominated in Commons Credits at the rate established under
    Section 306(b)(2)(A) of this Act, ensuring that as the commons economy matures
    repayment is discharged through commons productive output rather than through
    dollar revenue;

    (3) no personal guarantee required from individual worker-members;

    (4) acquisition support security limited to the assets of the cooperative
    enterprise itself; and

    (5) a two-year deferral period during which no repayment is required,
    allowing the cooperative to stabilize operations following conversion.

(e) TAX TREATMENT OF COOPERATIVE CONVERSION.--

    (1) SELLER INCENTIVES.-- A business owner who sells their business to a worker
    cooperative pursuant to this Section shall be eligible for:

        (A) deferral of capital gains tax on the proceeds of the sale for a period
        of ten years, provided the proceeds are reinvested in commons-compatible
        assets -- including Community Land Trust ground leases, Commons Financial
        Node accounts, or IP Commons contributions -- within two years of the
        sale;

        (B) a Legacy Credit, as defined in subsection (f) of this Section,
        recognizing the owner's contribution to the commons economy; and

        (C) a partial exclusion from estate taxation on the deferred capital
        gains, where the business owner dies during the deferral period, in
        recognition of the owner's decision to prioritize community benefit over
        maximum financial extraction.

    (2) COOPERATIVE TAX TREATMENT.-- Worker cooperatives certified as Qualified
    Federated Cooperatives pursuant to this Act shall be treated as pass-through
    entities for federal income tax purposes, with income and losses passing
    through to individual worker-members in proportion to their patronage, and
    shall additionally be eligible for:

        (A) a deduction for the full amount of wages and benefits paid to
        worker-members, including the imputed value of Guaranteed Provision
        Standard provisions received through Federated Commons Membership;

        (B) a deduction for contributions to the IP Commons and the Data Commons;
        and

        (C) exemption from the corporate alternative minimum tax.

(f) LEGACY CREDITS.--

    (1) DEFINITION.-- A Legacy Credit is a non-transferable, non-monetary
    recognition granted to individuals and entities that make substantial
    contributions to the Federated Land Commons or the broader commons economy,
    acknowledging their role as founding stewards of the commons and providing
    them with defined governance participation rights in the network.

    (2) AWARD.-- Legacy Credits shall be awarded to:

        (A) business owners who sell their enterprises to worker cooperatives
        pursuant to this Section;

        (B) landowners who voluntarily contribute land to Community Land Trusts
        pursuant to Section 305 of this Act;

        (C) corporate entities that contribute intellectual property to the IP
        Commons pursuant to Title V of this Act; and

        (D) such other contributors as the IP Commons Governance Council
        determines have made extraordinary contributions to the commons economy.

    (3) BENEFITS.-- Legacy Credit holders shall be entitled to:

        (A) a permanent, non-transferable Founding Steward designation on the
        National Resilience Ledger, recognizing their contribution to the commons
        economy for the historical record;

        (B) a non-voting advisory seat on the governance council of the Qualified
        Federated Network within whose geographic boundaries their contribution
        was made, for a period of ten years from the date of the Legacy Credit
        award; and

        (C) priority access to advanced IP Commons resources and technical
        infrastructure for research and development purposes, for a period of ten
        years from the date of the Legacy Credit award.

    (4) LIMITATIONS.-- Legacy Credits do not confer voting rights in any
    Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network, do not
    provide access to the Guaranteed Provision Standard without active Federated
    Commons Membership, and do not create any financial claim against any commons
    asset. Legacy Credits are recognition of contribution, not compensation for
    it.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 305. VOLUNTARY LAND CONTRIBUTION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) CONTRIBUTION PATHWAY.-- Any natural person or legal entity holding title to
land may voluntarily contribute that land to a Community Land Trust operating
within a Qualified Federated Network at any time. Voluntary land contributions
shall be:

    (1) irrevocable upon recording of the deed transfer on the National Resilience
    Ledger;

    (2) eligible for the property tax treatment established under Section 301(c)(3)
    of this Act from the date of contribution;

    (3) recognized with a Legacy Credit pursuant to Section 304(f) of this Act;
    and

    (4) eligible for a charitable contribution deduction under the Internal
    Revenue Code equal to the full fair market value of the contributed land,
    without reduction for the limited-equity restrictions imposed by CLT
    stewardship, in recognition of the permanent public benefit created by the
    contribution.

(b) CORPORATE LAND CONTRIBUTION -- LEGACY SWAP.-- Corporate entities holding
large-scale land portfolios may contribute land to the Federated Land Commons
through a Legacy Swap arrangement, under which:

    (1) the corporate entity transfers title to defined land parcels to one or
    more Community Land Trusts in exchange for Legacy Credits and the tax benefits
    of subsection (a) of this Section;

    (2) the transfer is structured to minimize disruption to existing tenants and
    occupants of the contributed parcels, with all existing residential tenancies
    converting to CLT ground leases at the contributed land's use value rate
    within one year of the transfer;

    (3) the corporate entity receives a Founding Steward designation and advisory
    governance participation rights as provided in Section 304(f)(3) of this Act;
    and

    (4) the corporate entity is recognized on the National Resilience Ledger as a
    contributing institution, with its contribution permanently recorded as part
    of the commons governance history.

(c) ANTI-COERCION PROVISION.-- No provision of this Act shall be construed to
require any natural person or legal entity to contribute land to a Community Land
Trust. Voluntary land contribution under this Section is entirely elective. This
Act provides incentives for voluntary contribution and mechanisms for the
purchase of land through the Right of First Refusal and the Commons
Infrastructure Capitalization Fund, but does not authorize the involuntary 
transfer of privately held land to the commons except through the eminent domain 
provisions of existing federal law exercised for legitimate public purposes and 
subject to just compensation.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 306. THE NATIONAL RESILIENCE LEDGER -- LAND FUNCTIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STEWARDSHIP CREDIT ISSUANCE.-- The National Resilience Ledger shall perform
the following land-related functions pursuant to this Title:

    (1) AUTOMATED STEWARDSHIP CREDIT ISSUANCE.-- Upon the recording of a land
    title transfer to a Community Land Trust on the National Resilience Ledger --
    whether through federal surplus land transfer pursuant to Section 302,
    exercise of the Right of First Refusal pursuant to Section 303, cooperative
    business conversion pursuant to Section 304, or voluntary land contribution
    pursuant to Section 305 -- the National Resilience Ledger shall automatically
    issue Stewardship Credits to the receiving CLT's account in an amount
    calculated as follows:

        (A) the base issuance amount shall equal one hundred twenty percent of
        the five-year average annual property tax yield of the transferred parcel,
        calculated from the most recent five years of property tax records
        preceding the transfer;

        (B) where the transferred parcel is located in a designated Underserved
        Area pursuant to Section 105(b) of this Act, the base issuance amount
        shall be increased by fifty percent;

        (C) where the transferred parcel is located in a designated Priority
        Underserved Area, the base issuance amount shall be increased by one
        hundred percent; and

        (D) where the transferred parcel contains agricultural land with
        documented soil health degradation requiring restoration, an additional
        issuance of Stewardship Credits sufficient to fund the ecological
        restoration measures recommended by the USDA Natural Resources
        Conservation Service shall be included.

    (2) RATIONALE.-- The Stewardship Credit issuance mechanism is designed to
    replace the extractive financial logic of property taxation with a
    commons-reinforcing financial logic. Property taxation of commons land, 
    addressed through the elective exemption and Stewardship Payment in Lieu of 
    Taxes mechanism of Section 301(c)(3) and (d) of this Act -- would otherwise 
    impose a financial burden that undermines the affordability protection the 
    commons provides. The Stewardship Credit issuance provides the CLT with 
    liquidity equivalent to the tax revenue the land previously generated, 
    ensuring that the transition to commons stewardship is financially
    self-sustaining rather than dependent on recurring appropriations.

(b) COMMONS LAND ASSET RECOGNITION.--

    (1) NATURE OF THE MECHANISM.-- The acquisition of land by a Community Land
    Trust pursuant to Sections 303 and 304 of this Act is hereby recognized as
    the creation of a permanent productive commons asset. The mechanism established
    by this subsection is not a loan. It is an act of asset recognition: the
    National Resilience Ledger, upon recording a land title transfer to a CLT,
    issues Stewardship Credits against the assessed productive and social value of
    the land entering commons stewardship. No repayment obligation attaches to
    Stewardship Credits issued pursuant to this subsection. The land itself is the
    asset; the Stewardship Credits are the commons economy's acknowledgment of
    that asset's existence and value.

    (2) ISSUANCE FOR ACQUISITION COSTS.-- Where a Qualified Federated Cooperative
    or Qualified Federated Network incurs acquisition costs in bringing land into
    commons stewardship pursuant to Sections 303 and 304 of this Act, whether
    through purchase, exercise of the Right of First Refusal, or cooperative
    business conversion, the National Resilience Ledger shall issue Acquisition
    Stewardship Credits in addition to the automated Stewardship Credit issuance
    of subsection (a) of this Section. Acquisition Stewardship Credits shall be
    issued as follows:

        (A) the issuance amount shall equal the documented acquisition cost of
        the parcel, denominated in Commons Credits at the exchange rate established
        by the Commons Credit Governance Council pursuant to Section 608(c)(3) of
        Title VI of this Act at the time of acquisition, or, during the transition
        period preceding the establishment of a functioning Commons Credit exchange
        rate, in United States dollars through the Commons Infrastructure
        Capitalization Fund established under paragraph (3) of this subsection;

        (B) Acquisition Stewardship Credits are issued against the productive value
        of the land entering stewardship and carry no repayment obligation,
        interest, or maturity date; the land's permanent removal from the
        speculative market constitutes the full consideration for the issuance;

        (C) where the acquisition cost exceeds the assessed productive value of
        the parcel -- as may occur where speculative market pricing has inflated
        land values above their use value -- the Commons Credit Governance Council
        shall determine the appropriate issuance amount, which shall not exceed
        the assessed productive value, with any shortfall addressed through
        Bootstrap Grant supplementation pursuant to Section 106 of this Act; and

        (D) Acquisition Stewardship Credits may be used by the receiving entity
        solely for the purposes established in Section 603(c) of Title VI of this
        Act and may not be converted to United States dollars, transferred to any
        party outside the Federated Network, or used as collateral for any
        dollar-denominated obligation.

    (3) COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE CAPITALIZATION FUND.-- There is hereby established
    within the Department of the Treasury a Commons Infrastructure Capitalization
    Fund, to provide dollar-denominated acquisition support for land purchases
    during the transition period preceding the maturation of the Commons Credit
    economy. The Fund shall:

        (A) be capitalized through the appropriations authorized under Section
        1106 of this Act, and shall not depend on Federal Reserve operations for
        its funding or operation;

        (B) provide acquisition support to certified Qualified Federated
        Cooperatives and Qualified Federated Networks through Commons Financial
        Nodes registered pursuant to Section 4(3) of this Act, on terms of zero
        percent interest and with repayment denominated in Commons Credits at the
        rate established under subparagraph (A) of paragraph (2) of this
        subsection, such that as the commons economy matures and Commons Credits
        become the primary medium of exchange, the repayment obligation
        progressively converts from a dollar-denominated to a commons-denominated
        obligation, and is ultimately discharged through commons productive output
        rather than through dollar revenue;

        (C) treat all disbursements as investments in permanent commons
        infrastructure rather than as conventional debt, with the Fund's financial
        statements reflecting the productive value of land in commons stewardship
        as an asset of equivalent standing to the disbursement made to acquire it;

        (D) be administered by career civil servants of the Department of the
        Treasury without dependence on Federal Reserve Board discretion, ensuring
        that the land acquisition mechanism functions regardless of the composition
        or monetary policy posture of the Federal Reserve Board of Governors; and

        (E) sunset automatically upon the Commons Credit Governance Council
        certifying to the Secretary of the Treasury that the Commons Credit
        exchange infrastructure established under Title VI of this Act is
        sufficient to denominate all new land acquisitions entirely in Commons
        Credits without dollar-denominated bridge support.

(c) LAND COMMONS REGISTRY.-- The National Resilience Ledger shall maintain a
publicly accessible registry of all land held in commons stewardship pursuant to
this Act, including:

    (1) the legal description and geographic location of each parcel;

    (2) the name and certification status of the CLT holding the parcel in
    stewardship;

    (3) the date and mechanism of transfer to commons stewardship;

    (4) the current use of the parcel and the number of Commons Members receiving
    provisions from it;

    (5) the ecological health metrics of the parcel, as reported through the
    CLT's Peer-to-Peer Audit self-reporting; and

    (6) any deed restrictions, reversion conditions, or other encumbrances on the
    parcel.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 307. ANTI-SPECULATION AND COMMONS PERMANENCE PROVISIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PROHIBITION ON RE-ENTRY INTO SPECULATIVE MARKETS.-- Land once transferred to
commons stewardship pursuant to this Act shall be permanently and irrevocably
removed from the speculative real estate market. Specifically:

    (1) no Community Land Trust shall mortgage, hypothecate, or otherwise use
    commons land as collateral for any dollar-denominated debt obligation, provided
    that acquisition support received through the Commons Infrastructure
    Capitalization Fund pursuant to Section 306(b)(3) of this Act does not
    constitute a mortgage or hypothecation for purposes of this paragraph, the land
    remaining unencumbered commons stewardship property throughout;

    (2) no commons land shall be subject to foreclosure, tax sale, or any other
    involuntary transfer mechanism that would result in its re-entry into private
    ownership, with the federal government bearing residual obligation to ensure
    that commons land remains in commons stewardship through the mechanisms of
    Section 302(c)(4) of this Act if a CLT becomes unable to maintain its
    stewardship obligations; and

    (3) no amendment to a CLT's governing documents that would remove or weaken
    the anti-speculation protections of this Section shall be effective unless
    approved by a supermajority of not less than seventy-five percent of the
    CLT's membership through its collective-choice processes and ratified by the
    regional federation governance layer.

(b) COMMONS PERMANENCE ASSETS.-- The following categories of land and
land-based resources are hereby designated as Commons Permanence Assets pursuant
to Section 4(5) of this Act and shall be subject to the most stringent
protection against alienation and external trade:

    (1) agricultural land with documented soil health sufficient to support food
    production for the local community;

    (2) freshwater sources, watersheds, and riparian corridors within or adjacent
    to CLT land holdings;

    (3) seed stocks, plant genetic resources, and traditional agricultural
    knowledge associated with food production on commons land;

    (4) old-growth forest, wetland, and other ecologically critical land within
    CLT holdings; and

    (5) land currently used for housing Commons Members, the stewardship of which
    is essential to the delivery of the housing component of the Guaranteed
    Provision Standard.

(c) REVERSION CLAUSES.-- Every deed transferring land to commons stewardship
pursuant to this Act shall contain a reversion clause providing that:

    (1) if the receiving CLT is dissolved, decertified, or otherwise becomes
    unable to fulfill its stewardship obligations, the land shall transfer
    automatically to the nearest certified Qualified Federated Network for
    continued commons stewardship;

    (2) if no certified Qualified Federated Network is available to receive the
    land within one hundred eighty days of the CLT's dissolution or
    decertification, the land shall revert to federal ownership for safekeeping
    pending transfer to a new certified CLT formed through the mechanisms of
    Section 302(c)(3) of this Act; and

    (3) under no circumstances shall commons land revert to the private ownership
    of any individual, corporation, or non-commons entity.

(d) PROVISION PRIORITY RULE FOR EXTERNAL RESOURCE TRADE.-- In recognition of the
risk that federated networks might divert commons resources to external markets
for financial gain at the expense of their members' provisions, the following
rule shall govern the external trade of land-based resources:

    (1) no Commons Permanence Asset may be sold, traded, or otherwise transferred
    to any party outside the Federated Network under any circumstances;

    (2) surplus land-based resources -- defined as resources produced on commons
    land in excess of the amount required to meet the Guaranteed Provision
    Standard of all current Commons Members -- may be traded with other Qualified
    Federated Networks through commons-to-commons exchange at use value rates,
    without the intervention of market pricing mechanisms;

    (3) surplus land-based resources may be sold into the external market economy
    only upon:

        (A) a finding by the QFN's collective-choice governance process that all
        Commons Members' provision standards are fully met and that a genuine
        surplus exists above any reasonable reserve requirement;

        (B) a determination that no neighboring Qualified Federated Network has an
        unmet need for the surplus resources, making commons-to-commons exchange
        the preferred disposition; and

        (C) a commitment that the proceeds of any external sale are reinvested in
        the commons -- in land acquisition, infrastructure improvement, provision
        standard enhancement, or Bootstrap Grant contribution -- and are not
        distributed as private profit to any individual member or officer;

    (4) any external sale of surplus resources that violates the conditions of
    paragraph (3) of this subsection shall constitute a serious violation of
    Standard 2 -- Local Congruence -- of the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship,
    subject to Level 2 graduated response under Section 103(c)(2)(B) of this Act;
    and

    (5) systematic or repeated violation of the provision priority rule shall
    constitute grounds for Level 3 or Level 4 sanctions under Section 103(c)(2)
    of this Act.


================================================================================
TITLE IV -- THE FEDERATED DATA COMMONS
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the legal architecture by which data
-- the collectively produced informational substrate of the commons economy --
is governed as a common-pool resource rather than as a commodity to be
extracted, enclosed, and sold. Data generated by Commons Members in the course
of their lives, their cooperative participation, and their creative and
productive work belongs to those who generate it. The Federated Data Commons
does not prohibit the use of data for legitimate commons governance purposes. It
prohibits the enclosure of data -- its capture by private parties for extraction,
surveillance, and behavioral manipulation -- and establishes the community data
trust as the governance institution through which data is stewarded for
collective benefit. The architecture of this Title is designed from its
foundations to prevent the reproduction within the commons of the surveillance
capitalism model it is designed to replace.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 401. DATA SOVEREIGNTY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FOUNDATIONAL PRINCIPLE.-- Personal data generated by a Commons Member is an
inalienable attribute of that member's personhood. It is not property in the
conventional sense -- it cannot be owned, bought, or sold by any party other
than its generator -- but it carries enforceable rights of control, privacy, and
governance that this Title establishes and protects.

(b) INALIENABILITY.-- The data sovereignty rights established by this Title are
inalienable, meaning:

    (1) no Commons Member may permanently waive their data sovereignty rights
    through contract, terms of service agreement, or any other legal instrument,
    provided that a member may grant revocable, specific, and time-limited consent
    to defined data uses as provided in Section 403 of this Title;

    (2) no Qualified Federated Cooperative, Qualified Federated Network,
    governmental authority, or private party may acquire ownership of a Commons
    Member's personal data through any mechanism, including purchase, inheritance,
    corporate acquisition, or governmental seizure except as provided in Section
    209(e) of this Act;

    (3) data sovereignty rights survive the Commons Member's death for a period of
    fifty years, during which they vest in the member's designated beneficiary or,
    in the absence of a designation, in the commons data trust of the network in
    which the member held their most recent active membership; and

    (4) data sovereignty rights are not diminished by the Commons Member's
    participation in any commons governance process, cooperative enterprise, or
    provision delivery system, except through the specific, revocable consent
    mechanisms of Section 403 of this Title.

(c) DEFINITION OF PERSONAL DATA.-- For the purposes of this Title, personal data
means any information that relates to, describes, or could reasonably be used to
identify a specific natural person, including:

    (1) identity information -- legal name, pseudonymous identity, biometric
    characteristics, and cryptographic identity;

    (2) location information -- geographic position, movement patterns, and
    residential and workplace addresses;

    (3) behavioral information -- consumption patterns, browsing and interaction
    history, purchasing behavior, and activity patterns;

    (4) communications -- the content and metadata of private communications
    through any medium;

    (5) health information -- medical records, health status, mental health
    information, substance use history, and genetic information;

    (6) financial information -- Commons Credit balances and transaction
    histories, income and asset information, and debt obligations;

    (7) social information -- family composition, associational relationships,
    political and religious affiliations, and community memberships; and

    (8) creative and productive information -- the content of creative works prior
    to voluntary IP Commons contribution, work product, and professional
    activities.

(d) DISTINCTION FROM COMMONS RESOURCE DATA.-- Personal data as defined in
subsection (c) of this Section is categorically distinct from Commons Resource
Data -- information about the health, availability, and utilization of shared
commons resources -- which is appropriately transparent within the network for
Asynchronous Resource Coordination and Peer-to-Peer Audit purposes. The
distinction shall be maintained as follows:

    (1) Commons Resource Data is aggregated and anonymized at the point of
    collection, such that no individual Commons Member's personal data contributes
    identifiably to any commons resource metric;

    (2) where the aggregation of individual data points is technically necessary
    to produce a commons resource metric, the aggregation shall occur through
    privacy-preserving computation methods -- including secure multi-party
    computation, differential privacy, and Zero-Knowledge Proofs pursuant to
    Section 4(22) of this Act -- that produce the required aggregate without
    exposing any individual's data;

    (3) any system that cannot produce the required commons resource metric
    without exposing individual personal data shall not be deployed within the
    Federated Network until a privacy-preserving alternative is available; and

    (4) the boundary between personal data and Commons Resource Data shall be
    governed by the Data Commons Governance Council established under Section 405
    of this Title, which shall publish clear definitional guidelines and update
    them as technology and network practices evolve.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 402. CATEGORIES OF DATA PROTECTION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) THREE-TIER PROTECTION ARCHITECTURE.-- Data within the Federated Network
shall be governed under a three-tier protection architecture that calibrates
privacy protections to the sensitivity of the data and the legitimate governance
purposes served by its use:

    (1) TIER 1 -- COMMONS GOVERNANCE DATA.-- Data about shared resources,
    infrastructure, and productive outputs that is appropriately transparent
    within the network for collective governance purposes, subject to the
    aggregation and anonymization requirements of Section 401(d) of this Title;

    (2) TIER 2 -- PERSONAL PROVISION DATA.-- Data about an individual Commons
    Member's membership status, provisions, and contributions record, held in the
    member's custody through their Commons Membership Record pursuant to Section
    209 of this Act, disclosed only with the member's active consent through
    Zero-Knowledge Proof verification, and never accessible to other Commons
    Members without consent; and

    (3) TIER 3 -- SENSITIVE PERSONAL INFORMATION.-- The most protected category,
    comprising health data, mental health data, substance use data, family
    composition data, sexual orientation and gender identity data, immigration
    status data, political and religious affiliation data, and any other data
    whose disclosure could expose the Commons Member to discrimination, violence,
    or other serious harm.

(b) TIER 1 GOVERNANCE DATA -- STANDARDS.-- Commons Governance Data shall be:

    (1) collected only for defined commons governance purposes -- resource
    coordination, Peer-to-Peer Audit compliance monitoring, and collective
    decision-making support -- and not for any other purpose;

    (2) aggregated and anonymized as required by Section 401(d) of this Title
    before publication on the National Resilience Ledger;

    (3) governed by the Data Commons Governance Council pursuant to Section 405
    of this Title, which shall establish and maintain clear data minimization
    standards specifying the minimum data collection necessary for each defined
    governance purpose; and

    (4) subject to automatic deletion on a schedule established by the Data
    Commons Governance Council once the governance purpose for which the data was
    collected has been fulfilled, unless the data has been aggregated and
    anonymized in a form that no longer constitutes personal data.

(c) TIER 2 PERSONAL PROVISION DATA -- STANDARDS.-- Personal Provision Data shall
be:

    (1) held exclusively in the individual Commons Member's custody through their
    Commons Membership Record, with no centralized copy maintained by any network
    institution or governmental authority;

    (2) disclosed to other parties only through Zero-Knowledge Proof verification
    that confirms the binary fact of active membership without revealing any
    underlying data;

    (3) updated and corrected by the Commons Member at any time through their
    cryptographic identity, with corrections recorded on the National Resilience
    Ledger without deletion of the prior record, ensuring auditability of the
    member's own data history; and

    (4) portable -- upon the Commons Member's request, their complete Personal
    Provision Data shall be exportable in a machine-readable, open-standard format
    within forty-eight hours, for use at any Qualified Federated Network or in any
    external context the member chooses.

(d) TIER 3 SENSITIVE PERSONAL INFORMATION -- STANDARDS.-- Sensitive Personal
Information shall be:

    (1) never contributed to any commons data pool, aggregate metric, or shared
    governance dataset under any circumstances, regardless of anonymization
    claims;

    (2) held exclusively by the individual Commons Member, or where the member has
    explicitly consented, by their healthcare cooperative provider, legal
    representative, or other specifically designated trusted party, under strict
    fiduciary obligations established under subsection (e) of this Section;

    (3) never accessible to law enforcement authorities except pursuant to the
    heightened warrant standard of Section 209(e)(3) of this Act;

    (4) never used as a basis for any commons governance determination, provision
    delivery decision, or sanctions proceeding, except where the member has
    explicitly consented to its use for a specific defined purpose; and

    (5) subject to the right of erasure -- the Commons Member's right to require
    the permanent deletion of their Sensitive Personal Information from any system
    in which it has been stored with their prior consent, exercisable at any time
    and without any obligation to provide a reason.

(e) FIDUCIARY DATA OBLIGATIONS.-- Any party that holds a Commons Member's Tier 2
or Tier 3 data pursuant to a consent-based disclosure under Section 403 of this
Title shall be deemed a data fiduciary with the following obligations:

    (1) to use the disclosed data solely for the specific purpose for which
    consent was given and for no other purpose;

    (2) to protect the data using security measures meeting the standards
    established by the Data Commons Governance Council;

    (3) to delete the data upon the revocation of consent, the fulfillment of the
    specific purpose, or the expiration of the consent period, whichever occurs
    first;

    (4) to notify the Commons Member within seventy-two hours of any unauthorized
    access to, disclosure of, or loss of their data; and

    (5) to refrain from sharing the data with any third party without separate,
    specific consent from the Commons Member.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 403. CONSENT ARCHITECTURE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) CONSENT PRINCIPLES.-- The consent of a Commons Member to any use of their
personal data shall be:

    (1) ACTIVE -- expressed through a specific, affirmative action by the member,
    and not implied from silence, inaction, or general terms of service
    acceptance;

    (2) SPECIFIC -- limited to a defined data use, defined purpose, defined
    recipient, and defined time period, and not valid for uses, purposes,
    recipients, or periods beyond those specifically identified;

    (3) INFORMED -- preceded by a clear, plain-language explanation of the data
    use, the purpose it serves, the recipient who will hold the data, the period
    for which it will be held, and the member's right to revoke consent;

    (4) REVOCABLE -- withdrawable by the member at any time through their
    cryptographic identity, with the revocation taking immediate effect, without
    penalty, and without requirement of explanation; and

    (5) NON-COERCIVE -- not conditioned on the receipt of any commons provision,
    governance right, or other benefit, such that a member who withholds or
    revokes consent suffers no diminution of their Guaranteed Provision Standard
    entitlements or governance participation rights.

(b) PROHIBITED CONSENT PRACTICES.-- The following consent practices are
prohibited within the Federated Network:

    (1) bundled consent -- the conditioning of a single consent on agreement to
    multiple data uses, such that the member cannot consent to some uses while
    withholding consent to others;

    (2) consent by default -- the collection or use of personal data on an opt-out
    basis, where the member must take affirmative action to prevent data use rather
    than to enable it;

    (3) dark patterns -- interface designs, default settings, or procedural
    requirements that make withholding or revoking consent more difficult than
    granting it;

    (4) consent laundering -- the transfer of consented data to a third party who
    then uses it for purposes beyond the scope of the original consent; and

    (5) coercive consent -- the conditioning of provision delivery, governance
    participation, or any other commons benefit on the grant of data consent
    beyond the minimum necessary for the specific provision or service to
    function.

(c) PSEUDONYMOUS PARTICIPATION.-- A Commons Member may participate in the
Federated Network under a pseudonymous identity -- a cryptographic keypair that
does not reveal their legal name or other identifying information -- and shall
have full access to the Guaranteed Provision Standard, all governance rights, and
all commons benefits under their pseudonymous identity. Pseudonymous
participation shall be supported at every level of the network's technical and
governance infrastructure. No network institution shall require disclosure of a
member's legal identity as a condition of commons participation except where:

    (1) the member is engaging in a transaction that requires legal identity
    verification under federal law, such as certain financial transactions
    governed by the Bank Secrecy Act; or

    (2) the member has been the subject of a specific judicial determination
    requiring identity disclosure in connection with the investigation of a
    documented serious harm.

(d) ANONYMOUS CONTRIBUTION.-- A Commons Member may contribute creative works,
traditional knowledge, or other intellectual contributions to the IP Commons
under a Dedicated Commons Contribution -- an irrevocable attribution waiver --
through which the contribution enters the commons without attribution to any
identity, pseudonymous or otherwise. Anonymous contributions shall be governed by
the provisions of Section 504(d) of Title V of this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 404. COMMUNITY KNOWLEDGE PRIVACY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) COLLECTIVE DATA RIGHTS.-- Communities -- including indigenous communities,
immigrant communities, and other communities defined by shared cultural identity,
geographic location, or historical experience -- hold collective data rights in
traditional knowledge, cultural practices, ecological knowledge, and other
collectively developed information resources that are distinct from the individual
data sovereignty rights of Section 401 of this Title.

(b) NATURE OF COLLECTIVE DATA RIGHTS.-- Collective data rights:

    (1) vest in the community as a collective entity, represented through the
    community's legitimate governance structure -- which may be a tribal
    government, a community cooperative, a cultural organization, or any other
    representative body recognized by the community itself;

    (2) are not reducible to the sum of individual members' data sovereignty
    rights -- the community's collective right to govern its traditional knowledge
    is not extinguished by the individual consent of any member or subset of
    members;

    (3) include the right to define the terms on which the community's collective
    knowledge is shared, used, and built upon within and beyond the Federated
    Network; and

    (4) include the right to require attribution of the community as the source of
    collectively developed knowledge in any use, deployment, or derivative work.

(c) BOUNDED COMMONS CONTRIBUTION.-- A community exercising collective data rights
may contribute its traditional knowledge or other collectively held information
to the IP Commons through a Bounded Commons Contribution -- a contribution that
makes the knowledge available to certified QFN members for defined beneficial
uses while imposing restrictions that protect the originating community's
interests. A Bounded Commons Contribution shall:

    (1) specify the permitted uses of the contributed knowledge -- which may
    include specific agricultural, medical, ecological, or cultural applications
    -- and prohibit uses inconsistent with the community's values and the
    knowledge's appropriate context;

    (2) require attribution of the originating community in all uses and
    derivative works;

    (3) prohibit commercial extraction of the contributed knowledge by any party
    outside the Federated Network;

    (4) be governed by the originating community's governance structure, which
    retains the right to modify the terms of the Bounded Commons Contribution
    through its collective-choice processes at any time; and

    (5) be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger in a form that makes the
    bounded nature of the contribution visible to all potential users, preventing
    inadvertent use in violation of the contribution's terms.

(d) INDIGENOUS DATA SOVEREIGNTY.-- The collective data rights of Native American,
Alaska Native, and Native Hawaiian communities shall be recognized and protected
with particular care, consistent with the federal trust responsibility and the
principles of tribal self-determination. Specifically:

    (1) indigenous communities retain inherent sovereignty over data generated
    within their territories and relating to their peoples, cultures, and lands,
    independent of and prior to any rights conferred by this Act;

    (2) this Act shall be construed to supplement and strengthen indigenous data
    sovereignty, not to define or limit it;

    (3) the Data Commons Governance Council shall include permanent, dedicated
    representation for indigenous communities pursuant to Section 405(b) of this
    Title; and

    (4) no data governance standard, technical requirement, or commons
    participation mechanism established under this Title shall be applied to
    indigenous communities in a manner that conflicts with the exercise of tribal
    sovereignty or the government-to-government relationship between tribal
    nations and the federal government.

(e) TRADITIONAL KNOWLEDGE PROTECTION.-- Traditional knowledge held by communities
that has not been contributed to the IP Commons through either an open or Bounded
Commons Contribution shall be protected from enclosure through the following
mechanisms:

    (1) no party may patent, copyright, or otherwise claim intellectual property
    rights in traditional knowledge that has not been independently developed by
    the claiming party, regardless of whether the knowledge has been previously
    documented, published, or made accessible in any form;

    (2) the IP Commons attribution registry established under Title V of this Act
    shall maintain a Traditional Knowledge Prior Art Database, recording the
    existence and community origin of traditional knowledge without disclosing its
    specific content where the originating community wishes to maintain privacy,
    for the purpose of defeating enclosure claims by parties asserting novelty;

    (3) any intellectual property claim asserted against traditional knowledge
    documented in the Traditional Knowledge Prior Art Database shall be
    presumptively invalid, with the burden of proof resting on the claimant to
    demonstrate independent development; and

    (4) the Office of Federated Stewardship shall provide legal assistance to
    communities seeking to defend their traditional knowledge against enclosure
    claims, funded through the Bootstrap Grant Program pursuant to Section
    106(b)(4) of this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 405. DATA COMMONS GOVERNANCE COUNCIL.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established the Data Commons Governance Council,
a self-governing body of the Federated Network responsible for the ongoing
governance of the Federated Data Commons established by this Title. The Data
Commons Governance Council is a commons governance institution, not a
governmental body. It operates under the authority of the Federated Network's
nested governance architecture pursuant to Standard 8 of Section 102(i) of this
Act, and is accountable to the Commons Members whose data it governs. This 
Council is constituted as a Division of the Commons Governance Council
pursuant to Section 509(f) of Title V of this Act.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The Data Commons Governance Council shall comprise:

    (1) elected representatives of Qualified Federated Networks, with
    representation allocated on a proportional basis reflecting the number of
    Commons Members in each network, subject to a minimum of one representative
    per certified QFN regardless of size;

    (2) permanent dedicated seats for indigenous and tribal communities, with not
    fewer than five seats held by representatives of Native American, Alaska
    Native, and Native Hawaiian communities, selected through processes determined
    by those communities themselves;

    (3) dedicated seats for communities with particular data vulnerability --
    including immigrant communities, communities of color, LGBTQ+ communities,
    and communities with histories of governmental surveillance -- with not fewer
    than three seats allocated through a process determined by the IP Commons
    Governance Council in consultation with relevant community organizations; and

    (4) technical advisors -- non-voting members with expertise in cryptography,
    privacy-preserving computation, distributed systems, and data governance --
    appointed by the elected representatives for two-year terms.

(c) FUNCTIONS.-- The Data Commons Governance Council shall:

    (1) establish and maintain the boundary definition between personal data and
    Commons Resource Data pursuant to Section 401(d) of this Title;

    (2) establish and update data minimization standards for all Tier 1 Commons
    Governance Data collection pursuant to Section 402(b)(3) of this Title;

    (3) establish and update security standards for fiduciary data holders
    pursuant to Section 402(e)(2) of this Title;

    (4) govern the Traditional Knowledge Prior Art Database pursuant to Section
    404(e)(2) of this Title;

    (5) adjudicate disputes between Commons Members and network institutions
    regarding data sovereignty rights, through a process that constitutes the
    Standard 6 conflict resolution mechanism for data-related disputes;

    (6) conduct the biennial adequacy review of the Data Commons governance
    framework and submit recommendations to Congress and the Federated Network
    governance bodies; and

    (7) coordinate with the IP Commons Governance Council established under Title
    V of this Act on matters affecting both data governance and intellectual
    property governance, including the governance of AI-generated works and the
    privacy implications of IP Commons participation.

(d) DECISION-MAKING.-- The Data Commons Governance Council shall make decisions
through a consensus-seeking process that:

    (1) prioritizes achieving genuine agreement across the council's diverse
    constituencies before resorting to voting;

    (2) requires a supermajority of two-thirds of seated representatives for any
    decision that reduces existing data protections or expands permissible data
    uses;

    (3) requires a simple majority for decisions that strengthen existing data
    protections or restrict permissible data uses, reflecting the principle that
    privacy protection is the default and reduction of protection requires a
    higher burden of justification; and

    (4) provides that decisions of the Data Commons Governance Council are subject
    to override by the full Federated Network membership through a network-wide
    referendum conducted through the participatory governance tools of Title VII
    of this Act, upon petition by not less than five percent of active Commons
    Members.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 406. PROHIBITION ON SURVEILLANCE CAPITALISM WITHIN THE FEDERATED NETWORK.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL PROHIBITION.-- The surveillance capitalism model -- in which personal
data is extracted from individuals without meaningful consent, aggregated into
behavioral profiles, and used to predict, influence, and monetize individual
behavior for the benefit of third parties -- is hereby prohibited within the
Federated Network. No Qualified Federated Cooperative, Qualified Federated
Network, Commons Financial Node, or any other entity operating within or through
the Federated Network's infrastructure shall:

    (1) collect personal data beyond what is strictly necessary for the delivery
    of a specific, consented service or the performance of a defined commons
    governance function;

    (2) aggregate personal data from multiple sources to create behavioral
    profiles of individual Commons Members without their explicit, specific, and
    revocable consent;

    (3) use personal data -- including behavioral predictions derived from
    personal data -- to present Commons Members with targeted content,
    communications, or resource offers designed to influence their decisions
    without their knowledge;

    (4) sell, transfer, license, or otherwise provide personal data or behavioral
    profiles to any party outside the Federated Network; or

    (5) use Commons Membership Record data, National Resilience Ledger data, or
    Federated Mesh data for any purpose other than the specific commons governance
    functions for which the data was collected.

(b) PROHIBITION ON SURVEILLANCE PRICING.-- No entity operating within the
Federated Network shall use personal data -- including location data, behavioral
data, or Commons Credit transaction history -- to offer different prices,
provision levels, or service terms to different Commons Members based on
algorithmic assessments of their individual circumstances, vulnerability, or
willingness to accept less favorable terms. All commons provisions and services
shall be offered on equivalent terms to all Commons Members meeting the relevant
eligibility criteria.

(c) PROHIBITION ON BEHAVIORAL MANIPULATION.-- No entity operating within the
Federated Network shall use personal data, behavioral prediction algorithms, or
interface design techniques to manipulate the governance participation, purchasing
decisions, or personal choices of Commons Members in ways that serve the
interests of the entity at the expense of the member's autonomous judgment. This
prohibition applies specifically to:

    (1) the use of attention-capture techniques in commons governance platforms,
    which shall be designed to facilitate informed deliberation rather than to
    maximize engagement time;

    (2) the use of algorithmic content curation in commons information systems
    that systematically presents members with information reinforcing their
    existing views while withholding contrary information; and

    (3) the use of dark patterns in any commons digital interface.

(d) ENFORCEMENT.-- Violations of this Section shall constitute:

    (1) a serious violation of the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship subject to
    Level 3 graduated response under Section 103(c)(2)(C) of this Act for first
    violations;

    (2) grounds for Level 4 decertification under Section 103(c)(2)(D) of this
    Act for repeated or systematic violations; and

    (3) an independent cause of action for any affected Commons Member in any
    federal court of competent jurisdiction, with statutory damages of not less
    than one thousand dollars per violation and not more than ten thousand dollars
    per violation, plus attorney's fees.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 407. DATA INFRASTRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) OPEN-SOURCE REQUIREMENT.-- All software, algorithms, and technical systems
used to collect, process, store, or transmit personal data within the Federated
Network shall be open-source and publicly auditable. No proprietary data
processing system shall be operated within the Federated Network's infrastructure
without:

    (1) full disclosure of its source code to the Data Commons Governance Council;

    (2) independent security audit by a technical reviewer approved by the Data
    Commons Governance Council; and

    (3) a binding commitment to open-source the system within three years.

(b) DATA MINIMIZATION BY DESIGN.-- All technical systems deployed within the
Federated Network shall be designed from their inception to collect the minimum
personal data necessary for their defined function. Data minimization is a
technical design requirement, not merely a policy aspiration. Specifically:

    (1) systems shall be designed to perform their functions using aggregate or
    anonymized data wherever technically feasible, collecting individual-level
    data only where aggregate data is demonstrably insufficient;

    (2) systems shall automatically delete personal data upon fulfillment of the
    purpose for which it was collected, without requirement of a separate deletion
    request; and

    (3) systems shall not be designed with data collection capabilities that
    exceed their current defined function, even if those capabilities might serve
    future purposes.

(c) PRIVACY-PRESERVING COMPUTATION.-- The Federated Network shall prioritize the
development and deployment of privacy-preserving computation methods -- including
secure multi-party computation, homomorphic encryption, differential privacy, and
Zero-Knowledge Proofs -- that enable commons governance functions to be performed
without exposing individual personal data. The Bootstrap Grant Program shall
include specific funding streams for the development of privacy-preserving
computation tools pursuant to Section 106(b)(1) of this Act.

(d) MESH-NATIVE ARCHITECTURE.-- All data systems serving commons governance
functions shall be designed to operate on the Federated Mesh rather than on
centralized servers, consistent with the distributed architecture requirements of
Title VII of this Act. No data system that requires the routing of personal data
through a centralized server under the control of any single entity shall be
deployed for commons governance functions.

(e) ANALOG REDUNDANCY.-- Consistent with the analog redundancy requirements of
Section 105(d)(4) of this Act, all data governance functions that are essential
to the delivery of the Guaranteed Provision Standard shall have analog fallback
procedures that can maintain basic provision continuity for not less than ninety
days without digital connectivity. The analog fallback shall not require the
collection or processing of personal data beyond what is strictly necessary for
provision delivery.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 408. TRANSITION FROM EXISTING DATA REGIMES.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) EXISTING DATA HOLDINGS.-- Personal data about Commons Members that is
currently held by commercial entities, governmental bodies, or other parties
prior to the member's enrollment in the Federated Network shall be subject to the
following transition provisions:

    (1) PORTABILITY RIGHT.-- Upon achieving Federated Commons Membership, a
    Commons Member shall have the right to demand, within forty-eight hours, the
    transfer of all personal data held by any commercial entity to the member's
    Commons Membership Record in a machine-readable, open-standard format, for
    the member's own use and control;

    (2) DELETION RIGHT.-- Upon achieving Federated Commons Membership, a Commons
    Member shall have the right to demand the permanent deletion of all personal
    data held by any commercial entity, subject to such retention requirements as
    are imposed by federal law for specific regulatory purposes;

    (3) ENFORCEMENT.-- Commercial entities that fail to comply with portability or
    deletion demands within the forty-eight-hour period shall be subject to civil
    penalties of not less than one thousand dollars per day of non-compliance per
    affected Commons Member, recoverable by the member in any federal court of
    competent jurisdiction; and

    (4) COORDINATION WITH EXISTING LAW.-- The portability and deletion rights
    established by this Section are in addition to and shall not be construed to
    limit any rights established by the California Consumer Privacy Act, the
    General Data Protection Regulation as applied to transactions with European
    Union members, or any other applicable data protection law.

(b) GOVERNMENT DATA HOLDINGS.-- Personal data about Commons Members held by
federal, state, and local governmental agencies shall be subject to the following
transition provisions:

    (1) federal agencies shall conduct a comprehensive audit of their personal
    data holdings relating to Commons Members within one year of the date of
    enactment of this Act and shall publish the results of that audit -- in
    aggregate, anonymized form -- on the National Resilience Ledger;

    (2) federal agencies shall delete personal data about Commons Members
    that was collected for law enforcement or national security purposes but
    that pertains to individuals whose related criminal or civil records
    have been sealed or expunged pursuant to applicable Federal, State, or
    local law, including any sealing or expungement that occurs through a
    reparative or restorative process later established by Federal law; and

    (3) no federal agency shall share personal data about Commons Members with
    commercial entities for surveillance, targeting, or profiling purposes,
    consistent with the prohibition on surveillance capitalism established in
    Section 406 of this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 409. COVERED PLATFORM MIGRATION INTERFACE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DEFINITIONS.-- In this Section:

    (1) COVERED PLATFORM.-- The term "Covered Platform" means a person or
    entity operating a digital platform, network, or service used by not
    fewer than one million individual accounts in the United States, where
    either or both of the following apply:

        (A) PUBLIC FUNDING LINEAGE.-- the foundational technology of the
        platform, network, or service was developed in material part through
        funding received under the Small Business Innovation Research
        Program, the Small Business Technology Transfer Program, a federally
        funded university research grant, or a program of the Defense
        Advanced Research Projects Agency, the Intelligence Advanced Research
        Projects Activity, or In-Q-Tel; or

        (B) EXISTING ANTITRUST JUDGMENT.-- the person or entity is, at the
        time the duty established by subsection (b) of this Section would
        apply, operating under a final judgment, consent decree, or
        comparable enforceable order of the Department of Justice, the
        Federal Trade Commission, or a federal court, finding that the person
        or entity engaged in anticompetitive conduct with respect to the
        platform, network, or service.

    (2) MIGRATION INTERFACE.-- The term "migration interface" means a
    documented, machine-readable export interface through which a Commons
    Member's or prospective Commons Member's account data, content, and
    social or professional connection data, to the extent such data exists
    and is held by the Covered Platform, can be transferred in bulk to a
    Qualified Federated Network at the direction of the account holder.

(b) DUTY TO EXPOSE MIGRATION INTERFACE.-- A Covered Platform shall make
available, without charge to the account holder or to the receiving Qualified
Federated Network, a migration interface meeting the technical specifications
established for Covered Platform interfaces under Section 701 of Title VII of
this Act, not later than one year after the date the platform, network, or
service first meets the definition of Covered Platform under subsection (a)
of this Section.

(c) ACCOUNT HOLDER DIRECTION REQUIRED.-- A Covered Platform may transfer data
under this Section only at the explicit direction of the account holder, and
shall provide the account holder with a clear, conspicuous, and revocable
mechanism for directing or halting such a transfer at any time.

(d) RELATIONSHIP TO EXISTING PORTABILITY RIGHTS.-- The duty established by
this Section is in addition to, and does not limit, the portability right
established under Section 408(a)(1) of this Title. Where a Covered Platform
is also subject to Section 408(a)(1) with respect to a particular Commons
Member, compliance with the migration interface requirements of this Section
shall be deemed to satisfy the format requirements of Section 408(a)(1),
provided the forty-eight-hour transfer deadline of that Section is otherwise
met.

(e) ENFORCEMENT.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall maintain a
public registry of Covered Platforms and shall refer noncompliance with
subsection (b) of this Section to the Federal Trade Commission as an unfair
or deceptive act or practice under section 5 of the Federal Trade Commission
Act. A Qualified Federated Network denied access to a migration interface
required under this Section may bring an action for injunctive relief in any
federal court of competent jurisdiction.

(f) LIMITATIONS.-- Nothing in this Section shall be construed to:

    (1) apply to any platform, network, or service that does not meet the
    definition of Covered Platform under subsection (a) of this Section;

    (2) require the disclosure of any data not held by the Covered Platform
    in the ordinary course of its operation, or require the creation of new
    data;

    (3) require a Covered Platform to disclose trade secrets in its
    underlying software, algorithms, or systems beyond the documented
    interface specification required for migration; or

    (4) constitute a determination by Congress that any particular Covered
    Platform holds or has exercised monopoly power, that determination being
    reserved to the Department of Justice, the Federal Trade Commission, or a
    court of competent jurisdiction under existing antitrust law.


================================================================================
TITLE V -- THE FEDERATED INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY COMMONS
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the legal architecture by which
knowledge, creative expression, and innovation -- the collectively produced
intellectual substrate of human civilization -- are governed as a common-pool
resource rather than as private property to be enclosed, monopolized, and
extracted. The Federated Intellectual Property Commons does not abolish the
recognition of creative and innovative contribution. It abolishes the enclosure
of that contribution -- the legal mechanism by which the temporary monopoly
grant intended to promote the progress of science and the useful arts has been
captured and extended to serve the permanent rent extraction of corporate
rights-holders at the expense of individual creators, the broader public, and
the advancement of knowledge itself. The IP Commons returns intellectual
contribution to its natural condition: non-rivalrous, freely available to all,
permanently attributed to its creators, and governed by the communities that use
and build upon it. People create because they are human. The material conditions
for creation are provided by the Guaranteed Provision Standard. What remains is
the freedom to create, the permanence of attribution, and the protection of the
commons from re-enclosure.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 501. FOUNDATIONAL PRINCIPLES.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) NON-RIVALRY OF KNOWLEDGE.-- Congress finds that knowledge, creative
expression, and innovation are non-rivalrous resources -- their use by one person
does not diminish their availability to others -- and that the application of
scarcity-based property logic to non-rivalrous resources creates artificial
scarcity that imposes deadweight losses on the economy, restricts the free flow
of knowledge, and concentrates the benefits of collective intellectual production
in corporate entities at the expense of individual creators and the public.

(b) CONSTITUTIONAL MANDATE.-- Congress finds that the current intellectual
property regime, having extended copyright terms beyond any reasonable
interpretation of "limited times" as used in Article I, Section 8 of the
Constitution, having permitted the systematic shelving of patents without
productive deployment, and having concentrated intellectual property ownership in
corporate entities rather than the individual authors and inventors the
Constitution contemplates, no longer fulfills the constitutional mandate to
promote the progress of science and the useful arts, and that the Federated
Intellectual Property Commons established by this Title better fulfills that
mandate by ensuring that the benefits of creative and innovative work are widely
shared, that creators are permanently attributed and materially supported through
the Guaranteed Provision Standard, and that knowledge flows freely to accelerate
further creation and innovation.

(c) CREATIVE FREEDOM THROUGH MATERIAL SECURITY.-- Congress finds that the
primary obstacle to creative and innovative freedom is not the absence of
intellectual property protection but the absence of material security. The
coupling of creative workers' survival to the commercial exploitation of their
intellectual output -- through the copyright and patent systems -- has made
creative work dependent on market success rather than on creative merit, cultural
value, or social contribution. The Guaranteed Provision Standard established
under Title II of this Act decouples material security from commercial
exploitation, creating the conditions under which creative and innovative work
can proceed freely, without the distortion introduced by the need to enclose
output for survival.

(d) ATTRIBUTION AS DISTINCT FROM ENCLOSURE.-- Congress finds that the right of
creators to be permanently and unbreakably identified as the authors of their
work -- attribution -- is a distinct right from the right to exclude others from
using that work -- enclosure -- and that the conflation of these rights in the
current intellectual property regime has served primarily to justify enclosure
under the guise of protecting creators. This Title protects attribution
absolutely and permanently while eliminating enclosure as the mechanism by which
that protection is provided.

(e) SCOPE OF ANTITRUST PROVISIONS.-- Congress finds that the
commons-protective measures established by this Title, including the
shelved patent recapture mechanism of Section 503(d) and the anti-thicket
provisions of Section 506(d), are limited by design to the defense of
commons resource pools recognized under this Act against enclosure,
monopolization, or suppression by private or governmental actors. Nothing
in this Title shall be construed as a comprehensive exercise of Congress's
antitrust authority, and nothing in this Title shall be construed to limit,
displace, or substitute for the existing antitrust authority of the
Department of Justice or the Federal Trade Commission under the Sherman
Act, the Clayton Act, or the Federal Trade Commission Act. Congress finds
that comprehensive reform of antitrust law as applied to digital platforms
and concentrated markets generally, while a related and urgent legislative
priority, is a distinct undertaking from the commons-protective
architecture established by this Act and is appropriately addressed through
separate legislation.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 502. ESTABLISHMENT OF THE INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY COMMONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is hereby established the Federated Intellectual
Property Commons -- a federated repository of creative works, technical
innovations, traditional knowledge, and other intellectual contributions held in
common for the benefit of all Commons Members and the general public, governed
by the IP Commons Governance Council established under Section 509 of this Title,
freely accessible to any Commons Member for use, deployment, performance, remix,
or further development, and permanently protected from re-enclosure by the
copyleft mandate established under Section 507 of this Title.

(b) SCOPE.-- The Intellectual Property Commons shall encompass contributions in
all of the following categories:

    (1) CREATIVE WORKS -- including literary works, musical compositions and
    recordings, visual art, film, photography, performance works, architectural
    designs, and any other work of creative expression regardless of medium or
    form;

    (2) TECHNICAL INNOVATIONS -- including inventions, manufacturing processes,
    engineering designs, software, algorithms, agricultural methods, medical
    treatments and formulations, and any other innovation with practical
    application;

    (3) TRADITIONAL AND COMMUNITY KNOWLEDGE -- including indigenous agricultural
    practices, traditional medicine, ecological knowledge, craft traditions, and
    other collectively developed knowledge resources, governed according to the
    collective data rights and bounded commons contribution provisions of Section
    404 of Title IV of this Act;

    (4) EDUCATIONAL RESOURCES -- including curricula, instructional materials,
    textbooks, training programs, and other resources designed to transmit
    knowledge and skills;

    (5) SCIENTIFIC AND RESEARCH OUTPUTS -- including the findings, data,
    methodologies, and publications resulting from scientific research, with
    particular emphasis on publicly funded research subject to the mandatory
    commons contribution provisions of Section 503 of this Title; and

    (6) GOVERNANCE INNOVATIONS -- including cooperative governance models,
    conflict resolution protocols, commons management frameworks, and other
    innovations in the organization of collective human activity.

(c) COMMONS MEMBERSHIP RECORD INTEGRATION.-- Every Commons Member's attribution
registrations in the IP Commons shall be recorded in their Commons Membership
Record pursuant to Section 209(b)(4) of this Act and shall remain associated with
the member's cryptographic identity regardless of the member's network
affiliation, location, or membership status changes.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 503. MANDATORY COMMONS CONTRIBUTIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PUBLICLY FUNDED RESEARCH.-- Any creative work, technical innovation, or
other intellectual output developed in whole or in significant part through
federal funding -- including grants from the National Institutes of Health, the
National Science Foundation, the Department of Energy, the Department of Defense,
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, and all other federal agencies
providing research funding -- shall be contributed to the Intellectual Property
Commons upon the earlier of:

    (1) publication, public disclosure, or first use of the output; or

    (2) five years after the date of the federal funding award.

This requirement builds upon and extends the federal open access policy
established by the August 2022 Office of Science and Technology Policy
memorandum directing federal agencies to require immediate public access to
federally funded research, and the National Institutes of Health public access
policy requiring deposit of funded research in PubMed Central. SPARC (the
Scholarly Publishing and Academic Resources Coalition), whose sustained advocacy
produced those policies over two decades, is recognized as a technical
assistance partner for institutions seeking to comply with this subsection; the
Office of Federated Stewardship shall enter into a memorandum of understanding
with SPARC within one year of the date of enactment to coordinate compliance
guidance, institutional outreach, and training for universities and research
institutions navigating the transition from existing open access policies to
full IP Commons contribution. The Confederation of Open Access Repositories
(COAR), which coordinates open access repository networks representing more than
130 institutions in 35 countries and maintains technical interoperability
standards for open repository infrastructure, provides the primary existing
international infrastructure for commons-compatible research dissemination; the
Technical Standards Body established under Section 701(d) of Title VII of this
Act shall ensure that the IP Commons attribution and access architecture is
interoperable with COAR repository standards, enabling seamless contribution
pathways for research outputs already deposited in COAR-member repositories.

(b) REVERSAL OF BAYH-DOLE.-- The Bayh-Dole Act, codified at 35 U.S.C. sections
200-212, is hereby amended to provide that:

    (1) the right of universities, nonprofit organizations, and small businesses
    to elect title to inventions made with federal funding is hereby eliminated
    with respect to inventions made after the date of enactment of this Act;

    (2) all inventions made with federal funding after the date of enactment of
    this Act shall be contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons pursuant to
    subsection (a) of this Section, with attribution recorded in the name of the
    individual inventors or, where the invention is the product of a team, in the
    names of all contributing team members;

    (3) institutions that facilitated the research through which the invention was
    made shall be recognized as contributing institutions in the attribution
    record, without receiving exclusive rights to the invention; and

    (4) inventions made with federal funding prior to the date of enactment of
    this Act that are held by universities, nonprofit organizations, or small
    businesses shall be eligible for voluntary contribution to the IP Commons
    pursuant to Section 505 of this Title, with Legacy Credits awarded pursuant
    to Section 304(f) of Title III of this Act.

(c) FEDERAL GOVERNMENT WORKS.-- Works created by officers or employees of the
United States government as part of their official duties are, pursuant to 17
U.S.C. section 105, not subject to copyright protection. All such works are
hereby deemed contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons and shall be
recorded on the National Resilience Ledger with attribution to the creating
agency.

(d) SHELVED PATENT RECAPTURE.--

    (1) DEFINITION.-- A patent is shelved within the meaning of this Section if
    the patent holder has not actively deployed the patented invention in
    commercial production, licensed the patent to a party actively deploying the
    invention, or made the invention available for use in a manner that
    substantially fulfills the social purpose of the patented technology, for a
    continuous period of three or more years after the date of patent issuance or,
    for patents issued prior to the date of enactment of this Act, for a
    continuous period of three or more years preceding the date of enactment.
    For the purposes of this Section:

        (A) a patent shall be presumed not shelved where the patent holder
        demonstrates that the patented invention is the subject of active clinical
        trials, active regulatory review, active good-faith licensing negotiations,
        or active commercial development with documented investment within the
        preceding twelve months; the burden of overcoming this presumption rests
        with the Office of Federated Stewardship;

        (B) a patent held by an entity that received federal funding constituting
        thirty percent or more of the documented total development costs of the
        patented invention shall be subject to the additional mandatory commons
        contribution provisions of subsection (a) of this Section and Section
        503(b) of this Title, as publicly funded intellectual property, in addition
        to and not in lieu of the shelved patent recapture mechanism of this
        subsection; and

        (C) defensive patent holding -- the retention of a patent by an entity
        that does not deploy the patented invention but asserts the patent solely
        to prevent infringement claims against its other products -- does not
        constitute active deployment and does not rebut the shelved patent
        presumption.

    (2) RECAPTURE MECHANISM.-- A shelved patent shall be subject to commons
    recapture through the following process:

        (A) the Office of Federated Stewardship shall publish a quarterly Shelved
        Patent Registry on the National Resilience Ledger, identifying patents
        that appear to meet the shelved patent definition based on publicly
        available deployment data;

        (B) the patent holder shall have one hundred eighty days from the date of
        listing on the Shelved Patent Registry to demonstrate active deployment,
        provide evidence of a licensing arrangement with active deployment, or
        commit to a deployment plan with a binding timeline not to exceed two
        years;

        (C) where the patent holder fails to provide a satisfactory response
        within one hundred eighty days, the patent shall be subject to commons
        recapture through an expedited administrative proceeding before the
        Federated Accountability Board established under Section 1103 of this Act;

        (D) upon a finding of shelved patent status by the Federated
        Accountability Board, the patent shall be contributed to the Intellectual
        Property Commons, with:

            (i) attribution recorded in the name of the original inventor or
            inventors;

            (ii) compensation to the patent holder, at the patent holder's
            election, in either: (I) Stewardship Credits valued at the patent's
            assessed productive potential -- the estimated value of the productive
            output that active deployment would generate -- calculated using
            a methodology modeled on eminent domain appraisal standards and
            subject to the independent judicial review provided in subparagraph
            (E) of this paragraph; or (II) United States dollars in an amount
            equal to the assessed productive potential as determined by the
            same appraisal methodology, payable from the Bootstrap Grant Program
            fund within ninety days of the Federated Accountability Board's
            finding; the compensation mechanism and the commons contribution
            obligation are severable, such that a judicial finding that the
            Stewardship Credit valuation is constitutionally inadequate shall
            require dollar substitution but shall not void the commons
            contribution; and

            (iii) a Legacy Credit awarded to the patent holder pursuant to
            Section 304(f) of Title III of this Act; and

        (E) the patent holder may appeal the Federated Accountability Board's
        finding to a federal court of competent jurisdiction, which shall review
        the finding de novo. The filing of an appeal shall not stay the commons
        contribution unless the court grants a preliminary injunction upon a
        specific finding that the patent holder is likely to succeed on the merits
        and that the harm of contribution outweighs the public benefit.

    (3) PRIORITY CATEGORIES.-- The following categories of shelved patents shall
    be given priority in the Shelved Patent Registry and shall be subject to
    expedited recapture proceedings:

        (A) patents covering pharmaceutical compounds, medical devices, or medical
        treatments whose shelving has contributed to unmet medical need or to
        prices that make the patented treatment inaccessible to persons without
        substantial financial resources;

        (B) patents covering renewable energy technologies, carbon sequestration
        methods, or other climate-relevant innovations whose shelving has delayed
        their deployment in the transition to a sustainable energy system; and

        (C) patents covering agricultural technologies, seed varieties, or food
        production methods whose shelving has contributed to food insecurity or
        reduced agricultural resilience.

    (4) AI TRAINING ELECTION.--

        (A) IN GENERAL.-- During the one hundred eighty day period
        established under paragraph (2)(B) of this subsection, the patent
        holder may elect one of the following with respect to the use of
        the patent's disclosure as training data for an artificial
        intelligence system generating technical innovations:

            (i) EXCLUSION.-- a permanent election that the patent's
            disclosure shall not be used to train any artificial
            intelligence system for that purpose, which election shall be
            enforceable as a condition of the patent's contribution to the
            IP Commons against any party, regardless of affiliation with a
            Qualified Federated Network, in the same manner as the
            copyleft mandate of Section 507 of this Title; or

            (ii) CONTINUING PAYMENT.-- an election, or, in the absence of
            any election under this paragraph, a default, that the patent
            holder shall receive continuing payment for AI-training use of
            the patent's disclosure within the Federated Network,
            calculated and allocated pursuant to Section 511 of this Title.

        (B) NO RETROACTIVE EFFECT; FINDING.-- Congress finds that, because
        a patent's disclosure is a matter of public record from the date of
        its publication under existing patent law, an exclusion elected
        under subparagraph (A)(i) of this paragraph cannot affect, and
        shall not be construed to affect, any artificial intelligence
        training that occurred before the date of the election, including
        training that occurred before the patent became eligible for
        recapture under this subsection. The election established by this
        paragraph governs only the use of the patent's disclosure occurring
        after the date of the election.

        (C) ADMINISTRATION.-- An election under this paragraph may be made
        individually or through a Collective Licensing Body recognized
        under Section 511(e) of this Title, and the priority established
        under Section 511(e)(2) of this Title for individual and
        small-entity creators shall apply equally to individual inventors
        and small entities under this paragraph.

