SEC. 504. ATTRIBUTION REGISTRATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) IMMUTABLE ATTRIBUTION.-- Every contribution to the Intellectual Property
Commons shall be registered with immutable attribution -- a permanent,
cryptographically secured record on the National Resilience Ledger identifying
the creator or creators of the work, the date of creation, and the date of
commons contribution. Attribution registration is:

    (1) permanent -- it does not expire, cannot be cancelled, and survives the
    contributor's death, vesting in their designated beneficiary for purposes of
    the historical record;

    (2) cryptographically secured -- registered through the contributor's
    cryptographic keypair, such that the attribution record cannot be altered,
    transferred, or disputed without possession of the contributor's private key;

    (3) unconditional -- it does not depend on the work's commercial success,
    cultural reception, deployment frequency, or any other measure of external
    validation; and

    (4) protective -- it constitutes the primary evidentiary record against
    enclosure claims, establishing the work's existence in the commons prior to
    any subsequent private claim of independent creation.

(b) REGISTRATION PATHWAYS.-- Attribution registration shall be accessible through
the following pathways:

    (1) SELF-REGISTRATION.-- A contributor with access to a Federated
    Mesh-connected device may register their work directly through their
    cryptographic keypair, creating an attribution record on the National
    Resilience Ledger that is immediately effective.

    (2) COMMUNITY PROXY REGISTRATION.-- A community exercising collective data
    rights pursuant to Section 404 of Title IV of this Act may register
    collectively held knowledge through its designated governance structure, with
    the community's governance keypair serving as the attribution identifier.

    (3) WITNESSED PHYSICAL REGISTRATION.-- A contributor who lacks direct access
    to a Federated Mesh-connected device may register their work through a QFN
    Witness pursuant to Section 4(21) of this Act. The registration pathway
    established by this paragraph shall be:

        (A) available in every Qualified Federated Network and in every designated
        Underserved Area through the mobile technical assistance teams established
        under Section 107(c)(4) of this Act;

        (B) conducted without cost to the contributor;

        (C) capable of registering any category of contribution -- including
        physical objects, oral traditions, performance works, and other
        contributions that do not exist in digital form -- through appropriate
        documentation methods; and

        (D) legally equivalent to self-registration in all respects.

    (4) RETROSPECTIVE REGISTRATION.-- A contribution that has entered circulation
    prior to the contributor's registration may be registered retrospectively,
    with the ledger recording both the documented original creation date and the
    registration date. Where a work has been circulating without attribution and
    benefits have accrued to parties without legitimate attribution, the
    retrospective registration shall trigger a restitution process governed by the
    IP Commons Governance Council.

(c) PSEUDONYMOUS ATTRIBUTION.-- A contributor who wishes to maintain privacy
while retaining attribution rights may register their work under a pseudonymous
keypair -- a cryptographic identity that does not reveal the contributor's legal
name or other personally identifying information. Pseudonymous attribution:

    (1) provides full attribution protection -- the work is permanently associated
    with the pseudonymous identity, establishing creation priority against
    enclosure claims;

    (2) supports keypair rotation -- a contributor may transition from one
    pseudonymous keypair to another through a cryptographically verified handoff
    recorded on the National Resilience Ledger, maintaining continuity of
    attribution across the transition without revealing the contributor's
    real-world identity; and

    (3) is irrevocable as to existing registrations -- once a work is registered
    under a pseudonymous keypair, the registration cannot be retroactively linked
    to the contributor's legal identity without their explicit consent.

(d) ANONYMOUS CONTRIBUTION -- DEDICATED COMMONS CONTRIBUTION.-- A contributor
who wishes to contribute a work to the commons without any attribution -- not
even a pseudonymous attribution -- may do so through a Dedicated Commons
Contribution, comprising:

    (1) a formal, irrevocable attribution waiver recorded on the National
    Resilience Ledger, documenting the contributor's deliberate choice to
    contribute the work without attribution;

    (2) the work's entry into the commons as collectively owned -- not attributed
    to any individual or community -- with no benefit accruing to any party on the
    work's behalf; and

    (3) any commons engagement generated by the work flowing to the commons
    general fund, used to increase Bootstrap Grant availability or baseline
    provision standards across the network.

