SEC. 505. VOLUNTARY CONTRIBUTION PATHWAYS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) INDIVIDUAL VOLUNTARY CONTRIBUTION.-- Any individual creator, inventor, or
traditional knowledge holder who holds copyright, patent, or other intellectual
property rights in a work may voluntarily contribute that work to the
Intellectual Property Commons at any time of their choosing, including
immediately upon creation or first publication, before any commercial release,
or at any point thereafter. No minimum holding period, waiting period, or prior
commercial activity is required. The decision of when, whether, and on what
terms to contribute belongs entirely to the creator. Voluntary contributions:

    (1) are irrevocable upon recording on the National Resilience Ledger;

    (2) are immediately protected by the copyleft mandate of Section 507 of this
    Title;

    (3) are eligible for attribution registration through any of the pathways
    established in Section 504 of this Title;

    (4) do not require the contributor to hold Federated Commons Membership,
    though contributors who are not Commons Members shall not have access to the
    full IP Commons knowledge base pursuant to Section 207 of Title II of this
    Act; and

    (5) may be made at any time notwithstanding any prior commercial exploitation
    of the work, it being the purpose of this provision to ensure that a creator
    who has made their first year of sales, or ten years of sales, or any other
    period of commercial return they consider sufficient, may thereafter dedicate
    the work to the commons freely, receiving full attribution registration and
    all associated commons benefits, without any condition that prior commercial
    activity has expired or been exhausted.

Works already released by their creators under a Creative Commons Attribution
(CC BY), Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike (CC BY-SA), Creative Commons
Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike (CC BY-NC-SA), CC0 public domain
dedication, or any other license meeting the Open Definition maintained by the
Open Knowledge Foundation, are eligible for IP Commons contribution without
relicensing or additional permissions from the creator. The IP Commons
Governance Council shall, within one year of its establishment, publish a
compatibility schedule identifying all existing open licenses whose terms are
compatible with IP Commons contribution, and shall maintain that schedule as
open licenses evolve. Works contributed to the IP Commons under this subsection
retain their original open license in addition to receiving IP Commons
registration, such that the IP Commons contribution does not narrow the rights
of parties who were already accessing the work under its original open license.

(b) CREATOR REVERSION RIGHT.-- An individual creator whose work is currently held
under copyright by a corporate rights-holder -- including a recording label,
publishing house, film studio, technology company, or other entity that acquired
the copyright through assignment, work-for-hire arrangement, or other mechanism
-- shall have the right to reclaim that copyright and contribute the work to the
Intellectual Property Commons, subject to the following conditions:

    (1) the reversion right shall be exercisable at any time after the earlier of:
    thirty-five years from the date of the original copyright assignment or
    work-for-hire arrangement; or twenty years from the date of enactment of this
    Act;

    (2) the creator shall provide written notice of intent to exercise the
    reversion right to the corporate rights-holder not less than two years before
    the intended reversion date;

    (3) upon exercise of the reversion right, copyright shall vest in the creator,
    who may then contribute the work to the IP Commons or retain the copyright
    under the terms of the amended copyright regime established in Section 506 of
    this Title;

    (4) any contractual provision that purports to waive or restrict the creator's
    reversion right established by this Section is void and unenforceable; and

    (5) the Creator Transition Grant established under Section 106(b)(5) of this
    Act shall be available to creators exercising the reversion right who are
    transitioning from IP income dependence to the commons economy.

(c) CORPORATE VOLUNTARY CONTRIBUTION.-- Corporate entities holding intellectual
property portfolios may contribute works, patents, or other intellectual property
to the IP Commons through the Legacy Swap arrangement established under Section
305(b) of Title III of this Act, adapted for intellectual property as follows:

    (1) the corporate entity transfers defined intellectual property to the IP
    Commons, with attribution recorded in the names of the individual inventors,
    authors, or creators where identifiable, and in the name of the contributing
    institution where individual creators are not identifiable;

    (2) the transfer is irrevocable and subject to the copyleft mandate of Section
    507 of this Title;

    (3) the corporate entity receives Legacy Credits pursuant to Section 304(f) of
    Title III of this Act; and

    (4) the corporate entity receives a charitable deduction under the Internal
    Revenue Code equal to the assessed productive potential of the contributed
    intellectual property.

(d) TRADE SECRET DISSOLUTION UPON QFN CONVERSION.-- Any business enterprise
converting to worker cooperative ownership and Qualified Federated Cooperative
status pursuant to Section 304 of Title III of this Act shall contribute all
trade secrets held by the enterprise to the Intellectual Property Commons as a
condition of QFC certification, subject to the following:

    (1) the contribution of trade secrets shall occur not later than one hundred
    eighty days after the completion of the cooperative conversion;

    (2) trade secrets shall be registered with attribution to the individual
    employees who developed them, where identifiable, and to the enterprise as a
    collective where individual attribution is not feasible;

    (3) the contributed trade secrets shall be subject to the copyleft mandate of
    Section 507 of this Title from the date of contribution; and

    (4) a Bootstrap Grant supplement shall be available to cover the transition
    costs associated with trade secret contribution, including the costs of
    documenting and formalizing trade secret knowledge that has previously existed
    only in the tacit knowledge of employees.

