SEC. 506. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY REGIME TRANSITION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) VOLUNTARY COMMONS DEDICATION AND ABANDONED WORKS.--

    (1) VOLUNTARY DEDICATION -- PRIMARY MECHANISM.-- The primary mechanism by
    which works enter the Intellectual Property Commons is voluntary dedication
    by the creator pursuant to Section 505(a) of this Title. A creator who holds
    copyright in a work may dedicate that work to the IP Commons at any time after
    creation, without any minimum holding period, by recording the dedication on
    the National Resilience Ledger through any attribution registration pathway
    established in Section 504 of this Title. Upon dedication, the work enters
    the commons, attribution is permanently registered, and the copyleft mandate
    of Section 507 of this Title attaches. The availability of copyright protection
    for the full duration otherwise provided by law is not reduced by this Section;
    it remains available to any creator who chooses not to dedicate.

    (2) ABANDONED WORKS -- SECONDARY MECHANISM.-- A work shall be deemed abandoned
    and contributed automatically to the Intellectual Property Commons where:

        (A) the work has not been commercially distributed, publicly performed,
        licensed, sold, or otherwise actively deployed or exploited in any medium
        by or with the authorization of the copyright holder for a continuous
        period of fourteen or more years following its first publication or public
        disclosure; provided that any act of commercial exploitation within the
        fourteen-year period, however brief, shall restart the fourteen-year
        inactivity period and preclude a finding of abandonment until a new
        fourteen-year period of continuous inactivity has elapsed;

        (B) the copyright holder has not voluntarily dedicated the work to the IP
        Commons pursuant to paragraph (1) of this subsection during that period;
        and

        (C) the work is not currently the subject of active litigation over
        copyright ownership, licensing, or infringement, in which case the
        abandonment determination shall be held in abeyance until the conclusion
        of that litigation.

    (3) ABANDONMENT NOTICE AND CURE.-- Before any work is deemed abandoned under
    paragraph (2) of this subsection, the IP Commons Governance Council shall:

        (A) publish a notice of potential abandonment on the National Resilience
        Ledger identifying the work and the copyright holder of record, not less
        than one hundred eighty days before the deemed abandonment date;

        (B) provide the copyright holder with one hundred eighty days within which
        to recommence active commercial deployment, voluntarily dedicate the work
        to the IP Commons, or demonstrate to the IP Commons Governance Council
        that active deployment has occurred within the preceding fourteen years and
        was not captured by available records; and

        (C) deem the work contributed to the IP Commons only where the copyright
        holder fails to act within the one-hundred-eighty-day cure period, with
        attribution registered in the name of the original creator as of the
        original creation date.

    (4) TREATY CONSISTENCY.-- The abandoned-works mechanism of this subsection
    does not reduce the copyright protection period available to any creator who
    makes an active choice about their work, whether by commercializing it or by
    voluntarily dedicating it to the commons. The mechanism operates as an
    abandonment doctrine applicable only to works whose rights-holders have made
    neither choice for fourteen consecutive years. Abandonment doctrines governing
    the disposition of unclaimed intellectual property do not conflict with the
    minimum term requirements of the Berne Convention or the TRIPS Agreement,
    which establish floors for available protection rather than mandates for the
    perpetual retention of rights that have been abandoned in practice. The
    Secretary of State is directed to confirm this interpretation with the World
    Intellectual Property Organization within one year of the date of enactment
    and to pursue formal clarification through WIPO's standing committee on
    copyright if any member state raises an objection.

    (5) EXISTING WORKS -- APPLICATION.-- The abandoned-works mechanism of this
    subsection applies to existing works whose rights-holders have not actively
    deployed them for fourteen or more consecutive years as of the date of
    enactment, subject to the notice and cure procedure of paragraph (3) of this
    subsection. No work shall be deemed abandoned under this paragraph until at
    least one hundred eighty days after the date of enactment, ensuring that all
    rights-holders have a full cure period from the date the mechanism takes
    effect.

    (6) CONSTITUTIONAL BASIS.-- Congress finds that the abandoned-works
    mechanism established by paragraph (2) of this subsection is grounded in
    the common law doctrine of abandonment, under which a property right may
    be relinquished through sustained non-use combined with conduct
    manifesting an intent to abandon, and in the limitation that Article I,
    Section 8 of the Constitution places on Congress's own power to grant
    exclusive rights only "for limited times." The notice and cure procedure
    established in paragraph (3) of this subsection supplies the
    manifest-intent element that abandonment doctrine requires: a copyright
    holder who has taken no commercial action for fourteen consecutive years,
    who receives actual notice of the impending abandonment determination, and
    who is afforded a further period of one hundred eighty days to act and
    does not do so, has manifested the intent to abandon as clearly as if the
    abandonment had been declared affirmatively. Because the mechanism
    operates only upon a finding of abandonment, and not upon an exercise of
    eminent domain against a right the holder continues to assert, no
    compensation is constitutionally required; a right that has been
    abandoned is, by definition, a right no longer held. This mechanism is
    therefore properly understood not as a reduction of the term Article I,
    Section 8 permits Congress to secure, but as recognition that a right left
    unexercised and undefended for the full statutory period was never
    extended in practice beyond the date of abandonment, consistent with the
    constitutional design that protection be available, not perpetual.

    (7) AI TRAINING ELECTION.--

        (A) IN GENERAL.-- At any time before a work is deemed abandoned
        under paragraph (2) of this subsection, including during the cure
        period established under paragraph (3) of this subsection, the
        rights holder may elect one of the following with respect to the
        use of the work as training data for an artificial intelligence
        system:

            (i) EXCLUSION.-- a permanent election that the work shall not
            be used to train any artificial intelligence system, which
            election shall be enforceable as a condition of the work's
            contribution to the IP Commons against any party, regardless
            of affiliation with a Qualified Federated Network, in the same
            manner as the copyleft mandate of Section 507 of this Title; or

            (ii) CONTINUING PAYMENT.-- an election, or, in the absence of
            any election under this paragraph, a default, that the rights
            holder shall receive continuing payment for AI-training use of
            the work within the Federated Network, calculated and
            allocated pursuant to Section 511 of this Title.

        (B) ADMINISTRATION.-- An election under this paragraph may be made
        individually or through a Collective Licensing Body recognized
        under Section 511(e) of this Title.

        (C) NO RETROACTIVE EFFECT.-- An exclusion elected under
        subparagraph (A)(i) of this paragraph applies prospectively only
        and does not affect any use of the work that occurred before the
        date of the election.

(b) EXISTING COPYRIGHTS.-- Copyrights in works created prior to the date of
enactment of this Act shall not be retroactively shortened. However:

    (1) existing copyrights held by corporate entities -- including recording
    labels, publishing houses, film studios, and technology companies -- shall be
    subject to the creator reversion right established in Section 505(b) of this
    Title;

    (2) existing copyrights in works that have not been actively deployed for
    fourteen or more consecutive years as of the date of enactment are subject to
    the abandoned-works mechanism of Section 506(a)(2) through (5) of this Title,
    with the notice and cure period running from the date of enactment rather than
    from the date the fourteen-year inactivity period would otherwise have expired;
    and

    (3) all existing copyrights in works whose copyright term expires under
    current law after the date of enactment of this Act shall, upon that
    expiration, be automatically contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons
    rather than entering the unstructured public domain, ensuring that attribution
    registration is maintained even for works entering the public domain.

(c) PATENT TERM.-- For patents issued after the date of enactment of this Act:

    (1) the patent term shall remain at twenty years from the date of application,
    consistent with current law, provided that active deployment of the patented
    invention shall be required to maintain patent protection, with the shelved
    patent recapture mechanism of Section 503(d) of this Title applicable
    throughout the patent term; and

    (2) upon expiration of the patent term, the patented invention shall be
    automatically contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons with
    attribution recorded in the name of the original inventors.

(d) ANTI-THICKET PROVISIONS.-- Congress finds that the accumulation of large
portfolios of patents covering incremental variations of a core technology --
sometimes called patent thickets -- has been used systematically to block
competition, suppress innovation, and extend effective monopoly beyond the term
of any individual patent. To address this practice:

    (1) no single entity shall hold more than twenty-five patents covering
    substantially similar technology in the same technology domain, defined as
    patents whose claims overlap in a manner that would require a competitor to
    license multiple patents to practice the core technology;

    (2) patent portfolios held by corporate entities in excess of this limit as of
    the date of enactment shall be subject to a mandatory portfolio review within
    two years, with excess patents contributed to the IP Commons in order of their
    age, beginning with the oldest;

    (3) the determination of whether patents are in the same technology domain and
    whether claims overlap substantially shall be made by a Technical Review Panel
    constituted under the IP Commons Governance Council, with members selected for
    technical expertise in the relevant field and for absence of financial
    interest in the outcome; and

    (4) the anti-thicket provisions of this subsection shall be enforced by the IP
    Commons Governance Council, with appeals to the Federated Accountability Board
    established under Section 1103 of this Act.

(e) RIGHT TO REPAIR AND MIGRATION; CIRCUMVENTION EXEMPTIONS.--

    (1) IN GENERAL.-- Section 1201 of title 17, United States Code, is
    amended by adding at the end the following new subsections:

    "(k) REPAIR.--

        "(1) DEFINITION.-- For purposes of this subsection, the term
        'repair' means the diagnosis, maintenance, or repair of a device or
        piece of equipment, including the restoration of the device or
        equipment to its original specifications or lawful operating
        condition following diagnosis, maintenance, or repair.

        "(2) PERMISSIBLE ACTS OF CIRCUMVENTION.-- Notwithstanding subsection
        (a)(1), it is not a violation of this section for a person to
        circumvent a technological measure that effectively controls access
        to a computer program contained in, or that controls the function
        of, a device or piece of equipment, where the circumvention is
        undertaken solely for the purpose of repair and is undertaken by, or
        with the authorization of, the owner of the device or equipment.

        "(3) TOOLS.-- Notwithstanding subsection (a)(2), it is not a
        violation of this section to manufacture, import, offer to the
        public, provide, or otherwise traffic in a technology, product,
        service, device, component, or part thereof that is primarily
        designed or produced for the purpose of enabling circumvention
        described in paragraph (2) of this subsection, that has only limited
        commercially significant purpose or use other than to enable such
        circumvention, or that is marketed for use in achieving such
        circumvention.

        "(4) SCOPE.-- The exemption established by this subsection applies
        without regard to whether the owner or repairer of the device or
        equipment is affiliated with any cooperative, network, or
        organization recognized under this Act or any other provision of
        Federal law, and without regard to the make, model, manufacturer, or
        category of the device or equipment. Nothing in this subsection
        authorizes circumvention undertaken for any purpose other than
        repair as defined in paragraph (1), and nothing in this subsection
        shall be construed to permit the infringement of any copyright in a
        computer program or other work by means of the reproduction or
        distribution of that program or work following circumvention.".

    "(l) MIGRATION.--

        "(1) DEFINITION.-- For purposes of this subsection, the term
        'migration' means the transfer of an account holder's data from a
        Covered Platform, as defined in section 409(a)(1) of title IV of the
        Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act, to a
        Qualified Federated Network, at the explicit direction of the
        account holder, pursuant to the migration interface duty established
        under section 409 of that title.

        "(2) PERMISSIBLE ACTS OF CIRCUMVENTION.-- Notwithstanding subsection
        (a)(1), it is not a violation of this section for a Qualified
        Federated Network or its authorized technical agents to circumvent a
        technological measure that effectively controls access to a computer
        program or data structure maintained by a Covered Platform, where the
        circumvention is undertaken solely for the purpose of migration as
        defined in paragraph (1) of this subsection, and where the Covered
        Platform has failed to make available a documented migration
        interface meeting the requirements of section 409(b) of title IV of
        the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives Act within
        the time period required by that section.

        "(3) TOOLS.-- Notwithstanding subsection (a)(2), it is not a
        violation of this section to manufacture, import, offer to the
        public, provide, or otherwise traffic in a technology, product,
        service, device, component, or part thereof that is primarily
        designed or produced for the purpose of enabling circumvention
        described in paragraph (2) of this subsection.

        "(4) SUNSET UPON COMPLIANCE.-- The exemption established by
        paragraph (2) of this subsection ceases to apply to a specific
        Covered Platform upon that platform's publication of a compliant
        migration interface meeting the requirements of section 409(b) of
        title IV of the Federal Resilience and Decentralization Initiatives
        Act. The exemption does not authorize ongoing circumvention as a
        substitute for use of a compliant interface once one is made
        available.".

    (2) RULE OF CONSTRUCTION.-- The exemptions established by subsections
    (k) and (l) of section 1201 of title 17, United States Code, as added by
    paragraph (1) of this subsection, apply in addition to, and not in lieu
    of, any exemption granted under the rulemaking authority of the
    Librarian of Congress pursuant to section 1201(a)(1)(C) of title 17,
    United States Code, or under any other provision of section 1201 of
    title 17, United States Code.

