SEC. 507. THE COPYLEFT MANDATE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL REQUIREMENT.-- All works created by building upon, remixing,
adapting, or otherwise deriving from any work or innovation held in the
Intellectual Property Commons shall themselves be contributed to the IP Commons
upon their completion or first public use, whichever occurs earlier. The copyleft
mandate is the primary anti-enclosure mechanism of the IP Commons -- it ensures
that the commons grows with each use rather than being depleted by it, and that
private parties cannot extract commons knowledge, add value through derivative
development, and re-enclose the result as proprietary property.

(b) SCOPE.-- The copyleft mandate applies to:

    (1) any work that incorporates, quotes, samples, remixes, or otherwise
    directly uses any portion of a commons work in a manner that would constitute
    copyright infringement under current law absent a license;

    (2) any technical innovation that is functionally dependent upon, directly
    implements, or substantially improves upon any patent, process, or technical
    design held in the IP Commons; and

    (3) any software that links to, compiles with, or otherwise incorporates
    commons-licensed code in a manner that creates a functional dependency between
    the derivative work and the commons work.

(c) EXCEPTIONS.-- The copyleft mandate does not apply to:

    (1) works that use commons materials in a manner analogous to fair use under
    current copyright law -- including criticism, commentary, parody, education,
    and research -- where the use does not create a derivative work that
    substitutes for the commons original;

    (2) works that reference commons technical concepts at a level of generality
    that does not incorporate specific commons expression -- for example, a work
    that implements a general programming concept present in a commons algorithm
    without incorporating the specific code of that algorithm; and

    (3) works created by Commons Members for purely personal use that are not
    publicly distributed or deployed within the network.

(d) ENFORCEMENT.-- The copyleft mandate shall be enforced as follows:

    (1) any Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network that
    deploys a derivative work without contributing it to the IP Commons pursuant
    to this Section shall be subject to the graduated response procedures of
    Section 103(c)(2) of this Act;

    (2) any party outside the Federated Network that uses commons materials to
    create a derivative work without contributing the derivative to the IP Commons
    shall be subject to civil action by the IP Commons Governance Council in any
    federal court of competent jurisdiction, with remedies including injunctive
    relief, disgorgement of profits attributable to the commons contribution, and
    statutory damages; and

    (3) the IP Commons Governance Council shall maintain a monitoring function --
    the Commons Integrity Monitor -- that tracks public uses of commons materials
    and identifies potential copyleft mandate violations, prioritizing monitoring
    resources on uses by large commercial entities with the capacity to re-enclose
    commons knowledge at scale.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 508. ANTI-CONCENTRATION PROVISIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) COMMONS GOVERNANCE CONCENTRATION LIMIT.-- No individual Commons Member shall
receive commons governance recognition -- in the form of governance weight,
priority resource access, or other non-monetary recognition within the IP Commons
governance framework -- that is disproportionate to their actual contribution to
the commons, as assessed through the governance processes of the IP Commons
Governance Council. Where a member's contribution would generate recognition that
concentrates governance influence inconsistently with the democratic governance
principles of Standard 3 of Section 102(d) of this Act, the IP Commons
Governance Council shall:

    (1) apply a progressive contribution requirement, under which members whose
    contributions generate above-threshold recognition are required to contribute
    additional works, technical assistance, or governance participation to the
    commons at rates that scale with the degree of recognition concentration; and

    (2) ensure that recognition within the IP Commons governance framework never
    translates into a financial claim against any commons asset or a voting
    advantage in any Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated
    Network.

(b) PROHIBITION ON IP COMMONS OLIGARCHY.-- The IP Commons shall be governed as a
genuinely democratic commons institution, and no individual, enterprise, or
coordinated group of individuals shall be permitted to accumulate governance
influence within the IP Commons disproportionate to the broader membership.
Specifically:

    (1) no individual or enterprise shall hold more than five percent of the total
    governance weight in the IP Commons Governance Council through any combination
    of electoral representation, contribution recognition, or other mechanism;

    (2) the IP Commons Governance Council shall monitor governance weight
    distribution on a continuous basis and shall take corrective action --
    including adjustment of representation formulas, mandatory contribution
    requirements, and governance weight redistribution -- where concentration
    approaches the five percent threshold; and

    (3) any Commons Member who believes that governance weight concentration is
    distorting IP Commons governance may petition the Data Commons Governance
    Council for an independent assessment, which shall be completed within sixty
    days.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 509. IP COMMONS GOVERNANCE COUNCIL.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established the IP Commons Governance Council --
the primary governance institution of the Federated Intellectual Property
Commons. The IP Commons Governance Council is a commons governance institution
accountable to the Commons Members whose knowledge it stewards, operating under
the nested governance architecture of Standard 8 of Section 102(i) of this Act.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The IP Commons Governance Council shall comprise:

    (1) elected representatives of Qualified Federated Networks, with
    representation proportional to the number of IP Commons contributors within
    each network, subject to a minimum of one representative per certified QFN;

    (2) dedicated seats for contributors in each major IP category -- creative
    works, technical innovations, traditional knowledge, educational resources,
    scientific research, and governance innovations -- with not fewer than two
    representatives per category selected through processes determined by
    contributors within that category;

    (3) dedicated seats for indigenous communities pursuant to the provisions of
    Section 404(d) of Title IV of this Act, with not fewer than five seats
    selected through processes determined by those communities; and

    (4) technical advisors -- non-voting members with expertise in intellectual
    property law, open-source governance, commons management, and relevant
    technical domains -- appointed by the elected representatives for two-year
    renewable terms, with the following institutions invited to nominate standing
    technical advisors in their respective domains of expertise:

        (A) the Open Knowledge Foundation, for matters relating to open data
        standards, the Open Definition, and the interoperability of the IP
        Commons with existing open knowledge infrastructure;

        (B) the Ostrom Workshop in Political Theory and Policy Analysis at
        Indiana University, for matters relating to the operationalization and
        adequacy review of the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship as applied to IP
        governance; and

        (C) the Platform Cooperativism Consortium, for matters relating to
        the governance of digital platform cooperatives, cooperative
        ownership of algorithmic systems, and the intersection of IP commons
        governance with the automation and data governance provisions of
        this Act.

    Nominations from these institutions are advisory; the elected representatives
    retain full discretion over appointments to technical advisor seats and are
    not bound to accept any particular nominee.

(c) FUNCTIONS.-- The IP Commons Governance Council shall:

    (1) govern the attribution registration system, including oversight of QFN
    Witness certification and the retrospective registration and restitution
    processes;

    (2) govern the copyleft mandate, including operation of the Commons Integrity
    Monitor and enforcement proceedings against copyleft violations;

    (3) oversee the shelved patent recapture proceedings pursuant to Section
    503(d) of this Title;

    (4) govern the anti-thicket provisions pursuant to Section 506(d) of this
    Title;

    (5) conduct the mandatory adequacy reviews of the IP Commons framework
    pursuant to Section 212 of Title II of this Act;

    (6) govern the Traditional Knowledge Prior Art Database pursuant to Section
    404(e)(2) of Title IV of this Act;

    (7) coordinate with the Data Commons Governance Council on matters affecting
    both IP governance and data governance;

    (8) represent the IP Commons in any legal proceedings involving the commons'
    intellectual property rights, including enforcement actions against enclosure
    attempts and defense of commons contributions against external claims; and

    (9) draw upon the research findings of the DARPA Systematizing Confidence in
    Open Research and Evidence program, and any successor research on automated
    credibility assessment, in developing the multi-dimensional knowledge quality
    assessment frameworks used to govern the IP Commons, recognizing the empirical
    finding that scientific credibility is multidimensional and not reducible to
    single algorithmic metrics, consistent with the multi-layer governance
    approach established by this Act.

(d) OPEN GOVERNANCE REQUIREMENT.-- All proceedings of the IP Commons Governance
Council -- including deliberations, votes, and decisions -- shall be conducted in
public and recorded on the National Resilience Ledger, subject to the following
exceptions:

    (1) proceedings involving specific individuals' attribution disputes or
    enforcement actions may be conducted in private where the privacy of the
    individuals concerned requires it, with a public summary of the outcome
    recorded on the ledger; and

    (2) proceedings involving matters of network security or the integrity of the
    commons infrastructure may be conducted in private where public disclosure
    would undermine the security purpose, with a public record of the fact of the
    private proceeding and the general subject matter.

(e) NETWORK-WIDE REFERENDUM OVERRIDE.-- Decisions of the IP Commons Governance
Council are subject to override by the full Federated Network membership through
a network-wide referendum conducted through the participatory governance tools of
Title VII of this Act, upon petition by not less than five percent of active
Commons Members. A referendum override requires a simple majority of
participating Commons Members, with a minimum participation threshold of ten
percent of the total active Commons Member population.

(f) UNIFIED COMMONS GOVERNANCE COUNCIL STRUCTURE.--

    (1) ESTABLISHMENT.-- The IP Commons Governance Council established under
    subsection (a) of this Section, the Data Commons Governance Council
    established under Section 405(a) of Title IV of this Act, and the
    Commons Credit Governance Council established under Section 608(a) of
    Title VI of this Act are hereby constituted as the three Divisions of a
    single unified body, the Commons Governance Council. Each Division
    retains the composition, functions, decision-making procedures, and name
    specified for it in the Section of this Act establishing that Division,
    and every reference elsewhere in this Act to the IP Commons Governance
    Council, the Data Commons Governance Council, or the Commons Credit
    Governance Council refers to that Division of the Commons Governance
    Council established by this subsection.

    (2) PURPOSE OF CONSOLIDATION.-- The consolidation effected by this
    subsection is structural, not substantive. It does not alter the
    composition, jurisdiction, or decision-making procedures of any Division
    as established elsewhere in this Act. Its purpose is to replace three
    separate nomination, confirmation, and oversight processes with a single
    one, reducing the number of distinct federally cognizable governance
    bodies subject to appointment, capture, or defunding, while preserving
    the full substantive independence and distinct constituencies of each
    Division's governance.

    (3) COORDINATING BOARD.-- There is established a Coordinating Board of
    the Commons Governance Council, comprising the elected chair of each
    Division, which shall:

        (A) meet not less than quarterly to resolve jurisdictional questions
        arising at the boundary of two or more Divisions' authority,
        including the matters already subject to inter-Division coordination
        duties under Section 405(c)(7) of Title IV, Section 509(c)(7) of this
        Title, and Section 608(c)(6) of Title VI of this Act;

        (B) constitute the body responsible for any function this Act
        assigns jointly to more than one Division, including the
        composition determination for the Federated Accountability Board
        under Section 1103(b)(2) of Title XI of this Act; and

        (C) have no authority to direct, override, or alter the substantive
        decisions of any individual Division, whose governance autonomy
        within its own jurisdiction is preserved in full.

    (4) SINGLE CONFIRMATION PROCESS.-- Where any provision of this Act would
    otherwise require separate appointment, nomination, or confirmation
    processes for the IP Commons Governance Council, the Data Commons
    Governance Council, or the Commons Credit Governance Council, those
    processes are hereby consolidated into a single process administered
    jointly, with each Division's distinct seats, selection criteria, and
    constituency-specific procedures preserved exactly as specified in the
    Section of this Act establishing that Division, and with only the
    administrative machinery of the appointment process, not the substantive
    composition requirements, consolidated.

    (5) NO EFFECT ON EXISTING CROSS-REFERENCES.-- Every cross-reference
    elsewhere in this Act to a Section establishing the composition,
    functions, or decision-making procedures of the IP Commons Governance
    Council, the Data Commons Governance Council, or the Commons Credit
    Governance Council remains valid and continues to refer to the same
    Section number and the same governing text, notwithstanding the
    consolidation effected by this subsection.

