SEC. 510. AI-GENERATED WORKS AND AUTOMATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDINGS.--

    (1) Congress finds that the questions raised by artificial intelligence
    training and generation are not separate from the questions this Title
    otherwise addresses regarding human creativity and innovation, but are
    the same underlying commons problem viewed from two points of use: the
    extraction of value from collectively created knowledge without
    reciprocity, whether that extraction takes the form of corporate
    enclosure of human creative and inventive output or the uncompensated
    use of commons-held work as training data for artificial intelligence
    systems. The rapid advancement of artificial intelligence systems
    capable of generating creative works, technical innovations, and other
    intellectual output raises novel questions about attribution,
    contribution, and governance that the traditional intellectual property
    framework is ill-equipped to address, and the IP Commons framework,
    with its emphasis on collective governance, open attribution, and
    anti-enclosure, provides a more appropriate foundation for governing
    AI-generated intellectual output, and the relationship between human
    creators and the artificial intelligence systems trained on their work,
    than the enclosure-based alternatives, for the same reasons it provides
    a more appropriate foundation for governing human creative and
    innovative work generally.

    (2) Congress finds that this Title accordingly applies a single
    governance architecture, permanent attribution, anti-enclosure through
    the copyleft mandate of Section 507 of this Title, and material
    security through the Guaranteed Provision Standard, to both human and
    artificial creative and inventive processes, while calibrating the
    specific mechanisms of artificial intelligence training compensation
    according to the cosmo-local principle articulated in the peer-to-peer
    commons research of Michel Bauwens: that knowledge and creative
    expression, being non-rivalrous and costless to replicate, should
    circulate and be governed according to the community of practice that
    depends on them rather than according to geographic or sectoral
    boundary, while the deployment of physical resources, including the
    pharmaceutical, energy, and agricultural technology addressed by the
    priority categories of Section 503(d)(3) of this Title, properly
    remains governed according to the urgency already established there.

(b) AI-GENERATED WORKS -- ATTRIBUTION RULES.-- The following attribution rules
shall apply to works generated by artificial intelligence systems within the
Federated Network:

    (1) works generated by an AI system operating entirely autonomously, without
    substantial human creative direction, shall be contributed to the IP Commons
    as collectively owned works without individual attribution, with any commons
    engagement generated by the work flowing to the commons general fund;

    (2) works generated by an AI system in response to substantial human creative
    direction -- defined as a level of direction that would constitute authorship
    under the pre-existing legal standard for human-AI collaboration -- shall be
    attributed to the directing human, with the AI system's role documented in the
    attribution record;

    (3) works generated by an AI system trained on commons materials shall carry
    in their attribution record a reference to the commons training data that
    contributed to their generation, ensuring that the collective intellectual
    contribution of the commons is acknowledged in AI outputs; and

    (4) the boundary between autonomous AI generation and substantially
    human-directed AI generation shall be governed by the IP Commons Governance
    Council, which shall develop and maintain standards for this distinction
    through its open governance process.

(c) PROHIBITION ON AI ENCLOSURE.-- No party shall use an AI system to generate
works based on commons materials and then assert proprietary intellectual property
rights in the generated works. AI-generated works that are substantially derived
from commons materials are subject to the copyleft mandate of Section 507 of this
Title regardless of the degree of human direction involved in their generation.

(d) AI TRANSPARENCY -- TRAINING DATA AND OUTPUT DISCLOSURE.-- Any AI system
deployed within the Federated Network for the generation of creative works or
technical innovations shall:

    (1) maintain a publicly accessible record of the training data used to
    develop the system, with sufficient specificity to allow determination
    of whether commons materials contributed to the system's training;

    (2) provide attribution references to commons training data in all
    outputs as required by subsection (b)(3) of this Section;

    (3) contribute to the IP Commons any technical innovations in AI
    methodology developed during the system's operation within the
    network, subject to the copyleft mandate of Section 507 of this Title;
    and

    (4) OUTPUT DISCLOSURE.-- include, in a machine-readable format attached
    to or accompanying each output, a disclosure identifying the output as
    generated in whole or in part by an artificial intelligence system,
    recorded in a manner compatible with the Federated Mesh Open Standard
    established under Section 701 of Title VII of this Act; this
    requirement applies regardless of whether the output incorporates
    commons training data and is independent of the attribution
    requirements of subsection (b) of this Section.

(e) AUTOMATION AND CREATIVE LABOR.-- Congress finds that the increasing capacity
of AI systems to perform work previously requiring human creative and technical
labor creates both risks and opportunities for the commons economy. Within the
Federated Network:

    (1) AI-assisted production that reduces the labor burden on Commons Members
    shall be understood as a commons benefit -- freeing members for creative,
    governance, and community activities that machines cannot perform -- rather
    than as a threat to members' Guaranteed Provision Standard, which is
    unconditional and does not depend on labor contribution;

    (2) the productivity gains generated by AI-assisted production within the
    commons shall be distributed through improvements to the Guaranteed Provision
    Standard and reductions in required labor contributions, rather than through
    accumulation by any individual member or enterprise; and

    (3) the IP Commons Governance Council shall monitor the impact of AI-assisted
    production on the distribution of commons benefits and shall report annually
    on whether the commons is successfully capturing the productivity gains of
    automation for the benefit of all members.

(f) HUMAN PROVENANCE AND DISCOVERY INFRASTRUCTURE.--

    (1) ESTABLISHMENT.-- The Technical Standards Body established under
    Section 701(d) of Title VII of this Act shall develop and maintain an
    open, non-proprietary specification for a voluntary provenance record,
    through which a Commons Member or other creator may document the
    creative process by which a work was produced, including the sequence
    of drafts, revisions, and tool use involved, for the purpose of
    providing a verifiable record of human creative contribution distinct
    from the attribution and training-data disclosures otherwise required
    by this Section.

    (2) VOLUNTARY AND ZERO-COST.-- Use of the provenance record established
    under this subsection is voluntary, available without charge to any
    creator, and shall not be required as a condition of participation in
    any Federated Network, attribution registration under Section 504 of
    this Title, or any benefit otherwise available under this Act.

    (3) RECORD CONTENT.-- The provenance record shall accommodate a
    graduated disclosure of the degree and nature of artificial
    intelligence involvement in a work's creation, rather than a binary
    designation of the work as human-made or AI-made, recognizing that most
    creative work involving digital tools reflects some combination of
    human direction and automated assistance.

    (4) RECORDATION.-- A creator electing to use the provenance record
    shall log the relevant process information on the National Resilience
    Ledger contemporaneously with the work's creation, to the extent
    practicable, rather than asserting provenance after the fact.

    (5) MONITORING AND VERIFICATION.-- Verification of provenance records
    shall be conducted by members of the Qualified Federated Network or
    Qualified Federated Cooperative with which the creator is affiliated,
    through a graduated process established by that Network's or
    Cooperative's own governance procedures, beginning with correction of
    inaccurate records and escalating to suspension of provenance
    recordation privileges only upon a demonstrated pattern of false
    attestation. Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to require
    the establishment of a centralized federal verification authority.

    (6) DISCOVERY AND CURATION.-- Each Qualified Federated Network or
    Qualified Federated Cooperative may develop its own tools, platforms,
    or curation practices for surfacing works documented through the
    provenance record established under this subsection, and nothing in
    this subsection shall be construed to establish a single national
    standard for the curation or promotion of such works.

