SEC. 511. AI TRAINING CALIBRATION AND COLLECTIVE LICENSING INFRASTRUCTURE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PURPOSE.-- This Section establishes the institutional infrastructure
through which the elections available to creators and inventors under
Section 506(a)(7) and Section 503(d)(4) of this Title are calibrated and
administered.

(b) DOMAIN-OF-PRACTICE CALIBRATION BODIES.--

    (1) ESTABLISHMENT.-- The IP Commons Governance Council shall establish
    standing committees, to be known as Domain-of-Practice Calibration
    Bodies, organized according to communities of creative and inventive
    practice rather than according to geographic network or political
    subdivision, consistent with the principle that knowledge and creative
    expression, being non-rivalrous, are properly governed by the community
    that depends on and contributes to them rather than by territorial
    boundary.

    (2) ILLUSTRATIVE DOMAINS.-- Domains may include, without limitation,
    literary and textual work, musical composition and recording, visual
    and audiovisual art, software and technical design, pharmaceutical and
    medical technology, renewable energy and climate technology, and
    agricultural technology, provided that the IP Commons Governance
    Council retains discretion to define, combine, subdivide, or add
    domains as the composition of the commons evolves, and shall not be
    bound to the domains enumerated in this paragraph.

    (3) COMPOSITION.-- Each Domain-of-Practice Calibration Body shall be
    composed of Commons Members and, where applicable, Collective
    Licensing Bodies recognized under subsection (e) of this Section, who
    create or invent within that domain, selected through the open
    governance process established under Section 509(d) of this Title.

(c) STATUTORY FLOOR.-- Where a creator or inventor elects the continuing
payment option under Section 506(a)(7)(A)(ii) or Section 503(d)(4)(A)(ii) of
this Title, or receives that option by default, that creator or inventor
shall receive not less than fifty percent of the value attributed to the
AI-training use of their work or invention, calculated pursuant to
subsection (d) of this Section, regardless of any contrary determination by
a Domain-of-Practice Calibration Body; the remaining share shall be
allocated as provided in subsection (d) of this Section.

(d) ALLOCATION ABOVE THE FLOOR.-- Subject to the floor established by
subsection (c) of this Section, each Domain-of-Practice Calibration Body
shall determine, through its own governance process and subject to revision
not less often than once every two years:

    (1) the methodology for calculating the value attributed to AI-training
    use of a work or invention within its domain;

    (2) the allocation of any share above the statutory floor between the
    individual creator or inventor and the monitoring, verification, and
    collective licensing infrastructure of that domain, including the
    provenance and discovery infrastructure established under Section
    510(f) of this Title; and

    (3) such other procedures as are necessary to administer the elections
    available under Section 506(a)(7) and Section 503(d)(4) of this Title
    within that domain.

(e) COLLECTIVE LICENSING BODIES.--

    (1) RECOGNITION.-- The IP Commons Governance Council shall recognize
    Collective Licensing Bodies, voluntary associations of creators or
    inventors organized to negotiate and administer AI training licenses,
    elections, and payments on behalf of their members, modeled on the
    function performed by performing rights organizations for musical works
    and patent pools for patented technology.

    (2) ELIGIBILITY.-- Any creator or inventor may join a Collective
    Licensing Body recognized under this subsection. The IP Commons
    Governance Council shall prioritize technical assistance and support
    for the formation of Collective Licensing Bodies organized by or for
    the benefit of individual creators, individual inventors, and small
    entities, recognizing that the bargaining power a Collective Licensing
    Body provides is most needed by creators and inventors who would
    otherwise negotiate alone.

    (3) ANTITRUST SAFE HARBOR.-- The collective negotiation and
    administration of AI training elections, licenses, and payments by a
    Collective Licensing Body recognized under this subsection, on behalf
    of its members, shall not be construed to violate the Sherman Act or
    the Federal Trade Commission Act solely by virtue of that collective
    conduct, provided the Collective Licensing Body's conduct is limited to
    the administration of the elections and payments established under
    Section 506(a)(7) and Section 503(d)(4) of this Title.

(f) REVIEW.-- The IP Commons Governance Council shall report to Congress
not less often than once every four years on whether the allocation
determinations of the Domain-of-Practice Calibration Bodies under
subsection (d) of this Section, and the maturity of the Guaranteed
Provision Standard's coverage of affected creators and inventors, warrant
any adjustment to the statutory floor established by subsection (c) of
this Section.


================================================================================
TITLE VI -- THE COMMONS CREDIT SYSTEM
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the monetary architecture of the
commons economy -- a system of value exchange that serves the coordination needs
of the Federated Network without reproducing the extractive dynamics of
debt-based fiat currency. The Commons Credit is not a cryptocurrency, a
stablecoin, or a speculative digital asset. It is a unit of account backed by
the verifiable productive capacity of the commons -- the energy generated, the
food produced, the knowledge shared, the labor contributed -- and governed as a
commons resource by the communities that use it. The Commons Credit does not
compete with the United States dollar. It makes the dollar progressively less
necessary within the commons economy by providing a medium of exchange
calibrated to the actual productive metabolism of the network rather than to the
speculative dynamics of global financial markets.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 601. THE NATIONAL RESILIENCE LEDGER -- CREDIT FUNCTIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT OF CREDIT FUNCTIONS.-- The National Resilience Ledger
established as a land registry under Section 306 of Title III of this Act shall
additionally serve as the distributed ledger infrastructure for the Commons
Credit system established by this Title. The credit functions of the National
Resilience Ledger shall:

    (1) record the issuance, transfer, and redemption of Commons Credits with
    cryptographic integrity and public auditability;

    (2) maintain the Commons Credit accounts of all certified Qualified Federated
    Cooperatives, Qualified Federated Networks, Commons Financial Nodes, and
    individual Commons Members;

    (3) execute automated credit transactions triggered by defined on-ledger
    conditions -- including Stewardship Credit issuances upon CLT land
    acquisition, Bootstrap Grant disbursements, and inter-network resource
    exchange settlements -- without requiring off-ledger authorization;

    (4) support time-banking credit transactions pursuant to Section 604 of this
    Title;

    (5) provide publicly auditable records of the total Commons Credit supply, the
    distribution of credits across the network, and the velocity of credit
    circulation, sufficient to allow the Commons Credit Governance Council to
    monitor the credit system's health and make informed governance decisions; and

    (6) implement the technical protections against executive override of
    automated disbursements established under Section 104(c) of this Act.

(b) DISTRIBUTED ARCHITECTURE.-- The credit functions of the National Resilience
Ledger shall be implemented on the Federated Mesh rather than on any centralized
server, consistent with the distributed architecture requirements of Title VII of
this Act, such that:

    (1) no single entity -- governmental, corporate, or individual -- holds a
    master key or administrative override capability that would permit unilateral
    modification of credit balances, transaction records, or issuance mechanisms;

    (2) the ledger's transaction validation shall operate through a consensus
    mechanism that requires agreement among a distributed set of validator nodes,
    with validator node status available to any certified Qualified Federated
    Network that meets the technical requirements established under Title VII of
    this Act; and

    (3) the smart contract code governing automated credit transactions shall be
    open-source, publicly auditable, and modifiable only through the governance
    process established under Section 608 of this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 602. COMMONS CREDIT -- DEFINITION AND LEGAL STATUS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) NATURE AND CONSTITUTIONAL BASIS.-- Congress finds that the Commons Credit
is a privately denominated unit of account operating within a defined closed
cooperative network, analogous in legal character to other non-governmental
exchange instruments that have operated within the United States without
constitutional conflict, including mutual credit systems, time-banking credits,
and cooperative scrip. The Commons Credit does not constitute an attempt to
establish a competing national currency. It does not displace the United States
dollar as the medium of exchange for any obligation incurred outside the
Federated Network, does not satisfy any obligation denominated in United States
dollars except through the limited interface mechanisms expressly authorized by
subsection (c) of this Section, and is not intended to, and shall not be
construed to, impair the constitutional monetary authority of Congress or the
operational authority of the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System.

(b) DEFINITION.-- The Commons Credit is the unit of account of the commons
economy, as defined in Section 4(2) of this Act. Commons Credits are:

    (1) ASSET-BACKED -- each Commons Credit issued through the National Resilience
    Ledger represents a verifiable unit of commons productive output, including
    energy generated by cooperative microgrids, food produced by commons
    agricultural enterprises, labor contributed through time-banking, knowledge
    added to the IP Commons, and infrastructure maintained through cooperative
    stewardship;

    (2) NON-SPECULATIVE -- Commons Credits are not issued as debt obligations, do
    not bear interest, and are not subject to fractional reserve multiplication.
    The total Commons Credit supply at any time reflects the actual accumulated
    productive output of the commons economy, not a speculative multiple of that
    output;

    (3) NON-INFLATIONARY WITHIN THE COMMONS ECONOMY -- because each Commons
    Credit represents a defined unit of actual productive output, the issuance of
    additional credits in proportion to the growth of the commons economy does not
    constitute inflation but rather the accurate reflection of increased
    productive capacity; and

    (4) LEGALLY RECOGNIZED -- Commons Credits are hereby recognized as legal
    tender for all transactions within a certified Qualified Federated Network,
    including the delivery of Guaranteed Provision Standard components, including 
    the delivery of Guaranteed Provision Standard components, the settlement of 
    Reparative Debt obligations recognized under Section 606 of this Title, and 
    inter-network resource exchange transactions.

(c) RELATIONSHIP TO THE UNITED STATES DOLLAR.-- Commons Credits are not pegged
to, convertible into, or redeemable for United States dollars except through the
limited mechanisms established in subsection (d) of this Section. The Commons
Credit and the United States dollar are parallel monetary instruments serving
different economic functions:

    (1) the United States dollar remains the medium of exchange for transactions
    in the external market economy, including transactions between Commons Members
    and non-commons parties, payment of federal taxes, and purchases of goods and
    services not available within the Federated Network;

    (2) the Commons Credit is the medium of exchange for transactions within the
    Federated Network, including provision delivery, inter-cooperative resource
    exchange, time-banking, and commons governance processes; and

    (3) the coexistence of the two monetary systems is a transitional feature of
    the commons economy -- as the network's productive capacity grows and its
    ability to provide for its members' needs without recourse to the external
    market economy increases, the proportion of members' material lives conducted
    in Commons Credits will grow correspondingly.

(d) LIMITED DOLLAR INTERFACE.-- Commons Credits may interface with the United
States dollar through the following limited mechanisms:

    (1) BOOTSTRAP GRANT DISBURSEMENT -- Bootstrap Grants issued in United States
    dollars pursuant to Section 106 of this Act may be converted to Commons
    Credits by receiving organizations through the Commons Financial Nodes
    established under Section 4(3) of this Act, at exchange rates established by
    the Commons Credit Governance Council pursuant to Section 608 of this Title;

    (2) EXTERNAL TRADE SETTLEMENT -- proceeds from the sale of surplus commons
    resources into the external market economy pursuant to Section 307(d)(3) of
    Title III of this Act shall be received in United States dollars and may be
    held in Commons Financial Node accounts pending reinvestment in the commons;
    and

    (3) MEMBER DOLLAR TRANSACTIONS -- individual Commons Members may convert
    Commons Credits to United States dollars through Commons Financial Nodes for
    the purpose of transactions in the external market economy, at exchange rates
    established by the Commons Credit Governance Council, subject to the
    anti-speculation restrictions of subsection (e) of this Section.

(e) ANTI-SPECULATION RESTRICTIONS.-- To prevent Commons Credits from becoming
instruments of financial speculation:

    (1) no Commons Member, Qualified Federated Cooperative, or Qualified Federated
    Network shall hold Commons Credits in excess of a reasonable reserve amount
    established by the Commons Credit Governance Council, beyond which excess
    credits must be redeemed for goods and services within the network or
    transferred to other members;

    (2) no financial instrument -- including derivatives, futures, options, or
    structured products -- shall be created using Commons Credits as the
    underlying asset, and any attempt to create such an instrument shall be void
    and unenforceable; and

    (3) no party outside the Federated Network shall be permitted to hold, trade,
    or speculate in Commons Credits, and the Commons Financial Nodes shall
    implement technical controls preventing the transfer of Commons Credits to
    parties without active Federated Commons Membership.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 603. STEWARDSHIP CREDITS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) DEFINITION.-- Stewardship Credits are a specialized category of Commons
Credits issued by the National Resilience Ledger to recognize and capitalize
specific acts of commons stewardship -- including CLT land acquisition, IP
Commons contribution, and military-civilian technology transfer -- that generate
long-term productive value for the Federated Network.

(b) ISSUANCE EVENTS.-- Stewardship Credits shall be issued automatically by the
National Resilience Ledger upon verification of the following stewardship acts:

    (1) CLT land acquisition, at the rates established under Section 306(a)(1) of
    Title III of this Act;

    (2) contribution of shelved patents to the IP Commons following recapture
    proceedings under Section 503(d) of Title V of this Act, at rates reflecting
    the assessed productive potential of the contributed patent;

    (3) voluntary contribution of intellectual property to the IP Commons pursuant
    to Section 505 of Title V of this Act, at rates established by the IP Commons
    Governance Council reflecting the scope and significance of the contribution;

    (4) transfer of dual-use military technology to the IP Commons pursuant to
    Section 903 of Title IX of this Act, at rates reflecting the civilian
    deployment potential of the transferred technology;

    (5) completion of cooperative business conversion pursuant to Section 304 of
    Title III of this Act, at rates reflecting the number of employees converted
    and the assessed productive capacity of the enterprise; and

    (6) such other acts of commons stewardship as the Commons Credit Governance
    Council may designate, upon a finding that the act generates verifiable
    long-term productive value for the Federated Network.

(c) USE OF STEWARDSHIP CREDITS.-- Stewardship Credits issued pursuant to this
Section shall be used by the receiving entity for:

    (1) land acquisition through the Right of First Refusal pursuant to Section
    303 of Title III of this Act;

    (2) repayment of acquisition support received through the Commons
    Infrastructure Capitalization Fund pursuant to Section 306(b)(3) of Title III
    of this Act;

    (3) Bootstrap Grant matching contributions for cooperative formation
    initiatives within the receiving network's geographic area;

    (4) commons infrastructure development, including Federated Mesh hardware,
    renewable energy infrastructure, food production equipment, and community
    facilities; and

    (5) contributions to the Portability Solidarity Fund pursuant to Section
    210(c) of Title II of this Act.

(d) NON-TRANSFERABILITY.-- Stewardship Credits are not transferable between
entities except through the inter-network resource exchange mechanisms
established under Section 606 of this Title. They may not be converted to United
States dollars and may not be held as a reserve asset.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 604. TIME-BANKING INTEGRATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) RECOGNITION OF CARE AND COMMUNITY LABOR.-- Congress finds that a substantial
portion of the labor that sustains human communities -- including childcare, elder
care, mutual aid, community organizing, cultural production, and informal
teaching -- is systematically excluded from conventional monetary accounting and
thereby rendered economically invisible. The time-banking integration established
by this Section recognizes this labor as a genuine economic contribution and
creates a mechanism for its recognition within the Commons Credit system.

(b) TIME CREDIT ISSUANCE.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall operate or
affiliate with a time bank through which:

    (1) a Commons Member who contributes one hour of labor -- in any of the
    categories recognized by the network's collective-choice governance processes
    -- earns one Time Credit, regardless of the market value of the labor
    performed, consistent with the time-banking principle of equal valuation of
    all labor;

    (2) Time Credits are recorded on the National Resilience Ledger through the
    time bank's Commons Financial Node connection, providing a permanent and
    portable record of the member's labor contributions; and

    (3) Time Credits may be redeemed for equivalent hours of labor from other
    network members, for goods and services available within the network at
    exchange rates established through the network's collective-choice processes,
    or for Commons Credits at exchange rates established by the Commons Credit
    Governance Council.

(c) CARE WORK RECOGNITION.-- The following categories of labor shall be
recognized for Time Credit issuance as a mandatory minimum within every Qualified
Federated Network, with networks having discretion to recognize additional
categories through their collective-choice processes:

    (1) childcare and early childhood education;

    (2) elder care and care for members with disabilities;

    (3) healthcare support and community health work;

    (4) cooperative governance participation -- including attendance at governance
    meetings, participation in collective decision-making processes, and service
    on governance bodies;

    (5) community food production and preparation;

    (6) commons infrastructure maintenance and repair;

    (7) teaching, mentoring, and knowledge transmission; and

    (8) conflict resolution and community mediation.

(d) INTER-NETWORK TIME CREDIT PORTABILITY.-- Time Credits earned within one
Qualified Federated Network shall be recognized and redeemable within any other
Qualified Federated Network, at exchange rates established through inter-network
agreements recorded on the National Resilience Ledger, ensuring that a Commons
Member who relocates does not lose the value of their accumulated labor
contributions.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 605. COMMONS FINANCIAL NODES.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FUNCTIONS.-- Commons Financial Nodes registered pursuant to Section 4(3) of
this Act shall perform the following financial infrastructure functions within the
Federated Network:

    (1) COMMONS CREDIT ISSUANCE -- issuing Commons Credits in exchange for
    verified productive outputs reported through the Federated Mesh, at issuance
    rates established by the Commons Credit Governance Council;

    (2) BOOTSTRAP GRANT DISTRIBUTION -- receiving Bootstrap Grant funds from the
    Office of Federated Stewardship and distributing them to eligible recipients
    pursuant to Section 106 of this Act, converting dollar-denominated grant
    funds to Commons Credits where requested by recipient organizations;

    (3) COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE CAPITALIZATION FUND ADMINISTRATION -- originating,
    disbursing, and monitoring acquisition support provided through the Commons
    Infrastructure Capitalization Fund pursuant to Section 306(b)(3) of Title III
    of this Act, in coordination with the Secretary of the Treasury;

    (4) MEMBER FINANCIAL SERVICES -- providing individual Commons Members with
    access to their Commons Credit accounts, Time Credit records, and Commons
    Membership Record financial components, and facilitating the limited
    dollar-Commons Credit exchanges authorized under Section 602(c) of this
    Title; and

    (5) INTER-NETWORK SETTLEMENT -- facilitating the settlement of inter-network
    resource exchange transactions between Qualified Federated Networks, ensuring
    that Commons Credit transfers associated with commons-to-commons resource
    exchanges are recorded accurately on the National Resilience Ledger.

(b) FIDUCIARY OBLIGATIONS.-- Commons Financial Nodes shall operate under the
following fiduciary obligations to their member networks and individual Commons
Members:

    (1) to hold all Commons Credits, Stewardship Credits, and dollar-denominated
    funds in accounts that are segregated from the node's own operating funds and
    are not subject to the claims of the node's creditors;

    (2) to invest any dollar-denominated funds held pending conversion or
    disbursement only in instruments that are consistent with the commons values
    of this Act, specifically excluding investments in fossil fuel companies,
    private equity funds, hedge funds, and any other instrument whose returns
    depend on the extraction of value from communities or the exploitation of
    labor;

    (3) to provide each Commons Member with a complete, accurate, and
    comprehensible account statement not less than quarterly, recording all
    transactions affecting the member's Commons Credit and Time Credit balances;
    and

    (4) to report any suspected fraud, misappropriation, or system integrity
    failure to the IP Commons Governance Council and the Office of Federated
    Stewardship within seventy-two hours of detection.

(c) GOVERNANCE OF COMMONS FINANCIAL NODES.-- Commons Financial Nodes shall be
governed as cooperatively structured entities, with governance rights held by
their member networks and individual member depositors on a one-member-one-vote
basis consistent with Standard 3 of Section 102(d) of this Act. No Commons
Financial Node shall be governed by or subject to the direction of any private
equity fund, bank holding company, or other extractive financial institution.

