SEC. 606. REPARATIVE DEBT SETTLEMENT.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that communities harmed by historical injustices --
including the displacement of indigenous peoples from their lands, the
enslavement of African Americans and the subsequent century of economic
exclusion, the internment of Japanese Americans, and the systematic
underdevelopment of communities of color through redlining, disinvestment, and
extractive economic arrangements -- are owed forms of reparative recognition that
monetary payments alone cannot fully discharge. The commons economy, with its
emphasis on land stewardship, cooperative ownership, and community self-
determination, provides a framework within which reparative obligations can be
met through the transfer of productive capacity and governance rights rather than
solely through financial transfers.

(b) REPARATIVE DEBT DEFINED.-- Reparative Debt, for the purposes of this
Section, means the outstanding obligation owed by the federal government
and, where applicable, state governments and private institutions, to
communities that have been the systematic victims of governmental policies
producing demonstrable material harm, including:

    (1) forced displacement from land, whether through treaty violation, eminent
    domain abuse, discriminatory land use regulation, or other governmental
    action;

    (2) denial of access to economic opportunity through legally enforced
    discrimination, including racially restrictive covenants, redlining, exclusion
    from federal housing and mortgage programs, and discriminatory enforcement of
    criminal law resulting in labor exploitation; and

    (3) extraction of wealth from communities through environmental contamination,
    predatory financial practices sanctioned or facilitated by governmental
    actors, and other forms of institutionally supported economic harm.

(c) COMMONS CREDIT SETTLEMENT ARCHITECTURE.-- Reparative Debt obligations
recognized pursuant to this Section shall be discharged through the
following commons credit settlement architecture:

    (1) the federal government shall issue Stewardship Credits to designated
    reparative beneficiary communities -- defined as Qualified Federated Networks
    serving communities documented to have been subject to the harms described in
    subsection (b) of this Section -- at rates determined by the Commons Credit 
    Governance Council established under Section 608 of this Title; where a Reparative 
    Justice Commission or comparable body is later established by Federal law for
    the specific purpose of adjudicating reparative claims, the Commons Credit 
    Governance Council shall incorporate that body's rate determinations in lieu of 
    setting rates independently;

    (2) Stewardship Credits issued pursuant to this subsection shall be in
    addition to any other Bootstrap Grant or Stewardship Credit issuances to
    which the receiving network is entitled under this Act;

    (3) Stewardship Credits issued for reparative purposes shall be designated as
    Reparative Stewardship Credits on the National Resilience Ledger, shall carry
    a doubled use value for land acquisition purposes pursuant to Section 603(c)
    of this Title, and shall not be subject to the reserve accumulation
    restrictions of Section 602(d)(1) of this Title; and

    (4) the issuance of Reparative Stewardship Credits pursuant to this Section
    shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger as an act of federal
    reparative recognition, with the historical basis for the issuance documented
    in the ledger record as part of the commons governance history.

(d) RELATIONSHIP TO ACCOUNTABILITY COORDINATION DAO.-- The determination of which 
communities qualify as reparative beneficiary communities pursuant to subsection 
(b) of this Section, and the assessment of the appropriate Reparative Stewardship 
Credit issuance rates, shall be made through a process that includes meaningful
participation by the affected communities through the Accountability Coordination 
DAO governance structures established under Section 804 of Title VIII of this Act, 
ensuring that reparative recognition is not imposed upon communities from above but 
is shaped by those communities' own articulations of the harms suffered and the
remedies sought.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 607. ANTI-POVERTY AND PROVISION FLOOR.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the Guaranteed Provision Standard established
under Title II of this Act constitutes the primary anti-poverty mechanism of the
commons economy, and that no Commons Member who holds active Federated Commons
Membership shall experience material deprivation in the domains of housing,
nutrition, healthcare, connectivity, or knowledge access. The Commons Credit
system established by this Title reinforces the Guaranteed Provision Standard by
providing every Commons Member with a baseline Commons Credit allocation
sufficient to participate meaningfully in the commons economy beyond the minimum
provision floor.

(b) BASELINE COMMONS CREDIT ALLOCATION.-- Every Commons Member shall receive, at
the commencement of their Federated Commons Membership and on a renewable annual
basis thereafter, a baseline Commons Credit allocation sufficient to:

    (1) participate in at least one elective cooperative enterprise within the
    Federated Network beyond the mandatory baseline portfolio;

    (2) make at least one contribution to the IP Commons attribution registry;

    (3) access cooperative transportation services within the network for a
    minimum number of trips per year, as determined by the Commons Credit
    Governance Council based on typical mobility needs; and

    (4) maintain a minimal time-banking reserve sufficient to access emergency
    community care services if needed.

(c) BASELINE ALLOCATION MECHANISM.-- The baseline Commons Credit allocation
established by this Section shall be funded through the National Resilience
Ledger capitalization mechanism, issued automatically upon the recording of a new
Commons Membership on the ledger, and shall not be subject to means-testing,
behavioral conditions, or any other eligibility requirement beyond active
Federated Commons Membership.

(d) RELATIONSHIP TO GUARANTEED PROVISION STANDARD.-- The baseline Commons Credit
allocation established by this Section supplements but does not substitute for
the Guaranteed Provision Standard. A Commons Member's Guaranteed Provision
Standard entitlements are delivered through the mandatory baseline cooperative
memberships of Section 201(b) of this Act and do not depend on the member's
Commons Credit balance. The baseline allocation provides the member with
resources for participation and choice beyond the provision floor, not the floor
itself.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 608. COMMONS CREDIT GOVERNANCE COUNCIL.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established the Commons Credit Governance Council
-- the primary governance institution of the Commons Credit system established by
this Title. The Commons Credit Governance Council is a commons governance
institution, not a governmental or financial regulatory body, operating under the
nested governance architecture of Standard 8 of Section 102(i) of this Act. This 
Council is constituted as a Division of the Commons Governance Councilpursuant 
to Section 509(f) of Title V of this Act.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The Commons Credit Governance Council shall comprise:

    (1) elected representatives of Qualified Federated Networks, with
    representation proportional to the volume of Commons Credit transactions
    within each network, subject to a minimum of one representative per certified
    QFN;

    (2) representatives of Commons Financial Nodes, with not fewer than one
    representative per registered Node, selected through the cooperative
    governance processes of the Nodes themselves;

    (3) representatives of time-banking networks operating within the Federated
    Network, with not fewer than three seats allocated through a process
    determined by the time-banking community;

    (4) a non-voting liaison from the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve
    System, appointed by the Chair of the Federal Reserve, for the purpose of
    coordinating the interface between the Commons Credit system and the federal
    monetary system pursuant to Section 1004(d) of Title X of this Act; and

    (5) technical advisors -- non-voting members with expertise in monetary
    economics, cooperative finance, and distributed ledger systems -- appointed
    by the elected representatives for two-year terms.

(c) FUNCTIONS.-- The Commons Credit Governance Council shall:

    (1) establish and periodically revise the Commons Credit issuance rates --
    the rates at which specific categories of productive output are converted into
    Commons Credits -- ensuring that issuance rates accurately reflect the
    productive value of the outputs being recognized;

    (2) establish and periodically revise the Time Credit exchange rates --
    the rates at which Time Credits may be exchanged for Commons Credits -- based
    on the network's assessment of the relationship between care labor and
    productive output;

    (3) establish and periodically revise the dollar-Commons Credit exchange rates
    for the limited interface mechanisms of Section 602(c) of this Title;

    (4) monitor the total Commons Credit supply and circulation velocity and take
    such governance actions as are necessary to maintain the non-speculative,
    asset-backed character of the Commons Credit system;

    (5) govern the anti-speculation restrictions of Section 602(d) of this Title,
    including setting and enforcing the reserve accumulation limits;

    (6) coordinate with the Federal Reserve liaison on the relationship between
    Commons Credit growth and federal monetary policy, with the explicit
    understanding that neither Commons Credit issuance nor the Commons Land Asset
    Recognition mechanism of Section 306(b) of Title III of this Act constitutes
    monetary expansion subject to Federal Reserve policy, and that the Federal
    Reserve's role is to monitor and report rather than to regulate or constrain
    the commons economy's financial architecture;

    (7) report annually to the Federated Network membership and to Congress on the
    state of the Commons Credit system, including the total credit supply, the
    distribution of credits across networks and member categories, the velocity of
    credit circulation, and any governance concerns regarding the system's
    integrity or equity; and

    (8) govern the Reparative Stewardship Credit issuance rates established
    under Section 606(c) of this Title, incorporating the determinations of
    any Reparative Justice Commission or comparable body later established
    by Federal law for that purpose, and setting rates independently in the
    absence of such a body.

(d) MONETARY POLICY COORDINATION.-- The Commons Credit Governance Council shall
coordinate with the Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System on the
following matters:

    (1) the treatment of Commons Credit growth and Commons Land Asset Recognition
    issuances for monetary policy purposes, consistent with the directive of
    Section 1004(d) of Title X of this Act that these constitute asset-backed
    productive output rather than monetary expansion subject to Federal Reserve
    policy;

    (2) the development of monetary policy tools that account for the coexistence
    of the Commons Credit system and the United States dollar as parallel monetary
    instruments serving different economic functions; and

    (3) the long-term trajectory of the commons economy's independence from the
    dollar monetary system, treated as a measure of the commons economy's growing
    productive maturity rather than as a monetary policy threat.


================================================================================
TITLE VII -- TECHNICAL INFRASTRUCTURE AND HARDWARE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the open technical standards,
hardware requirements, and distributed systems architecture that make the
Federated Network physically real. The governance architecture established in
Titles I through VI is only as durable as the technical infrastructure on which
it runs. A commons economy governed through proprietary platforms, centralized
servers, or hardware whose identity mechanisms can be spoofed or cloned is not
genuinely self-sovereign -- it is dependent on the continued cooperation of the
technology vendors whose infrastructure it occupies. This Title establishes the
Federated Mesh Open Standard, the Physical Unclonable Function hardware
requirement, the Asynchronous Resource Coordination protocol, and the systemic
redundancy architecture that together ensure the Federated Network can govern
itself, provision its members, and resist both technical failure and deliberate
sabotage without dependence on any centralized party.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 701. FEDERATED MESH OPEN STANDARD -- ESTABLISHMENT AND ADOPTION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- The Secretary of Commerce, acting through the National
Institute of Standards and Technology, shall establish the Federated Mesh Open
Standard within one year of the date of enactment of this Act. The FMOS shall
be:

    (1) open and non-proprietary -- published under a royalty-free, perpetual,
    irrevocable license that permits any party to implement, deploy, modify, and
    distribute compliant implementations without payment of any license fee or
    compliance with any patent encumbrance;

    (2) publicly documented -- maintained as a living specification in a
    publicly accessible repository on the National Resilience Ledger, with all
    proposed modifications subject to the governance process established under
    subsection (d) of this Section before taking effect;

    (3) technically complete -- specifying in sufficient detail to enable
    independent implementation all protocols governing: peer-to-peer device
    discovery and authentication through Physical Unclonable Functions; resource
    availability signaling and Asynchronous Resource Coordination; Commons Credit
    transaction processing and National Resilience Ledger integration;
    Zero-Knowledge Proof verification for membership and certification status; and
    inter-network federation and data exchange; and

    (4) backward compatible -- such that subsequent versions of the FMOS maintain
    compatibility with devices certified under prior versions, ensuring that no
    mandatory hardware upgrade cycle is imposed on Commons Members or Qualified
    Federated Networks.

(b) MANDATORY ADOPTION.-- All integrated circuits manufactured or imported into
the United States that are designed for use in devices serving networked resource
management, energy management, agricultural production management, water
management, communications, or consumer computing functions shall comply with the
Federated Mesh Open Standard on the following schedule:

    (1) not later than three years after the date of enactment of this Act, for
    integrated circuits designed for energy management, agricultural production,
    and water management devices;

    (2) not later than four years after the date of enactment of this Act, for
    integrated circuits designed for consumer electronics and communications
    infrastructure devices; and

    (3) not later than five years after the date of enactment of this Act, for
    all other networked integrated circuits not covered by paragraphs (1) and (2)
    of this subsection.

(c) GOVERNMENT PROCUREMENT.-- All federal agencies shall, within two years of the
establishment of the FMOS, require FMOS compliance as a condition of procurement
for all networked devices, including energy management systems, building
automation, communications infrastructure, and computing devices. The Federal
Acquisition Regulation shall be amended to incorporate FMOS compliance as a
mandatory procurement criterion.

(d) TECHNICAL STANDARDS GOVERNANCE.-- The FMOS shall be governed through a
Technical Standards Body comprising:

    (1) technical representatives of certified Qualified Federated Networks,
    selected through the nested governance architecture of the Federated Network;

    (2) representatives of open-source hardware and software communities,
    including the relevant working groups of the Internet Engineering Task Force,
    the Open Hardware Association, and comparable bodies;

    (3) representatives of the National Institute of Standards and Technology,
    in a non-voting advisory capacity;

    (4) representatives of the semiconductor industry, in a non-voting technical
    advisory capacity, without authority to veto or delay standard modifications
    on the basis of commercial interest; and

    (5) security researchers with demonstrated expertise in hardware security,
    cryptographic protocols, and distributed systems, appointed through a process
    determined by the Technical Standards Body itself.

(e) DECIDIM-DAO BRIDGE AS NATIONAL COMMONS INFRASTRUCTURE PRIORITY.-- The
development of an open-source bridge between Decidim-compatible participatory
democracy platforms and the Federated Network's DAO governance layer is hereby
designated a National Commons Infrastructure Priority. The Technical Standards
Body shall:

    (1) establish the technical specifications for the Decidim-DAO bridge within
    one year of its establishment;

    (2) coordinate with the Decidim Foundation and comparable open governance
    software communities to ensure that the bridge is compatible with existing
    Decidim deployments internationally; and

    (3) ensure that the bridge is available as open-source software under a
    copyleft license consistent with Section 507 of Title V of this Act, enabling
    any Qualified Federated Network to deploy it without cost or proprietary
    dependency.

(f) COVERED PLATFORM MIGRATION INTERFACE SPECIFICATIONS.--

    (1) ESTABLISHMENT.-- The Technical Standards Body established under
    subsection (d) of this Section shall, within one year of the date of
    enactment of this Act, publish technical specifications for the
    migration interface required of Covered Platforms under Section 409 of
    Title IV of this Act. The specifications shall define the data schema,
    transfer protocol, and authentication mechanism through which a Covered
    Platform transmits an account holder's data to a Qualified Federated
    Network at the account holder's direction.

    (2) FMOS COMPATIBILITY.-- The specifications published under paragraph
    (1) of this subsection shall be:

        (A) interoperable with the Federated Mesh Open Standard established
        under subsection (a) of this Section, such that data received
        through a Covered Platform migration interface can be ingested
        directly into a Qualified Federated Network's Commons Membership
        Record and FMOS-compliant data storage without an intermediate
        proprietary conversion step;

        (B) published under the same open and non-proprietary licensing
        terms required of the FMOS under subsection (a)(1) of this Section;
        and

        (C) designed to accommodate the range of data categories a Covered
        Platform may hold, including but not limited to text, image, video,
        and structured social or professional connection data, without
        requiring a Covered Platform to convert its data into a format
        inconsistent with how the data is ordinarily maintained.

    (3) UPDATES.-- The Technical Standards Body shall update the
    specifications published under this subsection not less than once every
    two years, or more frequently as needed to accommodate new categories of
    Covered Platform or new data types, through the governance process
    established under subsection (d) of this Section.

    (4) NO DELAY OF UNDERLYING DUTY.-- The duty of a Covered Platform to
    expose a migration interface under Section 409(b) of Title IV of this
    Act is not contingent on the Technical Standards Body's publication of
    specifications under this subsection beyond the one-year deadline
    established in paragraph (1) of this subsection. A Covered Platform
    whose one-year compliance deadline under Section 409(b) precedes the
    publication of specifications under this subsection shall comply using
    the most recent draft specification published by the Technical Standards
    Body, and shall update its interface within ninety days of the
    publication of final specifications under this subsection.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 702. PHYSICAL UNCLONABLE FUNCTION REQUIREMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) MANDATORY PUF IMPLEMENTATION.-- Every integrated circuit subject to FMOS
compliance pursuant to Section 701(b) of this Act shall implement a Physical
Unclonable Function meeting the requirements of this Section, providing a
hardware-level cryptographic identity that cannot be cloned, transferred, or
simulated without physical replication of the specific circuit at the atomic
level.

(b) PUF TECHNICAL REQUIREMENTS.-- Physical Unclonable Functions implemented
pursuant to this Section shall meet the following technical requirements:

    (1) UNIQUENESS -- the PUF response for any given circuit shall be
    statistically distinguishable from the PUF response of any other circuit
    manufactured to the same design, with a uniqueness metric meeting the
    threshold established by the Technical Standards Body;

    (2) RELIABILITY -- the PUF response for any given circuit shall be
    reproducible across temperature variations, voltage fluctuations, and aging
    effects within the operational parameters specified by the Technical Standards
    Body, with a reliability metric meeting the established threshold;

    (3) UNCLONABILITY -- the PUF response shall be derived from manufacturing
    process variations at the sub-micron level that are not reproducible through
    any currently available manufacturing technique, and shall be updated to
    maintain this property as manufacturing techniques advance; and

    (4) TAMPER EVIDENCE -- any physical attempt to extract or reverse-engineer the
    PUF response from a circuit shall result in a detectable change in the PUF
    response, providing tamper evidence that is verifiable through the Federated
    Mesh authentication protocol.

(c) ZERO-KNOWLEDGE PROOF INTEGRATION.-- PUF-based device authentication within
the Federated Mesh shall be implemented through Zero-Knowledge Proof protocols
that:

    (1) allow a device to prove possession of a valid PUF response to the
    Federated Mesh without revealing the PUF response itself, preventing the
    interception and replay of authentication credentials;

    (2) allow the Federated Mesh to verify a device's certification status,
    network affiliation, and compliance flags without accessing any information
    beyond what is necessary for the specific verification purpose; and

    (3) support the pseudonymous participation provisions of Section 403(c) of
    Title IV of this Act, allowing a Commons Member's device to authenticate
    within the network without linking the device's PUF identity to the member's
    personal identity.

(d) KEY MANAGEMENT.-- The cryptographic key infrastructure associated with PUF
identities shall be managed in accordance with the following requirements:

    (1) NO MASTER KEYS -- no entity -- governmental, corporate, or other --
    shall hold a master key or root certificate that would permit the unilateral
    revocation, spoofing, or override of PUF-based device identities within the
    Federated Mesh;

    (2) DISTRIBUTED KEY RECOVERY -- mechanisms for the recovery of PUF identity
    credentials by a Commons Member who has lost access to their device shall
    operate through a distributed multi-party protocol requiring the cooperation
    of not fewer than three independent Qualified Federated Networks, ensuring
    that no single entity can recover another entity's credentials unilaterally;
    and

    (3) DEVICE LIFECYCLE MANAGEMENT -- upon the decommissioning, loss, or
    destruction of a device, its PUF identity shall be revoked through a
    governance process recorded on the National Resilience Ledger, and a
    replacement identity shall be issued to the device's owner through the
    distributed key recovery process.

(e) ANTI-SPOOFING ENFORCEMENT.-- The Technical Standards Body shall maintain a
continuously updated Threat Intelligence Registry documenting known or suspected
PUF spoofing techniques, and shall update the FMOS authentication protocols to
counter identified spoofing threats within ninety days of their documentation in
the Registry. Criminal penalties for PUF spoofing are established under Section
1104(d) of Title XI of this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 703. ASYNCHRONOUS RESOURCE COORDINATION PROTOCOL.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) PROTOCOL ESTABLISHMENT.-- The Asynchronous Resource Coordination protocol,
as defined in Section 4(1) of this Act, shall be implemented as a component of
the FMOS and shall govern the peer-to-peer discovery and exchange of metabolic
resources within and between Qualified Federated Networks. A critical dimension
of resource coordination within the commons is the discoverability of social
services, community resources, and cooperative enterprise offerings available
to Commons Members at any given location. The ARC protocol's resource
availability signaling architecture shall be designed to be interoperable with
the Human Services Data Specification (HSDS) maintained by the Open Referral
Initiative, which has developed the primary open data standard for machine-
readable social service directory information and whose standard is already
deployed by numerous municipal governments, 211 networks, and social service
aggregators. The Technical Standards Body established under Section 701(d) of
Title VII of this Act shall, within one year of its establishment, publish ARC
protocol specifications for social service and cooperative enterprise resource
signals that are compatible with HSDS, and shall enter into a technical
coordination agreement with the Open Referral Initiative to ensure ongoing
interoperability as both standards evolve. This interoperability ensures that
the resource coordination functions of the Federated Mesh can draw upon and
contribute to the existing ecosystem of community resource information without
requiring the replacement of functioning municipal and regional data
infrastructure.

(b) AUTHORIZATION AND SCOPE.-- The ARC protocol is hereby authorized to
coordinate the following categories of resource flows without requiring
centralized administrative approval for each transaction:

    (1) energy flows -- including the routing of surplus renewable energy from
    cooperative microgrids to deficit areas within and between networks, governed
    by network-level parameters established through collective-choice processes;

    (2) food and agricultural outputs -- including the coordination of surplus
    food production with deficit areas, subject to the Commons Permanence Asset
    protections and provision priority rule of Section 307 of Title III of this
    Act;

    (3) material goods and equipment -- including the sharing of cooperative
    tools, fabrication equipment, and other productive assets across network
    boundaries;

    (4) labor availability signals -- including the publication of available
    skills, time-banking opportunities, and cooperative work needs, enabling
    members to find and offer labor without dependence on a centralized platform;
    and

    (5) Commons Credit transactions -- including the automated settlement of
    inter-network resource exchanges through the National Resilience Ledger.

(c) METABOLIC SIGNAL TYPES.-- The ARC protocol shall support the following
categories of metabolic signal:

    (1) SURPLUS SIGNALS -- broadcast by a device or network reporting resources
    available above its current provision requirements and reserve thresholds;

    (2) DEFICIT SIGNALS -- broadcast by a device or network reporting a shortfall
    in a specific resource category requiring external supply;

    (3) CAPACITY SIGNALS -- broadcast by a device or network reporting available
    production, processing, or storage capacity that could serve neighboring
    networks; and

    (4) EMERGENCY SIGNALS -- broadcast by a device or network reporting a critical
    provision failure requiring immediate inter-network response, triggering the
    priority routing protocols of subsection (e) of this Section.

(d) GOVERNANCE PARAMETERS.-- All ARC transactions are subject to the governance
parameters established by the relevant Qualified Federated Network through its
collective-choice processes, including:

    (1) resource reservation thresholds -- the minimum reserve of each resource
    category that the network maintains before authorizing outbound surplus
    signals, ensuring that the provision floor for current Commons Members is
    protected before surplus is offered to neighboring networks;

    (2) inter-network exchange rate parameters -- the Commons Credit rates at
    which specific resource categories are exchanged between networks, set through
    collective-choice processes and recorded on the National Resilience Ledger;
    and

    (3) authorized trading partners -- the specific networks and network
    categories with which the QFN authorizes automated ARC exchanges, with the
    ability to exclude networks under sanctions or with known governance
    deficiencies.

(e) PROHIBITION ON CENTRALIZED KILL SWITCHES.-- The ARC protocol shall be
designed and implemented such that no single entity -- governmental, corporate,
or other -- possesses the technical capability to disable, suspend, or redirect
resource coordination signals across the Federated Network. Specifically:

    (1) no administrative interface, API endpoint, or governance mechanism shall
    exist that would permit a single actor to issue a network-wide suspension of
    ARC functions;

    (2) the suspension of ARC functions for a specific network or device shall
    require the consensus of not fewer than three independent validator nodes
    through the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism; and

    (3) any suspension of ARC functions triggered through the graduated response
    procedures of Section 103(c) of this Act shall be limited in scope to the
    sanctioned entity and shall not affect the ARC functions of neighboring
    networks.

(f) STIGMERGIC COORDINATION PRINCIPLE.-- The ARC protocol operates on the
principle that distributed systems achieve efficient resource coordination through
local signal-response interactions rather than through centralized planning. The
protocol shall be designed to:

    (1) enable each network node to make locally informed resource decisions based
    on the signals it receives from its neighbors, without requiring global
    knowledge of the network's state;

    (2) allow emergent coordination patterns to develop through the aggregation of
    local decisions, without requiring those patterns to be pre-specified in the
    protocol; and

    (3) remain functional and adaptive as the network grows in scale and
    complexity, without requiring architectural changes to accommodate larger
    network sizes.

