SEC. 704. SYSTEMIC REDUNDANCY AND RESILIENCE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) REDUNDANCY REQUIREMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall implement
technical redundancy measures sufficient to maintain the delivery of the
Guaranteed Provision Standard to its Commons Members for not less than ninety
days in the event of:

    (1) complete loss of connectivity to the broader Federated Mesh;

    (2) failure of the network's primary Commons Financial Node;

    (3) loss of access to the National Resilience Ledger; or

    (4) any combination of the above.

(b) LOCAL RESILIENCE MODE.-- The FMOS shall include a Local Resilience Mode --
a reduced-function operating state that activates automatically when a network's
connection to the broader Federated Mesh is interrupted -- providing:

    (1) continued operation of the network's internal Commons Credit transactions
    through a local ledger cache that synchronizes with the National Resilience
    Ledger upon reconnection;

    (2) continued operation of the network's food, energy, and water coordination
    functions through locally cached ARC protocols that do not require external
    network connectivity;

    (3) continued access to Commons Membership Records through locally cached
    encrypted records held on members' personal devices; and

    (4) continued operation of basic governance functions through the network's
    internal Decidim-DAO governance platform, with decisions taken during the
    Local Resilience Mode period synchronized to the National Resilience Ledger
    upon reconnection.

(c) ENTROPY LOCK.-- The FMOS shall implement an Entropy Lock mechanism that:

    (1) detects attempts to flood the Federated Mesh with fraudulent resource
    signals, invalid transaction requests, or spoofed PUF identities, and
    automatically isolates the source of the fraudulent signals without disrupting
    the broader network;

    (2) activates automatically upon detection of Byzantine fault conditions --
    defined as the simultaneous failure or compromise of more than one-third of a
    network's validator nodes -- isolating the affected network from the broader
    Federated Mesh pending Human-in-the-Loop review; and

    (3) provides the isolated network with access to Local Resilience Mode
    functions during the period of isolation, ensuring that Commons Members'
    provision entitlements are maintained pending resolution of the detected
    fault condition.

(d) BYZANTINE FAULT TOLERANCE.-- The consensus mechanism of the National
Resilience Ledger shall implement Byzantine Fault Tolerant protocols that:

    (1) maintain ledger integrity and transaction validity in the presence of up
    to one-third of validator nodes operating incorrectly, whether due to
    technical failure or deliberate compromise;

    (2) detect and isolate validator nodes exhibiting Byzantine behavior -- defined
    as behavior inconsistent with correct protocol execution that cannot be
    explained by hardware failure alone -- through the Peer-to-Peer Audit
    mechanism;

    (3) recover ledger integrity following a Byzantine fault event through a
    documented recovery protocol that requires Human-in-the-Loop authorization
    for any transaction reversal or ledger state modification, ensuring that
    fault recovery does not become a mechanism for unauthorized ledger
    manipulation; and

    (4) scale the validator node set as the Federated Network grows, ensuring
    that Byzantine fault tolerance is maintained at network sizes significantly
    larger than those anticipated at enactment.

(e) ANALOG REDUNDANCY.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall maintain analog
redundancy systems that can sustain basic provision delivery for not less than
ninety days without any digital infrastructure, comprising:

    (1) physical paper ledger records of all current Commons Members, their
    provision entitlements, and their Stewardship Credit balances, updated not
    less than monthly and stored in distributed physical locations within the
    network's geographic boundaries;

    (2) paper-based Commons Membership credentials that can be used to verify
    membership status and provision entitlements without digital verification;

    (3) physical seed banks, preserved food stocks, and fuel reserves sufficient
    to maintain the nutrition and energy components of the Guaranteed Provision
    Standard for the ninety-day period; and

    (4) documented non-digital protocols for the coordination of resource
    distribution, conflict resolution, and governance decision-making that can be
    executed by network members without access to any digital infrastructure.

