SEC. 705. OPEN-SOURCE MANDATE AND COMMONS ANALYTICS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) OPEN-SOURCE MANDATE.-- All software, firmware, and hardware designs used to
implement the FMOS, the National Resilience Ledger, the Peer-to-Peer Audit
mechanism, the Decidim-DAO bridge, and all other technical infrastructure
specified in this Title shall be:

    (1) released under a copyleft open-source license consistent with the
    requirements of Section 507 of Title V of this Act;

    (2) publicly accessible through a repository maintained on the National
    Resilience Ledger;

    (3) subject to ongoing security audit by the open-source security community,
    with identified vulnerabilities disclosed through a responsible disclosure
    process established by the Technical Standards Body; and

    (4) free from any patent encumbrance that would restrict their implementation,
    deployment, or modification, with any patents held by contributors to the
    commons technical infrastructure automatically contributed to the IP Commons
    pursuant to Section 505 of Title V of this Act.

(b) GOVERNMENT PROCUREMENT PREFERENCE.-- In all federal procurement decisions
involving networked computing infrastructure, communications systems, and data
management systems, federal agencies shall give preference to implementations
that are FMOS-compliant and open-source over proprietary alternatives, and shall
document any procurement of non-FMOS-compliant or proprietary systems with a
specific finding that no FMOS-compliant or open-source alternative is available
that meets the agency's operational requirements.

(c) COMMONS ANALYTICS PLATFORM.-- The Technical Standards Body shall oversee the
development of an open-source Commons Analytics Platform that:

    (1) provides Qualified Federated Networks with tools for analyzing their
    resource flows, Commons Credit circulation, and Ostrom Standards compliance
    data in forms that support informed collective decision-making;

    (2) enables inter-network comparison of resource efficiency, provision
    quality, and governance health metrics, facilitating peer learning and the
    identification of best practices across the Federated Network;

    (3) implements privacy-preserving analytics that generate network-level
    insights without exposing individual Commons Members' data, consistent with
    the data governance requirements of Title IV of this Act; and

    (4) is designed to be interoperable with the Decidim participatory democracy
    platform and comparable open governance tools, enabling Commons Members to
    access analytics data through the same governance interfaces they use for
    collective decision-making; and

    (5) draws upon the open-source commons governance tooling developed by the
    Commons Stack and analogous Web3 commons infrastructure projects, including
    token engineering frameworks for commons parameter setting and the Augmented
    Bonding Curve mechanism for commons fund management, adapted for commons-
    governed use cases that do not require speculative token economies; the
    Technical Standards Body shall engage with the Commons Stack and comparable
    organizations through the open-source development process for the Decidim-DAO
    bridge designated as a National Commons Infrastructure Priority under Section
    701(e) of this Title.

(d) INDIRECT CAPTURE PREVENTION.-- The commons analytics platform developed
pursuant to subsection (c) of this Section serves as the primary mechanism
through which the Federated Network develops its own analytical and planning
capabilities, reducing dependence on proprietary analytics platforms and
surveillance-based data infrastructure that would reproduce, within the commons
economy, the data extraction dynamics the commons is designed to replace.

