SEC. 706. NON-DIGITAL PARTICIPATION PATHWAYS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) UNIVERSAL PARTICIPATION OBLIGATION.-- The Federated Network shall be
accessible to all Commons Members regardless of their technical literacy,
disability status, age, or access to digital devices. No governance function,
provision entitlement, attribution registration pathway, or commons benefit
established by this Act shall be available exclusively through digital means.
Every function shall have a non-digital equivalent that provides substantively
equivalent access to all commons benefits.

(b) REQUIRED NON-DIGITAL PATHWAYS.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall
maintain non-digital pathways for:

    (1) COMMONS MEMBERSHIP REGISTRATION -- including the ability to register as a
    Commons Member, receive a physical Commons Membership credential, and access
    provision entitlements through in-person processes at a designated network
    service location;

    (2) GOVERNANCE PARTICIPATION -- including the ability to participate in
    collective-choice processes through in-person assembly, paper balloting, and
    oral participation in governance proceedings, with all collective decisions
    reflecting the input of members who participated through non-digital means
    equally with those who participated digitally;

    (3) IP COMMONS REGISTRATION -- through the Witnessed Physical Registration
    pathway established under Section 504(b)(3) of Title V of this Act;

    (4) COMMONS CREDIT TRANSACTIONS -- including the ability to conduct Commons
    Credit transactions through a Commons Financial Node service location, using
    physical credential verification in lieu of digital authentication; and

    (5) DISPUTE RESOLUTION -- including the ability to initiate and participate in
    conflict resolution and Accountability Coordination DAO proceedings through in-person processes,
    without requirement of digital participation at any stage.

(c) ACCESSIBILITY STANDARDS.-- All non-digital participation pathways shall meet
the accessibility standards of the Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990, shall
be available in all languages spoken by more than one percent of the network's
Commons Member population, and shall be located within a reasonable distance of
all areas within the network's geographic boundaries.


================================================================================
TITLE VIII -- SELF-SOVEREIGN GOVERNANCE ARCHITECTURE
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the integrated three-layer governance
architecture through which the Federated Network governs itself -- automated
protocol execution at the base layer, adversarial peer audit at the verification
layer, and irreducible human deliberation at the authority layer. No single layer
is sufficient alone. The automated layer provides speed and consistency; the
audit layer provides verification and accountability; the human layer provides
judgment, context, and the protection of individual rights that no automated
system can reliably supply. The architecture is designed so that automation
serves governance rather than replacing it, and so that the human layer is never
weakened, bypassed, or made contingent on resource availability. The permanence
and accessibility of human oversight is the architectural commitment from which
no efficiency argument can derogate.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 801. THE AUTOMATED PROTOCOL LAYER.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) SCOPE AND FUNCTION.-- The Automated Protocol Layer comprises the set of
rule-bound, deterministic functions executed by the FMOS and the National
Resilience Ledger without requiring individual human authorization for each
transaction. These functions include:

    (1) the automated issuance of Stewardship Credits upon verified land transfers
    pursuant to Section 306(a) of Title III of this Act;

    (2) the execution of Commons Credit transactions within and between Qualified
    Federated Networks pursuant to Title VI of this Act;

    (3) the routing of resource availability signals through the Asynchronous
    Resource Coordination protocol pursuant to Section 703 of Title VII of this
    Act;

    (4) the generation of Compliance Flags through the automated cross-validation
    functions of the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism pursuant to Section 103(c)(1)
    of Title I of this Act; and

    (5) the execution of Local Resilience Mode functions during periods of mesh
    connectivity disruption pursuant to Section 704(b) of Title VII of this Act.

(b) GOVERNANCE PARAMETERIZATION.-- The Automated Protocol Layer executes within
the governance parameters established by each Qualified Federated Network through
its collective-choice processes. The automation executes governance decisions
made by humans -- it does not make governance decisions itself. The distinction
between execution of a governance decision and making of a governance decision
shall be maintained rigorously in the design of all automated protocol functions:

    (1) any function that determines the rights, entitlements, or obligations of
    an individual Commons Member is a governance decision and shall not be
    executed without human authorization through the Human-in-the-Loop Layer
    pursuant to Section 803 of this Title;

    (2) any function that adjusts the governance parameters within which automated
    execution occurs is a governance decision and shall be executed only upon
    authorization through the collective-choice processes of the relevant
    Qualified Federated Network; and

    (3) any function whose outcome was not specifically anticipated by the
    governance parameters under which it operates is not a purely automated
    execution and shall be escalated to the Human-in-the-Loop Layer for
    determination before the outcome takes effect.

(c) TRANSPARENCY REQUIREMENT.-- The complete logic of all Automated Protocol
Layer functions shall be:

    (1) documented in plain language accessible to non-technical Commons Members;

    (2) available in open-source code form on the National Resilience Ledger; and

    (3) subject to ongoing review by the Technical Standards Body pursuant to
    Section 701(d) of Title VII of this Act, with any proposed modifications
    subject to the governance process before taking effect.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 802. THE ADVERSARIAL PEER AUDIT LAYER.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ADVERSARIAL DESIGN PRINCIPLE.-- The Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism established
under Section 103(c) of Title I of this Act shall be designed on an adversarial
basis -- that is, auditing peers shall be selected and incentivized to find
discrepancies rather than to confirm compliance. Compliance confirmation is the
expected outcome of a genuine commons network reporting accurately; the audit
mechanism's value lies in its capacity to detect the unexpected rather than to
ratify the expected. Specifically:

    (1) auditing peers shall be algorithmically selected to maximize geographic,
    demographic, and functional diversity, minimizing the probability of pre-
    existing relationships or shared interests between auditor and auditee that
    could compromise audit independence;

    (2) auditing peers shall receive Stewardship Credits for the identification of
    genuine discrepancies that are subsequently confirmed through Human-in-the-
    Loop review, creating a positive incentive for rigorous audit rather than
    perfunctory confirmation; and

    (3) auditing peers that systematically fail to identify discrepancies that
    are subsequently detected through algorithmic cross-validation shall be
    subject to removal from the audit rotation and to Level 1 graduated response
    under Section 103(c)(2)(A) of this Act, creating a negative incentive for
    collusion with or protection of non-compliant networks.

(b) ROTATION REQUIREMENTS.-- Auditing peer assignments shall rotate on a schedule
established by the Technical Standards Body, ensuring that:

    (1) no auditing pair -- a specific auditor assigned to a specific auditee --
    persists for more than six consecutive months;

    (2) no network audits the same peer network more than twice in any twenty-
    four-month period; and

    (3) networks that have recent commercial, resource-sharing, or governance
    relationships with each other are not assigned as auditing pairs during the
    period of that relationship.

(c) DATA VALIDATION METHODOLOGY.-- The Peer-to-Peer Audit data validation
methodology shall:

    (1) prioritize physical verification of claims through FMOS sensor data over
    documentary verification, recognizing that physical sensor outputs are more
    difficult to falsify than records;

    (2) cross-reference reported resource flows against the flows of neighboring
    networks whose outputs or inputs are logically connected, using network-level
    material balance accounting to identify systematic discrepancies that may not
    be visible at the individual network level;

    (3) apply statistical anomaly detection to identify reporting patterns that
    are inconsistent with the network's physical characteristics, historical
    reporting, or peer network benchmarks; and

    (4) distinguish between discrepancies that are consistent with honest error,
    sensor malfunction, or extraordinary circumstances, and discrepancies that are
    consistent with deliberate misreporting, with the latter triggering escalated
    graduated response.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 803. THE HUMAN-IN-THE-LOOP LAYER.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) SCOPE AND MANDATORY CHARACTER.-- The Human-in-the-Loop Layer is the final
and non-delegable authority over any determination made within the Federated
Network that materially affects the rights, provisions, standing, or obligations
of an individual Commons Member. The following determinations shall never be made
by automated process alone and shall always be subject to human review and
authorization through the mechanisms of this Section:

    (1) any determination that a Commons Member's Guaranteed Provision Standard
    entitlements are to be modified, suspended, or terminated;

    (2) any determination that a Commons Member's governance rights are to be
    restricted or suspended;

    (3) any determination imposing a Level 3 or Level 4 sanction on a Qualified
    Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network, given the consequences
    for the Commons Members within that entity;

    (4) any determination resolving a dispute between a Commons Member and a
    cooperative institution;

    (5) any attribution determination affecting a Commons Member's IP Commons
    registration; and

    (6) any determination involving the application of the graduated sanctions
    of Standard 5 of Section 102(f) of this Act to an individual Commons Member.

(b) CIRCUIT BREAKER.-- The Circuit Breaker mechanism established under Section
103(d)(2) of Title I of this Act shall be implemented as a mandatory, technically
enforced pause in any automated process that is escalated for Human-in-the-Loop
review. Specifically:

    (1) upon any Commons Member's request for Human-in-the-Loop review of any
    automated determination affecting their individual rights, the automated
    process shall be immediately and unconditionally suspended for seventy-two
    hours;

    (2) during the seventy-two-hour Circuit Breaker period, no automated process
    shall escalate, compound, or add additional consequences to the determination
    under review;

    (3) the Circuit Breaker shall be technically implemented such that it cannot
    be overridden by any party -- including network administrators, the Office of
    Federated Stewardship, or any other authority -- without a specific finding by
    a Human Review Panel that the suspension poses an immediate threat to the
    physical safety of Commons Members; and

    (4) the activation of a Circuit Breaker shall be recorded on the National
    Resilience Ledger, providing an auditable record of all instances in which
    human review was invoked.

(c) HUMAN REVIEW PANEL.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall maintain a
standing Human Review Panel comprising:

    (1) not fewer than three Commons Members who have completed the human review
    training program established under subsection (d)(2) of this Section, selected
    through a rotation system that ensures no panel member reviews determinations
    in which they have a personal interest;

    (2) at least one member with expertise in the subject matter of the
    determination under review -- for example, a member with healthcare expertise
    for determinations involving healthcare provision, or a member with technical
    expertise for determinations involving FMOS compliance; and

    (3) no member who participated in any automated process that generated the
    determination under review, ensuring genuine independence between the
    automated and human review functions.

(d) HUMAN REVIEW PANEL PROCEDURES.--

    (1) TIMELINE.-- Human Review Panel proceedings shall be completed within the
    following timeframes:

        (A) for determinations involving imminent threats to a Commons Member's
        housing, nutrition, healthcare, or physical safety: twenty-four hours;

        (B) for determinations involving other Guaranteed Provision Standard
        components: seventy-two hours;

        (C) for determinations involving governance rights: fourteen days; and

        (D) for all other determinations: thirty days.

    (2) TRAINING.-- All Human Review Panel members shall complete a training
    program covering: the Ostrom Standards of Stewardship and their application
    to individual determinations; the restorative justice principles underlying
    the graduated sanctions of Standard 5; the privacy protections of Title IV
    of this Act and their application in review proceedings; bias identification
    and mitigation in human review processes; and the technical operation of the
    automated systems whose determinations are subject to review. The training
    program shall be developed by the Federated Network's regional federation
    governance layer in consultation with the IP Commons Governance Council and
    organizations with demonstrated expertise in restorative justice facilitation
    and human oversight of automated systems. Where an Automation Governance
    Council or comparable body is later established by Federal law, the regional
    federation governance layer shall incorporate that body's expertise into
    subsequent revisions of the training program. The IP Commons Governance
    Council shall maintain a model training curriculum on the National Resilience 
    Ledger, available to all networks, which satisfies the requirements of this 
    subsection; networks may adopt the model curriculum or develop equivalent 
    programming independently, provided the resulting program covers all required 
    subject areas.

    (3) AFFECTED PARTY PARTICIPATION.-- The Commons Member whose rights are
    affected by the determination under review shall have the right to:

        (A) present evidence, testimony, and argument to the Human Review Panel
        through any accessible means, including in-person presentation, written
        submission, and digital submission;

        (B) be represented by another Commons Member, a cooperative advocate, or
        legal counsel of their choosing;

        (C) access all information held by the network that is relevant to the
        determination, subject to the privacy protections of Title IV of this Act
        with respect to other individuals; and

        (D) receive a written explanation of the Panel's determination and its
        reasoning, recorded on the National Resilience Ledger.

    (4) ANTI-AUTOMATION BIAS TRAINING.-- Human Review Panel training shall
    include specific instruction in the risk of automation bias -- the tendency
    of human reviewers to defer to automated determinations rather than exercising
    independent judgment. Panel members shall be trained to treat automated
    determinations as one input among several rather than as presumptively correct,
    and the training program shall include exercises designed to identify instances
    in which automation bias has produced unjust outcomes.

(e) PERMANENT AVAILABILITY.-- The Human-in-the-Loop Layer shall be permanently
available to all Commons Members without exception. Specifically:

    (1) no Qualified Federated Network shall condition access to Human-in-the-
    Loop review on any prior exhaustion of automated processes, on the payment of
    any fee, or on the demonstration of any threshold showing of merit;

    (2) no resource constraint, technical difficulty, or governance burden shall
    justify the suspension or limitation of Human-in-the-Loop availability; and

    (3) any Qualified Federated Network that fails to maintain a functioning Human
    Review Panel meeting the requirements of subsection (c) of this Section shall
    be subject to Level 2 graduated response under Section 103(c)(2)(B) of this
    Act, with the understanding that the availability of human review is as
    fundamental to network certification as the delivery of the Guaranteed
    Provision Standard.

(f) COMMONS GOVERNANCE JURISPRUDENCE.-- The written determinations of Human
Review Panels, recorded on the National Resilience Ledger pursuant to subsection
(d)(3) of this Section, shall collectively constitute a body of commons
governance jurisprudence -- a publicly accessible record of how the commons
governance principles have been applied to specific factual circumstances. The
IP Commons Governance Council shall:

    (1) maintain a searchable index of Human Review Panel determinations on the
    National Resilience Ledger, organized by subject matter and relevant Ostrom
    Standard;

    (2) publish an annual synthesis of significant Human Review Panel
    determinations and their implications for network governance; and

    (3) make this jurisprudence available as a training resource for new Human
    Review Panel members and as a governance reference for Qualified Federated
    Networks addressing novel circumstances.

(g) APPEALS FROM HUMAN REVIEW PANEL DETERMINATIONS.-- A Commons Member
dissatisfied with a Human Review Panel determination may appeal to the Federated
Accountability Board established under Section 1103 of Title XI of this Act,
within thirty days of receiving the written determination. The Federated
Accountability Board shall apply a de novo standard of review.

(h) EMPIRICAL BASIS FOR HUMAN OVERSIGHT.-- Congress finds that the permanent
availability of Human-in-the-Loop review established by this Section is supported
by empirical evidence that automated systems are not consistently effective at
assessing complex knowledge quality, governance compliance, or contextual
judgment. In particular, the DARPA Systematizing Confidence in Open Research and
Evidence program demonstrated that automated methods were not consistently
effective at predicting the replicability of research claims, underscoring the
necessity of human judgment as a final governance layer that no automated system
can replace.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 804. ACCOUNTABILITY COORDINATION DAO.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall constitute an
Accountability Coordination DAO pursuant to the definition of Section 4(13) of
this Act within one year of its certification. The Accountability Coordination
DAO is the technical coordination and registry infrastructure through which the
commons coordinates, records, and tracks the resolution of non-criminal harm,
interpersonal conflict, and community safety responses without recourse to the
carceral mechanisms of the state. Substantive accountability determinations are
made through human deliberation by the peer-elected members of the body; the
Accountability Coordination DAO records and coordinates that process but does not
itself adjudicate the rights or standing of any Commons Member.

(b) JURISDICTION.-- The Accountability Coordination DAO shall have jurisdiction over:

    (1) disputes between Commons Members arising from their participation in
    cooperative governance, resource allocation, or provision delivery;

    (2) interpersonal harms occurring within the network's geographic boundaries
    that do not constitute serious violent offenses requiring emergency law
    enforcement response;

    (3) violations of the network's governance rules subject to graduated
    sanctions under Standard 5 of Section 102(f) of this Act;

    (4) reparative justice proceedings for historical harms recognized pursuant
    to Section 606 of Title VI of this Act within the network's community; and

    (5) inter-cooperative disputes within the Qualified Federated Network that
    are not resolvable through the cooperative's internal conflict resolution
    mechanisms.

(c) PROCESS PRINCIPLES.-- Accountability Coordination DAO proceedings shall be
governed by the following process principles:

    (1) VOLUNTARY PARTICIPATION -- all parties to a proceeding participate
    voluntarily, and no Commons Member may be compelled to participate in an
    Accountability Coordination DAO proceeding as a condition of accessing their
    Guaranteed Provision Standard entitlements, except that appearance before the
    Accountability Coordination DAO in response to a documented harm allegation is
    required as a condition of maintaining governance rights;

    (2) RESTORATIVE ORIENTATION -- proceedings are oriented toward the restoration
    of harm, the repair of relationships, and the reintegration of all parties
    into the commons community, not toward the assignment of blame or the
    imposition of punishment;

    (3) HUMAN DELIBERATION -- all determinations are reached through human
    deliberation by peer-elected members of the Accountability Coordination DAO,
    without recourse to automated behavioral prediction, algorithmic risk
    assessment, or any other automated decision-making tool; no automated output
    of the Accountability Coordination DAO's coordination infrastructure shall
    constitute a final determination affecting the rights or standing of any
    Commons Member, and no failure by a Commons Member to fulfill an accountability
    milestone shall trigger automatic sanctions without human review and
    authorization through the Human-in-the-Loop Layer established under Section
    803 of this Act;

    (4) PRIVACY PROTECTION -- proceedings are conducted in private, with only the
    parties, their chosen advocates, and members of the Accountability Coordination
    DAO present, and with the outcome recorded on the National Resilience Ledger in
    an anonymized form that protects the privacy of all parties; and

    (5) APPEAL PATHWAY -- any party to an Accountability Coordination DAO
    proceeding may appeal a determination to the Human Review Panel established
    under Section 803(c) of this Title if they believe the proceeding was conducted
    in violation of the process principles of this subsection.

(d) RELATIONSHIP TO EXTERNAL LEGAL SYSTEM.-- The Accountability Coordination
DAO operates alongside, not in replacement of, the external legal system.
Specifically:

    (1) the Accountability Coordination DAO has no authority to prevent any
    Commons Member from seeking redress through the external legal system for any
    harm, and no Accountability Coordination DAO proceeding shall constitute a
    waiver of any Commons Member's legal rights;

    (2) where a matter pending before the Accountability Coordination DAO involves
    conduct that constitutes a serious criminal offense under federal or state law,
    the Accountability Coordination DAO shall notify the affected party of their
    right to report the matter to law enforcement, without itself making any such
    report except where required by mandatory reporting obligations under
    applicable law; and

    (3) determinations of the Accountability Coordination DAO shall not be binding
    on any court of competent jurisdiction and shall not constitute admissions of
    liability in any external legal proceeding, though they may be introduced as
    evidence of the parties' good-faith efforts at resolution.

(e) ENTROPY LOCK AND PROTOCOL DECOUPLING.-- The Accountability Coordination DAO
is the designated governance body for authorizing Entropy Lock actions under
Section 704(c) of Title VII of this Act and Protocol Decoupling actions under
Section 103(c)(2)(D) of Title I of this Act. No Entropy Lock or Protocol
Decoupling action shall be authorized without a determination by the
Accountability Coordination DAO, subject to Human Review Panel review, that the
action is necessary to protect the integrity of the Federated Network or the
physical safety of Commons Members.

(f) REPARATIVE DEBT PROCEEDINGS.-- The Accountability Coordination DAO shall
serve as the primary local institution through which reparative justice
proceedings pursuant to Section 606 of Title VI of this Act are conducted,
ensuring that reparative recognition is shaped by the affected communities' own
governance processes rather than imposed through external administrative
determination.

(g) SCOPE LIMITATION.-- For the avoidance of doubt, the Accountability
Coordination DAO established by this Section is a local commons governance
institution, not a court of law. It has no authority to impose criminal
penalties, to order incarceration or detention, to issue injunctions enforceable
by state power, or to exercise any other power that is properly the province of
the judicial branch of government. Its authority is the authority of community
governance, backed by the graduated sanctions of Standard 5 of Section 102(f) of
this Act and the Entropy Lock mechanism of Section 704(c) of Title VII of this
Act, not the authority of the state backed by coercive force.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 805. SYSTEMIC CONTINUITY AND ANTI-OSSIFICATION.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) SYSTEMIC CONTINUITY.-- The governance architecture established by this Title
shall be maintained in functional operation at all times, including during periods
of network stress, resource shortage, political challenge, and technical failure.
Specifically:

    (1) the Human-in-the-Loop Layer shall operate continuously regardless of the
    operational status of the Automated Protocol Layer or the Adversarial Peer
    Audit Layer, with manual processes substituting for automated functions
    wherever necessary to maintain its availability;

    (2) the Accountability Coordination DAO shall operate continuously regardless
    of the availability of digital infrastructure, with in-person proceedings
    substituting for digital proceedings wherever necessary; and

    (3) the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism shall operate continuously regardless of
    individual network failures, with neighboring networks absorbing audit
    functions for networks operating in Local Resilience Mode.

(b) ANTI-OSSIFICATION PROVISIONS.-- The governance architecture established by
this Title shall remain capable of evolution and adaptation in response to
demonstrated needs, emerging challenges, and new knowledge about commons
governance. The following anti-ossification mechanisms are established:

    (1) MANDATORY REVIEW.-- The IP Commons Governance Council shall conduct a
    comprehensive review of the three-layer governance architecture not less than
    once every four years, assessing whether the architecture is functioning as
    intended and identifying modifications that would strengthen its effectiveness,
    its accessibility, or its resilience;

    (2) COMMONS GOVERNANCE JURISPRUDENCE.-- The body of Human Review Panel
    determinations established under Section 803(f) of this Title shall be
    actively used as a learning resource for ongoing governance improvement, with
    the IP Commons Governance Council publishing annual syntheses identifying
    patterns, problems, and best practices;

     (3) MEMBER INNOVATION PATHWAY.-- Any Qualified Federated Network may propose
    modifications to the governance architecture directly to the IP Commons
    Governance Council, which shall evaluate all such proposals and report on
    them in its annual adequacy reviews; and

    (4) PROHIBITION ON GOVERNANCE CAPTURE.-- No governance modification shall be
    adopted that reduces the scope or availability of the Human-in-the-Loop Layer,
    weakens the adversarial character of the Peer-to-Peer Audit, or concentrates
    governance authority in any entity -- governmental, corporate, or other --
    in a manner inconsistent with the distributed governance principles of the
    Ostrom Standards of Stewardship.

(c) SUCCESSION PLANNING.-- Every Qualified Federated Network shall maintain
documented succession plans for all governance roles, ensuring that:

    (1) the departure, incapacitation, or removal of any individual governance
    participant does not disrupt the continuous operation of any governance
    function;

    (2) the training program for Human Review Panel members produces a sufficient
    pool of qualified candidates to replace departing members without interruption;
    and

    (3) governance authority does not become concentrated in any individual through
    the accumulation of institutional knowledge, with active measures taken to
    distribute governance knowledge across the network's membership.


================================================================================
TITLE IX -- MILITARY-CIVILIAN STRATEGIC SYNC
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the Phase 1 mechanisms by which
technologies, data, and land developed or held by the Department of Defense and
related federal agencies are made available to the Federated Network for civilian
commons purposes. This Title does not compromise national security. It recognizes
that a nation whose communities possess distributed, locally governed capacity to
generate energy, produce food, manufacture essential goods, and coordinate
resources through resilient peer-to-peer networks is materially more secure
against both foreign adversarial action and domestic systemic failure than a
nation dependent on centralized corporate infrastructure. The transfer of
non-kinetic, life-support technologies from military to civilian commons custody
is not a weakening of national defense. It is the construction of the civilian
resilience infrastructure that constitutes the most durable foundation of
national security in an era of systemic fragility. Technologies developed
primarily for kinetic military operations remain outside the scope of this Title.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 901. FINDINGS -- DUAL-USE TECHNOLOGY AND CIVILIAN RESILIENCE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) Congress finds that:

    (1) the Department of Defense has, over decades of research and development
    investment funded by American taxpayers, accumulated a substantial portfolio
    of technologies with significant civilian application, including Small Modular
    Reactor designs, advanced water purification and atmospheric water generation
    systems, decentralized logistics and supply chain management software,
    environmental monitoring and meteorological modeling systems, advanced medical
    treatment protocols and biosensor technologies, and materials science
    innovations with agricultural and construction applications;

    (2) the classification and restricted licensing of these technologies for
    national security purposes has, as a secondary consequence, prevented their
    deployment in civilian communities that could benefit from them, creating a
    gap between the productive potential of publicly funded research and its
    actual contribution to public welfare;

    (3) the domestic resilience infrastructure established by this Act -- including
    the distributed energy microgrids, cooperative food systems, and federated
    resource coordination architecture of Titles II through VII -- requires access
    to advanced technologies that the Department of Defense has developed and
    holds, and that are available nowhere else at equivalent maturity and
    reliability;

    (4) the deployment of these technologies in civilian communities through the
    Federated Network would materially enhance national security by reducing the
    dependence of those communities on centralized corporate infrastructure
    vulnerable to disruption, creating a distributed civilian resilience capacity
    that complements and extends military defensive capability;

    (5) the social and behavioral science research tools developed through the
    DARPA Systematizing Confidence in Open Research and Evidence program --
    including research credibility assessment methodologies, replicability
    prediction algorithms, and the associated open datasets -- constitute federally
    funded intellectual outputs with significant civilian application in the
    governance of the Intellectual Property Commons and the broader commons
    knowledge infrastructure, and should be transferred to civilian commons
    custody consistent with the mandatory commons contribution provisions of
    Title V of this Act;

    (6) surplus military land -- including former base sites, underutilized federal
    installations, and land adjacent to military facilities -- represents a public
    asset whose productive potential for community resilience, food security,
    renewable energy generation, and affordable housing remains unrealized under
    current disposition policies; and

    (7) the phased integration of military technology, data, and land into the
    civilian commons, beginning with the non-sensitive dual-use transfers of this
    Title and proceeding as the commons infrastructure matures, serves the
    national interest by creating a self-sustaining civilian resilience capacity
    that reduces the military's burden as a provider of last resort in domestic
    emergencies.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 902. THE CIVILIAN-USE BOARD.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- Within ninety days of the date of enactment of this Act,
the Secretary of Defense shall establish a Civilian-Use Board to conduct the
dual-use technology audit required by Section 903 of this Title and to provide
ongoing oversight of the military-civilian technology transfer process.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The Civilian-Use Board shall comprise:

    (1) five representatives of the Department of Defense, including not fewer
    than two with technical expertise in the specific technology domains subject
    to audit, appointed by the Secretary of Defense;

    (2) five civilian scientists and engineers with expertise in the technology
    domains subject to audit, appointed jointly by the Secretary of Energy, the
    Secretary of Agriculture, and the Secretary of Health and Human Services;

    (3) five representatives of certified Qualified Federated Networks, selected
    through the governance processes of the Federated Network to represent the
    communities that will receive transferred technologies, appointed upon the
    certification of sufficient QFNs to provide representation or, prior to that
    threshold, appointed by the Office of Federated Stewardship from among the
    most advanced proto-QFN organizations identified through the Transition
    Economics provisions of Title X of this Act;

    (4) two representatives of open-source scientific communities -- including the
    Center for Open Science, the P2P Foundation, or comparable institutions with
    expertise in open research governance -- appointed by the Director of the
    Office of Science and Technology Policy; and

    (5) a non-voting chairperson appointed jointly by the Secretary of Defense and
    the Director of the Office of Federated Stewardship, who shall be a person
    with demonstrated expertise in both national security and commons governance
    and shall have no current financial interest in any defense contractor.

(c) INDEPENDENCE REQUIREMENTS.-- No member of the Civilian-Use Board shall:

    (1) hold a current financial interest in any defense contractor, technology
    company, or other entity with a financial stake in the outcome of any transfer
    determination made by the Board;

    (2) have been employed by a defense contractor within the two years preceding
    their appointment; or

    (3) accept employment with a defense contractor within two years following the
    conclusion of their service on the Board.

(d) DECISION-MAKING.-- The Civilian-Use Board shall make transfer determinations
by a simple majority vote, with the five civilian scientist and engineer members
and the five QFN representatives constituting a majority capable of overriding
the DoD representatives where the transfer of a technology clearly meets the
criteria of Section 903(b) of this Title. Transfer determinations shall be
recorded on the National Resilience Ledger and made publicly available, with the
reasoning for each determination documented.

(e) TERM AND RENEWAL.-- The Civilian-Use Board shall operate on a continuous
basis, with members serving staggered three-year terms. The Board shall conduct
a comprehensive audit pursuant to Section 903 of this Title within one hundred
eighty days of its establishment, and shall conduct subsequent annual reviews of
the DoD technology portfolio to identify newly eligible transfers.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 903. DUAL-USE TECHNOLOGY AUDIT AND TRANSFER.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) MANDATORY AUDIT.-- Within one hundred eighty days of the Civilian-Use
Board's establishment pursuant to Section 902 of this Title, the Secretary of
Defense shall provide the Board with full access to the Department's patent
portfolio, technology licensing records, and research and development program
outputs for the purpose of conducting a comprehensive audit to identify
technologies eligible for transfer to the Intellectual Property Commons pursuant
to this Section.

(b) ELIGIBILITY CRITERIA.-- A technology shall be eligible for transfer to the
Intellectual Property Commons under this Section if:

    (1) it has achieved a Technology Readiness Level of 7 or higher -- meaning it
    has been demonstrated in an operational environment -- indicating that it is
    sufficiently mature for civilian deployment without requiring substantial
    additional development;

    (2) its primary applications are in one or more of the following life-support
    domains:

        (A) energy generation, storage, or distribution -- including Small Modular
        Reactor designs, advanced battery technologies, hydrogen fuel cell
        systems, and distributed grid management software;

        (B) water purification, desalination, or atmospheric water generation;

        (C) food production, agricultural yield improvement, or food
        preservation;

        (D) medical treatment, diagnostic technology, biosensor systems, or
        public health monitoring;

        (E) environmental monitoring, meteorological modeling, or ecological
        restoration;

        (F) logistics, supply chain management, or resource coordination --
        including non-kinetic elements of the Department's logistics artificial
        intelligence systems;

        (G) construction materials, building systems, or infrastructure
        resilience; and

        (H) social and behavioral science research credibility assessment,
        including the tools and datasets developed through the DARPA
        Systematizing Confidence in Open Research and Evidence program;

    (3) its transfer to civilian commons use would not:

        (A) directly enable the production of weapons systems, kinetic offensive
        capabilities, or technologies whose primary application is the infliction
        of physical harm;

        (B) compromise classified operational security information;

        (C) provide a foreign adversary with a material military advantage; or

        (D) undermine the operational readiness of any active military program in
        which the technology is currently deployed; and

    (4) its civilian deployment would generate material benefit to the communities
    of the Federated Network that substantially outweighs any theoretical security
    cost of its transfer.

(c) MANDATORY RELEASE TRIGGER.-- Any technology identified by the Civilian-Use
Board as meeting the eligibility criteria of subsection (b) of this Section shall
be transferred to the Intellectual Property Commons within thirty days of the
Board's determination, subject to the following:

    (1) the transfer shall include all documentation necessary for civilian
    deployment -- engineering specifications, operational manuals, safety
    protocols, and training materials -- in sufficient detail for a competent
    engineer or scientist to deploy the technology without reference to any
    proprietary or classified materials;

    (2) attribution shall be recorded on the National Resilience Ledger in the
    name of the individual inventors, researchers, or development teams
    responsible for the technology, where those individuals are identifiable and
    consent to attribution, and in the name of the relevant DoD program or agency
    where individual attribution is not feasible;

    (3) the transferred technology shall be subject to the copyleft mandate of
    Section 507 of Title V of this Act from the date of transfer, ensuring that
    derivative developments remain in the commons; and

    (4) the transfer shall be accompanied by a Legacy Credit award to the relevant
    DoD program pursuant to Section 304(f) of Title III of this Act, recognizing
    the program's contribution to the commons.

(d) SECRETARY OF DEFENSE OVERRIDE.-- The Secretary of Defense may override a
Civilian-Use Board transfer determination within thirty days of the
determination, upon a specific written finding that:

    (1) the transfer would compromise national security in a manner that the
    Board's deliberations did not adequately consider; and

    (2) the specific security concern cannot be addressed through partial transfer,
    delayed transfer, or the application of bounded commons contribution
    restrictions pursuant to Section 404(c) of Title IV of this Act.

    (3) An override pursuant to this subsection shall be subject to judicial
    review in any federal court of competent jurisdiction upon the application of
    any certified Qualified Federated Network, under the de novo standard of
    Section 104(e)(3) of this Act. The burden of demonstrating that the override
    is justified on genuine national security grounds shall rest with the
    Secretary of Defense.

(e) SOCIAL AND BEHAVIORAL SCIENCE RESEARCH TOOLS.-- The research outputs of the
DARPA Systematizing Confidence in Open Research and Evidence program -- including
the credibility assessment algorithms, reproducibility prediction tools,
replication datasets, and associated methodological innovations -- are hereby
deemed to meet the eligibility criteria of subsection (b) of this Section and
shall be transferred to the Intellectual Property Commons within ninety days of
the date of enactment of this Act, without requirement of individual Civilian-Use
Board determination, subject to:

    (1) attribution recorded in the names of the contributing research teams and
    the Center for Open Science as coordinating institution;

    (2) coordination with the Center for Open Science to ensure that the transfer
    is consistent with COS's own open science commitments and does not duplicate
    or disrupt COS's ongoing stewardship of the Open Science Framework; and

    (3) the copyleft mandate of Section 507 of Title V of this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 904. NON-KINETIC DATA ACCESS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT OF DATA ACCESS PROTOCOL.-- The Secretary of Defense shall
establish, within two hundred seventy days of the date of enactment of this Act,
a Non-Kinetic Data Access Protocol providing Qualified Federated Networks with
read-only, real-time access to the following categories of Department of Defense
data through a secure application programming interface connected to the
Federated Mesh:

    (1) METEOROLOGICAL AND CLIMATE DATA -- including high-resolution weather
    modeling outputs, long-range climate projections, extreme weather event
    predictions, and atmospheric monitoring data, at a resolution and update
    frequency sufficient to support agricultural planning, energy management, and
    emergency preparedness within Qualified Federated Networks;

    (2) ENVIRONMENTAL AND ECOLOGICAL DATA -- including satellite imagery, land
    use monitoring data, watershed health assessments, and ecosystem monitoring
    outputs, at a resolution sufficient to support the ecological stewardship
    functions of Community Land Trusts and the ecological restoration programs of
    cooperative agricultural enterprises;

    (3) LOGISTICS AND SUPPLY CHAIN DATA -- including non-sensitive elements of
    the Department's supply chain modeling and logistics optimization outputs that
    can inform the Asynchronous Resource Coordination functions of the Federated
    Mesh, specifically excluding any data whose disclosure would reveal military
    operational details, force movements, or procurement strategies;

    (4) PUBLIC HEALTH AND EPIDEMIOLOGICAL DATA -- including disease surveillance
    data, outbreak modeling outputs, and biosurveillance information at the level
    of resolution currently shared with the Centers for Disease Control and
    Prevention, enabling cooperative healthcare systems within the Federated
    Network to monitor and respond to public health threats with the same
    situational awareness available to federal public health authorities; and

    (5) GEOSPATIAL AND INFRASTRUCTURE DATA -- including publicly available
    geospatial data about federal land boundaries, infrastructure locations, and
    environmental conditions that supports the land commons functions of Title III
    of this Act.

(b) PRIVACY AND SECURITY REQUIREMENTS.-- The Non-Kinetic Data Access Protocol
shall be designed and operated in accordance with the following requirements:

    (1) all data provided through the Protocol shall be at the level of
    classification of Unclassified or Controlled Unclassified Information, with
    no classified data accessible through the Protocol under any circumstances;

    (2) data provided through the Protocol shall be aggregated or anonymized where
    necessary to prevent the identification of specific military personnel,
    operational assets, or sensitive facilities;

    (3) access to the Protocol shall be limited to certified Qualified Federated
    Networks, verified through the Zero-Knowledge Proof authentication mechanism
    of Section 702(c) of Title VII of this Act; and

    (4) the Protocol shall implement the data minimization and privacy-preserving
    computation requirements of Title IV of this Act with respect to any personal
    data of Commons Members that may be incidentally captured in the data streams.

(c) GOVERNANCE OF DATA ACCESS.-- The scope, format, and update frequency of data
provided through the Non-Kinetic Data Access Protocol shall be governed jointly
by:

    (1) the Secretary of Defense, who retains authority to restrict or suspend
    access to any data stream upon a specific written finding of national security
    necessity;

    (2) the Technical Standards Body established under Section 701(d) of Title VII
    of this Act, which shall establish the technical specifications for the
    Protocol's interface with the Federated Mesh; and

    (3) the IP Commons Governance Council, which shall advocate for the broadest
    possible data access consistent with security requirements and shall report
    annually on any restrictions that limit the commons' ability to use military
    data for civilian resilience purposes.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 905. SURPLUS MILITARY LAND TRANSFER.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) IDENTIFICATION.-- The Secretary of Defense shall, within the comprehensive
inventory conducted pursuant to Section 302(a) of Title III of this Act, identify
all military land that:

    (1) has been formally designated for closure, realignment, or disposal under
    the Base Realignment and Closure process or any successor process;

    (2) is not currently in active operational use and has not been designated for
    future operational use within the Department's ten-year facility plan;

    (3) is not required for the military-civilian strategic sync purposes of this
    Title -- specifically including land needed for dual-use technology
    deployment, research facilities supporting the Civilian-Use Board's ongoing
    audit function, or installations whose proximity to population centers makes
    them valuable for emergency response purposes; and

    (4) has productive potential for residential, agricultural, renewable energy,
    or ecological restoration uses consistent with the purposes of the Federated
    Land Commons.

(b) TRANSFER PROCESS.-- Surplus military land identified pursuant to subsection
(a) of this Section shall be transferred to Community Land Trust stewardship
through the federal surplus land transfer process of Section 302 of Title III of
this Act, subject to the following additional requirements:

    (1) ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION PRIORITY.-- Many former military installations
    contain contamination from fuels, munitions, industrial solvents, and other
    hazardous materials. The transfer of any such parcel to CLT stewardship shall
    be conditioned on:

        (A) a comprehensive environmental assessment conducted at DoD expense
        within one hundred eighty days of the parcel's identification for
        transfer;

        (B) a remediation plan developed by the DoD in consultation with the
        receiving CLT and the Environmental Protection Agency, with remediation
        costs borne entirely by the federal government;

        (C) completion of remediation to a standard sufficient for the intended
        commons use -- residential, agricultural, or ecological -- before title
        transfer, or, where full remediation prior to transfer is not feasible, a
        binding federal commitment to complete remediation within a defined
        timeline with financial assurance mechanisms protecting the receiving CLT
        from remediation costs; and

        (D) ongoing monitoring of remediation effectiveness for not less than ten
        years following transfer, with monitoring costs borne by the DoD.

    (2) COMMUNITY ENGAGEMENT.-- The identification of surplus military land for
    CLT transfer shall be accompanied by meaningful community engagement with the
    populations most directly affected by the transfer, including:

        (A) public hearings conducted in the communities adjacent to the proposed
        transfer parcel, with adequate notice and accessibility for all community
        members;

        (B) consultation with tribal governments where the parcel is located
        within or adjacent to tribal territory, consistent with the
        government-to-government consultation requirements of Section 105(c)(4)
        of this Act; and

        (C) a community needs assessment identifying the most beneficial commons
        use of the parcel -- residential, agricultural, energy, ecological, or
        mixed-use -- conducted in partnership with the Office of Federated
        Stewardship and potential receiving CLTs.

    (3) DEFENSE MISSION COMPATIBILITY.-- Where a former military installation is
    adjacent to an active military facility, the transfer agreement shall include
    provisions ensuring that the CLT's use of the transferred land does not
    interfere with the active facility's operations, with any use restrictions
    clearly documented in the deed and subject to the anti-speculation provisions
    of Section 307 of Title III of this Act.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 906. IRREVOCABILITY OF PHASE 1 TRANSFERS AND ANTICIPATORY FINDING.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) IRREVOCABILITY.-- The Phase 1 transfers authorized by Sections 901 through
905 of this Title are irrevocable upon completion. No executive order,
administrative determination, agency rule, or subsequent Department of Defense
decision shall have the effect of:

    (1) reclaiming any technology transferred to the Intellectual Property Commons
    pursuant to Section 903 of this Title;

    (2) revoking access to the Non-Kinetic Data Access Protocol established
    pursuant to Section 904 of this Title, except upon a specific written national
    security finding by the Secretary of Defense subject to judicial review
    pursuant to Section 903(d)(3) of this Title; or

    (3) reversing the transfer of surplus military land to Community Land Trust
    stewardship pursuant to Section 905 of this Title.

(b) SCOPE OF THIS TITLE.-- The provisions of Sections 901 through 905 of this
Title, together with this Section, constitute the complete scope of
military-civilian commons integration under this Act. Further integration of
military technology, data, and governance with the civilian commons
infrastructure is anticipated in subsequent legislation and is beyond the scope
of this Act.

(c) ANTICIPATORY FINDING.-- Congress finds that the domestic commons
infrastructure established by this Act, as it matures and demonstrates its
resilience, will create conditions in which further integration of military and
civilian commons governance becomes strategically coherent and publicly
beneficial, and anticipates addressing such further integration through
subsequent legislative vehicles in due course.


================================================================================
TITLE X -- TRANSITION ECONOMICS AND PHASE 0
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the transition architecture through
which the commons economy moves from its current condition -- fragmented,
undercapitalized, and legally precarious at the margins of the extractive economy
-- to the federated, self-sustaining, and legally protected infrastructure that
the preceding Titles establish. This transition does not begin from nothing. The
cooperative institutions, community land trusts, open-source commons, and
solidarity economy networks that this Act recognizes, connects, and capitalizes
already exist and already function throughout the United States and
internationally. This Act removes the legal barriers that keep them fragmented,
provides the technical infrastructure that connects them, and supplies the
financial capitalization that allows them to scale from the margins of the economy
to its foundation. The transition economics provisions of this Title ensure that
this scaling occurs in an orderly, equitable, and resilient manner -- building on
demonstrated success rather than speculative theory, prioritizing the communities
most harmed by the extractive economy, and maintaining the adaptive flexibility
that Ostrom identified as essential to the long-term resilience of any commons
institution.

