SEC. 1001. EXISTING COMMONS RECOGNITION -- PROTO-QFN STATUS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) IMMEDIATE RECOGNITION.-- Upon the date of enactment of this Act, the
following categories of existing organizations are hereby recognized as
Proto-Qualified Federated Networks or Proto-Qualified Federated Cooperatives --
entities that already embody the substantive values and many of the governance
practices required for full QFN or QFC certification, and that are presumptively
eligible for the expedited certification pathways of Section 103(e) of this Act:

    (1) community land trusts currently holding land in perpetual stewardship for
    the benefit of a defined community, operating under a ground lease structure
    that limits speculative resale, and governed by a board with meaningful
    resident and community representation, including without limitation the
    Champlain Housing Trust in Burlington, Vermont; Dudley Neighbors Incorporated
    in Boston, Massachusetts; and the member CLTs of Grounded Solutions Network
    and the California Community Land Trust Network;

    (2) worker cooperatives in which the enterprise is owned and democratically
    governed by its workers on a one-member-one-vote or equivalent
    collective-choice basis, including without limitation all member cooperatives
    of the United States Federation of Worker Cooperatives (USFWC) and member
    enterprises of NCBA CLUSA;

    (3) tenant cooperatives in which residential occupants collectively own and
    govern the housing in which they live;

    (4) food cooperatives governed by their members -- whether as consumer
    cooperatives, producer cooperatives, or multi-stakeholder cooperatives --
    on a democratic collective-choice basis;

    (5) credit unions chartered under federal or state law as member-owned,
    democratically governed financial cooperatives;

    (6) community development financial institutions certified by the CDFI Fund
    of the Department of the Treasury as mission-driven lenders serving
    underserved communities, including without limitation Native CDFIs certified
    under the Native CDFI Assistance (NACA) Program;

    (7) rural electric cooperatives organized under the Rural Electrification Act
    of 1936, operating as member-owned, democratically governed energy utilities;

    (8) agricultural marketing cooperatives organized under the Capper-Volstead
    Act, operating as farmer-owned enterprises for the collective marketing of
    agricultural products;

    (9) time banks and mutual aid networks operating on the principle of
    reciprocal community exchange, with documented membership, contribution
    tracking, and community governance, including without limitation hOurworld
    and TimeBanks USA;

    (10) solidarity economy networks serving as coordinating bodies for two or
    more of the above organization types within a defined geographic area or
    functional domain, including without limitation the New Economy Coalition,
    the U.S. Solidarity Economy Network (USSEN), the Federation of Southern
    Cooperatives, the National Cooperative Business Association (NCBA CLUSA),
    and the United States Federation of Worker Cooperatives (USFWC) in their
    capacity as national coordinating bodies; and

    (11) open-source software communities, commons-oriented research
    institutions, and commons governance infrastructure organizations -- including
    the Center for Open Science and its Open Science Framework; the Apache
    Software Foundation; the Linux Foundation; the Mozilla Foundation; Creative
    Commons; the Open Knowledge Foundation; SPARC (the Scholarly Publishing and
    Academic Resources Coalition); the Confederation of Open Access Repositories
    (COAR); the Platform Cooperativism Consortium; and the Commons Stack -- that
    operate under open governance principles, maintain publicly accessible outputs
    under open licenses, and have demonstrated sustained commitment to commons
    values in their organizational practice.

The National Cooperative Bank, as a specialized national cooperative lending
institution, is hereby recognized as presumptively eligible for Commons
Financial Node registration under Section 4(3) of this Act.

(b) EFFECT OF PROTO-QFN RECOGNITION.-- Recognition as a Proto-QFN or Proto-QFC
under this Section:

    (1) makes the organization immediately eligible for the expedited
    certification pathways of Section 103(e) of this Act, with the organization's
    existing governance structures treated as presumptive evidence of Ostrom
    Standards compliance to the extent they demonstrate functional equivalence;

    (2) makes the organization immediately eligible for Transition Grants and
    Technical Integration Grants under Section 106 of this Act, without waiting
    for full QFC or QFN certification;

   (3) makes the organization's existing members immediately eligible for the
    creator transition pathway of Section 106(b)(5) of this Act where applicable.

(c) NO OBLIGATION TO SEEK CERTIFICATION.-- Recognition as a Proto-QFN or
Proto-QFC under this Section creates no obligation on the recognized organization
to seek QFN or QFC certification. Participation in the Federated Network is
entirely voluntary. Proto-QFN recognition is a designation of eligibility and
presumptive compatibility, not a requirement or a compulsion.

