SEC. 1002. CDFI INTEGRATION AS COMMONS FINANCIAL NODES.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) STRATEGIC ROLE.-- Community Development Financial Institutions represent the
most immediately deployable financial infrastructure for the commons economy's
transition phase. CDFIs already possess:

    (1) established lending relationships with cooperative enterprises, community
    land trusts, and low-income communities across the United States;

    (2) mission alignment with the commons economy's goals of serving underserved
    communities, building community wealth, and providing patient, below-market
    capital;

    (3) regulatory frameworks and compliance infrastructure that can be adapted
    for Commons Financial Node functions with relatively modest modification;

    (4) geographic distribution that complements the network's coverage
    obligations under Section 105 of this Act, with CDFIs operating in many of
    the Underserved Areas designated pursuant to Section 105(b); and

    (5) existing relationships with federal agencies -- including the CDFI Fund,
    the SBA, and the USDA -- that can be leveraged for coordinated program
    delivery during the transition period.

The 64 Native CDFIs certified under the Treasury CDFI Fund's Native CDFI
Assistance (NACA) Program represent particularly critical existing infrastructure
for the tribal community coverage obligations of Section 105(c)(4) of this Act.
NACA-certified Native CDFIs shall be given the highest registration priority
among CDFIs seeking Commons Financial Node status, and their existing NACA
certification shall be treated as satisfying the simplified registration
requirements of subsection (b) of this Section in full, requiring only the
technical integration steps of subsection (b)(2). The National Cooperative Bank,
as a specialized national cooperative lending institution, is separately eligible
for Commons Financial Node registration and shall be treated for registration
purposes as holding CDFI-equivalent status for all purposes of this Section,
given its decades of cooperative-sector lending and mission alignment.

(b) SIMPLIFIED REGISTRATION PATHWAY.-- CDFIs seeking registration as Commons
Financial Nodes pursuant to Section 4(3) of this Act shall be eligible for a
simplified registration process that:

    (1) accepts the CDFI Fund's certification as prima facie evidence of the
    organization's mission alignment and governance integrity, without requiring
    duplicative governance assessment by the Office of Federated Stewardship;

    (2) requires only the technical integrations necessary to connect to the
    National Resilience Ledger and participate in the Commons Credit system, with
    Technical Integration Grant funding available for those costs;

    (3) may be completed within sixty days of application submission, reflecting
    the urgency of establishing functional financial infrastructure for the
    early-stage Federated Network; and

    (4) automatically confers Commons Financial Node status on any CDFI that
    achieves registration, without requirement for further certification steps.

(c) TRANSITION LENDING MANDATE.-- Commons Financial Nodes that are registered
CDFIs are directed to prioritize the following categories of lending during the
transition period, consistent with their existing community development missions:

    (1) acquisition support disbursements for CLT land acquisition through the
    Commons Infrastructure Capitalization Fund pursuant to Section 306(b)(3) of
    Title III of this Act;

    (2) cooperative business conversion financing pursuant to Section 304(d) of
    Title III of this Act;

    (3) Bootstrap Grant bridge financing for organizations awaiting Bootstrap
    Grant disbursement;

    (4) technical integration financing for organizations undertaking Federated
    Mesh connection pursuant to Title VII of this Act; and

    (5) coverage extension financing for Qualified Federated Networks expanding
    into designated Underserved Areas.

(d) COORDINATION WITH EXISTING FEDERAL PROGRAMS.-- The Office of Federated
Stewardship shall coordinate with the CDFI Fund to align existing federal CDFI
support programs -- including the CDFI Program, the New Markets Tax Credit, the
Capital Magnet Fund, and the CDFI Bond Guarantee Program -- with the transition
lending priorities of this Section, ensuring that federal financial support for
CDFIs flows preferentially to institutions that are actively serving as Commons
Financial Nodes. The OFS shall further coordinate with the CDFI Fund to ensure
that NACA Program resources are directed toward Native CDFIs pursuing Commons
Financial Node registration, consistent with the tribal community coverage
obligations of Section 105(c)(4) of this Act.

