SEC. 1003. FEDERATED RESILIENCE DEMONSTRATION ZONES.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- The Office of Federated Stewardship shall, within one year
of the date of enactment of this Act, designate between ten and twenty communities
as Federated Resilience Demonstration Zones -- communities selected for
comprehensive, priority implementation of the full commons infrastructure stack
established by this Act, which will serve as visible proof of concept for the
Federated Network's capacity to deliver the Guaranteed Provision Standard, govern
commons resources democratically, and provide genuine community resilience.

(b) SELECTION CRITERIA.-- Communities shall be selected as Federated Resilience
Demonstration Zones based on the following criteria:

    (1) EXISTING INFRASTRUCTURE DENSITY -- the presence of existing proto-QFN
    institutions sufficient to provide a foundation for rapid commons buildout,
    including at minimum one community land trust or housing cooperative, one
    worker or food cooperative, and one CDFI or credit union;

    (2) COMMUNITY READINESS -- demonstrated community interest in and
    organizational capacity for commons development, evidenced by community
    organizing activity, municipal government support, or existing solidarity
    economy coordination;

    (3) GEOGRAPHIC AND DEMOGRAPHIC DIVERSITY -- the set of designated zones shall
    collectively represent the geographic, demographic, urban-rural, and economic
    diversity of the United States, ensuring that the demonstration program does
    not concentrate in already-advantaged communities;

    (4) UNDERSERVED AREA REPRESENTATION -- not fewer than forty percent of
    designated zones shall be located in communities designated as Underserved
    Areas or Priority Underserved Areas pursuant to Section 105(b) of this Act,
    prioritizing the demonstration of the commons model's effectiveness in the
    communities most harmed by the extractive economy;

    (5) TRIBAL COMMUNITY REPRESENTATION -- not fewer than two designated zones
    shall be located in or primarily serving Native American, Alaska Native, or
    Native Hawaiian communities, subject to the government-to-government
    consultation requirements of Section 105(c)(4) of this Act and the consent
    of the relevant tribal governance bodies; and

    (6) SCALABILITY POTENTIAL -- each designated community shall have demonstrated
    potential to serve as a model and anchor for broader regional network
    development, such that the demonstration zone becomes a nucleus for expanding
    commons coverage into surrounding communities.

(c) ENHANCED SUPPORT FOR DEMONSTRATION ZONES.-- Designated Federated Resilience
Demonstration Zones shall receive:

    (1) Resilience Demonstration Grants pursuant to Section 106(b)(6) of this
    Act, at funding levels determined by the Office of Federated Stewardship to
    be sufficient for comprehensive commons infrastructure implementation within
    a five-year buildout timeline;

    (2) priority access to dual-use technology transfers under Title IX of this
    Act, ensuring that demonstration zone communities have access to the most
    advanced commons-compatible energy, water, and agricultural technologies
    available;

    (3) dedicated technical assistance from the Office of Federated Stewardship,
    including embedded staff support for the duration of the five-year buildout
    period;

    (4) priority consideration in federal program coordination under Section
    107(c)(7) of this Act, ensuring that all relevant federal agencies direct
    available resources to demonstration zone communities; and

    (5) expedited Decidim-DAO bridge deployment under Section 705(c) of Title VII
    of this Act, making demonstration zones the first communities to operate under
    the full integrated governance platform.

(d) DEMONSTRATION ZONE REPORTING.-- Each designated Federated Resilience
Demonstration Zone shall submit annual progress reports to the Office of
Federated Stewardship documenting:

    (1) the number of Commons Members enrolled and the provision components
    successfully delivered;

    (2) the governance participation rates of Commons Members in cooperative
    decision-making processes;

    (3) the ecological health metrics of commons land within the zone;

    (4) the Commons Credit circulation velocity and time-banking participation
    rates;

    (5) qualitative assessments of community wellbeing, social cohesion, and
    member satisfaction with the commons model, gathered through participatory
    assessment processes; and

    (6) lessons learned -- including honest assessments of what has not worked as
    well as what has -- to be shared with the broader Federated Network through
    the National Resilience Ledger.

(e) PUBLIC ACCESSIBILITY OF DEMONSTRATION ZONE EXPERIENCE.-- The Office of
Federated Stewardship shall ensure that the experience of Federated Resilience
Demonstration Zones is documented and made accessible to communities considering
commons development throughout the United States and internationally, through:

    (1) publication of annual demonstration zone reports on the National
    Resilience Ledger in plain language and in all languages spoken by more than
    one percent of the demonstration zone populations;

    (2) an annual convening of demonstration zone representatives, commons
    governance practitioners, and community organizers from across the country and
    internationally, to share experience and accelerate commons development; and

    (3) coordination with the international commons networks identified in Section
    1005 of this Title to ensure that demonstration zone experience informs global
    commons development.

