SEC. 1004. PETRODOLLAR HEDGE AND MONETARY RESILIENCE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that the material security of the United States is
currently dependent upon a global monetary architecture whose structural fragility
poses a significant and growing risk to domestic economic stability. The
concentration of global energy markets in dollar-denominated transactions has
required the United States to maintain expensive military commitments to protect
dollar hegemony, has constrained domestic monetary policy, and has made the
American economy vulnerable to disruptions in global oil markets, currency
speculation, and the monetary decisions of foreign governments and international
financial institutions. The domestic commons infrastructure established by this
Act -- including distributed renewable energy cooperatives, cooperative food
systems, resilient local manufacturing, and the Commons Credit monetary
architecture -- constitutes a strategic hedge against petrodollar fragility by
providing communities with the material self-sufficiency to maintain the
Guaranteed Provision Standard regardless of the condition of global currency
markets.

(b) COMMONS ECONOMY AS STRATEGIC RESERVE.-- The productive capacity of the
Federated Network -- its energy generation, food production, knowledge commons,
and cooperative manufacturing -- is hereby recognized as a form of strategic
reserve that supplements and over time reduces dependence on the dollar-
denominated strategic reserves currently maintained by the federal government.
Specifically:

    (1) the distributed renewable energy capacity of cooperative energy
    enterprises within the Federated Network constitutes a strategic energy
    reserve that reduces dependence on imported fossil fuels and dollar-
    denominated energy markets;

    (2) the food production capacity of commons agricultural enterprises
    constitutes a strategic food reserve that reduces dependence on global
    commodity markets and long-distance supply chains vulnerable to currency
    disruption;

    (3) the knowledge commons of the Intellectual Property Commons constitutes a
    strategic knowledge reserve -- freely available technical designs for energy
    systems, water treatment, medical treatment, and agricultural production --
    that provides communities with the capacity to maintain essential functions
    without dependence on proprietary supply chains; and

    (4) the Commons Credit monetary architecture constitutes a strategic monetary
    reserve -- a parallel medium of exchange backed by the productive capacity of
    the commons rather than by dollar-denominated debt -- that maintains community
    economic function during periods of dollar instability.

(c) DOLLAR TRANSITION PRINCIPLE.-- The progressive reduction of the commons
economy's dependence on the United States dollar -- as the Federated Network's
productive capacity grows and its ability to provide for its members' needs
without recourse to the external market economy increases -- is a measure of the
commons economy's growing maturity and self-sufficiency, not a threat to the
federal monetary system. This Act does not predict, advocate, or plan for dollar
collapse. It ensures that American communities have the material foundation to
maintain dignified lives regardless of the condition of global monetary systems.

(d) FEDERAL RESERVE COORDINATION.-- The Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve
System shall:

    (1) monitor the growth of the commons economy and the Commons Credit system,
    and report annually to Congress on their relationship to the broader monetary
    system;

    (2) treat Commons Credit growth as asset-backed productive output rather than
    as monetary expansion, consistent with the Commons Land Asset Recognition
    architecture of Section 306(b) of Title III of this Act and the Commons Credit
    definition of Section 602(a) of Title VI of this Act, neither of which
    constitutes money creation in the Federal Reserve Act sense; and

    (3) coordinate with the Commons Credit Governance Council on monetary policy
    matters that affect the interface between the dollar economy and the commons
    economy, ensuring that federal monetary policy does not inadvertently undermine
    the transition to commons self-sufficiency, including by treating the
    progressive decline of dollar-denominated economic activity within the
    Federated Network as a measure of the commons economy's growing productive
    maturity rather than as a monetary policy concern requiring intervention.

