SEC. 1005. INTERNATIONAL FEDERATION FRAMEWORK.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) POLICY.-- It is the policy of the United States to support the development
of commons institutions -- including community land trusts, worker cooperatives,
data commons, and intellectual property commons -- internationally, as an
expression of genuine solidarity with communities worldwide that are seeking
alternatives to extractive economic arrangements, and as a recognition that the
global commons transition serves American interests by creating a more stable,
equitable, and resilient international order.

(b) INTERNATIONAL COMMONS RECOGNITION.-- The federal government shall recognize
foreign commons networks -- including community land trust federations, worker
cooperative networks, solidarity economy organizations, and open-source commons
communities -- as legitimate governance institutions and potential partners of
the United States Federated Network, subject to demonstrated alignment with the
Ostrom Standards of Stewardship and the commons values of this Act.

(c) BILATERAL COMMONS FEDERATION AGREEMENTS.-- The Secretary of State is hereby
authorized to negotiate and, subject to Senate advice and consent where required
by the Constitution, conclude bilateral and multilateral commons federation
agreements with foreign governments and international commons networks providing
for:

    (1) mutual recognition of commons membership -- enabling Commons Membership
    portability for individuals moving between the United States Federated Network
    and participating foreign commons networks, pursuant to Section 210(d) of
    Title II of this Act;

    (2) inter-commons IP sharing -- enabling the exchange of commons-licensed
    intellectual property between the United States IP Commons and participating
    foreign knowledge commons, under reciprocal copyleft obligations;

    (3) inter-commons data governance -- establishing privacy-compatible protocols
    for data exchange between the United States Data Commons and participating
    foreign data trusts, under mutual privacy protection obligations consistent
    with Title IV of this Act; and

    (4) commons-to-commons resource exchange -- establishing frameworks for the
    exchange of surplus commons resources between the United States Federated
    Network and participating foreign networks, at use value rates and under the
    provision priority rule of Section 307(d) of Title III of this Act.

(d) EXISTING INTERNATIONAL COMMONS NETWORKS.-- The Office of Federated
Stewardship shall, within one year of the date of enactment of this Act, publish
a comprehensive assessment of existing international commons networks with which
bilateral commons federation agreements would be mutually beneficial, including:

    (1) the international community land trust movement, coordinated through the
    International Center for Community Land Trusts (ICCLT), whose member CLTs
    and affiliated regional networks span multiple continents and whose shared
    governance principles are substantially equivalent to the Ostrom Standards
    of Stewardship;

    (2) the Mondragon cooperative federation and its international network of
    partner cooperatives;

    (3) the Barcelona en Comu municipal commons network and the broader fearless
    cities movement;

    (4) the P2P Foundation's global commons research and governance network;

    (5) the Solidarity Economy networks of Catalonia, the Basque Country, and
    other Spanish regional commons economies, including the XES (Xarxa
    d'Economia Solidaria) network and the REAS (Red de Redes de Economia
    Alternativa y Solidaria) national network;

    (6) RIPESS (Intercontinental Network for the Promotion of Social
    Solidarity Economy), the primary global coordinating body for solidarity
    economy networks across five continental networks, with which the U.S.
    Solidarity Economy Network (USSEN) is already affiliated, and whose
    governance structures provide an existing framework for international
    commons federation recognition processes; and

    (7) the Sarafu Network and comparable mutual credit and time-banking systems
    operating in the Global South, including the Community Exchange System (CES)
    operating across multiple African nations.

The assessment required by this subsection shall include a recommended priority
ordering for federation agreement negotiations, with RIPESS, ICCLT, and the
Mondragon international network recommended as first-tier priorities given their
existing governance maturity, geographic scope, and alignment with the Ostrom
Standards of Stewardship.

(e) COMMONS SOLIDARITY FUND.-- There is hereby established a Commons Solidarity
Fund, administered by the Office of Federated Stewardship in coordination with
the Department of State, to provide technical assistance, open-source technology
transfer, and capacity-building support to commons institutions in developing
nations. The Commons Solidarity Fund:

    (1) shall be funded through a defined percentage of the surplus generated by
    external resource trade under Section 307(d)(3) of Title III of this Act,
    ensuring that international solidarity is funded by the commons economy's own
    productive success rather than through general appropriations that may be
    subject to political disruption;

    (2) shall prioritize support for commons institutions in nations most affected
    by the extractive dynamics that the FRDI Act is designed to replace
    domestically, including nations whose economies have been distorted by
    structural adjustment programs, resource extraction by multinational
    corporations, and intellectual property regimes that have prevented access to
    essential medicines and agricultural technologies; and

    (3) shall operate on a commons-to-commons solidarity principle -- providing
    support without political conditions, respecting the governance autonomy of
    recipient communities, and measuring success by the recipient communities'
    own assessments of their progress rather than by metrics imposed by the
    funding institution.

