SEC. 1006. SUCCESSION CRISIS TRANSITION PROGRAM.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FINDING.-- Congress finds that a significant and growing proportion of small
and medium-sized business owners in the United States are approaching retirement
age without an identified succession plan, and that this succession crisis
represents both a threat to the communities that depend on these businesses and
an extraordinary opportunity for the cooperative transition established by this
Act. The cooperative business conversion mechanisms of Section 304 of Title III
of this Act are the primary legislative response to this crisis, but their
effectiveness depends on the availability of transition support infrastructure
that this Section establishes. Existing federal programs addressing this crisis
include the Department of Labor's Employee Ownership Initiative, the first
federal worker ownership grant program, which funds Employee Ownership Centers
providing technical assistance for conversions; the Main Street Employee
Ownership Act, which requires the Small Business Administration to train Small
Business Development Centers on employee ownership succession pathways and
authorizes the SBA 7(a) loan program to finance employee acquisitions; and the
WORK Act, which expands DOL Employee Ownership Center funding. The Succession
Transition Support Program established by this Section builds upon, coordinates
with, and expands the reach of these existing programs, supplementing their
worker-ownership-specific focus with the broader cooperative formation,
multi-stakeholder cooperative, and CLT-connected business conversion pathways
that those programs do not currently address.

(b) SUCCESSION TRANSITION SUPPORT INFRASTRUCTURE.-- The Office of Federated
Stewardship shall, in coordination with the Small Business Administration and the
Department of Labor, establish a Succession Transition Support Program
comprising:

    (1) a national registry of businesses whose owners have expressed interest in
    cooperative conversion, maintained on the National Resilience Ledger and
    accessible to worker cooperative development organizations, CDFIs, and
    potential employee buyer groups;

    (2) a network of cooperative conversion technical assistance providers --
    including existing worker cooperative development organizations, DOL-funded
    Employee Ownership Centers, USFWC's Co-op Clinic, DAWI (Democracy at Work
    Institute), law firms specializing in cooperative law, and financial advisors
    experienced in cooperative financing -- accessible to business owners and
    employee groups throughout the United States, with Bootstrap Grant funding
    available to expand existing Employee Ownership Centers' capacity to cover
    multi-stakeholder and CLT-connected conversion pathways not currently within
    their scope;

    (3) a cooperative conversion curriculum available through the IP Commons
    educational resources of Section 207 of Title II of this Act, providing
    business owners and employee groups with the knowledge necessary to evaluate
    and execute a cooperative conversion; and

    (4) a peer network connecting business owners who have completed cooperative
    conversions with those considering conversion, enabling the sharing of
    practical experience and the reduction of the uncertainty that deters many
    owners from pursuing this path.

(c) SECTOR-SPECIFIC CONVERSION PROGRAMS.-- The Succession Transition Support
Program shall include sector-specific conversion programs for industries with
particularly high concentrations of businesses approaching succession crisis,
including:

    (1) manufacturing enterprises, where cooperative conversion preserves local
    industrial capacity and skilled employment that would otherwise be lost to
    private equity acquisition and offshoring;

    (2) agricultural enterprises, where cooperative conversion aligns with the
    food commons objectives of Section 204 of Title II of this Act and provides a
    transition pathway for retiring farmers whose land would otherwise enter
    speculative agricultural commodity markets;

    (3) healthcare practices, where cooperative conversion aligns with the
    healthcare commons objectives of Section 205 of Title II of this Act and
    provides an alternative to private equity consolidation of primary care and
    specialty practices; and

    (4) technology enterprises, where cooperative conversion aligns with the
    open-source development mandate of Section 705 of Title VII of this Act and
    provides an alternative to venture capital acquisition that typically results
    in IP enclosure.

