SEC. 1007. PHASE 0 IMPLEMENTATION TIMELINE.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) IMMEDIATE ACTIONS -- WITHIN 90 DAYS OF ENACTMENT.--

    (1) The Office of Federated Stewardship shall be established within the
    Department of Commerce and the Director appointment process shall be
    initiated.

    (2) The Bootstrap Grant Program application portal shall be opened for
    Formation Grants and Transition Grants.

    (3) The CDFI Fund shall begin the simplified Commons Financial Node
    registration process for interested CDFIs.

    (4) The DARPA SCORE program outputs shall be transferred to the Intellectual
    Property Commons pursuant to Section 903(e) of Title IX of this Act.

    (5) The Secretary of the Interior shall initiate the comprehensive federal
    land inventory required by Section 302(a) of Title III of this Act.

    (6) The Director of the Office of Federated Stewardship shall convene the
    first expanded session of the Interagency Working Group on Cooperative
    Development, established pursuant to the Agricultural Act of 2014, with
    expanded membership including the Federal Communications Commission, the
    Department of Energy, and any other agencies not currently represented whose
    programs bear on this Act's implementation, and shall establish that working
    group as the primary interagency coordination mechanism for Phase 0
    implementation pursuant to Section 107(c)(7) of Title I of this Act.

(b) SHORT-TERM ACTIONS -- WITHIN 180 DAYS OF ENACTMENT.--

    (1) The Civilian-Use Board shall be established and shall begin the dual-use
    technology audit pursuant to Section 902 of Title IX of this Act.

    (2) The initial Underserved Area map shall be published pursuant to Section
    105(b) of this Act.

    (3) The first Bootstrap Grant awards shall be made, prioritizing organizations
    in designated Underserved Areas and Priority Underserved Areas.

    (4) The Office of Federated Stewardship shall publish the initial assessment
    of existing international commons networks pursuant to Section 1005(d) of
    this Title.

    (5) The first certification applications from existing proto-QFN organizations
    shall be processed through the expedited pathway of Section 103(e) of this
    Act.

(c) MEDIUM-TERM ACTIONS -- WITHIN ONE YEAR OF ENACTMENT.--

    (1) Not fewer than twenty-five Qualified Federated Cooperatives shall have
    achieved certification, drawn from the existing proto-QFN organizations
    identified through the Transition Economics provisions of this Title.

    (2) Not fewer than five Qualified Federated Networks shall have achieved
    certification, demonstrating the network's capacity to federate existing
    cooperative institutions.

    (3) The Federated Resilience Demonstration Zones shall be designated pursuant
    to Section 1003 of this Title.

    (4) The first Commons Land Asset Recognition issuance shall occur in
    connection with a CLT land acquisition, demonstrating the NRL's automated
    Stewardship Credit function; and the first Commons Infrastructure
    Capitalization Fund disbursement shall be made in connection with a Right of
    First Refusal purchase or cooperative business conversion, demonstrating the
    Treasury's acquisition support mechanism.

    (5) The first dual-use technology transfer from the DoD shall be completed
    pursuant to Title IX of this Act.

(d) NETWORK MATURITY TRAJECTORY.-- The implementation timeline of this Section
is designed to ensure that the network maturity threshold of Section 107(f) of
this Act is achievable within ten years of enactment, with:

    (1) years one through three focused on establishing the institutional and
    technical infrastructure -- the OFS, the NRL, the FMOS, the initial QFN
    certifications, and the Demonstration Zones;

    (2) years three through six focused on network expansion -- using demonstrated
    Demonstration Zone success to accelerate certification of new QFNs, extending
    coverage into Underserved Areas, and building the commons financial
    infrastructure;

    (3) years six through eight focused on network deepening -- increasing Commons
    Member enrollment within certified networks, strengthening inter-network
    resource coordination, and completing the dual-use technology transfer
    program; and

    (4) years eight through ten focused on threshold approach -- achieving the
    specific quantitative conditions of Section 107(f) of this Act and preparing
    for the transfer of certification authority to the Peer-to-Peer Audit
    mechanism.


