TITLE XI -- ADMINISTRATIVE AND JUDICIAL PROVISIONS
================================================================================

The purpose of this Title is to establish the administrative framework, judicial
review mechanisms, conforming amendments to existing federal law, and
appropriations authorities necessary to make the preceding Titles of this Act
operative and enforceable. This Title does not create new substantive rights or
obligations -- those are established in Titles I through X. It provides the legal
infrastructure through which those rights and obligations are administered,
enforced, protected from constitutional challenge, and integrated into the
existing body of federal law. The provisions of this Title are drafted with
particular attention to durability -- to ensuring that the legal architecture of
this Act survives changes in administration, withstands constitutional challenge,
and cannot be quietly dismantled through administrative inaction, regulatory
reinterpretation, or the selective denial of appropriations.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 1101. CONSTITUTIONAL SAFE HARBOR.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GOOD FAITH IMPLEMENTATION IMMUNITY.-- Any federal officer, employee, or
agent who in good faith takes any action to implement the provisions of this Act
-- including actions that result in the transfer of federal land to Community
Land Trust stewardship, the contribution of federally funded intellectual
property to the Intellectual Property Commons, the issuance of Stewardship
Credits through the National Resilience Ledger, or the reduction of executive
authority over the Federated Network pursuant to Section 104 of this Act --
shall not be subject to civil or criminal liability under any federal or state
law arising solely from the performance of those implementation duties.

(b) SCOPE OF IMMUNITY.-- The immunity established by subsection (a) of this
Section:

    (1) extends to officers and employees of the Office of Federated Stewardship,
    the Department of the Interior, the Department of Defense, the Department of
    the Treasury, the Federal Reserve, and all other federal agencies with
    implementation responsibilities under this Act;

    (2) does not extend to actions taken in bad faith, in knowing violation of
    this Act, or for purposes unrelated to the implementation of this Act; and

    (3) does not limit the liability of any officer or employee for violations of
    the civil rights of any person, including Commons Members whose Guaranteed
    Provision Standard entitlements are improperly denied or whose privacy rights
    under Title IV of this Act are violated.

(c) CONGRESSIONAL INTENT.-- It is the intent of Congress that no federal officer
or employee shall face personal legal jeopardy for implementing the reduction of
centralized governmental authority over the Federated Network that this Act
requires. The transition from governmental oversight to self-sovereign commons
governance is a deliberate legislative choice, not a dereliction of duty, and
the officers who implement it faithfully serve the public interest.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
SEC. 1102. SEVERABILITY.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL SEVERABILITY.-- If any provision of this Act, or the application of
any provision to any person or circumstance, is held invalid by a court of
competent jurisdiction, the remainder of this Act and the application of its
provisions to other persons or circumstances shall not be affected.

(b) TITLE-LEVEL SEVERABILITY.-- Each Title of this Act is independently operative
and shall remain in full force and effect if any other Title or any provision
thereof is held invalid. The invalidity of any single Title shall not affect the
operation of the remaining Titles, which are designed to function independently
as well as in combination.

(c) DISTRIBUTED NETWORK SEVERABILITY.-- In recognition of the distributed,
polycentric architecture of the Federated Network established by this Act, the
invalidity of any provision governing any specific node, institution, or function
of the network shall not impair the operation of other nodes, institutions, or
functions. The network's governance and provision functions shall continue through
alternative pathways where specific provisions are invalidated, consistent with
the systemic continuity provisions of Section 805 of Title VIII of this Act.

(d) AUTOMATED PROTOCOL CONTINUITY.-- Where any provision governing the automated
functions of the National Resilience Ledger, the Federated Mesh, or the
Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism is held invalid, the remaining automated functions
shall continue to operate, with the invalidated function replaced by the nearest
available human governance equivalent through the Human-in-the-Loop Layer
established under Section 803 of Title VIII of this Act, until such time as
Congress enacts a replacement provision.

