SEC. 1103. THE FEDERATED ACCOUNTABILITY BOARD.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) ESTABLISHMENT.-- There is established the Federated Accountability Board --
an independent appellate body composed of representatives of the Federated
Network itself, providing the primary forum for appeals of certification
determinations, Bootstrap Grant denials, graduated response sanctions, and other
administrative decisions made under this Act.

(b) COMPOSITION.-- The Federated Accountability Board shall comprise:

    (1) during the OFS Phase established under Section 107(f) of this Act: nine
    members selected by random sortition from the pool of all active Commons
    Members who have held Federated Commons Membership for not less than two years
    and have completed Human Review Panel training pursuant to Section 803(d)(2)
    of Title VIII of this Act, with no more than two members from any single
    Qualified Federated Network;

    (2) following the network maturity threshold: a standing body of fifteen
    members constituted through the nested governance architecture of the
    Federated Network, with composition, selection process, and terms established
    by the IP Commons Governance Council in consultation with the Data Commons
    Governance Council and the Commons Credit Governance Council; and

    (3) in all cases: no member who served as an auditing peer, certification
    reviewer, or decision-maker in the proceeding being appealed, and no member
    with a direct personal or financial relationship with any party to the appeal.

(c) JURISDICTION.-- The Federated Accountability Board shall have jurisdiction
over appeals of:

    (1) certification denials and decertification decisions pursuant to Section
    103(f) of Title I of this Act;

    (2) Bootstrap Grant denials and grant fund recovery actions pursuant to
    Section 106 of Title I of this Act;

    (3) shelved patent recapture determinations pursuant to Section 503(d) of
    Title V of this Act;

    (4) anti-thicket patent portfolio determinations pursuant to Section 506(d)
    of Title V of this Act;

    (5) dual-use technology transfer determinations made by the Civilian-Use Board
    pursuant to Section 903 of Title IX of this Act; and

    (6) such other administrative determinations as this Act specifically
    designates for Federated Accountability Board review.

(d) PROCEDURES.-- The Federated Accountability Board shall:

    (1) conduct all proceedings through the Human-in-the-Loop Layer principles
    established in Section 803 of Title VIII of this Act, including the Circuit
    Breaker mechanism, the evidence gathering process, and the affected party
    participation requirements;

    (2) issue written determinations with documented reasoning, recorded on the
    National Resilience Ledger;

    (3) apply the de novo review standard established in Section 103(f)(4) of
    Title I of this Act, without deference to the initial determination;

    (4) complete proceedings within the timeframes established in Section 103(f)(5)
    of Title I of this Act for standard appeals, with expedited procedures for
    appeals involving imminent threats to Commons Members' provision entitlements;
    and

    (5) make its decisions publicly available on the National Resilience Ledger in
    appropriately anonymized form, contributing to the commons governance
    jurisprudence established under Section 805(c)(1) of Title VIII of this Act.

(e) JUDICIAL REVIEW OF BOARD DECISIONS.-- Decisions of the Federated
Accountability Board shall be subject to judicial review in the United States
Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit, on the administrative
record, under the arbitrary and capricious standard of the Administrative
Procedure Act, except that:

    (1) decisions involving the rights of individual Commons Members -- including
    provision entitlements, attribution rights, and privacy protections -- shall
    be reviewed de novo with respect to questions of law; and

    (2) decisions involving the certification or decertification of Qualified
    Federated Networks shall be reviewed under the substantial evidence standard
    with respect to factual findings and de novo with respect to questions of law.

