SEC. 1104. JUDICIAL REVIEW -- GENERAL PROVISIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FEDERAL COURT JURISDICTION.-- The federal district courts shall have original
jurisdiction over:

    (1) actions by Commons Members challenging the denial or termination of
    Guaranteed Provision Standard entitlements pursuant to Section 202(d)(4) of
    Title II of this Act;

    (2) actions by Qualified Federated Networks or Commons Members challenging
    executive overreach pursuant to Section 104(e) of Title I of this Act;

    (3) actions enforcing the Right of First Refusal pursuant to Section 303(g)
    of Title III of this Act;

    (4) actions enforcing the copyleft mandate pursuant to Section 507(d) of
    Title V of this Act;

    (5) actions enforcing the prohibition on surveillance capitalism pursuant to
    Section 406(d) of Title IV of this Act;

    (6) actions enforcing the Neighbor Visibility Prohibition pursuant to Section
    209(d)(4) of Title II of this Act; and

    (7) such other actions arising under this Act as present a federal question
    within the meaning of 28 U.S.C. section 1331.

(b) STANDING.-- Standing to bring actions under this Act shall be construed
broadly, consistent with the Act's purpose of enabling commons institutions and
their members to protect their legal rights without dependence on governmental
enforcement. Specifically:

    (1) any Commons Member shall have standing to challenge any action or omission
    that affects their Guaranteed Provision Standard entitlements, governance
    rights, or privacy rights under this Act;

    (2) any Qualified Federated Cooperative or Qualified Federated Network shall
    have standing to challenge any action or omission that affects its
    certification status, its access to commons infrastructure, or the rights of
    its members; and

    (3) any organization recognized as a Proto-QFN pursuant to Section 1001 of
    Title X of this Act shall have standing to challenge any action or omission
    that affects its ability to seek certification or access bootstrap resources
    under this Act.

(c) PRELIMINARY INJUNCTION STANDARD.-- In any action under this Act, the court
shall apply the modified preliminary injunction standard established in Section
104(e)(4) of Title I of this Act, under which:

    (1) a showing that the challenged action violates a provision of this Act
    shall constitute a sufficient showing of likelihood of success on the merits;

    (2) any disruption to the Guaranteed Provision Standard of Commons Members
    shall constitute irreparable harm per se; and

    (3) the continuity of Commons Members' provision entitlements shall be
    considered a substantial component of the public interest analysis, as
    established under Section 104(e)(5) of Title I of this Act.

(d) CRIMINAL PENALTIES -- ANTI-SPOOFING.-- Section 1030 of Title 18, United
States Code, is hereby amended to add the following as a prohibited offense:

    (1) knowingly deploying a spoofed Physical Unclonable Function signature or
    other mechanism designed to misrepresent the identity of a device within the
    Federated Mesh, with intent to manipulate the Peer-to-Peer Audit mechanism,
    defraud the Commons Credit system, or disrupt the Asynchronous Resource
    Coordination functions of a Qualified Federated Network, shall be punishable
    by imprisonment of not more than ten years, a fine of not more than one
    million dollars, or both.

    (2) MIGRATION ACCESS EXCEPTION.-- Section 1030 of Title 18, United States
    Code, is further amended to provide that access to a Covered Platform's
    systems, as that term is defined in Section 409(a)(1) of Title IV of
    this Act, by a Qualified Federated Network or its authorized technical
    agents, for the sole purpose of receiving data transmitted through a
    migration interface required under Section 409(b) of Title IV of this
    Act, at the explicit direction of the account holder pursuant to Section
    409(c) of that Title, does not constitute access without authorization
    or access in excess of authorization within the meaning of this section,
    regardless of any contrary provision of the Covered Platform's terms of
    service, user agreement, or other unilateral access policy.

(e) CIVIL RIGHTS ENFORCEMENT.-- Nothing in this Act shall be construed to limit
the application of any federal civil rights law to the operations of Qualified
Federated Cooperatives, Qualified Federated Networks, or any institution
operating within the Federated Network. The prohibition on exclusionary
membership criteria in Section 102(b)(3) of Title I of this Act shall be
enforceable through the civil rights enforcement mechanisms of Title VII of the
Civil Rights Act of 1964, the Fair Housing Act, the Americans with Disabilities
Act, and all other applicable federal civil rights statutes.

