SEC. 1105. CONFORMING AMENDMENTS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) FEDERAL RESERVE ACT.-- The Federal Reserve Act, codified at 12 U.S.C.
section 221 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) direct the Board of Governors to conduct the annual monitoring and
    reporting functions established under Section 1004(d) of Title X of this Act;
    and

    (2) authorize the Federal Reserve to recognize Commons Financial Nodes
    registered pursuant to Section 4(3) of this Act as participants in the
    federal payment system for the limited purpose of facilitating Commons Credit
    transactions through the National Resilience Ledger.

    The land acquisition and asset recognition functions of Section 306(b) of
    Title III of this Act are administered entirely through the Commons
    Infrastructure Capitalization Fund within the Department of the Treasury and
    do not require Federal Reserve authorization or participation.

(b) INTERNAL REVENUE CODE.-- The Internal Revenue Code of 1986, codified at
26 U.S.C. section 1 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) add a new section establishing the property tax exemption for commons land
    pursuant to Section 301(c)(3) of Title III of this Act, add a new section 
    establishing the elective property tax exemption and corresponding Stewardship 
    Payment in Lieu of Taxes program for commons land pursuant to Section 301(c)(3) 
    and (d) of Title III of this Act;

    (2) add a new section establishing the capital gains tax deferral for
    cooperative business conversions pursuant to Section 304(e)(1) of Title III
    of this Act;

    (3) add a new section establishing the cooperative tax treatment provisions of
    Section 304(e)(2) of Title III of this Act, including the pass-through
    treatment, the labor deduction, and the corporate alternative minimum tax
    exemption;

    (4) add a new section establishing the charitable contribution deduction for
    voluntary land contributions pursuant to Section 305(a)(4) of Title III of
    this Act; and

    (5) add a new section establishing the tax treatment of Bootstrap Grants as
    non-taxable capital contributions to Qualified Federated Cooperatives, not
    subject to income tax in the hands of the recipient organization.

(c) BAYH-DOLE ACT.-- The Bayh-Dole Act, codified at 35 U.S.C. sections 200-212,
is hereby amended as specified in Section 503(b) of Title V of this Act,
eliminating the right of universities, nonprofit organizations, and small
businesses to elect title to inventions made with federal funding after the date
of enactment of this Act, and directing the contribution of all such inventions
to the Intellectual Property Commons.

(d) STEVENSON-WYDLER TECHNOLOGY INNOVATION ACT.-- The Stevenson-Wydler
Technology Innovation Act of 1980, codified at 15 U.S.C. section 3701 et seq.,
is hereby amended to:

    (1) mandate the transfer of dual-use technologies identified by the
    Civilian-Use Board pursuant to Section 903 of Title IX of this Act directly
    to the Intellectual Property Commons, without requirement for a Cooperative
    Research and Development Agreement or other intermediary licensing
    arrangement; and

    (2) establish the IP Commons as a recognized recipient institution for
    technology transfers under the Act.

(e) COPYRIGHT ACT.-- Title 17 of the United States Code is hereby amended to:

    (1) establish the voluntary commons dedication pathway of Section 506(a)(1)
    of Title V of this Act, enabling any copyright holder to dedicate a work to
    the Intellectual Property Commons at any time after creation by recording the
    dedication on the National Resilience Ledger, with the dedication constituting
    an irrevocable transfer to the commons for purposes of Title 17;

    (2) establish the abandoned-works mechanism of Section 506(a)(2) through (5)
    of Title V of this Act, providing that works not actively deployed for fourteen
    consecutive years and not voluntarily dedicated are subject to the notice and
    cure procedure of that Section and, upon expiration of the cure period without
    action by the rights-holder, enter the Intellectual Property Commons with
    attribution permanently registered;

    (3) establish the creator reversion right pursuant to Section 505(b) of Title
    V of this Act, providing individual creators with the right to reclaim
    copyright from corporate rights-holders after the earlier of thirty-five years
    from assignment or twenty years from the date of enactment, and providing
    that any contractual waiver of this right is void and unenforceable;

    (4) establish the automatic contribution of expired copyrights to the
    Intellectual Property Commons pursuant to Section 506(b)(3) of Title V of
    this Act; and

    (5) establish the copyleft mandate for derivative works of commons-licensed
    materials pursuant to Section 507 of Title V of this Act.

    (6) establish the right to repair circumvention exemption pursuant to
    Section 506(e) of Title V of this Act, adding a new subsection (k) to
    section 1201 of title 17, United States Code.

(f) PATENT ACT.-- Title 35 of the United States Code is hereby amended to:

    (1) establish the active deployment requirement for patent maintenance
    pursuant to Section 506(c)(1) of Title V of this Act, making patents subject
    to shelved patent recapture proceedings under Section 503(d) of Title V of
    this Act where active deployment is not demonstrated;

    (2) establish the anti-thicket provisions of Section 506(d) of Title V of
    this Act, limiting corporate patent portfolio concentration in any single
    technology domain; and

    (3) establish the automatic contribution of expired patents to the Intellectual
    Property Commons pursuant to Section 506(c)(2) of Title V of this Act.

(g) ECONOMIC ESPIONAGE ACT.-- The Economic Espionage Act of 1996, codified at
18 U.S.C. sections 1831-1839, is hereby amended to:

    (1) establish an exception to trade secret protection for trade secrets
    contributed to the Intellectual Property Commons through the QFN conversion
    pathway of Section 505(d) of Title V of this Act, providing that such
    contributions do not constitute misappropriation of trade secrets regardless
    of any pre-existing contractual obligation of confidentiality; and

    (2) provide that any contractual obligation of confidentiality that would
    prevent an employee from contributing trade secret knowledge to the IP Commons
    through the QFN conversion pathway is void and unenforceable to that extent.

(h) RURAL ELECTRIFICATION ACT.-- The Rural Electrification Act of 1936,
codified at 7 U.S.C. section 901 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) recognize rural electric cooperatives as Proto-QFN institutions pursuant
    to Section 1001 of Title X of this Act; and

    (2) direct the Rural Utilities Service to align its loan and grant programs
    with the technical integration requirements of Title VII of this Act,
    prioritizing funding for rural electric cooperatives seeking to achieve FMOS
    compliance and connect to the Federated Mesh.

(i) LOBBYING DISCLOSURE ACT.-- The Lobbying Disclosure Act of 1995, codified at
2 U.S.C. section 1601 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) require disclosure of lobbying activities directed at influencing the
    certification determinations, Bootstrap Grant allocations, or technology
    transfer decisions established by this Act; and

    (2) prohibit the use of Bootstrap Grant funds for lobbying activities,
    consistent with Section 106(e)(2)(B) of this Act.

(j) COMMUNICATIONS ACT.-- The Communications Act of 1934, codified at 47 U.S.C.
section 151 et seq., is hereby amended to:

    (1) direct the Federal Communications Commission to enforce the FMOS adoption
    requirements of Section 701(b) of Title VII of this Act through its existing
    device certification authority; and

    (2) recognize FMOS-compliant mesh communications infrastructure as a
    protected communications service eligible for universal service support under
    section 254 of the Act.

(k) COMPUTER FRAUD AND ABUSE ACT.-- Section 1030 of Title 18, United States
Code, is hereby amended as specified in Section 1104(d) of this Title, adding
the anti-spoofing offense to the list of prohibited computer fraud activities.

