SEC. 1106. AUTHORIZATION OF APPROPRIATIONS.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(a) GENERAL AUTHORIZATION.-- There are authorized to be appropriated to carry
out the purposes of this Act such sums as may be necessary for each fiscal year
following the date of enactment of this Act, subject to the specific
authorizations and funding mechanisms established in this Section.

(b) OFFICE OF FEDERATED STEWARDSHIP.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
to the Office of Federated Stewardship:

    (1) not less than two hundred fifty million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment, to cover establishment costs, initial staffing, and the
    first round of Bootstrap Grant awards;

    (2) not less than five hundred million dollars for each of the second through
    fifth fiscal years following enactment, covering ongoing operations, Bootstrap
    Grant distributions, and technical assistance programs; and

    (3) such reduced amounts as are necessary to carry out the residual functions
    of Section 107(e) of Title I of this Act following the network maturity
    threshold, with the reduction to be determined by the Director of the Office
    of Management and Budget in consultation with the Director of the Office of
    Federated Stewardship.

(c) BOOTSTRAP GRANT PROGRAM.-- There are authorized to be appropriated to the
Bootstrap Grant Program established under Section 106 of Title I of this Act:

    (1) not less than one billion dollars for the first fiscal year following
    enactment, prioritizing Formation Grants and Transition Grants for existing
    proto-QFN organizations;

    (2) not less than two billion dollars for each of the second through fifth
    fiscal years following enactment, expanding to cover Coverage Extension
    Grants, Creator Transition Grants, and Resilience Demonstration Grants; and

    (3) such sums as may be necessary for subsequent fiscal years, with the total
    Bootstrap Grant appropriation for any fiscal year not to exceed five percent
    of the estimated productive value of the Federated Network as reported by the
    Commons Credit Governance Council in its most recent annual report.

(d) NATIONAL RESILIENCE LEDGER AND TECHNICAL INFRASTRUCTURE.-- There are
authorized to be appropriated for the development, deployment, and maintenance
of the National Resilience Ledger, the Federated Mesh Open Standard, and related
technical infrastructure:

    (1) not less than five hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment, for initial development and deployment;

    (2) not less than two hundred fifty million dollars for each of the second
    through fifth fiscal years, for ongoing development and maintenance; and

    (3) such sums as may be necessary for subsequent fiscal years, with the
    expectation that technical infrastructure maintenance costs will be
    progressively assumed by the Federated Network's own financial architecture
    as the network matures.

(e) DECIDIM-DAO BRIDGE AND COMMONS ANALYTICS PLATFORM.-- There are authorized to
be appropriated for the open-source development of the Decidim-DAO bridge and
the commons analytics platform established under Section 705 of Title VII of
this Act:

    (1) not less than one hundred million dollars for the first fiscal year
    following enactment; and

    (2) not less than fifty million dollars for each of the second through fifth
    fiscal years following enactment.

(f) MILITARY-CIVILIAN STRATEGIC SYNC.-- There are authorized to be appropriated
for the implementation of Title IX of this Act, including the operations of the
Civilian-Use Board, the development of the Non-Kinetic Data Access Protocol, and
the environmental remediation of surplus military land:

    (1) not less than one billion dollars for the first fiscal year following
    enactment; and

    (2) such sums as may be necessary for subsequent fiscal years, with the
    environmental remediation component funded entirely from DoD appropriations
    rather than from the Act's general authorization.

(g) COMMONS SOLIDARITY FUND.-- There are authorized to be appropriated to the
Commons Solidarity Fund established under Section 1005(e) of Title X of this
Act:

    (1) not less than fifty million dollars for the first fiscal year following
    enactment; and

    (2) such sums as may be necessary for subsequent fiscal years, supplemented
    by the surplus resource trade revenues specified in Section 1005(e)(1) of
    Title X of this Act.

(h) FUNDING PRINCIPLES.-- The appropriations authorized by this Section shall be
governed by the following principles:

    (1) COMMONS ECONOMY SELF-FINANCING -- as the commons economy grows, an
    increasing proportion of the costs authorized by this Section shall be
    financed through the commons economy's own productive capacity, through the
    NRL capitalization mechanism of Section 601 of Title VI of this Act, the
    Bootstrap Grant Program's commons reinvestment obligations, and the Commons
    Solidarity Fund's surplus revenue mechanism, reducing dependence on annual
    congressional appropriations over time;

    (2) FRONT-LOADING -- the appropriations authorized for the first five years
    following enactment are deliberately front-loaded, reflecting the capital-
    intensive nature of infrastructure establishment and the importance of
    demonstrating early success through the Federated Resilience Demonstration
    Zones; and

    (3) ANTI-DEFUNDING PROTECTION -- the Guaranteed Provision Standard
    entitlements established under Title II of this Act are entitlements within
    the meaning of the Congressional Budget Act of 1974, not discretionary
    spending subject to annual appropriations, ensuring that the baseline
    provision obligations of the Federated Network cannot be eliminated through
    the failure to appropriate funds.

